Segment: Gardening has continued to be one of the favorite hobbies of Americans. According to the National Gardening Association in 2014, 35% of all households in America, or 42 million households, are growing food at home or in a community garden, up 17% in five years. UW-Extension and Master Gardener Volunteers provide research based programs and resources needed to support gardening as an enjoyable, satisfying, and environmentally responsible activity. However, still many working adults, parents and senior citizens in the county lack the knowledge and confidence to be successful gardeners.

Agriculture is the top industry in Clark County and Trempealeau Counties and much of my programming reflects that, whether it is offering Farm Succession Workshops, water quality testing, or agricultural plastics recycling. A majority of farms are family owned and the average age of a cropland owner is 65 years or older, hence a need for farm succession planning. In addition, as farmers look to diversify in changing economic climates, the need for farm management education is more important than ever.

Improving forage quality, production and management practices continues to be a key factor in the success of dairy and livestock farms. Forage crops account for nearly half (48%) of all cropland in Waupaca county, primarily alfalfa (67%) and corn silage (33%). A new local watershed project received federal funding in 2018 to help improve and protect water quality in Bear Lake and the Lower Little Wolf River through expanded soil conservation and nutrient management practices. The Waupaca County Forage Council remains a primary avenue for local UW-Extension forage and soil/water conservation outreach efforts.

Dairy remains the leading farm enterprise in Waupaca County accounting for two-thirds of all farm sales. Low milk prices for 2-3 years and a shrinking labor supply has many dairy farmers exploring options to improve productivity and/or labor efficiency, and some exploring shifting from a dairy to beef farming.

Agriculture is a prominent industry in Grant County and one major concern for farmers is remaining profitable in this poor economic time. Low milk prices have plagued the dairy industry since 2015 with the low milk prices projected to continue into 2019. We have seen some transitions and diversification in enterprises. We have especially seen dairy farmers transitioning to beef enterprises. The need for beef production programming in this area is evident through the 2016 Grant County Extension Needs Assessment Survey where respondents were asked to rate 11 educational topic areas where Beef Production ranked third and 29% of respondents viewed Beef Production as "Very Important" to Grant County. Programing efforts will be focused on providing unbiased, researched based information.

Forage and grain crop production is a staple of livestock agriculture. Quality forage is essential for dairy farm profitability. Additionally small livestock farms and beef operations are common in Clark County. Clark County has 156,000 acres committed to forage production. Most of this forage production is used to feed the county's livestock. Clark County has 131,200 acres committed to grain production. Crop revenue is $33 million annually, 10% of the total agriculture production sales (2012 Census of Agriculture), but a majority of the grain produced is used to feed the 160,000 head of cattle and calves in the county.A goal is to improve yield and quality of forage and grain by all producers in Clark County. Producers must continually adapt new management practices to remain profitable. The needs assessment identified grain and forage production programming as a need in the county.

An area of interest and concern for dairy producers in Marathon County is remaining profitable. With low milk prices for the last three years and projected low prices to continue into 2019 this is even more important. In a needs assessment producers indicated that proper nutrition, milk quality, and reproductive success were important to keeping their business profitable. Designing breeding programs that optimize genetics and reproductive efficiency are important in creating a profitable dairy business. Therefore, this agent will focus on providing support and education to producers looking to create a profitable dairy business. Efforts will focus on milk quality, animal wellbeing, reproduction and genetic selection.The Dairy Industry remains paramount to the success of agriculture in Marathon County. With the low commodity prices seen in 2016 for both grain crops and milk, dairy producers need to have a close eye on their finances. Having a strong understanding of Farm Financial Business Management allows farmers to maximize their bottom line.In order to maintain profitable dairy farms, producers in Marathon County need to understand farm financial management. Farm financial management education in Marathon County centers on increasing awareness of budgeting and succession planning.

Marquette County has a formalized specialization agreement with Adams, Green Lake, Juneau, Portage, Waushara, and Wood Counties known as the Central Wisconsin Agriculture Specialization (CWAS). The responsibilities of this educator will primarily be planning and implementing educational sessions or services that relate to livestock management and production in Marquette County as well as the six counties listed here. The specialized agents in Adams, Green Lake, Juneau, Portage, Waushara, and Wood Counties have similar responsibilities in their respective agriculture education field: Adams historically provided agronomy and nutrient management; Green Lake provided commercial horticulture and nutrient management instruction; Juneau provided dairy and forage management; Portage provided vegetable production; Waushara provided farm business management; Wood provides dairy and cranberry production. At the start of 2019, the Adams and Green Lake positions are now filled and Waushara has an interim agent. With the addition of new staff, adjustments of areas of specialty may need to be addressed.In Marquette County, on an annual basis, agriculture provides $593 million of economic activity (66% of the county's total economic activity) and jobs for 43% of the county workforce. Livestock sales account for 45% of the market value of products sold by farms. The 2012 Census of Agriculture estimates that there are 14,569 cattle and calves in Marquette County. In Marquette County, there are 88 operations with beef cattle and 48 with dairy cattle. There are 25 operations raising pigs and 16 operations with sheep. In the larger CWAS area, there are a total of 13,291 beef cows on 872 farms. Most farms have under 50 cows.60,105 milking cows on 673 farms. Most farms have over 100 milking cows.24,416 broiler chickens on 137 farms. over 28,758 laying hens on 544 farms. Most farms have under 50 laying birds.763 turkeys on 45 farms.over 4,511 pigs on 183 farms. The majority of farms have under 25 pigs.3,507 sheep on 150 farms. The majority of farms have under 25 sheep.8,035 horses, ponies, burros, donkeys, and mules on 1,344 farms.997 rabbits on 61 farms.Having reviewed the farm statistics, the results support that the majority of livestock farmers in the area are generally small-scale farmers. These farms are often diversified with multiple species present based on my on-farm observations over the past five years.In the 2014 formal needs assessment, grazing and pasture management continues to be a prominent educational programming desire in Marquette County. In addition to the formal (written) needs assessment, based on the types of livestock questions made to the UW-Extension office throughout the year, education on animal nutrition, management, and care would be of interest to adult and youth livestock farmers. These observations lead to an interest in expanding the contact list to include more livestock producers (besides beef) and diversify livestock programming efforts to reach out to non-beef livestock producers in addition to beef programming efforts.According to a national study completed by the National Animal Health Monitoring System (published in 2012 by the USDA Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service), 56% of small-scale (under $500,000 in gross annual sales) livestock operators preferred to get management/care information from local Cooperative Extension offices. A preference for written publications for additional management/care information was a close second with 49.4% of operations. This information supports the importance of local Cooperative Extension offices in not only directly providing research-based information to farmers, but also the need to contribute to relevant periodicals that farmers may read.

Gardening and horticulture is one of the top leisure activities with some reports showing over 85% of people participate. Food production in home and community gardens continues to increase, and the therapeutic and mental health benefits of working with plants and nature are becoming increasingly recognized. Consumer gardening practices can greatly affect personal, public and environmental health. The high number of inquiries into Extension offices indicates local residents need research based information to be successful. The 6 county area of Pierce, Polk, St. Croix, Dunn, Eau Claire and Chippewa have a mix of urban and rural areas, with a strong history of participation in horticultural events and activities, and a commitment to environmental protection.

With several years of depressed agriculture commodity prices, farmers are looking for alternative ways to make a profit with their farm. In past years farmers have relied on corn and soybean production to supplement their on-farm income. With rising agriculture input costs coupled with low commodity prices in recent years, farmers are looking for new ways to meet their bottom line.A prior needs assessment revealed that farm financial/business management, specifically cost of production calculations, measuring enterprise profitability, and financial management information are priorities for producers in Marquette County. In addition, farm transfers/estate planning and tax management are of interest to farmers in Marquette County. Other topics of interest included farm product marketing and land use/natural resource management issues. The visioning session for this position also emphasized the importance of farm business management and meeting the needs of limited-resource farmers.

An area of interest and concern for dairy producers in Marathon County is remaining profitable. With low milk prices for the last three years and projected low prices to continue into 2019 this is even more important. In a needs assessment producers indicated that proper nutrition, milk quality, and reproductive success were important to keeping their business profitable. Designing breeding programs that optimize genetics and reproductive efficiency are important in creating a profitable dairy business. Therefore, this agent will focus on providing support and education to producers looking to create a profitable dairy business. Efforts will focus on milk quality, animal wellbeing, reproduction and genetic selection.The Dairy Industry remains paramount to the success of agriculture in Marathon County. With the low commodity prices seen in 2016 for both grain crops and milk, dairy producers need to have a close eye on their finances. Having a strong understanding of Farm Financial Business Management allows farmers to maximize their bottom line. In order to maintain profitable dairy farms, producers in Marathon County need to understand farm financial management. Farm financial management education in Marathon County centers on increasing awareness of budgeting and succession planning.

According to the Census of Agriculture-USDA 2016 Wisconsin Agriculture Statistics, Green County is home to 29,000 dairy cows and 245 licensed dairy farms. In 2018, Wisconsin lost 638 dairy farms which is a 7.25% decline. Green County also has around 46,000 head of beef cattle and other animal species. We farm over 192,000 acres of cropland. Farming across the United States has been hit with some tough times. Agriculture producers are trying to find ways to diversify farm income so their farms survive. At the present time, it's not just dairy farmers who are looking for ways to make extra income. Due to tight margins, programming is needed to share with producers ways to make extra income. Programs that focus on efficiency and sharing profitable production practices is one example. Another option is assisting dairy producers consider and implement income alternatives if they decide to sell the herd. Helping agriculture producers understand their current situation (financial and operational), where they want to be and how they can get there is something every producer needs to think about whether they stay in farming or choose another route. The average age of farmers is 56 years and it is difficult for them to determine their succession plan. I just started into this position in Green County in August of 2018. Part of my plans are to create a needs assessment for the farmers to see what their needs are. Currently planning is based on my personal experiences in the agriculture industry and what co-workers, Ag and Extension Committee, and the past educator has done. Green County is also working on developing a water testing plan protocol and along with the results of the SWIGG study in nearby counties, many farmers in Green County are wondering if agriculture is playing a part in water contamination. Providing seminars on water quality related to agriculture is being planned and continuing to talk about water quality in the future on radio shows and articles will be happening.

Wisconsin leads the nation in cranberry production with over 60% of the nations crop. In Wisconsin the cranberry crop is worth over $100 million at the farm and provides many job opportunities in support industries such as cranberry warehousing, processing, marketing and crop inputs. In Wood County the industry is over $40 million at the marsh level.The industry has suffered low prices for a number of years now and growers are looking for sustainable practices that improve yield while minimizing the cost of crop inputs. This includes more labor saving harvest practices, precision timing and research based fertilizer applications utilization of new chemistry of pesticides as released to replace old products no longer available utilizing pest management principles.

As Richland County continues to see changes in demographics and funding there has been a primary change to the role of the Agriculture agent in Richland County. The county decided to reduce the position to a half time position. Also with in that same time frame Crawford County had a vacancy in its agriculture position. It was then agreed upon to move to a split position were 50% time was in Richland and 50% time in Crawford. The two counties are very similar with regards to its agricultural community. According to the 2012 Census of Agriculture Data, Richland County has 1,260 farms and Crawford County has 1,105. Both counties showed a trend down from the 2007 census. While the number of farms has been decreasing, the average size has increased. Land used for agricultural production is predomantly used for crop production in both counties, with 45% and 49 % percent of Crawford and Richland County's Ag land devoted to crop production. The census data also shows us that market value of the products sold is increasing on Richland County farms as well. As a County, the market value of agricultural products sold in 2012 was $115,451,000 up 37% from the 2007 Census of Agriculture. Looking at the breakdown, Richland County is still heavily reliant on sales generated by livestock and their products (72% of the agricultural sales). While Crawford County is more balanced with 50% of its agricultural sales coming from Livestock sales. A quick overview of the agricultural sector in Richland County shows us that the top agricultural commodities in Richland County by sales are: Milk, Grain, Cattle & Calves, Fruits/ Tree nuts / Berries, and Vegetables. Top Commodities for Crawford County are: Cattle & Calves, Grains, and Hogs and Pigs. While being focused on livestock production, Richland and Crawford Counties offer very diverse landscape with many very small agricultural operations. Utilizing the farm finical data offered by USDA, 70% of Richland County farms and 68% of Crawford County Farms had less than $25,000 in gross sales (2012). Sales of agricultural products in this range are an indication that these producers are not utilizing agriculture as their primary income, and agriculture as a part of their lifestyle. Lifestyle producers view agriculture as a way to supplement their land base, add extra income or enhance their quality of life. From the increase in the number of calls and office visits; it is evident that basic animal husbandry, market development and environmental resources are needed.

Yearly weather variations make twice-weekly monitoring important to ensure harvesting high quality forage. Partner with the Sheboygan County Forage Council to implement the alfalfa quality monitoring project.

Waukesha County Extension has provided educational workshops to Plan Commission Member since 2011. In partnership with Waukesha County Planning Department, workshop topics are chosen to meet the needs of Plan Commission Members. Topics have included: Plan Commission Basics (offered twice); Land Use Decision Making Using a Sustainability Framework; Conservation Subdivision Design: Environmental Merits and Barriers to Implementation; Tax Increment Financing - New Perspective for a New Era; and Balancing community values, Local discretion & new state rule on conditional uses. The 2018 workshop evaluation showed that by attending the workshop, 69% of participants increased their knowledge of the workshop topic by 50% or more after attending the program.

The Green Industry (Greenhouse growers, lawn and landscape services, urban forestry) in Brown County is strong and growing, providing services and products to the ever expanding urban public. According to a Wisconsin agriculture and economy impact report in 2014, the horticulture business in Brown County has generated $6.3 million in economic activity, providing thousands of full-time and many seasonal jobs. This lucrative industry has an increasing need for educational programs on sustainable Green Industry practices and diagnostic services. They are listed as two of the top five educational needs at various short course program and Greenhouse growers' seminar evaluations. Sustainable Green Industry practices improve the environment by conserving resources, reduce chemical applications, save labor costs and improve the safety and health of the employees.

The past five years have seen margins on cash crops decline from all-time highs. At this same time farmers are seeing rapid increases in new technologies, that may or may not be profitable to adopt at this time, increases in herbicide resistance in weeds. There continues to be an increase in the number of acres of cash grain crop production in Monroe and the surrounding counties. With tight margins, many farmers are seeking unbiased information on crop management practices and pest management. Soil conservation, quality and nutrient management are also topics of great interest to farmers, especially ways to control input costs and maximizing returns in these areas. Observations and discussions with farmers regarding crop production have indicated that there is a need for unbiased information regarding risk management, best management practices and integrated pest management. There is also a need for updated basic crop marketing information to help producers help make it through the current economic situation. Farmers still get a lot of pressure from some sales people to purchase inputs that may not be most profitable for the farmer. There is an increase in herbicide resistance problems in the area , in particular increased incidences of waterhemp in fields , that require changes in management practices.Discussions with Land Conservation personel and Department of Agriculture Personel have also indicated an increased need for nutrient management planning in the area.

Situation StatementThe average age of farmers continues to increase in Trempealeau County (USDA, ERS, 2017). Finances to start a new farm business are often challenging for people that do not have an established family farm to work into because of the high value of land and buildings. The value of land and buildings in farms in Trempealeau County increased from $892,303 in the 2007 census of agriculture to $1,033,131 in the 2012 census of agriculture (USDA Census of Agriculture, 2012). Purchasing an existing farm is out of reach of many people that desire to start farming. Economics in commodity agriculture have been extremely bleak for the last five years as corn, soybean, and milk prices have been at or below the cost of production for most farmers. Adding value through direct marketing of farm products and agritourism are ways that existing or new farms can generate more revenue and profit. Needs analysis conducted with key stakeholder groups has highlighted the need to bring new farm businesses into Trempealeau County while enhancing the ability of farms to be profitable for the operators of the farms. Direct marketing of agricultural production can take many avenues as the commodities produced are varied. Some commodities may require processing to market direct while others may be sold without processing. Licensing requirements will vary from none needed with fresh vegetables at farmers markets to many with a dairy commodity such as cheese or ice cream. Setting up a direct marketing agricultural enterprise can be daunting. People need to enter the process fully aware of the requirements and challenges ahead of them. Soil erosion and soil health is a concern of partners and stakeholders of Trempealeau County UW-Extension as shown in key stakeholder needs analysis. Dairy farm numbers have decreased in Trempealeau County and more corn is grown in the county. Data from the Census of Agriculture show 195 dairy farms with a total of 21,373 cows in Trempealeau County (USDA, National Statistics Service, 2012) down from 733 dairy farms and 33,144 cows in 1987 (USDA, National Statistics Service, 1992). This shift in dairy production has left land available for row crop production. With less perennial forage crops needed in the rotation, the cropping system has become one of continuous corn. Corn acres have increased 48% from 1987 to 2012 with 63,966 acres of corn planted in Trempealeau County in 1987 and 94,597 acres of corn for silage and grain in 2012 (USDA, National Statistics Service, 1992, 2012). No-till planting carries a yield penalty with continuous corn, so tillage is performed to maintain yields (Wolkowski et al., 2009). Methods to increase soil health and increase crop yields are needed in Trempealeau County. Program priority #2 will address these issues in the county.

Aquatic invasive species (AIS) negatively impact Wisconsin through their ability to harm aquatic ecosystems, the economic value of those ecosystems, and human health. During 2019, the updated Wisconsin Aquatic Invasive Species Management Plan will be approved by the US Fish and Wildlife Service and the national Aquatic Nuisance Species Task Force. The updated plan is focused on the pathways AIS take into Wisconsin's waterbodies, such as organisms in trade, non-recreational fishing and aquaculture, and those who recreate in state waters as well and those who provide services where they touch lakes, rivers, and wetlands. Our AIS Outreach staff are working closely with WDNR Monitoring staff to identify how AIS are moving into and throughout the state, further developing our AIS picture, and in turn, helping the WI AIS Partnership develops actions to reduce the number propagules in transport.New and updated communication tools and outreach strategies will be needed to further the work the state has already accomplished to prevent AIS introductions through primary and secondary invasion pathways and to contain and control AIS that are already present. UW-Extension will play an important role in creating these tools and strategies and putting them into the hands of members of our AIS Prevention Network. As we learn more about each of the pathways of AIS, appropriate outreach methods will need to be developed and introduced to the partnership and directly to those engaged in specific pathways.

The Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources (WDNR), members of the AIS Partnership Network and volunteers store collected data in the WDNR's Surface Water Integrated Management System (SWIMS). The online database is used to collect a wide range of water related data for the state, including AIS monitoring reports, purple loosestrife biocontrol projects, stream and lake AIS signage projects, and other work that is often a deliverable of a WDNR AIS Education, Prevention and Planning grant. WDNR and partnership staffs are only recently learning how the database is useful beyond the collection of basic data. For each grant or project, it can contain the history of activities from project start to finish and include items such as personnel/project roles, specific work locations/actions, documents varying from press releases to final reports and maps, and AIS monitoring results that are fed directly to public facing webpages, including interactive maps. Beyond data collection, SWIMS acts as a work planning tool. The original SWIMS data manager left their position in early 2017. Various SWIMS project creation roles have been taken on by both WDNR Central Office and Regional staff, but no one had taken leadership of training WDNR AIS Coordinators or the AIS partners to use and manage the specific projects for the partnership. Working with staff from the Lakes and Rivers Section of the WDNR, I began developing training and piloting it in 2017 with two new AIS Coordinators from a grant funded partner and the WDNR AIS Coordinator who assists them. This educational effort will continue in 2019 to be expanded to new partners and additional WDNR staff. Because of my experience with the database as an AIS Coordinator and Monitoring Specialist with the WDNR, I'm in a unique position to provide this as a UW Extension educator. It is projected that by late 2019, SWIMS 2.0 will be out of production and ready for use. I anticipate assisting with training plans for the roll out in regards to AIS components.

Background information on Juneau County's part in the Central Wisconsin Agriculture Specialization (CWAS), which is a formal agreement with Adams, Green Lake, Marquette, Portage, Waushara, and Wood Counties. The Juneau County educator will mainly be focusing on creating educational programs and services that relate to dairy and crops in Juneau County as well as the six counties listed above. Each of the specialized agents in Adams, Green Lake, Marquette, Portage, Waushara, and Wood Counties have a topic area that they specialize in and create programs and services that go with their particular agriculture education fields: Adams offers agronomy and nutrient management; Green Lake offers commercial horticulture and nutrient management; Marquette offers livestock management; Portage offers vegetable production; Waushara offers farm business management; Wood offers dairy and cranberry production. In the beginning of 2019, the Waushara position was recently filled with a LTE position by the county, but there has been additional requests for time on the Adams, Green Lake, Juneau, Marquette, Portage, and Wood counties agriculture educators to help address local needs.In Juneau and Sauk Counties, on an annual basis, agriculture provides $348.6 billion (19.2% in Juneau Co.) and $865.3 million (13.8% in Sauk Co.) in each county's economic activity and $96.6 million (11.7% in Juneau Co.) and $331 million (10.4% in Sauk Co.) in each county's total income. Agriculture in Juneau County provides for 1,713 jobs (14.1%) of the county's workforce out of the 12,134 jobs as of 2014. In comparison, Sauk County Agriculture provides 5,463 jobs (11.7%) out of 46,653 jobs as of 2014.Note: The Juneau and Sauk Counties Educator has only transitioned to this 50/50 split position between the two county offices in mid-October. During this transition, the Educator has been trying to get to know key agriculture contacts in the counties and trying to get to know the county's needs. Meanwhile, hosting a few key programs this winter for certifications and licenses needed by the farmers.Just a reminder that there has not been a formal needs assessment done in a number of years for both counties and is a goal for the agricultural educator position this year. Making it difficult to determine the exact needs for the dairy and livestock industries. However, by going off of the 2012 census, milk was the first and second top selling commodity for Juneau and Sauk Counties. There is also 13 dairy product processing plants between the two counties and accounts for $92.1 million to Juneau County's economy and $348.9 million into Sauk County's economy. In comparison, livestock numbers for the counties show that livestock is an important part of the industry as well with cattle & calves placing in third and fourth top commodities for the two counties. Furthermore, hogs and pigs are ranked fourth for Sauk County's top commodities and ranks second in the state for hog and pig animal numbers. The 2012 Census of Agriculture states that Juneau is at 38% and Sauk County is at 66% for the market value of products sold. Making these important topics to look at and begin to create programming for in 2019. Reminder that in the beginning of 2019, Waushara had recently hired a LTE position, still placing additional requests for time on the Adams, Green Lake, Juneau, Marquette, Portage, and Wood counties agriculture educators to help address local needs in the CWAS area.

In Taylor County I coordinate the StrongBodies Program to offer a low-cost strength training program for middle-aged and older adults across the county. StrongBodies an evidence-based strength training program for middle-aged and older adults to increase strength, muscle mass, bone density, and activities of daily living while decreasing risk for chronic diseases.

Scott Reuss serves as the Crops/Soils/Horticulture Agent for Marinette and Oconto Counties, through his role as Marinette County Agriculture/Horticulture Agent and an agricultural specialization agreement with Oconto County. The agricultural economic outlook for 2019 is still very poor for dairy producers, and unclear for grain producers. Dairy producers will struggle to maintain their operational viability, and will need to make forage management decisions that optimize their return on investment and achieve maximum forage quantity and/or quality. Included in these decisions will likely be re-plant or supplementation planting of perennial forage acres due to the winter die-back experienced in 2018 and also poor overwintering conditions at current. This adds even more economic stress and forage quality/quantity uncertainty to all area livestock producers. Grain producers have the constant challenge of managing costs while maintaining yield potential. Projected 2019 breakeven yields for grain crops are higher than long-term county averages (accounting for increasing yield trends) would indicate we will be able to produce. One educational need that will be addressed in 2019 is producer decision-making regarding Farm Service Agency programs made available to producers through the new Farm Bill. All producers will need to make decisions regarding their grain crop acres and UW-Extension will play a pivotal role in helping them understand the potential outcomes of that decision. Regarding nutrient management and soil health, a distinct opportunity for higher level programming is now available in the two-county area due to funding received through the Natural Resources Conservation Service for a sub-watershed improvement program (North Branch of the Little River). This NWQI (National Water Quality Initiative) effort will involve UW-Extension personnel taking a lead in producer education efforts surrounding the conservation efforts that can be cost-shared for implementation. 2019 is the first year of this 5-year effort.The desired outcomes in this plan of work are based on continuing local needs assessment via producer/agent interactions and the needs assessment surveys conducted in Oconto & Marinette (2014) and Shawano (2013) Counties. In those needs assessments, Shawano County producers indicated that their four highest educational topic needs related to: Grain Crops Pest Management; Soil Quality; Forage Crops Nutrient Management; and Forage Crops Pest Management. Oconto/Marinette County producers were asked to focus on dairy and livestock-oriented educational topic needs, but did indicate forage crop production information is still needed. They also indicated that the single most important role of UW-Extension within agricultural education is the education of non-agricultural citizenry. The second most important is to be a consistent source of information for producers, especially on a one-on-one basis. The specific activities within the outcomes listed below will be supplemented by agricultural newsletter articles, local newspaper articles, local radio shows, and electronic media information availability. In addition to the primary local educational roles, Reuss also serves on the state-wide Produce Safety Rule training team. In this role, he will be working with other UW-Extension and WI Department of Agriculture, Trade, and Consumer Protection staff to train & certify producers in the Produce Safety Alliance producer course and also conduct On-farm Readiness Reviews. This role will consume approximately 10-15% of his time in 2019, but is not spelled out in specifics here, as it is a state-wide initiative.

Multiple years of negativecash flow have many farmers and lenders evaluating options. Selling less productive land to non-farmersis one option, but could lead to more unplanned non-farm development and morerural landowner conflicts in the future. Low net farm income often brings more demand for information about cashlease, as well as buying or selling standing crops. The new USDA Farm bill also includes newrisk management tools for farmers.

There are four different groups in Monroe County and surrounding area who are the target audience for commercial horticulture programming that I am part of. One of the groups is the cranberry growers, who have historically interacted directly with the specialists at UW. Occasionally I will get a call from them and will respond as needed. Fresh Market Vegetable and Fruit growers is another of the audiences. This group is primarily Amish, and I have worked with them for many years to help them with their crops. They primarily grow fresh market vegetables and flowers and bedding plants. They have become accomplished growers and the educational needs there have become more problem specific rather than basic production education like it was when they started. They grow a wide range of fresh market vegetables. Feedback from them has indicated that UW Extension is a highly valued resource for information. A current need for some Amish communities in the area is Food Safety and Modernization Act Training and Certification.Hops production in Wisconsin has had a great resurgence in the last 10 years as small craft brewers have increased their interest in Wisconsin produced hops to appeal to customers who appreciate local grown and local sourced foods and beverages. The hops growers have had to learn as they go because the majority of the current information on growing hops is from the Pacific northwest. One area of production I have helped to begin to address is that many acres of the hops are grown in coarse textured soils and nutrient leaching to groundwater is a concern on those soils. Hops growers do not want to be over fertilizing due to both environmental concerns and economic concerns. There are many other aspects of hops production that the group also assists with. We received a USDA Specialty Crop Block Grant to continue and expand the nitrogen rate trials for hops production in Wisconsin.The Ho-Chunk Native American Tribe has farm property in Monroe County and other counties as well and they are using the property near Tomah to begin to build and expand their Agriculture Division projects. They want to utilize their farm land for better opportunities than renting it out to other farmer to help provide better choices of food to tribal members, than what many of them, who are low income, may be able to get otherwise. I have worked with them for the past 4 years to help identify opportunities and implement a community garden in one of their housing subdivisions near Tomah. In late 2017 they set up funding for an Agriculture Division to begin additional larger scale fresh vegetable production projects at their Whirling Thunder Ranch property near Tomah.

Building from previous year's plan of work I am going to continue to build up a rapport with local agriculture and horticulture groups. This past year I was able to attend several meetings of various stakeholders and gained a better understanding of their needs. The meetings, along with the needs assessment survey I conducted this past year are driving the programming I am continuing to do in La Crosse County. Data indicates the top five programs survey participants would like to see include Farm Succession, New Farm Technology, Sustainable Farming, Environmental Protection, and Animal Health. Since all of these require a shift in farming practices my major focus will be on Farm Transitioning which will include programming such as shifting gears, estate planning, BQA, YQCA, and much more.

Situation statement (Why)University of Wisconsin-Madison Division of Extension is uniquely positioned to supply the technical expertise to educate citizens of Wisconsin on current issues and supply research on needed topics. UW Discovery Farms develops on-farm and related research to determine the economic and environmental effects of agricultural practices on a diverse group of Wisconsin farms; and educates and improves communications among the agricultural community, consumers, researchers and policymakers to better identify and implement effective environmental management practices that are compatible with profitable agriculture.Wisconsin has tremendous diversity in both the landscapes that are used for agricultural production as well as the types of animal and cropping systems. Therefore, practices to mitigate agriculture's potential impact to the environment will not only vary regionally, but also between different farms within a region or even between different fields on a farm. Understanding the timing and mechanisms for soil and nutrient loss from the diverse farming systems throughout Wisconsin will empower farmers, agricultural consultants and conservation professionals to determine effective, site-specific practices to protect Wisconsin's water resources while maintaining profitable agricultural production.The primary focus of UW Discovery Farms is to develop and implement research to more accurately assess water impairment sources, collaborate to develop effective practices to mitigate impairments, and educate stakeholders on methods to protect Wisconsin's water resources. It is vital that UW Extension engages in water quality issues as it has continued to become a developing problem at the local, state and national level. Water quality issues affect all populations, forms of business, recreation and tourism and have no civil rights factors and implications.

According to the Food Safety and Modernization Act all Produce Growers whose produce sales exceed $25000 or total food sales are more than $500000 are required to participate in the Food Safety and Modernization Act.

Livestock production, in particular beef and dairy, is a significant part of agriculture in Monroe County. The volatile markets over the past 4 years have continued to make very tight margins in many agricultural enterprises. We continue to see dairy producers exit the dairy business, some transition from dairy enterprises to beef enterprises, cash crop only or no longer actively engage in farming. The landscape in Monroe and surrounding counties is such that perennial forage production (cattle feed) is necessary for good land stewardship. The need for Quality Assurance Certification Training livestock packers demand it continues to grow. The need to provide programming for beef producers has been identified and supported in this area by beef producers, ag lenders, veterinarians, and producer organizations through their participation, financial support and willingness to partner on educational efforts to provide unbiased, research based information to address local needs.Dairy producers have begun to increase the use of beef semen on varying percentages of their dairy cows in an effort in add value to calves they do not intend to keep for replacements in the dairy herd. A survey was conducted in 2018 to determine management practices used and where there may be some need for improvement of those management practices. The results will be used to determine potential educational opportunities in that area.I intend to work with my counterparts in nearby counties to help offer educational programming to address local needs for dairy producers. Some dairy and livestock producers will also need information to help them determine if they should continue to farm or look at transitioning out of livestock enterprises and or farming due to the continued sour farm economy.

"Agriculture works hard for Manitowoc County every day. Family-owned farms, food processors and agriculture-related businesses generate thousands of jobs and millions of dollars of economic activity while contributing to local income and tax revenues. Manitowoc County is an agricultural powerhouse. The county is home to about 110,000 dairy cattle compared to approximately 81,000 people. Dairy farms of all sizes dot the rural landscape. Herd sizes range from fewer than 20 cows to more than 5,000 cows per farm. Located along Lake Michigan, the cool summer temperatures are ideal for milk production. As a leading dairy producer, Manitowoc County routinely ranks in the top five Wisconsin counties and the top 25 U.S. counties in dairy production. It also ranks in the top five Wisconsin counties in corn silage, hay, and winter wheat production. Manitowoc County agriculture provides 5,105 jobs, or about 11.5 percent, of the county's workforce of 44,370. Production jobs include farm owners and managers and farm employees. Agricultural service jobs include veterinarians, crop and livestock consultants, feed, fuel and other crop input suppliers, farm machinery dealers, barn builders and agricultural lenders, to name a few. Processing jobs include those employed in food processing and other value-added industries that support food processors. Every job in agriculture generates an additional 0.48 jobs in the county.Agriculture contributes $360 million to county income Manitowoc County agriculture accounts for $360.4 million, or 10 percent, of the county's total income. This includes wages, salaries, benefits and profits of farmers and workers in agriculture-related businesses. Every dollar of agricultural income generates an additional $0.49 of county income.Agriculture pumps $1.5 billion into local economy Manitowoc County agriculture generates $1.5 billion in economic activity, about 17 percent, of the county's total economic activity. Every dollar of sales from agricultural products generates an additional $0.16 of economic activity in other parts of the county's economy.The direct effect of agriculture equals$1.3 billion and includes the sale of farm products and value-added products.Purchases of agricultural and food processing inputs, services and equipment add another $129 million in economic activity. For example, this includes business-to-business purchases of fuel, seed, fertilizer, feed and farm machinery, as well as veterinary services, crop and livestock consultants and equipment leasing. This business-to-business activity then generates another $75.6 million in economic activity when people who work in agriculture-related businesses spend their earnings in the local economy.The 2017 average production per cow was 27,800 pounds tying Manitowoc County for first place in Wisconsin with Brown County. Furthermore, only Fond du Lac and Clark County dairy farmers produced more milk. Manitowoc County surpassed Dane County in 2017 to rank 3rd in the state in total milk production. Manitowoc County ranks third out of the 72 counties and in the top 25 counties in the U.S. in total annual milk production. In addition, Manitowoc County is tied for third with Dane County for the most dairy cows---55,000.Issues needing to be addressed in 2019 and beyond (Based on my experiences):Farmers have faced sustained low milk and commodity prices for the past four and one half years, making it difficult to meet the challenges of paying expenses. The December Class III milk price was $13.78 per cwt, the second lowest in 2018 (Only February's $13.40 per cwt was lower). This price equates to about $3 to $4 per cwt below the cost of production for the average Manitowoc County dairy farmer.Dairy farmers are being dropped by their milk processors if they do not meet certain parameters including animal comfort (tethered calves) and milk quality.There is a critical need for extension programming in the areas of farm succession (business transfer, retirement planning, and estate planning).There is a critical need for extension programming in the area of "gracefully" exiting the dairy industry.With the second highest inventory of heifers on record in the U.S. and with the cost of raising dairy calves and heifers exceeding the cost to purchase, farmers are looking for ways to be more efficient and profitable in raising the dairy replacement herd. Dairy farmers are looking at options to raising their own heifers.Manure management continues to be a major issue facing dairy farmers, custom manure haulers, and agronomists.Surface and groundwater protection is critical.Agricultural literacy needs to be addressed on a continual basis.When it comes to managing a dairy business operation, herd health, animal well-being, and sound financial management can have a substantial impact on profitability. Based on the 2011 needs assessment and emerging issues that I deal with on a daily basis, I will conduct programs for the 2019 program timeframe to help improve farm profitability via two program priorities: dairy production and management and farm business management. I will also devote a lot of time to agricultural literacy through the Farm Wisconsin Discovery Center as well as manure management and water quality related issues.

Taylor County is one of the lowest access to broadband counties in the State of Wisconsin according to the University Wisconsin Extension Digital Divide Publication. The Taylor County Broadband Committee is looking at way to address this and increase access to broadband.

Situation Statement:Youth leadership development programs provide skill development and the opportunity to apply applying learned leadership skills. University of Illinois Extension (Diaz et al, 2015) has identified six action areas where youth leaders develop competency in 4-H Youth Development: 1) planning, 2) promoting, 3) teaching, 4) mentoring, 5) advocating, and 6) advising. Program examples and outcomes in each of these six areas were highlighted in a 2016 Wisconsin 4-H impact report: https://fyi.uwex.edu/4h/files/2014/06/2016-Wisconsin-4-H-Foundational-Topics-Report.pdfThe 2010 Wisconsin 4-H Youth Leadership study found that all older 4-H youth demonstrated individual growth in life skills, youth participating in the program's intentional leadership practices (club officers, committee members, camp counselors, leadership training workshop participants, teen court panelists, etc.) had more opportunities in group and teamwork development. Intentional leadership activities give many opportunities to lead and work with both youth and adults. The study identified key program practices that contributed to leadership skill development, including:  Youth are working on meaningful issues and have significant responsibilities Program structure provides a scaffold for youth leadership Shared vision and commitment fosters teamwork Youth/adult partnershipThe strongest outcomes in the 2010 Wisconsin 4-H study were in community connectedness and self-efficacy (beliefs about one's capabilities to produce effects). The strongest skill outcomes were related to communication, decision-making and problem-solving skills.

During the course of 2018 I sought to engage business owners for feedback in Forest and Vilas Counties as often as I could. Coordinating with the Vilas County Economic Development Director, I conducted 23 business retention visits in eastern Vilas County as a follow up to the survey of 150 businesses that I had done in 2017. I engaged economic development boards of both Vilas and Forest County - including directors, board members and business people as often as possible to gather input on their thoughts about business and economic development. I helped a private citizen - along with a small team - to prepare and hold an event we collectively called the Northwoods Forum, which attracted 88 people, to discuss economic development issues common to Forest, Vilas and Oneida Counties. From all of these gatherings and 'listening sessions' of the people in the region, two major topics emerged that I feel I can contribute much to the region by addressing: workforce development and broadband. The second issue where we need to continue to make major improvements is on broadband. The status of our broadband - or diminished capacity thereof, has once again been brought up by Vilas County Supervisors and government officials directly to me and board members of economic development committees in this two-county region. I write "again" because I was heavily involved in the strategy to increase broadband deployment from 2013-2017 in Vilas County. It seems that in the last two years there was almost a respite on this subject while people waited for federally-funded providers (under Connect America Funds) to deploy fiber and wireless broadband in these two counties (as elsewhere in rural regions of Wisconsin). But there has been a "revival" of interest, a "re-wakening" - as UW-Extension s The importance of the workforce issue was captured in the statewide Situational Analysis conducted in 2018 by UW-Extension.se Broadband Coordinator Gail Huycke recently stated in an email message to me "It's almost like everybody wok up on January 1 [2019} and wanted more broadband. IN January, Northland Pines School District Administrator called me to talk about Broadband. Three local economic development committees in Vilas and Forest Counties have also picked up the drumbeat of seeking information relevant to improving their local broadband service. Thus, Preparing a Strategy to Improve the Quality of Rural Broadband is Major Program #2.

Agriculture in Chippewa County is vital to the overall county economy. In 2014, it was estimated Chippewa County agriculture contributes $618 million in economic activity and $205 million in total income. Agriculture also provides jobs for 3,387 Chippewa County residents. Over 1700 farms are located in Chippewa County according to the USDA 2012 Census of Agriculture. These farms average 219 acres in size. Horticulture contributes another $1 million in economic activity in the county with fruit crop and other specialty crops leading the way. Major crops grown in Chippewa County include corn (90,000 acres), soybean (50,000 acres, and alfalfa (25,000 acres). With a variety of agriculture and horticulture in Chippewa County, it is my intent to deliver programs in the areas of agronomy, soil and manure management, and horticulture.A Chippewa County Agriculture Needs Assessment Survey in 2015 revealed nutrient management as a top priority. Farmers indicated a need for improved nutrient management and utilization of on-farm nutrient sources in order to reduce input costs and increase profitability. Farmers will continue to seek out information and methods to better manage crop input costs as commodity prices in 2018 are forecasted to remain low and below a profitable range for many farms. Custom manure applicators and dairy and livestock producers remain interested in gaining information about new manure handling technology and safety. Demand for safety training and information has increased in response to recent farm accidents. Safety related to manure gases and manure handling equipment will be addressed through workshops and field meetings.Cover crops are being planted on several farms in Chippewa County as a result of an increased awareness of soil health and erosion benefits. NRCS has provided cost-sharing to farmers to incentivize and implement the practice of using cover crops. With limited cover crop data on Chippewa County soils and climate, the need for applied research to determine best management practices for cover crops and their benefits and challenges is needed. Commodity prices are projected to remain low in 2018 and some farmers are looking to alternative crops to provide additional income. Malting barley, hops, and industrial hemp have all peaked interest as alternative crops. UW-Extension is positioned to help farmers make decisions regarding these crops. Industrial hemp will only be addressed by this agent if approval to participate in the pilot research project from DATCP is secured.Chippewa County is home to 257 dairy farms, 26,000 milking cows, over 350 beef farms, and 4,500 head of beef cattle. The dairy industry remains the number one agricultural industry in Chippewa County and forage production is vitally important to milk production. Dairy and forage producers continue to put high quality forage as a priority for their farms. Alfalfa, hay, and corn silage production are top priorities for dairy and beef producers. The need for sound forage production and input management remains especially important. Forage production components including establishment, fertilization, pest management, and harvest and storage need to be addressed. Horticulture contributes over $1 million in economic activity to Chippewa County. Fruit crops, greenhouses, and fresh market enterprises make up a majority of the industry. Pest management is a major time commitment and production expense for these industries. Industrial hemp was approved for planting in Wisconsin in 2017 and included in the 2018 Farm Bill signed in December 2018. Farmers and land owners interested in planning industrial hemp have little to no local research and data to make decisions to grow the crop. Plans are to collaborate with Extension UW-Madison researchers and DATCP to provide a research location in Chippewa County.

Fond du Lac County Agriculture & Dairy Industry: "Agriculture works hard for Fond du Lac County every day. Family-owned farms, food processors and agriculture-related businesses generate thousands of jobs and millions of dollars of economic activity while contributing to local income and tax revenues. Fond du Lac County agriculture encompasses a mix of family farms, food processors, equipment manufacturers, retail and service providers. Dairy farms of all sizes dominate the rural landscape, ranging from fewer than 100 cows to more than 8,000.Fond du Lac County agriculture provides 7,790 jobs, or 13.6 percent, of the county's workforce of 57,293. Production jobs include farm owners, managers, and employees. Agricultural service jobs include veterinarians, crop and livestock consultants, feed, fuel and other crop input suppliers, farm machinery dealers, barn builders and agricultural lenders, to name a few. Processing jobs include those employed in food processing and other value-added industries that support food processors. Every job in agriculture generates an additional 0.73 jobs in the county. Agriculture contributes $591 million to county income Fond du Lac County agriculture accounts for $591.3 million, or 13.3 percent, of the county's total income. This includes wages, salaries, benefits and profits of farmers and workers in agriculture-related businesses. Every dollar of agricultural income generates an additional $0.79 of county income. Agriculture pumps $2.2 billion into local economy Fond du Lac County agriculture generates $2.2 billion in economic activity, about 21 percent, of the county's total economic activity. Every dollar of sales from agricultural products generates an additional $0.27 of economic activity in other parts of the county's economy. Here's how agriculture stimulates economic activity:  The direct effect of agriculture equals $1.75 billion and includes the sale of farm products and value-added products.  Purchases of agricultural and food processing inputs, services and equipment add another $316.7 million in economic activity. For example, this includes business-to-business purchases of fuel, seed, fertilizer, feed and farm machinery, as well as veterinary services, crop and livestock consultants and equipment leasing.   This business-to-business activity then generates another $157.3 million in economic activity when people who work in agriculture-related businesses spend their earnings in the local economy"Dairying remains paramount to the success of agriculture in Fond du Lac County. Fond du Lac County's 223 dairy farms (a 14 farm loss from the previous year) house 59,000 dairy cows (rank 3rd in state for cow numbers) which produce 26,300 pounds per milk per cow per year. With a total milk production of 1.55 billion pounds of milk in Fond du Lac County, Fond du Lac County is the leading county in the state for total milk production (Wisconsin Agriculture Statics Service, 2017) and falling in the top 25 US dairy-producing counties. "Dairy is a key Fond du Lac County industry Dairy farming is the major agricultural industry in Fond du Lac County. On-farm production and milk sales account for $239.6 million. Processing milk into dairy products generates another $1.02 billion.  Eleven plants process dairy products in Fond du Lac County.   On-farm milk production accounts for 1,119 jobs, and dairy processing accounts for 2,164 jobs.  At the county level, each dairy cow generates $3,645 in on-farm sales to producers.   At the state level, each dairy cow generates over $34,000 in total sales." Source: S. Deller, 2014 Fond du Lac County Agriculture: Value & Economic Impact2017 Program Needs Assessment: With a hire of both the Dodge County dairy & livestock agent, and the Fond du Lac/Dodge County area crops & soils agent, a joint needs assessment of both counties' farmers and agri-business community was conducted Winter 2016-2017 to identify programming priorities in the areas of dairy and agronomy. The needs assessment was distributed to extension meeting participants, as well as via email with an online survey. Based on the needs assessment (n=100), the following top educational dairy replated priorities were identified:  Nutrition ? Reproduction Animal well-being ? HousingCurrent & Emerging Issues: The dairy industry is a very dynamic industry, with new technologies and practices being developed, managing income and expenses with an ever-changing market, and an aging population.  Dairy farmers faced tight margins for the past couple years with 2019 milk prices predicted to be a better year, but still not good enough to support the farm families. The December Class III milk price was $13.78 per cwt, the second lowest in 2018. This price equates to about $3 to $4 per cwt below the cost of production for the average dairy farmer. With a large national dairy herd, declining domestic demand, reduced exports due to large global outputs of milk, and a strong dollar, prices for commodities such as milk are negatively affected. Lower milk checks means reduced income for the farm to pay expenses related to the farm business, as well as living expenses. Farmers have to watch more carefully on where they spend every dollar. With long-term low milk prices, farmers and their families are emotionally and mentally affected through stress. Many farms are exiting due to low milk prices, at a rate of over two farms per day state-wide.  Raising dairy replacement is the third largest expenditure on the farm in the production of milk, standing just behind feed costs and labor. The US dairy replacement herd continues to increase. In the 50+ years of reporting by USDA National Agriculture Statistics Service, the heifer inventory was the highest in 2016 and the second highest in 2017. With the cost of raising dairy replacement much higher than to purchase a replacement, there are opportunities to help farmer evaluate the opportunities to reduce costs in raising dairy replacements or to evaluate opportunities and risks to cull the heifer herd before a large investment is made.  Farm succession from one generation to the next can be overwhelming for families when added to the daily decisions necessary to run the farm. Farmers make decisions every day to improve their farm business and provide their family with a home and lifestyle they want for them. However, many of them have not planned for the family's and/or farm operation's long-term sustainability regarding farm succession and retirement. Based on USDA numbers, there are about 8,400 farms with operators between the ages of 45 and 64. Unfortunately, only an estimated one-third of these farms have a business succession plan in place. That means of the 8,400 farms, 5,600 farms will need some type of business succession or exit plan over the next few years (Source: J. Kirkpatrick presentation)When it comes to managing a dairy business operation, herd health, animal well-being, and sound financial management can have a substantial impact on profitability. Based on the educational priorities identified in the needs assessment as well as current and emerging issues within the overall dairy industry and community, this agent will conduct outreach for the 2018 programming year through two major program priorities: 1.) Dairy Production & Management and 2.) Farm Business Management. Please see the following Plan of Work for details.

The average age of the Wisconsin farmer is ever increasing. To be frank the land will be changing ownership as the war generation and the senior boomers die off. The millennial generation has shown a strong interest in going into farming. They seem to be attracted to farming because of their environmental awareness, their distrust of the established food infrastructure, the quality of life, and the chance to be their own boss. The situation is that the value of the land has increased many times over since the current lands owning generation got into farming. The cost of living has increased at least to at least four times the value of the cost of living in the 70's. Farm gate prices are relatively the same as they were in 1979. Although production potential has gone up, the level of production from an acre of land or out of a dairy cow has only doubled. Land values have gone up as a response to Baby Boomers buying recreational property to retire to, development and urban sprawl, higher commodity prices from 2010 to 2014, and investors looking to diversify their portfolio. As a whole the generation who is interested in taking up farming as a career tend to have more education than the current land owning generation but in spite of their education they were hit hardest by the great recession. As a result they carry more debt than any other generation before them. This generation is also living under the realization that for the first time since the nineteen thirties their quality of living and lifetime earnings will be lower than the generations who came before. This has put them at a great disadvantage in obtaining the farming lifestyle that they would like to achieve. The reality for them is that to try to outright purchase enough land to have a viable farming enterprise will put them into more debt than they can sustain.

Adult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 9,650 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2018, volunteers reported on average they donated over 58 hours per year. Approximately 72% of Wisconsin 4-H volunteers are female and 28% are male. Nationally, women continue to volunteer at a higher rate than men. (Bureau of Labor Statistics U.S. Department of Labor.) In Wisconsin 4-H, approximately 97% of the volunteers are white. WI 4-H Youth Development volunteers currently do not reflect the demographics of most counties.In 2018, Sawyer County had 21 adult volunteers. The demographics of volunteers were 76.2 % female and 23.8% male with approximately 100% of the volunteers being white. Sawyer County demographics indicates there is a potential audience of volunteers who reflect 22 % Native American racial and ethnic group who are currently not volunteering in 4-H Youth Development.Volunteers play a critical role in the delivery of quality educational programs. In a survey completed January 2015, 4-H Youth Development staff identified Volunteer Development as an area in need of program support. Additionally, a WI 4-H Youth Development Survey was conducted in February 2014 of over 1500 volunteers. Adult volunteers in 4-H indicated relatively low awareness and understanding of some of the educational principles (Essential Elements and the Experiential Learning Process) that are central to the work of 4-H Youth Development. In the 2014 survey, volunteers expressed an interest in learning through not only face-to-face modalities; but also through online-learning such as webinars and podcasts. The 2017 Strategic Plan released by USDA NIFA and National 4-H Council outlines a 4-H Youth Development Vision for 2025. Nationally the following goal has been established "Youth are surrounded with competent, prepared staff and volunteers." This goal includes the following outcomes: "The 4-H program is supported by a well-trained volunteer force." "4-H staff and volunteers engage in meaningful professional development."In addition, there is a responsibility of volunteers to ensure access, equity and opportunity. The National 4-H Strategic goal states "All youth engage in program and opportunities." To that end it has been identified that "4-H volunteers and staff are skilled, knowledgeable and prepared to work with all members of their community." Sawyer County is devoted to offering high quality positive youth development programing to the youth in Sawyer County, these programs are offered with the support of the Sawyer County 4-H volunteers. Historically, in the last 5 years, Sawyer County has had limited critical leaders that have been volunteering for several years, fulfilling most of the volunteering roles and supporting new 4-H volunteers. Sawyer County 4-H program continues to recruit new skilled volunteers to offer learning experiences to Sawyer County youth that were not offered as a leader lead projects in the past. With this historical knowledge and perspective of 4-H and a new eagerness for providing more high quality positive youth development learning experiences, Sawyer County 4-H will need to provide more training opportunities/experiences to the volunteers.

Brown County's 2016 Leading Indicators for Excellence (LIFE) Study identified high rates of obesity, hunger disparities by income, and racial/ethnic inequality and exclusion as top opportunities for county improvement.[1] Community gardens offer the unique opportunity to impact all of these areas and, since 1996, the Brown County UW-Extension Community Gardens Program has provided gardening space to the community that helps to address and alleviate these concerns. Additionally, since its inception, the Community Gardens Program has especially worked to reach low-income and immigrant populations due to the particular health, food security, and community building concerns this population often faces. Brown County statistics indicate a need for both physical and mental health intervention. The County Health Rankings reports a 30% obesity rate in Brown County, with a negative projected trend for the future.[2] The Rankings also lists a physical inactivity rate of 19% and a shortage of mental health care providers in Brown County. Statistics are especially concerning for low-income and ethnic and racial minority populations, whose physical and mental health are frequently below those of higher income and white, non-Hispanic populations. The National Health Interview Survey, for example, reported some diet and exercise-related health problem rates for low-income families as more than twice the population's average.[3] Food security, as well as access to healthy food, is also of concern. The percentage of Brown County community members living in poverty increased from 10.9% for 2008-2012 to 11.7% for 2012-2016.[4] Additionally, the County Health Rankings rates each county's food environment based on food insecurity and healthy food access, and Brown County received a score of 8.4 out of 10, lower than the statewide average of 8.8. [2] Access to healthy food correlates closely to income and food security: A 2014 study of Brown County food pantry users found that 73% of respondents reduced their fruit and vegetable intake because of these items' cost, an increase from 69% in 2009. [3] Food security also varies by race and ethnicity the USDA reports some minority families often have less food security than the national average [5] as well as by gender, as females are more likely to be food insecure than males (in Brown County, 50% vs 34% of respondents to the Brown County Household Food Security Survey [3]).In 2018, over 210 families, 70% of whom self-identified as being of low or moderate income, rented one or more community garden plots at one of the Brown County UW-Extension Community Gardens Program's 10 garden sites. Approximately 40% self-identified as Asian, and 12% as Hispanic. Additionally, 32% were male and 61% female (with the remaining 7% not responding).Each fall, community gardeners are surveyed about the program's impact and any benefits provided. Participants routinely report positive program impacts, including increased fruit and vegetable consumption (90% of respondents [30% survey response rate] in 2018), more physical activity (89%), being more easily able to provide enough food for their families (79%), and meeting more people from cultures and backgrounds different from their own (67%). In addition, 2018 gardeners raised an estimated nearly $325,000 worth of produce, calculated by applying a USDA formula.[6] These outcomes indicate community gardens' effectiveness in reaching its community improvement goals by improving health, food security, community, and inclusiveness. All of these impacts create a healthier, more connected, and more functional society.Lastly, participating gardeners are asked annually to submit their ideal garden size, and each year gardeners request multiple acres of space beyond what the program currently provides. Furthermore, 39% of surveyed Brown County food pantry users reported in 2014 that having access to a gardening space would help them improve food access.[7] This indicates both the value of the current programming and the additional opportunities and expansion needed to fully meet community needs.
