Green Industry (commercial horticulture) professionals in Wisconsin need continuing education to keep up with new developments, current trends and policies in the industry. Many industry members, such as professional arborists, also require continuing education units to meet and retain certification requirements in professional organizations such as the International Society of Arboriculture. UW-Extension programs help serve these needs.

The Microsoft and 4-H Digital Ambassadors partnership empowers youth to help close the broadband internet gap. Currently in the U.S. there are 23.4 million people who lack broadband internet access. Access is only half of the problem; feeling secure and knowledgeable enough to adapt and use the technology is the other half. We will elevate teens as teachers to provide training and communication to assist adults in 80 communities across 13 states. The objective of the training will be to increase the comfort level of adults in the community around technology.

According to the United States Census Bureau in 2017, this demographic data was reported for Sawyer County. It states that Sawyer County has a population of 16,384 (White 77.9%, Black or African American .7%, American Indian and Alaskan Native 17.6%), with a median income of $43,565. Sawyer County Youth are expected to graduate or obtain higher education at a rate of 91.4%. 17.7% of Sawyer County families are living in poverty.There are 3 public schools and 3 private schools in the County. There is an estimated 3,104 youth 3 years and older living in Sawyer County. The United States Census Bureau in 2107 estimated that there were approximately 838 elementary youth, intermediate 712 youth and high school 767 youth. Many of the intermediate and high school youth from Winter, Lac Courte Orielles and Hayward took part in Sawyer County's Dose of Reality survey on risky behaviors specific to alcohol and other drug use in 2018. The youth indicated the following:  Do you think many youth your age drink alcohol? 67% stated Yes How much of a problem do you think drinking and driving is for youth? 50% stated a Big problem Do you think that many youth your age use tobacco products? 57% stated yes  Do you think that there are many youth your age who abuse prescription drugs? 37% stated Yes Do you think youth your age abuse more than on substance such as alcohol, marijuana, and prescription drugs at a time? 41% stated YesThe same youth were also surveyed on what ways would make kids their age stop drinking/using drugs and what types of activities could the community provide to prevent the types of risky teen behavior? hey stated that "if there was something better to do like a sober event", "fun sober activities", "offer more in the community", "fun activities for free", "put on stuff like sports tournaments to keep kids away from drugs" and "having more stuff to do around for kids". The Sawyer County youth voice clearly states they want more Positive Youth Development opportunities in their county. Research indicates that young people who are surrounded by a variety of opportunities for positive encounters engage in less risky behavior and ultimately show evidence of higher rates of successful transitions into adulthood.1PYD programs are one venue to ensure that young people have access to adequate positive opportunities. The available evidence suggests that PYD programs can prevent a variety of risk behaviors among young people and improve social and emotional outcomes.

When considering the importance of science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) education, many reports speak of job opportunities and economic drivers in a global environment. Research strongly suggests that STEM educational initiatives are not just creating scientists and engineers, but producing STEM literate persons in all areas of the workforce. Eighty percent of the fastest growing occupations in the U.S. require STEM adequacy, and science and technology jobs are projected to grow by 20.6 percent through 2020, more than doubling the 10.1 percent overall U.S. labor force's projected growth (Beatty, National Research Council Committee on Highly Successful Schools or Programs for K-12 STEM Education, National Research Council Board on Science Education, & National Research Council Center for Education, 2011). Additionally, in middle-skill jobs (jobs that require more than a high school diploma, but less than a four year degree), over 67% of openings require, at a minimum, proficiency in productivity software such as Microsoft Excel or Microsoft Word and typically other digital literacy skills (Burning Glass Technologies, Captial One, 2015). Overall, it seems clear that middle-skills work has shifted decisively and is now digitally intensive.As a mission mandate, the impacts of STEM educational programming within 4-H have been investigated. Hershberg et al. found that youth in 4-H science programs were nearly two times more likely to participate in science, engineering and computer technology programs during OST (Grades 10 - 12). Additionally, girls who participate in 4-H are two times more likely (Grade 10) and nearly three times more likely (Grade 12) to take part in science programs compared to girls in other OST activities (Hershberg, DeSouza, Warren, Lerner, & Lerner, 2014). Other researchers state that STEM education within 4-H can improve science literacy (Smith, Heck, & Worker, 2012) and build problem solving skills (Daniels et al., 2013).

A committee at the Waukesha County Department of Health and Human Services made up of representatives from the Waukesha County Juvenile Court, Waukesha County Human Services Department, Waukesha County Corporation Counsel, Wisconsin State Public Defenders Office, Waukesha County Bar Association Juvenile Law Section, public defenders, the judge presiding in the Waukesha County Juvenile Court System was looking for alternatives to sanctions for some of their youth offenders. For some youth, the committee felt placing them in a juvenile facility should not be the only option. They contacted me (Ann Wied) to discuss the possibility of having a youth garden as an alternative option. This garden would provide an alternative while also providing cost effective savings for taxpayers. This garden project would allow youth to forego potential sanctions, or placement in a juvenile facility, in favor of participating in the community garden project a minimum of 12, 90-minute sessions. Committee members thought that there would be value in a garden program because it would allow youth to experience healthy, educational activities in a natural environment that would help youth feel just like themselves and find a sense of peace. It would also give youth an opportunity to give back to the community as well. This was important because a significant percent of the youth that would participate in this program suffered from anxiety, social anxiety, or depression .In 2018, this youth garden program completed its third year. Several Waukesha County Health and Human Services Department Social Workers who regularly attended the program with their clients reflected on the program: "The garden served a different purpose for each of my participants from my caseload, and the garden has a wide appeal. I also believe the garden was helpful for me to work and interact side by side with the kids and colleagues." "The youth participants formed connections, worked collectively and found meaning in helping to provide healthy food for the community of Waukesha." "The garden program was a great confidence booster for the youth we serve." "The Garden provided an emotionally supportive environment. The Staff working in the garden were extremely compassionate with the youth. Children were supported to work through their insecurities and feel successful."

Adult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 9,650 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2018, volunteers reported on average they donated over 58 hours per year. Approximately 72% of Wisconsin 4-H volunteers are female and 28% are male. Nationally, women continue to volunteer at a higher rate than men. (Bureau of Labor Statistics U.S. Department of Labor.) In Wisconsin 4-H, approximately 97% of the volunteers are white. WI 4-H Youth Development volunteers currently do not reflect the demographics of most counties.In 2018, Dodge County had 268 adult volunteers. The demographics of volunteers with approximately 99% of the volunteers being whiteVolunteers play a critical role in the delivery of quality educational programs. In a survey completed January 2015, 4-H Youth Development staff identified Volunteer Development as an area in need of program support. Additionally, a WI 4-H Youth Development Survey was conducted in February 2014 of over 1500 volunteers. Adult volunteers in 4-H indicated relatively low awareness and understanding of some of the educational principles (Essential Elements and the Experiential Learning Process) that are central to the work of 4-H Youth Development. In the 2014 survey, volunteers expressed an interest in learning through not only face-to-face modalities; but also through online-learning such as webinars and podcasts. The 2017 Strategic Plan released by USDA NIFA and National 4-H Council outlines a 4-H Youth Development Vision for 2025. Nationally the following goal has been established "Youth are surrounded with competent, prepared staff and volunteers." This goal includes the following outcomes: "The 4-H program is supported by a well-trained volunteer force." "4-H staff and volunteers engage in meaningful professional development."In addition, there is a responsibility of volunteers to ensure access, equity and opportunity. The National 4-H Strategic goal states "All youth engage in program and opportunities." To that end it has been identified that "4-H volunteers and staff are skilled, knowledgeable and prepared to work with all members of their community."

Situation Statement: Demographically, the United States continues to grow more diverse and this demographic trend is even more apparent nationwide with the youth population (Chart 1).Chart 1 (Child Trends, 2016)Wisconsin's racial minority population increased 500 percent between 1970 and 2013 including significant increases in Latino/Hispanic, Black/African American and Asian populations (Gordon, 2016). Similarly, the growing number of foreign-born youth and families provide opportunities for 4-H youth development to grow its membership base and reach new audiences. In 1990, census figures showed the foreign-born population at about 121,500; in 2015, that number had increased to nearly 279,000. This represents an increase of 130% over the 25 year span (Long, Jones, & and Ewald, 2017). These audiences are historically underserved by 4-H Youth Development. Families and individuals may lack familiarity with 4-H (knowledge barrier) or unable to access 4-H programs by traditional means (organizational barrier). 4-H Youth Development can benefit by welcoming youth and volunteers from diverse backgrounds. As an organization, UW-Extension needs diversity in its staff, volunteers and learners to effectively participate in an intercultural and global world.The 4-H Community Club program had 29,912 youth (grades 5K-13) enrolled in 2017. Of those youth enrolled in 4-H Community Clubs, 94.7% identified as White (4-H Youth Development State Office, 2018). Given that Wisconsin's population is 86% White according to Census 2010, it is clear that the community club program does not reflect the state's demographic profile (United States Census Bureau, 2010).In 2017, 10,787 adults had been certified as 4-H Youth Development volunteers of those 97.1% of these adults self-identified as White (4-H Youth Development State Office, 2018).In addition to the 4-H Community Club, 4-H Youth Development in Wisconsin offers programs for youth that include 4-H Afterschool programs, in-school enrichment programs, and group educational experiences at camps, demonstrations, library programs and more. In 2017, 27,392 youth participated in these experiences across the state and 82.3% of these youth were identified as White (4-H Youth Development State Office, 2018). Although gains have been made in delivering educational programs to underserved youth through these types of modalities, more effort must be made to provide racially and ethnically diverse 4-H participants with all the opportunities available through 4-H club programs, including staff support, awards, educational trips and scholarships.In April of 2016, National 4-H launched a new campaign aimed at rebranding 4-H as a strategy to increase the number of ethnically and racially diverse youth participating in the program. National 4-H has set their goal high. By 2025, 4-H wants to add 4 million new members and in so doing double the number of African American and Hispanic youth engaged in the program. This goal is especially pertinent in Wisconsin where the state's youth of color face extreme racial disparity across all measures of well-being and could benefit greatly from quality youth development programs. According to the 2016 KIDS COUNT Data Book, Wisconsin ranked 12th among the 50 states in overall child well-being, but persistent challenges hinder children living in immigrant families and children of color, especially African-American, Latinx and American Indian children (The Annie E. Casey Foundation, 2018; Kids Forward, 2018). Black children and American Indian children in Wisconsin are more than four times as likely to live in poverty as White non-Hispanic children, and Hispanic children are nearly three times as likely as White children (Kids Forward, 2018). In 2015, a 24/7 Wall Street Special Report listed Wisconsin as the worst state in the nation for Black Americans. Authors citied home ownership, unemployment, and incarceration rates as key indicators of extreme racial inequality (Frohlich, Sauter, & Stebbins, 2015). According to a 2002 study conducted at the Institute for Applied Research in Youth Development, Tufts University, researchers discovered that compared to their peers, youth involved in 4-H programs excel in several areas. 4-H Youth are: Four times more likely to make contributions to their communities (Grades 7-12); Two times more likely to be civically active (Grades 8-12);  Two times more likely to make healthier choices (Grade 7); Two times more likely to participate in Science, Engineering and Computer Technology programs during out-of-school time (Grades 10 - 12); and 4-H girls are two times more likely (Grade 10) and nearly three times more likely (Grade 12) to take part in science programs compared to girls in other out-of-school time activities (Tufts University).Adapting what works in 4-H Youth Development programming to the needs of emerging and underserved audiences is a major goal of the Expanding Access Team. We know from recent focus groups conducted with diverse stakeholders that parents are interested in these programs and willing to assist with programming in their communities. In April 2017, 4-H Youth Development was reviewed for Civil Rights Compliance by a team from NIFA-USDA (Hicks, 2017). The review was conducted to determine whether UWEX was complying with the provisions of the U.S. Civil Rights law and USDA's Civil Rights rules and regulations. The team found significant areas of improvement. Serious civil rights concerns include:  the ability to collect participant data inequitable access to participate in activities and opportunities supporting a diverse and inclusive volunteer base the absence of a strategic plan for expanding access the lack of a diverse and demographically representative advisory groupLocally in Waupaca County, the youth population has dropped from 11,450 youth ages 5-19 (Census 2000) to 10,077 youth ages 5-19 (Census 2010) or a 12% decrease. With these figures, the 4-H Community Club program has remained steady in enrollment. For 2019, there are 433 youth enrolled, with 435 enrolled in both 2017 and 2018. Adult volunteers enrolled this year are 211, up slightly from 204 in 2018 and 209 in 2017. Where we acknowledge some efforts need to be focused is on reaching parity in the Community Club program. According to Census 2010, 2.5% of the population of Waupaca County was Hispanic or Latino, this represents an 83.1% increase from Census 2000. Youth membership in 4-H currently includes 1.2% Hispanic or Latino individuals and 1.8% a race other than white. Three years ago, one Hispanic adult volunteer completed the training to become a certified 4-H leader. This volunteer has been an asset to our program with some help in promoting events and translating local brochures into Spanish (as two school districts requested for 4-H Day Camp brochures (up from 1 the year before). It is hoped that efforts will continue to build from here. As will be seen in thisplan of work, one particular school district in Waupaca County, Clintonville,has reached out to partner with UW-Extension and 4-H on some educationalopportunities. Partnerships such as this, or with other districts, can makeyouth and families more aware of the opportunities in 4-H and increaseenrollment and opportunities for all youth. According to the Wisconsin Department of Public Instruction DistrictReport Card for 2017-2018, the Clintonville School District in Waupaca Countyhas the highest percentage of students reported as races other than white, thanany other district in the county. Thewhite student population is 82.1% (decrease from 2016-2017) and theHispanic/Latino student population is recorded as 13.1% (almost 2% more thanlast year). There are also almost  ofthe students recorded as economically disadvantaged. Economic diversity across Waupaca County is veryprevalent and some response steps later in this plan will show efforts tobridge some of the financial burdens for participation.

Dairy farming is a large part of the agriculture economy in Vernon County. In 2017 there were 358 dairy herds totaling 21,000 cows according to the 2017 WI Agriculture Statistics survey. As milk prices continue to be depressed and in 2018 alone DATCP reported Wisconsin lost 691 dairy farms it is important to assist the producers in Vernon County with sustainability, profitability, and/or transition by providing non-biased, research based educational programming.

Pepin & Pierce counties have lost dairy farms at a rate that has resulted in the number of farms cut almost in half in the past 15 years. Research has shown that the lost of family farms in rural areas have had significant effects in depressing rural communities. During this same time, Wisconsin's local foods movement has demonstrated a desire for wholesome, local foods. I contend that the time is ripe for a local dairy movement that revisits Europe's continuing tradition of on-farm processing of milk into products that can be marketed directly by the farmer and result in a economically feasible farm business.

Overall Situation StatementOutagamie County is home to a large population of 180,430 people. The large urban population is mostly centered in the Fox Cities and the surrounding area. The rural areas are close by, just minutes in any direction. We have a thriving agricultural county, whereas in 2016 we had 37,000 cows producing 27,500 pounds of milk per cow. This rates our county in the top 10 milk producing counties in Wisconsin. In 2016, we had a total of 204 herds of dairy cattle, 95% being grade A.Because of this great agriculture base, we have many food processors and agricultural related businesses, which help support our communities, by generating thousands of jobs and millions of dollars of business. Our county residents enjoy the positive impact this has on their household income and local tax revenues. We are diversified in race and ethnicity with residents being 88.6% white, 3.93% Hispanic, 3.19% Asian, 1.57% native, and 1.47% of more than one ethnicity. Spanish is the most common foreign language with 5,489 speakers, followed by a large Hmong population of 3,192 speakers. In 2014, 85.9% of our farms were owned by individuals or families, 7.0% of our farms were owned by family partnerships, 4.9% of our farms were owned by family-owned corporations, and lastly 2.2% of our farms were owned by non-family corporations. Our county is largely family owned farms. The UW-Extension Outagamie County Dairy/Livestock Educator' main programming will focus on dairy, with additional programming reaching out to the needs of the livestock owners. In addition to the species specific programming needs, the general agriculture community will benefit from programming or educational material presented on dairy farm profitability, livestock producer education, and possibly programming on farm stress and farm succession. Along with programming, I reach out to the community, and bring agricultural awareness and education as much as possible. We are at a time in history, whereas most people are 50 years removed from agriculture. To preserve our agriculture lands and lifestyle, I reach out and teach the public about agriculture, answer questions, giving all opportunities to see, touch, smell, and hear everything on a farm. The primary production agriculture focus will be on milk quality, farm modernization or expansion, farms and roads, farm safety, farm profitability and farm succession. I will work with dairy and livestock farms and focus on their specific needs. Sources: United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), National Agricultural Statistics Service (NASS) Data USA: Outagamie County, Wisconsin UW-Extension, 2014 Outagamie County Agriculture: Value & Economic Impact

Document_Name: Volunteer Engagement at the Wehr Nature Center
Segment: Volunteers have always played an integral part of accomplishing Wehr's Mission of "Inspiring current and future generations to explore and value the natural world." Volunteers allow Wehr and its Outreach program to build its capacity to reach this goal. Volunteers are seen as a crucial part of our workforce. Volunteer opportunities are utilized in such a way that they are mutually beneficial to both the Center and the participants. Wehr's current volunteer is made up of approximately 350 regular volunteers and 250 episodic volunteers who contribute over 13,500 hours per year to the Center. These volunteers are engaged in a number of areas: Friends of Wehr Board of Directors (Wehr's non-profit support group)Teaching NaturalistsLand ManagementSpecial EventsAnimal CareOffice Support

Document_Name: Tile Drainage and Soil Health Research
Segment: Water quality is a concern in the agriculture sector. Agricultural nutrient losses are the driver of algal blooms and hypoxia in both fresh and salt water systems. One of the pathways for nutrient loss from agricultural fields is tile drainage. Previous tile drainage water quality studies conducted by Discovery Farms have shown tile drainage to be a source of nitrate loss and a potential source of dissolved phosphorous loss from Wisconsin agricultural fields. Soil health has become a recent focus in agriculture and numerous articles can be found in recent farming publications. NRCS has emphasized the importance of soil health and has built a team of educators, as well as allocated cost share dollars, to helping farmers improve their soil health. The soil health initiative has the potential to improve soil and water quality and make farmers more productive and sustainable. However, there is still much debate about how to measure soil health. There is also a lack of widespread evidence that healthy soils improve water quality. Discovery Farms is currently implementing a study to evaluate tile water quality and soil health. Farmers' financial well-being is affected by the efficiency that they produce their crops and reduced nutrient losses can improve efficiency.

The Green Industry in Wisconsin is strong and growing, providing services and products to the ever expanding urban public. There is an increasing need for continuing education by the green industry professionals, including all ranks of employees within horticultural businesses and government entities. From managers and supervisors to maintenance staff and technicians, all parties need to be kept informed of trends, policies, and procedures in the ever-changing nature of the industry. Green Industry practices improve the environment by conserving resources, reduce chemical applications, save labor costs and improve the safety and health of the employees. Extension has been a leader in providing educational opportunities and advice to green industry professionals for years, and employers count on Extension to assist in providing educational conferences, workshops, and training for employees. Many professional organizations require continuing education units to meet and retain certification requirements, and Extension programs help serve these needs.https://www.bls.gov/oes/current/oes373011.htmTo achieve success in this program:Educators work cooperatively to arrange and host educational sessions for employees in the commercial, public and private sectors of the green industry. This may include landscapers, grounds maintenance technicians, arborists, nurserymen, municipal and government employees, landscape designers and architects. Educators support each other by sharing programs throughout the state, developing partnerships, and creating networks between Extension staff, horticultural businesses, municipalities, government agencies and other institutions of higher learning.

Background information on Juneau County's part in the Central Wisconsin Agriculture Specialization (CWAS), which is a formal agreement with Adams, Green Lake, Marquette, Portage, Waushara, and Wood Counties. The Juneau County educator will mainly be focusing on creating educational programs and services that relate to dairy and crops in Juneau County as well as the six counties listed above. Each of the specialized agents in Adams, Green Lake, Marquette, Portage, Waushara, and Wood Counties have a topic area that they specialize in and create programs and services that go with their particular agriculture education fields: Adams offers agronomy and nutrient management; Green Lake offers commercial horticulture and nutrient management; Marquette offers livestock management; Portage offers vegetable production; Waushara offers farm business management; Wood offers dairy and cranberry production. In the beginning of 2019, the Waushara position was recently filled with a LTE position by the county, but there has been additional requests for time on the Adams, Green Lake, Juneau, Marquette, Portage, and Wood counties agriculture educators to help address local needs.In Juneau and Sauk Counties, on an annual basis, agriculture provides $348.6 billion (19.2% in Juneau Co.) and $865.3 million (13.8% in Sauk Co.) in each county's economic activity and $96.6 million (11.7% in Juneau Co.) and $331 million (10.4% in Sauk Co.) in each county's total income. Agriculture in Juneau County provides for 1,713 jobs (14.1%) of the county's workforce out of the 12,134 jobs as of 2014. In comparison, Sauk County Agriculture provides 5,463 jobs (11.7%) out of 46,653 jobs as of 2014.Note: The Juneau and Sauk Counties Educator has only transitioned to this 50/50 split position between the two county offices in mid-October. During this transition, the Educator has been trying to get to know key agriculture contacts in the counties and trying to get to know the county's needs. Meanwhile, hosting a few key programs this winter for certifications and licenses needed by the farmers.Juneau County's top commodities are grain with $38.3 million in first place and vegetables is number fifth in top commodities with $8.2 million as of 2012. Grain sales account for 62% of market value of products sold by farms in Juneau County. In comparison to Sauk County, where grain sales account for 34% of the market value of products sold by farms. Sauk County's top commodities vary just slightly with grain coming in second with $62.7 million in sales and other crops & hay coming in fifth with $4.7 million in sales. The 2012 Census of Agriculture estimates that there are 374 farms using 19,491 acres in Juneau County and 900 farms handling 53,690 acres in Sauk County for forage uses (hay, haylage, etc.). The next largest grown product in Juneau and Sauk Counties is corn for grain with 339 farms operating 40,373 acres in Juneau County and 720 farms working 80,683 acres in Sauk County. The third largest product grown in Juneau and Sauk Counties is soybeans for beans with 196 farms utilizing 26,355 acres in Juneau County and 466 farms managing 30,025 acres in Sauk County.There has not been a formal needs assessment done in a number of years for either counties and is a goal for the agricultural educator position this year. Having an updated needs assessment will help with programming options in the county and learning more about the interests from the farmers/producers/growers. Also, the 2017 Ag Census should be able to shed more light on the new numbers for the county's agricultural statistics. Before being able to update the needs assessment it has been noted that the agriculture mailing list has not been updated in a number of years. Due to this we are working on updating these lists prior to the needs assessment being mailed out to the counties residents that are involved in agriculture. The Juneau and Sauk Counties Educator is wanting to reach as large and diverse of an audience in the agriculture industry as possible. Without an updated mailing list, it will not be possible to reach the wide array of individuals in the county that should be included and in return may skew the survey results. Another way the educator has been trying to assess the county needs is to look at the questions that are coming into the office this past year and pull out any duplicating interests that could be addressed and potentially be useful to a larger audience in the county.

Situation Statement:Agriculture in Oconto and Marinette Counties:Agriculture is a key contributor to Oconto and Marinette Counties' economy. According to "Oconto County Agriculture: Value and Economic Impact" (Deller, 2014), agriculture provides 4,193 jobs and $126.4 million to the county's income. Dairy is Oconto County's leading agricultural sector. In 2012, 154 dairy farms housing 20,100 dairy cows, contributed $97.3 million to the local economy in on-farm milk production and milk sales. In addition to dairy production; grain, cattle and calves, and vegetable production drive approximately $1.3 billion in economic activity in Oconto County (United States Department of Agriculture National Agriculture Statistics Survey (USDA NASS, 2012)). During the same time period, Marinette County had 66 dairy farms housing 11,800 dairy cows and contributing $55.1 million to the local economy in on-farm milk production and milk sales (USDA NASS, 2012).Oconto and Marinette Counties have a formal specialization agreement allowing the county's agriculture agents to specialize in dairy and livestock (Oconto County) or agronomy and horticulture (Marinette County). The agents collaborate on educational programming where appropriate. The specialization agreement provides farmers, home gardeners, and agribusinesses in both counties specialized technical advice and assistance in solving complex production, management, and environmental challenges.Program Needs Assessment:In spring 2014, I conducted a local needs assessment, distributing surveys to 788 farmers and agribusiness professionals in Oconto and Marinette Counties. One hundred thirty-nine usable surveys were returned (17 percent response rate). Respondents were asked to rate agricultural topics based on individual educational needs (Likert scale, 1=no need to 5=high need). Highest ranked animal health topics included: calf/heifer management (2.74), dairy modernization (2.68), milk quality (2.65), and dairy facilities (2.55). Top farm management educational needs were: farm succession (3.11), financial management (2.88), and use of technology (2.76). The survey results, in addition to my educational background and experience in veterinary medicine, were used to guide and prioritize my educational programming in Oconto and Marinette Counties.Current and Emerging Issues:   Economic Hardship in the Dairy IndustryDairy farms have encountered tight margins over the past few years with low milk prices, low commodity prices, and high input costs. The outlook for dairy farmers is not predicted to change as low milk prices are forecasted throughout 2019. Many factors are driving the market price of milk in the United States: large national dairy herd, declining domestic demand, reduced global exports with imposed tariffs, and a strong dollar. Some dairy farms within the last few years have struggled financially finding themselves a statistic in the market downturn. Farms will be faced either mandated via creditors or voluntarily selling their farm business(es) to meet their outstanding debts. According to the Wisconsin Department of Agriculture, Trade and Consumer Protection, Wisconsin lost 691 farms in 2018, a calendar loss of 7.9%.Farms will continue to monitoring expenses tightly, but will also face emotional and mental stress due to the inability to pay monthly bills. Farm related suicides are double that of veteran suicides. Wisconsin farm families are seeking information to assist in discussing this topic in addition to ways to communicate family budget concerns with their children, and ways to take care of themselves.Farmers will also be exploring job opportunities off the farm to meet family expense needs. These individuals will be seeking opportunities to understand the private sector hiring, creation of resumes, and proper interview techniques. Individuals may be seeking alternative options to add income from their farm businesses such as a value-added product, or utilizing their current resources in other manners.  Dairy Replacements Dairy replacements, or young animals that will ultimately become lactating animals in the herd, are the foundation for genetic progress and improvement of the herd. Raising productive and successful dairy replacements is the second highest expenditure on Wisconsin dairy farms, behind feed costs, when all factors of milk production are considered (Hagedorn et al., 2013). It is estimated to cost $2,377 to raise a single replacement animal from birth to calving (Hagedorn et al., 2013). This cost can increase significantly if young animals are taxed with diarrheal diseases, which can reduce animal growth and productivity, require treatment, and/or lead to death. The USDA National Animal Health Monitoring System estimates 23.9 percent of pre-weaned heifers are treated for diarrheal diseases (NAHMS, 2007), with diarrhea cited as the leading cause of death of dairy heifers of all age groups (NAHMS, 2011).  Animal Well-Being Animal welfare concerns exist regarding painful procedures performed on young dairy animals. In January 2019, People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA) released an undercover video from a Marinette County heifer raiser on their practices of dehorning animals. This video is a vivid example of the need for continued education on the proper technique for pain mitigation in dehorning. Public perception of these procedures has resulted in greater scrutiny of all animal management practices. The average population is three-generations removed from an agrarian lifestyle.  Farm Succession/Transfer According to the 2012 Census of Agriculture, the average age of farmers in Oconto and Marinette Counties was 56.4 and 58.3 years of age, respectively. Currently, there are 129 and 66 dairy farms in Oconto and Marinette Counties, respectively. Across the country, the USDA estimates 70 percent of farmland will change hands in the next 20 years (National Institute of Food and Agriculture, 2017). Therefore, successfully transferring farms to the next generation will be a necessity to ensure the vitality of the agriculture industry. Farm succession is a complex, multi-faceted process, requiring consideration of a variety of topics such as profit margins, land value, farm size, and tax rates. Farm succession is often a laborious process, requiring strategic planning and open communication between all parties.  Alternative Dairy/Livestock: GoatWisconsin is known as "America's Dairyland". It is a widely accepted fact, Wisconsin is the leader in the dairy cow industry; however, Wisconsin is the leader in the nation of milk goat animals according to a United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) National Agriculture Statistics Survey on January 2016. From the January 2016 USDA report, Wisconsin has 44,000 head of milking goats. Most of the milk from these animals is used for making award-winning cheese which appeals to consumers across the nation. Dairy goat herds in northeast Wisconsin continue to grow both in number and size. Goat farmers are looking for educational resources from reliable sources.The Wisconsin dairy industry is a strong economic driver for the state. However, if current economic trajectories persist, farm profit margins will continue to tighten without strong educational interjections to improve production and financial efficiencies. As an educator with University of Wisconsin-Madison Division of Extension, I play a unique and key role to continued farm success by providing relevant, research-based information to decrease farm production costs, decrease costs associated with animal health, and streamline farm inputs, as evidenced by the impacts of my on-farm research, one-on-one farm consultations, and educational programming efforts. I will continue in developing both current and future educational program efforts in animal health and well-being and farm financial health and management to meet the needs of my clientele.My outreach educational programming will focus on the following emphasis areas: 1) animal health and well-being and 2) farm financial health and management. The scope of my educational work in animal health and well-being focuses on calf and heifer management, facilities management, milk and meat quality, and alternative dairy and livestock production. My work in farm financial health and management focuses on farm succession, financial management, and farm efficiencies achieved through farm modernization.

ISSUE: Within the county there exists more than 200 non-profits. With the economic downturn in 2008 the numbers of non-profits have been increasing with the focus on improving the lives of those within the county. Many are organized to take on specific needs within their communities while others are more broad addressing social issues within a region. Yearly, I have provided services to non-profits seeking assistance in enhancing their impact addressing problems, planning for the future. Many people have noticed the lack of volunteers and "leadership" within the communities to provide key positions and resources in human capital. I was approached to explore and design a leadership program as in other 51 locations around the state. Additionally, I have provided educational support to dozens of groups with on-going annual support to the Marinette & Oconto Literacy Council, Inc., and Oconto Tourism Committee and some others. I will provide facilitative techniques and educational materials at monthly meetings.INVOLVEMENT 20% - 25%: In 2017, the County Economic Development Director concluded a needs assessment ($45,000 process) which identified one of four pillars is the development of future leadership. I was asked if I would assist and provide educational, research into design, and facilitative skillsets to the program. We have called our program the Leadership Oconto County (LOC). My county oversight committee has agreed to the collaborative approach and has tentatively authorized me to commit some 20% of my time towards this program. UWEX is expertly equipped at providing the facilitated steps in getting this program off of the ground through its organizational development experience. Initial items to be undertaken such as bylaws, name, board of directors 9 members, assigning a fiduciary, marketing, relationship building, funding/grants have been identified for my work.EQUITY: Most leadership positions within the government are held by males with an average age of 60. Gaining a localized program exposing residents to issues within the county could expand leadership desires in other age groups, racial and gender as well. In the past, I have attempted such a program on a small scale with funding low because this is an economically depressed county. Our plans for this program are to aim high - get organizations and businesses to commit to success of the program by having them have greater "skin in the game". This is a 9 month program for the students, many more for me. It will need an operational budget just over $10,000 and tuition is set at $600 per person. We used the media as well as one-on-one contacts with organizations and businesses to get participants. Leadership training will also have a component on underserved/minority populations within the county. Additionally, Marinette & Oconto Literacy Council continues to serve primarily persons of color and English as a secondary language. Providing services to this underserved audience will likely increase community cohesion. In addition - I am in the early "exploratory" stages of working with the Stockbridge - Munsee Indian Tribe in addressing their strategic Tribal planning steps, and I continue to work with the oconto County Board of Supervisors in defining their Leadership Values and Vision.Priority Project #1 is the Leadership Oconto CountyPriority Project #2 is Non Profit General Support

Fond du Lac County Agriculture & Dairy Industry: "Agriculture works hard for Fond du Lac County every day. Family-owned farms, food processors and agriculture-related businesses generate thousands of jobs and millions of dollars of economic activity while contributing to local income and tax revenues. Fond du Lac County agriculture encompasses a mix of family farms, food processors, equipment manufacturers, retail and service providers. Dairy farms of all sizes dominate the rural landscape, ranging from fewer than 100 cows to more than 8,000.Fond du Lac County agriculture provides 7,790 jobs, or 13.6 percent, of the county's workforce of 57,293. Production jobs include farm owners, managers, and employees. Agricultural service jobs include veterinarians, crop and livestock consultants, feed, fuel and other crop input suppliers, farm machinery dealers, barn builders and agricultural lenders, to name a few. Processing jobs include those employed in food processing and other value-added industries that support food processors. Every job in agriculture generates an additional 0.73 jobs in the county. Agriculture contributes $591 million to county income Fond du Lac County agriculture accounts for $591.3 million, or 13.3 percent, of the county's total income. This includes wages, salaries, benefits and profits of farmers and workers in agriculture-related businesses. Every dollar of agricultural income generates an additional $0.79 of county income. Agriculture pumps $2.2 billion into local economy Fond du Lac County agriculture generates $2.2 billion in economic activity, about 21 percent, of the county's total economic activity. Every dollar of sales from agricultural products generates an additional $0.27 of economic activity in other parts of the county's economy. Here's how agriculture stimulates economic activity:  The direct effect of agriculture equals $1.75 billion and includes the sale of farm products and value-added products.  Purchases of agricultural and food processing inputs, services and equipment add another $316.7 million in economic activity. For example, this includes business-to-business purchases of fuel, seed, fertilizer, feed and farm machinery, as well as veterinary services, crop and livestock consultants and equipment leasing.   This business-to-business activity then generates another $157.3 million in economic activity when people who work in agriculture-related businesses spend their earnings in the local economy"Dairying remains paramount to the success of agriculture in Fond du Lac County. Fond du Lac County's 223 dairy farms (a 14 farm loss from the previous year) house 59,000 dairy cows (rank 3rd in state for cow numbers) which produce 26,300 pounds per milk per cow per year. With a total milk production of 1.55 billion pounds of milk in Fond du Lac County, Fond du Lac County is the leading county in the state for total milk production (Wisconsin Agriculture Statics Service, 2017) and falling in the top 25 US dairy-producing counties. "Dairy is a key Fond du Lac County industry Dairy farming is the major agricultural industry in Fond du Lac County. On-farm production and milk sales account for $239.6 million. Processing milk into dairy products generates another $1.02 billion.  Eleven plants process dairy products in Fond du Lac County.   On-farm milk production accounts for 1,119 jobs, and dairy processing accounts for 2,164 jobs.  At the county level, each dairy cow generates $3,645 in on-farm sales to producers.   At the state level, each dairy cow generates over $34,000 in total sales." Source: S. Deller, 2014 Fond du Lac County Agriculture: Value & Economic Impact2017 Program Needs Assessment: With a hire of both the Dodge County dairy & livestock agent, and the Fond du Lac/Dodge County area crops & soils agent, a joint needs assessment of both counties' farmers and agri-business community was conducted Winter 2016-2017 to identify programming priorities in the areas of dairy and agronomy. The needs assessment was distributed to extension meeting participants, as well as via email with an online survey. Based on the needs assessment (n=100), the following top educational dairy replated priorities were identified:  Nutrition ? Reproduction Animal well-being ? HousingCurrent & Emerging Issues: The dairy industry is a very dynamic industry, with new technologies and practices being developed, managing income and expenses with an ever-changing market, and an aging population.  Dairy farmers faced tight margins for the past couple years with 2019 milk prices predicted to be a better year, but still not good enough to support the farm families. The December Class III milk price was $13.78 per cwt, the second lowest in 2018. This price equates to about $3 to $4 per cwt below the cost of production for the average dairy farmer. With a large national dairy herd, declining domestic demand, reduced exports due to large global outputs of milk, and a strong dollar, prices for commodities such as milk are negatively affected. Lower milk checks means reduced income for the farm to pay expenses related to the farm business, as well as living expenses. Farmers have to watch more carefully on where they spend every dollar. With long-term low milk prices, farmers and their families are emotionally and mentally affected through stress. Many farms are exiting due to low milk prices, at a rate of over two farms per day state-wide.  Raising dairy replacement is the third largest expenditure on the farm in the production of milk, standing just behind feed costs and labor. The US dairy replacement herd continues to increase. In the 50+ years of reporting by USDA National Agriculture Statistics Service, the heifer inventory was the highest in 2016 and the second highest in 2017. With the cost of raising dairy replacement much higher than to purchase a replacement, there are opportunities to help farmer evaluate the opportunities to reduce costs in raising dairy replacements or to evaluate opportunities and risks to cull the heifer herd before a large investment is made.  Farm succession from one generation to the next can be overwhelming for families when added to the daily decisions necessary to run the farm. Farmers make decisions every day to improve their farm business and provide their family with a home and lifestyle they want for them. However, many of them have not planned for the family's and/or farm operation's long-term sustainability regarding farm succession and retirement. Based on USDA numbers, there are about 8,400 farms with operators between the ages of 45 and 64. Unfortunately, only an estimated one-third of these farms have a business succession plan in place. That means of the 8,400 farms, 5,600 farms will need some type of business succession or exit plan over the next few years (Source: J. Kirkpatrick presentation)When it comes to managing a dairy business operation, herd health, animal well-being, and sound financial management can have a substantial impact on profitability. Based on the educational priorities identified in the needs assessment as well as current and emerging issues within the overall dairy industry and community, this agent will conduct outreach for the 2018 programming year through two major program priorities: 1.) Dairy Production & Management and 2.) Farm Business Management. Please see the following Plan of Work for details.

Adult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 9,650 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2018, Lafayette County had adult volunteers. The demographics of volunteers were 71 % female and 29% male with approximately 99% of the volunteers being white. Lafayette County demographics indicates there is a potential audience of volunteers who reflect Hispanic ethnic groups who are currently not volunteering in 4-H Youth Development.

Adult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 10,500 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2018, volunteers reported on average they donated over 58 hours per year. Approximately 72% of Wisconsin 4-H volunteers are female and 28% are male. Nationally, women continue to volunteer at a higher rate than men. (Bureau of Labor Statistics U.S. Department of Labor.) In Wisconsin 4-H, approximately 97% of the volunteers are white. WI 4-H Youth Development volunteers currently do not reflect the demographics of most counties.In 2018, Sheboygan County had 240 adult volunteers. The demographics of volunteers were 76 % female and 24% male with approximately 98% of the volunteers being white. Sheboygan County demographics indicates there is a potential audience of volunteers who reflect Asian and Hispanic racial and ethnic groups who are currently not volunteering in 4-H Youth Development.Volunteers play a critical role in the delivery of quality educational programs. In a survey completed January 2015, 4-H Youth Development staff identified Volunteer Development as an area in need of program support. Additionally, a WI 4-H Youth Development Survey was conducted in February 2014 of over 1500 volunteers. Adult volunteers in 4-H indicated relatively low awareness and understanding of some of the educational principles (Essential Elements and the Experiential Learning Process) that are central to the work of 4-H Youth Development. In the 2014 survey, volunteers expressed an interest in learning through not only face-to-face modalities; but also through online-learning such as webinars and podcasts. The 2017 Strategic Plan released by USDA NIFA and National 4-H Council outlines a 4-H Youth Development Vision for 2025. Nationally the following goal has been established "Youth are surrounded with competent, prepared staff and volunteers." This goal includes the following outcomes: "The 4-H program is supported by a well-trained volunteer force." "4-H staff and volunteers engage in meaningful professional development."In addition, there is a responsibility of volunteers to ensure access, equity and opportunity. The National 4-H Strategic goal states "All youth engage in program and opportunities." To that end it has been identified that "4-H volunteers and staff are skilled, knowledgeable and prepared to work with all members of their community." In Sheboygan County 4-H, there has been some shifts in leadership with knowledgeable volunteers retiring out. With that, some of the programs that they ran are now needing new, informed, and reliable leadership to take over. There are approximately 240 enrolled volunteers in the Sheboygan County 4-H program. Distributing duties so that not all of the work lands on a select few is important. Once volunteers are in place to be part of a committee and/or chairing the committee, it is important that they know their roles and responsibilities in relation to that committee.

Agriculture is critical to the financial viability of Eau Claire County. The Eau Claire County agriculture industry plays a large role in economic impact creating over 7,000 jobs and accounting for $1.12 billion in economic activity. There are approximately 1,300 farms in Eau Claire County with an average size of 155 acres (2012 Census of Agriculture). This agent intends to design programs that will cover the needs of a wide variety of agricultural producers. A sizable amount of time will be spent on local dairy and livestock industry issues. Programs that cover dairy, livestock, crop, soil, farm safety and community awareness educational needs will be highlighted.In 2013 a needs assessment survey of farms in Eau Claire County was conducted and completed by this agent. Heifer Management, Beef Production, Nutrient Management, Forage Quality Management, Farm Transition/Modernization and Promotion of Agricultural Awareness were the topics garnering the highest level of interest. After learning more about the area, this agent believes that many of these concerns are an accurate reflection of today's producers. Using the needs assessment survey results, exiting comments made by previous agriculture agents and personal observations, this agent determined the following areas to focus programming efforts: 1) Dairy Modernization and Management, 2) Forage Crop Management and 3) Strategies for Improved Rural/Urban Agriculture Awareness. Dairy Modernization and Management is an area of interest and concern for dairy producers to remain profitable. In a past needs assessment survey, producers said that the main factor limiting their milk quality and profitability was facilities and cow comfort. Dairy expansion and modernization projects seem to be a way for local producers to improve the profitability of their operations. Whether they are building a completely new operation, retrofitting their current facilities, or making minor additions to their current barn, extension can play a role in these changes. This agent will focus on providing support and education to producers looking to make these changes. The efforts will focus on improving profitability, animal comfort, milk quality, employee training, and improving the way of life for these operations. Forage Crop Management will revolve around the production of quality forage and grains for use on Eau Claire County farms. Eau Claire County has 204,000 acres dedicated to crop production. According to the Wisconsin Ag Statistics Service 17,700 acres are dedicated to alfalfa and other forage production and 48,200 acres are utilized for the production of corn including corn for grain and silage. Of these aforementioned acres, 34,900 acres are utilized for corn silage. Extension has the ability to use scissor clipping and corn silage burn down programming as a platform to help producers make more informed management decisions regarding the feed quality of these crops with the result being improved farm profitability.Eau Claire County dairy numbers (10,000 head) and beef (20,000 head) continue to be relatively static. The county has seen a slight decrease in the number of dairy cows from 2013 to 2017 and a slight increase in the number of beef cow/calves. The county has lost approximately 5,000 acres of agricultural land during the previous decade. Almost all of the loss is due to urban sprawl and development. As indicated, animal numbers are static and the number of farms (farmers) are decreasing. This trend indicates there is a smaller percentage of the population feeling connected to agriculture than ever before in the history of the county. With urban centers moving further into traditionally agricultural areas, issues such as neighbor relations and manure management have become increasingly important. Eau Claire County Land Conservation, Natural Resources Conservation Service (NRCS) and Eau Claire County Farm Bureau have potential to be strong allies in this effort. There are opportunities for both the producers and their non-agriculture neighbors to increase understanding of each other's lifestyles through education and awareness. Chippewa, Dunn and Eau Claire counties are developing/implementing a formal specialization program involving the Agriculture and Horticulture educators in these counties. Based on the needs assessment and focus group results as well as the position description, this educator will be responsible for planning and implementing educational programs and services directly related to Animal Agriculture and Farm Management in the tri-county area.

Oconto County is a vast rural county located in the Northeast region of the state of Wisconsin. According to the current US census, 37,430 people reside in Oconto County, which covers a total area of 1,149 square miles, of which 998 square miles is land and 151 square miles (13%) is water.1 Geologically, Oconto County offers three unique sections; the Nicolet National Forest, Oconto River Valley, and the Historic Bay Shores. The landscape is characterized by thick forests and river valleys, which means that populations are often remote in small townships and farms, 81% of Oconto County residents live in a rural area.2 Many families have lived here for generations and longtime residents pride themselves on taking care of local needs and promoting respectable communities. The town of Oconto, referred to as 'The City on the Bay' is the county seat and largest town in Oconto County with a population of 4,486.1The larger metro areas nearest Oconto County are Marinette 25 miles to the North and Green Bay 35 miles to the South. A large number of residents (44%) commute to these locations or other surrounding counties to secure work.2 The key employers in Oconto County are dairy farmers, tourism and manufacturing (Springside Cheese, ST Paper and Cruisers Yachts). Oconto County has an unemployment rate of 4.6%, which is higher than the state average (4.1%). Additionally, Oconto County residents having obtained some college education is 58%, which also is lower than the state average (68%).3,5Aging Population:Currently there are 7,145 residents over the age of 65 in Oconto County, which makes up 19.3% of the total population.6 Logically, as our aging population increases the aging population movement will continue in Oconto County. To expand further, majority of people in the United States currently retire where they spend their final years of employment.4,7 Older adults lacking strong social networks are more likely to experience declines in cognitive functioning. According to the Wisconsin Department of Administration Demographic Service the projected population of individuals aged 65 years or older in Oconto County will increase to 25% by 2025.5,6 Over 92% of older adults (65 years and older) in Oconto County live out in the community.12 Therefore, family caregivers often play an important role in helping these individuals live independently. The projected growth of the older population in the U.S. will present challenges to policy makers and government programs, such as Medicare and Social Security.8.9 In turn, it will also affect families, businesses, and health care providers. Older adults lacking strong social networks are more likely to experience declines in cognitive functioning.13 More so, with an increasing older adult population in Oconto County, maintaining long-term health and overall well-being will be primary needs for this population.12 Health Influences: Approximately two-thirds of all deaths in Wisconsin are attributed to chronic diseases such as heart disease, cancer, stroke and diabetes.12 According to the County Health Rankings data (2018), Oconto County cancer incidence rate (481 per 100,000) is above the Wisconsin state rate (469 per 100,000).2 Physical inactivity and poor diet have been shown to be correlated with cancer, diabetes, heart disease and stroke.11 In Oconto County, current health behavior data specifies that 25% of adults are not physically active and only 20% of adults report eating the recommended quantities of fruits and vegetables each day.1 Frailty is the leading cause for falls among the older adult population.13Areas of evidence have shown over the years that health outcomes are not just driven by health care or by individual behaviors but also by social, economic, and environmental conditions that include the living conditions of individuals, families and communities.11 Leading health professionals and researchers agree that to advance health and health parity, we must address the social determinants of health, via the conditions where we live, learn, work, play and grow.Data suggest that mental health awareness, excessive alcohol use, and lack of physical activity are education areas needed by Oconto County residents. Gardening has continued to be one of the favorite hobbies of Americans. According to the National Gardening Association in 2014, 35% of all households in America, or 42 million households, are growing food at home or in a community garden, up 17% in five years. UW-Extension and Master Gardener Volunteers provide research based programs and resources needed to support gardening as an enjoyable, satisfying, and environmentally responsible activity. However, still many working adults, parents and senior citizens in the county lack the knowledge and confidence to be successful gardeners.

National studies, like afterschoolalliance.org, indicate that 1 in 5 kids are alone and unsupervised from 3 to 6 p.m. These are the hours when juvenile crime and victimization peak and many parents are still at work.After school programs in general tend to provide great outcomes in improved attitudes and less aggressive behavior, reduced engagement of risky behaviors, reduction of drug use, as well as an increase in physical activity and better diet choices.In La Crosse County, the Great Rivers United Way Compass 2018 reported that due to moderate abuse rates (3.3%) and an increase of out-of-home placements over the last 5 years (8% more), the well-being of our children is suffering. Juvenile arrest rates in La Crosse County are the highest in the region and about twice as high as the state average. Specific to La Crosse County and 4-H, an after school program would focus on providing children a safe, positive environment to explore mastery of certain interests thereby increasing their overall self-confidence, and by offering belonging in a 4-H club thereby increasing their ability to work as a team and build their self-esteem. These qualities are imperative to the well-being of our children.

Document_Name: Protecting Water Quality in Washburn County
Segment: Washburn County has over 900 lakes and numerous streams, including 33 trout streams. It also has two Wild and Scenic rivers, the Namekagon and the Totagatic. When lakes or rivers exceed state standards for water quality they are listed on the 303(d) list as an impaired waterbody. Only seven lakes and one stream in Washburn County are impaired due to high levels of phosphorus. However, land values, tourism economy, and the public health rely on maintaining high water quality. A study in Vilas and Oneida Counties found better water clarity was correlated with higher home values (Kemp et al. 2017). Natural resources are the top draws for tourism in Washburn County as well. Washburn County residents that do not own waterfront also benefit from good water quality through drinking water, quality hunting and fishing opportunities, and recreation opportunities. Water quality was also mentioned frequently in stakeholder conversations in 2018. Washburn County is highly susceptible to groundwater contamination due to the dominance of sandy soils. In Wisconsin 70% of residents and 95% of communities rely on groundwater for their drinking water. Excess nutrients such as nitrates can contaminate the groundwater and cause health problems when consumed. Thus it is important to protect Washburn County's waters from excess nutrients.The sources of excess nutrients are often varied, including waterfront properties and sources further from a waterbody, or upland sources (EPA 2017). Upland sources can be municipal, industrial, or agricultural. Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources (WI DNR) regulates most of the municipal and industrial point sources as well as Concentrated Animal Feeding Operations (CAFOs). Other farms are not regulated in the same way. In some cases, efforts to control nutrient loss are voluntary. Given the narrow profit margins for agriculture, voluntary efforts are often not considered due to the cost and difficulty of adopting alternative methods. A few organizations currently work with farmers to implement some water quality protection, including the Natural Resources Conservation Service branch of the US Department of Agriculture, the Washburn County Land and Water Department, and WI DNR. Current Extension Washburn County Agriculture efforts have not focused on the water quality-farm practice connection. With the breadth of Extension resources and connection to experts, Extension is positioned to help connect the farm and waterfront people for a common goal of protecting water quality. Many organizations are currently working with lakeshore owners to improve shorelines to better protect water quality through a variety of practices. These groups include The Washburn County Land and Water Department, Wisconsin DNR, Washburn County Lakes and Rivers Association, and individual lake associations. These groups have been focused on raising awareness and providing funds for implementation. One key minority group that is often not in the conversation for water quality in Washburn County is the Native American population. Being in the Ceded Territory means that the local tribes (St. Croix band of Ojibwe and Lac Courte Oreilles Band of Ojibwe) have retained their rights to hunt, fish, and gather on the lands and waters of Washburn county. They have a vested interest in maintaining their connection to the natural resources of Washburn county. Kemp, T., S.Zhou, S. Wu. 2017. The Impact of Water Clarity on Home Prices in Vilas and Oneida Counties, Wisconsin. https://vilascountywi.gov/uploads/LandWaterConservation/LWCC/VilasOneida%202.5tab.pdfEPA March 10, 2017. https://www.epa.gov/nutrientpollution/sources-and-solutions
