The World Health Organization (WHO) defines health as a state of complete physical, mental and social well-being and not merely the absence of disease or infirmity. A state of well-being suggests that every individual realizes his or her own potential, can cope with the normal stresses of life, can work productively and fruitfully, and is able to contribute to her or his community. There are four primary factors in communities that influence health either directly or indirectly. The factors form the social and political determinants of health, which include economic environment; social environment; physical environment and services. Determinants of Food and Nutrition Security An international study conducted by FoodSecure, an interdisciplinary research project to explore the future of food and nutrition security, created a framework that analyzed the determinants of food and nutrition security. Highlights from that study include the following: There are three major dimensions of the food and nutrition status--food availability, food access and food utilization. Unfortunately, not much research has examined the causal effect of financial literacy and household financial practices on food security. Financial literacy may be pivotal to understanding the prevalence food security that is restricted by household resources. As reported in Gundersen et al. (2011) and Coleman-Jensen et al (2014), higher levels of food insecurity are associated with households: Having incomes at or below the federal poverty line Headed by single parents, African-American and Hispanic individuals, renters, and less educated individuals. Primary earner's employment is defined by holding multiple jobs, working varied hours, or working a part-time job What is going on in People's Lives?The relationship between socioeconomic determinants of health (the conditions that contribute to health, such as income and education) and health outcomes is one of the most robust and well documented findings in social science (Marmot & Wilkinson, 2006). The social determinants of health demonstrate that not all communities have equal opportunity for health and wellness. The majority of the diversity for the State of Wisconsin is concentrated in the Southeastern region that includes Milwaukee proper. Across our lifecycles, there are multiple times and ways in which we are primed to look around us   for advice, for products, for a hand   before we make a decision that affects us financially. Some of the structural determinants include systems of healthcare, education, and economics. Social networks. The individual has direct contact and can easily be influenced by i.e. family and peers. Living and Working Conditions. Living and working conditions are indicators of health. The major indicators of health include education, employment status, educational attainment, rental occupancy, car ownership; home ownership, median income and female headed-households. Macro-level Conditions and Policies. Macro-level conditions and policies are broad social, economic, cultural, health and environmental conditions and policies at global, national, state and local levels. UW-Extension has a unique role in responding to the needs at the community and state level. We are positioned in countries with direct links to community partners, stakeholders and residents. We have links to University data and research. UW-Extension can better develop and support community-academic research partnerships, translate health interventions for dissemination for community leaders, and directly teach and create policy to better impact community health.According to the United Way ALICE Report for Milwaukee County Demographics: Milwaukee has a population: 956,406 Number of Households: 382,382 Median Household Income: $42,765 (state average: $52,622) Unemployment Rate: 8.5% (state average: 5.3%) Gini Coefficient (zero = equality; one = inequality): 0.48 (state average: 0.44) The Economic Viability Dashboard evaluates community conditions for ALICE in three core areas. Each is an index with a scale of 1 (worst) to 100 (best) Housing Affordability (18 = poor) Job Opportunities (42 = poor) Community Resources (53 = fair) What does it cost to afford the necessities? This bare-minimum budget does not allow for any savings, leaving a household vulnerable to unexpected expenses. Affording only a very modest living in each community, this budget is still significantly more than the Federal Poverty Level of $11,670 for a single adult and $23,850 for a family of four. According to the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, there are several factors that determine well-being: Social and economic environment What surrounds you, your family and community. Personality and Attitudes How you tend to feel, think and act. Behavior What you actually do. Personal financial well-being How satisfied you are with your financial situation. Decision context How a particular decision is presented. Knowledge and Skill What you know, what you know how to do. Available opportunities What options are open to you? Financial Capability LifecycleIt is imperative to have present and future financial goals as it relates to security and freedom of choice. Security is expressed in the present day through the ability to have control over day-to-day and month-to-month finances. It is having the freedom to make choices to enjoy life. Security is expressed in the future by the capacity to absorb financial shock and with the ability to make financial goals that are attainable. These decisions are critical not only for how they affect today's financial capability, but their downstream impacts as well -- how they affect a person's long-term financial well-being. To paint a picture of how financial capability develops, consider three types of lifecycle events:  Universal experiences: things that happen to everyone, like early childhood and middle school Expected or recurring experiences: things that happen for most of us, but at different points in life, like having kids, getting a post-secondary education, paying taxes and finding a place to live The unexpected: things that may or may not happen, but if they do there is a financial impact, like losing a job, getting sick or having to care for aging parentsA Framework for Improving Health Outcome for Children and AdultsRacism and other forms of discrimination; living in poverty; low educational attainment; poor access to public transit; little to no quality, affordable childcare; an incarcerated family member; or the inability to obtain affordable housing in a safe neighborhood are all examples of social conditions that increase stress levels in adults and children. However, because these are not one-time events, but actual living conditions, they lead to chronic stress (also referred to as "toxic stress") (http://astho.org/Health-Equity/Documents/Foundational-Practices-for-Health-Equity/).The predominant understanding of health inequities continues to focus on receipt of health care services and the behavioral choices of individuals. This understanding prevails despite a growing body of research and clear evidence of the influences of systems and structures on population health, all of which describe current and historical landscapes of policies, systems, and environments that create structural inequities and limit opportunities for health. The Commission on Social Determinants of Health (CSDH) of the World Health Organization (WHO) (WHO CSDH) Framework incorporates the social determinants of health and highlights many systemic influences on health and well-being. This framework recognizes that economic, social (including racial and ethnic discrimination), and political conditions are not naturally occurring, but are instead the result of public policy and other community or collective actions. These conditions are rooted in long-term structures and traditions that will require new partnerships and new strategies to change them. The WHO CSDH Framework (see Figure 1) synthesizes relevant evidence and theory in order to examine how health inequities arise and to support the development of effective actions to modify the differential distribution of health. The WHO CSDH Framework is best understood by focusing on the broad domains and how these domains connect to each other to influence health. Moving right to left, the framework describes how health outcomes are impacted by intermediary determinants, structural determinants, and cross-cutting determinants.Varieties of factors contribute to the health of Wisconsin residents. According to the County Health Rankings Model from the University of Wisconsin Population Health Institute, four major health factors shape health. Those factors and relative percent weight on shaping health are health behaviors, 30%; clinical care, 20%; social and economic factors, 40%; and physical environment, 10% (http://www.countyhealthrankings.org/our-approach). Individuals and families need knowledge and skills to make healthy decisions in all of these health factors. They also need community supports and environments, as well as systems and policies to assure that the healthy choice is the easiest choice for them and their families.According to the 2018 Wisconsin County Health Rankings, Milwaukee County ranks 71 out of the 72 Wisconsin counties in the area of health outcomes. Milwaukee County ranks 71 out of 72 counties when looking at all the factors related to health behaviors. (http://www.countyhealthrankings.org/app/wisconsin/...). Health outcomes include factors such as the length and quality of life. Health behaviors include factors such as smoking, obesity, access to food, physical activity and alcohol use.Equity is the key to increasing economic and social opportunity. With a racial equity lens we can identify, understand, make visible, support, and lift up the work of people and communities who understand the fallacy of whiteness as supremacy and lifting up those who lead from an inclusive or community self-determining framework. By initially focusing on racial equity, we can address Milwaukee's most persistent disparities while developing a permanent shift towards fairer practice and institutions that benefit all. The Cooperative Extension National Framework for Health and Wellness provides a clear plan for increasing the number of healthy and safe environments, and healthy choices will increase the number of healthy people. The framework supports a focus on integrating systems, improving health and health insurance literacy, improving chronic disease prevention and management, teaching positive youth development and providing health policy issues education to shape the factors that influence population health. Building peoples' financial capabilities can contribute to financial empowerment, which can result in the well-being of individuals, families and communities. Financial vulnerable families deserve our respect. To practice cultural humility is to maintain a willingness to suspend what you know, or what you think you know, about a person based on generalizations about their culture. Community Health literature suggests cultural humility has three dimensions: lifelong learning & critical self-reflection, recognizing and challenging power imbalances for respectful partnerships and institutional accountability. Individuals in special circumstances often face unique financial challenges that make it difficult for them to use effectively the mainstream personal financial options available to the public. These individuals often face barriers such as limited financial resources, language, low-literacy levels, or a lack of access to technology. It is imperative to utilize the principles of cultural humility when engaging in this work.

Daycare Summer Club: Current Vernon County demographics coincide with large enrollments of K-3 youth in the county's 4-H program. According to US Census data, the median age in Vernon County is approximately 42 years old, which implies that more families are moving into the area with or having young children. While numbers within clubs are growing, (there are 66 Cloverbuds enrolled currently) there are many younger youth, grades K-6, which have not been reached. As these new families increase, day cares are also encountering a strain in both staffing and programming. Through high quality programming and partnership with a large day care, 4-H staff and volunteers can continue to target K-6 youth through a chartered summer 4-H club.

Community members with an interest in agriculture economic development participated in a focus group conducted by this educator in 2011. Attendees of this focus group indicated future educational programming should include: developing niche and alternative markets, including value added processing, forms of direct marketing, and agricultural tourism/entertainment; entrepreneurship & business planning; develop networks and collaborations to promote agriculture economic development. As the non-farm population continues to increase throughout Dunn County, education of modern agricultural practices and assisting those consumers in identifying where people's feed comes from will be increasingly important.Women producing specialty and value-added products are a rapidly growing segment of the agriculture industry across the country and particularly in Western Wisconsin. The background of women principal operators is significantly different from the general population with a higher percentage of beginning farmers and small acreage farms.

Brown County's 2016 Leading Indicators for Excellence (LIFE) Study identified high rates of obesity, hunger disparities by income, and racial/ethnic inequality and exclusion as top opportunities for county improvement.[1] Community gardens offer the unique opportunity to impact all of these areas, and since 1996, the Brown County UW-Extension Community Gardens Program has provided gardening space to the community that helps to address and alleviate these concerns. Additionally, since its inception, the Community Gardens Program has especially worked to reach low-income and immigrant populations due to the particular health, food security, and community building concerns this population often faces. Brown County statistics indicate a need for both physical and mental health intervention. The County Health Rankings reports a 30% obesity rate in Brown County, with a negative projected trend for the future.[2] The Rankings also lists a physical inactivity rate of 19% and a shortage of mental health care providers in Brown County. Statistics are especially concerning for low-income and ethnic and racial minority populations, whose physical and mental health are frequently below those of higher income and white, non-Hispanic populations. The National Health Interview Survey, for example, reported some diet and exercise-related health problem rates for low-income families as more than twice the population's average.[3] Food security, as well as access to healthy food, is also of concern. Feeding America reports a 10.3% food insecurity rate in Brown County[4] and the rate of school-age children eligible for free or reduced lunch in Brown County nearly doubled between 2000 and 2012.[5] Additionally, the County Health Rankings rates each county's food environment, based on food insecurity and healthy food access, and Brown County received a score of 8.4 out of 10, lower than the statewide average of 8.8. Access to healthy food correlates closely to income and food security: A 2014 study of Brown County food pantry users found that 73% of respondents reduced their fruit and vegetable intake because of these items' cost, an increase from 69% in 2009. 3 Food security also varies by race and ethnicity: The USDA reports some minority families often have less food security than the national average. [6]In 2017, 211 families, over 70% of whom self-identified as being of low or moderate income, rented one or more community garden plots at one of the Brown County UW-Extension Community Gardens Program's 10 garden sites. Of responding participants, around 36% self-identified as Asian, and 9% as Hispanic. Each fall, community gardeners are surveyed about the program's impact and any benefits provided. Participants routinely report positive program impacts, including increased fruit and vegetable consumption (88% of respondents [36% response rate] in 2017), more physical activity (92% in 2017), being more easily able to provide enough food for their families (77% in 2017), and meeting more people from cultures and backgrounds different from their own (68% in 2017). In addition, 2017 gardeners raised an estimated nearly $300,000 worth of produce, applying a USDA formula.[7] These outcomes indicate community gardens' effectiveness in reaching its community improvement goals by improving health, food security, community, and inclusiveness. All of these impacts create a healthier, more connected, and more functional society.Lastly, participating gardeners are asked annually to submit their ideal garden size, and each year gardeners request multiple acres of space beyond what the program currently provides. Furthermore, 39% of surveyed Brown County food pantry users reported in 2014 that having access to a gardening space would help them improve food access.[8] This indicates both the value of the current programming and the additional opportunities and expansion needed to fully meet community needs. Kenosha County sits in the southeastern corner of Wisconsin; it is a fairly central location in between Milwaukee, WI and Chicago, IL and considered to be part of the Chicago metropolitan, Chicagoland, area. In the recent and coming years, Kenosha County has seen and will continue to see marked growth of population. The population of Kenosha County was estimated to be 168,521 in 2017[1] and is currently projected to be 200,620 by 2030.[2] It is important to address current health issues within the existing population, as well as think about the coming influx of residents. In 2018, Kenosha County ranked 59 of 72 Wisconsin counties for Health Outcomes (length and quality of life) and 66 of 72 for Health Factors (health behaviors, clinical care, social & economic factors, and physical environment). [3] As the county's population continues to expand, addressing facets to enhance the overall health of our residents is imperative. Kenosha County has fairly defined lines and areas that can be described as 'urban,' 'suburban,' and 'rural.' Understanding these portions of the county exist are important in ensuring all sectors of the population are reached, as lifestyles within these areas have a lot of variance.Well-being is a driving force of a person's ability to cope with and prosper in life. There are many elements which contribute to the overall well-being of an individual, family, and community. Behavioral health of the community can set the stage for residents' success and safety within the area. Kenosha County is in the midst of reframing their Community Health Improvement Plan (CHIP), 'Healthy People Kenosha County' for the coming years of 2020-2025. In late 2018, one of the three identified areas of concern was determined to be mental health. This topic has emerged to be an understood important facet of a strong community. Behavioral health has recently been identified as a program area for the Health & Well-Being Institute, with underscores of mental health (social/emotional well-being) and substance use prevention.Attaining financial well-being is a personal state and is not only defined by measurements. It is having financial security and freedom of choice. Cost of living in Kenosha as it is now and in the future has been a concern for residents living close to or under poverty thresholds. Kenosha County's median prices for homes and rental units continues to climb, as the county population and demand for housing climbs. Standards say only 30% of income should go toward collective housing costs; however, area median rent is $884 and rising. In 2016, Kenosha County had an eviction rate of 3.47%, which was the second highest county rate in the state, only behind neighboring Racine County. [4] Rent burden and general financial security holds people back from being able to plan for emergencies, save money, pay household bills, repair credit, among other things. Food is a necessity of life for everyone. It is the fuel that contributes to the ability to learn, work, and play. Food insecurity is the lack of assured access to enough food for a healthy and active life and is tied to a person's financial security in many ways. According to the UW-Madison Applied Population Lab, Wisconsin Food Security Project, Kenosha County holds an 11.2% rate of food insecurity of its residents, with an 18.6% rate for children specifically.[5] These rates are slightly higher than state rates of 11% and 17% respectively. UW-Extension has a history in working to strengthen food security across the state. The foundation for food security includes: communities that support economic well-being, strong federal food and nutrition programs, adequate access to and availability of safe, healthy, and affordable food, and a strong and accessible emergency/charitable food safety net. Meeting with potential partners and stakeholders in the community has been imperative, as Kenosha County's Extension office did not previously have an equivalent position (formerly Family Living) for a number of years and many did not have a frame of reference for possible programming. Through gathering input from community stakeholders, participating in the Area 22 Developmental Situational Analysis, and input from Kenosha County's Extension Education Committee, initial programming areas have been identified to be social/emotional well-being, financial security, and food security. Adult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 9,650 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2018, volunteers reported on average they donated over 58 hours per year. Approximately 72% of Wisconsin 4-H volunteers are female and 28% are male. Nationally, women continue to volunteer at a higher rate than men. (Bureau of Labor Statistics U.S. Department of Labor.) In Wisconsin 4-H, approximately 97% of the volunteers are white. WI 4-H Youth Development volunteers currently do not reflect the demographics of most counties.In 2018, Burnett County had 35 adult volunteers. The demographics of volunteers mirrors the state's demographics closely with 77% female and 23% male and approximately 97% of the volunteers being white. In 2018, 4-H welcomed our fifth club to Burnett County. This has helped increase the number of volunteers and members. Volunteers play a critical role in the delivery of quality educational programs. In a survey completed January 2015, 4-H Youth Development staff identified Volunteer Development as an area in need of program support. Additionally, a WI 4-H Youth Development Survey was conducted in February 2014 of over 1500 volunteers. Adult volunteers in 4-H indicated relatively low awareness and understanding of some of the educational principles (Essential Elements and the Experiential Learning Process) that are central to the work of 4-H Youth Development. In the 2014 survey, volunteers expressed an interest in learning through not only face-to-face modalities; but also through online-learning such as webinars and podcasts. Burnett County volunteers have told Beth Rank, on multiple occasions, that they have enjoyed participating in annual leader trainings that could be accessed from the comfort of their own homes. In addition to the needs for positive youth development education, many Burnett County 4-H families routinely forget to add the hyphen between the 4 and H in 4-H. According to USDA NIFA, Division of Youth & 4-H document 4-H Name and Emblem User Guide for non-Extension Entities (Revised February 2014), 4-H must always be displayed as numeral "4" separated from a capital "H" with a hyphen (not a dash, slash, or space). It is a violation of the name and emblem to use anything other than a hyphen. Beth Rank has tried to gently remind volunteers when she sees it written or typed. The problem seems to be getting worse instead of better. Youth leadership development programs provide skill development and the opportunity to apply learned leadership skills. University of Illinois Extension (Diaz et al, 2015) has identified six action areas where youth leaders develop competency in 4-H Youth Development: 1) planning, 2) promoting, 3) teaching, 4) mentoring, 5) advocating, and 6) advising. Program examples and outcomes in each of these six areas were highlighted in a 2016 Wisconsin 4-H impact report: https://fyi.uwex.edu/4h/files/2014/06/2016-Wisconsin-4-H-Foundational-Topics-Report.pdf.Thirty-one percent of currently enrolled leaders in Burnett County 4-H are youth. These youth self-select to be listed as a youth leader. Burnett County 4-H members who are in 6th grade or higher are highly encouraged, but not required, to enroll in the Youth Leadership project. Currently there are twenty-two youth enrolled in the Youth Leadership project in Burnett County, of the 22, two members are in 5th grade and can't wait to join the 4-H Junior Leaders group next year. The Jr Leaders group is for youth to learn together as older members. Jr. Leaders aim to expand their leadership role in their club, community, county, and beyond. Beth Rank has been advising this group and providing educational programming since March 2014. Every year new youth have chosen to attend the monthly meetings. The group has grown from 3 youth attending meetings in 2014 to 16 youth attending in 2018. Average attendance during 2017-2018 4-H year was 9 youth. Youth who attend Jr Leaders meetings have shared with Beth a desire to learn new leadership skills and expressed openness to learning a variety of different leadership skills. In 2014, a county-wide Cloverbud Leadership Team was created with four adult 4-H volunteers as leaders. They hosted monthly meetings in Siren. Cloverbuds is a project open only to youth in grades 5K-2nd grade. Over the years older youth who are interested in careers in education or other youth programming have asked to join the Cloverbud Leadership Team. During the 2016-2017 4-H year, almost all of the monthly Cloverbud meetings, now offered in two locations, were taught by youth leaders. Because of the amount of youth leader interest in this project area, there is a need to offer education to youth leaders. Beth Rank has identified a need to continue to expand youth leader knowledge of the Essential Elements of Positive Youth Development (belonging, independence, generosity, and mastery) in the Cloverbud project.Beyond the 4-H program, there may be a need for volunteer development of other non-profit organizations. To my knowledge statistics do not exist of how many non-profit organizations are active in Burnett County. And, regardless of how many there are, do any have unmet needs with regards to program development, bylaw creation, leadership education, etc. that UW-Extension could assist them with? This could be a gap in programming to be filled in future years.

Accurate assessment of nutrient management for crop production and forage quality for animal production has a huge impact on the ability of farms to optimize the economic and environmental impacts of management practices. Soil testing and science based fertilizer recommendations enable the farmers to apply nutrients to maximize crop production while avoiding overapplications of nutrients that threaten the environment. Accurate and appropriately applied forage analysis can help ensure good ration formulation, support the adoption of new crops. Laboratory analysis can be a key part of the optimization our agricultural system.

According to a recent Wisconsin Women's Council report, of the 13,000 elected offices in Wisconsin, women held only 23% of the seats overall and 14% of leadership positions. Only about 23% of city council and 22% of village board members statewide are women.* Systematically encouraging more women to run for office may be part of the solution to identifying the next generation of leaders, electing more diverse governing bodies, and giving voice to citizens otherwise lacking advocates.Wisconsin election laws require election workers complete at least two hours of training every year. While it is the duty of the municipal clerk to ensure election inspectors meet training requirements, there is no official curriculum provided. This leaves County Clerks responsible for developing their own training materials.

Small Animal Committee: Since beginning my position as a 4-H Coordinator for Vernon County in June 2018, I have become aware of several areas within the program that need attention. While 4-H offers projects in a variety of different subject areas, Vernon County is struggling to provide leadership, education, and assistance within county-wide projects. Currently, only the dairy, shooting sports, dog, and horse projects are active. Given the amount of projects that members can sign up for, this is an area that needs attention through the implementation of high quality programming. After reviewing project membership, 243 youth were signed up in the 2017-18 year for the rabbit, poultry, sheep, and goat projects. There was a high breakdown of youth enrolling in either all 4 or a combination of the projects thus providing the possibility to form a small animal committee.

Farm gate prices have been in a slump for 5 years in a row. The slump is affecting farms of all types and sizes. Many farms are questioning the viability of their farming business. Many farms are trying to figure out if they are viable enough to continue into the next generation or stay in business at all. As of 9/30/18 there had been 458 chapter 12 bankruptcy filings for the fiscal year in Wisconsin alone. Farmer's who are able to stay in farming are wondering where to go next. These farms are feeling the stress of finances while trying to make clear decisions about what to do. Many farms have tried to expand by adding more acreage. This has lead to an increase in cash rent prices and greater animosity towards other farmers who are now viewed as competition for the same land. There is a very real fear that the rapid expansion of some farms will accelerate the demise of neighboring farms. The fear and stress often manifests itself as anger and depression.

Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 10,500 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2017, volunteers reported on average they donated over 54 hours per year. Approximately 70% of Wisconsin 4-H volunteers are female and 30% are male. Nationally, women continue to volunteer at a higher rate than men. (Bureau of Labor Statistics U.S. Department of Labor.) In Wisconsin 4-H, approximately 97% of the volunteers are white. WI 4-H Youth Development volunteers currently do not reflect the demographics of most counties.In 2018, Marathon County had 268 adult volunteers. The demographics of volunteers were 76% female and 24% male with approximately 99% of the volunteers being white. Marathon County demographics indicates there is a potential audience of volunteers who reflect Asian, Hispanic, Black and other racial and ethnic groups who are currently not volunteering in 4-H Youth Development.Volunteers play a critical role in the delivery of quality educational programs. In a survey completed January 2015, 4-H Youth Development staff identified Volunteer Development as an area in need of program support. Additionally, a WI 4-H Youth Development Survey was conducted in February 2014 of over 1500 volunteers. Adult volunteers in 4-H indicated relatively low awareness and understanding of some of the educational principles (Essential Elements and the Experiential Learning Process) that are central to the work of 4-H Youth Development. In the 2014 survey, volunteers expressed an interest in learning through not only face-to-face modalities; but also, through online-learning such as webinars and podcasts. The 2017 Strategic Plan released by USDA NIFA and National 4-H Council outlines a 4-H Youth Development Vision for 2025. Nationally the following goal has been established "Youth are surrounded with competent, prepared staff and volunteers." This goal includes the following outcomes: "The 4-H program is supported by a well-trained volunteer force." "4-H staff and volunteers engage in meaningful professional development."In addition, there is a responsibility of volunteers to ensure access, equity and opportunity. The National 4-H Strategic goal states "All youth engage in program and opportunities." To that end it has been identified that "4-H volunteers and staff are skilled, knowledgeable and prepared to work with all members of their community." Few Marathon County volunteers know their roles or scope of opportunities to them as volunteers. Also, the 2013-2017 5-Year Estimate of Marathon County Population by Race and Ethnicity projects 89.1% White alone, 5.7% Asian and 2.7% Hispanic or Latino demographics, provides a target of having our volunteer group reflect the demographics.

Community club leadership is undergoing significant change in Wood County. There are or will be leadership transitions in eight of sixteen (50%) clubs during the 2018-19 club year. The experience level of the incoming general and co-general leaders varies considerably. Current Volunteer in Preparation (VIP) training does not include how to be an effective leader.In the last five years, the Wood County 4-H program has undergone considerable staffing changes. Three (3) FTE positions dedicated to 4-H Youth Development (one educator, one program advisor, and one support staff) have been reduced to about 1.85 (1.0 program coordinator, 0.5 educator, and 0.35 support staff.) Staff are not able to fulfill all of the tasks that they have in the past. Volunteers will be needed to fill the gap, ensuring that the county program maintains a high level of quality, while intentionally reaching out to new audiences.

Agriculture in Chippewa County is vital to the overall county economy. In 2014, it was estimated Chippewa County agriculture contributes $618 million in economic activity and $205 million in total income. Agriculture also provides jobs for 3,387 Chippewa County residents. Over 1700 farms are located in Chippewa County according to the USDA 2012 Census of Agriculture. These farms average 219 acres in size. Horticulture contributes another $1 million in economic activity in the county with fruit crop and other specialty crops leading the way. Major crops grown in Chippewa County include corn (90,000 acres), soybean (50,000 acres, and alfalfa (25,000 acres). With a variety of agriculture and horticulture in Chippewa County, it is my intent to deliver programs in the areas of agronomy, soil and manure management, and horticulture.A Chippewa County Agriculture Needs Assessment Survey in 2015 revealed nutrient management as a top priority. Farmers indicated a need for improved nutrient management and utilization of on-farm nutrient sources in order to reduce input costs and increase profitability. Farmers will continue to seek out information and methods to better manage crop input costs as commodity prices in 2018 are forecasted to remain low and below a profitable range for many farms. Custom manure applicators and dairy and livestock producers remain interested in gaining information about new manure handling technology and safety. Demand for safety training and information has increased in response to recent farm accidents. Safety related to manure gases and manure handling equipment will be addressed through workshops and field meetings.Cover crops are being planted on several farms in Chippewa County as a result of an increased awareness of soil health and erosion benefits. NRCS has provided cost-sharing to farmers to incentivize and implement the practice of using cover crops. With limited cover crop data on Chippewa County soils and climate, the need for applied research to determine best management practices for cover crops and their benefits and challenges is needed. Commodity prices are projected to remain low in 2018 and some farmers are looking to alternative crops to provide additional income. Malting barley, hops, and industrial hemp have all peaked interest as alternative crops. UW-Extension is positioned to help farmers make decisions regarding these crops. Industrial hemp will only be addressed by this agent if approval to participate in the pilot research project from DATCP is secured.Chippewa County is home to 257 dairy farms, 26,000 milking cows, over 350 beef farms, and 4,500 head of beef cattle. The dairy industry remains the number one agricultural industry in Chippewa County and forage production is vitally important to milk production. Dairy and forage producers continue to put high quality forage as a priority for their farms. Alfalfa, hay, and corn silage production are top priorities for dairy and beef producers. The need for sound forage production and input management remains especially important. Forage production components including establishment, fertilization, pest management, and harvest and storage need to be addressed. Horticulture contributes over $1 million in economic activity to Chippewa County. Fruit crops, greenhouses, and fresh market enterprises make up a majority of the industry. Pest management is a major time commitment and production expense for these industries. Industrial hemp was approved for planting in Wisconsin in 2017 and included in the 2018 Farm Bill signed in December 2018. Farmers and land owners interested in planning industrial hemp have little to no local research and data to make decisions to grow the crop. Plans are to collaborate with Extension UW-Madison researchers and DATCP to provide a research location in Chippewa County.Chippewa, Dunn and Eau Claire counties are developing/implementing a formal specialization program involving the Agriculture and Horticulture educators in these counties. Based on the needs assessment and focus group results as well as the position description, this educator will be responsible for planning and implementing educational programs and services directly related to crop, soil, and farm management in the tri-county area.

When considering the importance of science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) education, many reports speak of job opportunities and economic drivers in a global environment. Research strongly suggests that STEM educational initiatives are not just creating scientists and engineers, but producing STEM literate persons in all areas of the workforce. Eighty percent of the fastest growing occupations in the U.S. require STEM adequacy, and science and technology jobs are projected to grow by 20.6 percent through 2020, more than doubling the 10.1 percent overall U.S. labor force's projected growth (Beatty, National Research Council Committee on Highly Successful Schools or Programs for K-12 STEM Education, National Research Council Board on Science Education, & National Research Council Center for Education, 2011). Additionally, in middle-skill jobs (jobs that require more than a high school diploma, but less than a four year degree), over 67% of openings require, at a minimum, proficiency in productivity software such as Microsoft Excel or Microsoft Word and typically other digital literacy skills (Burning Glass Technologies, Captial One, 2015). Overall, it seems clear that middle-skills work has shifted decisively and is now digitally intensive.As a mission mandate, the impacts of STEM educational programming within 4-H have been investigated. Hershberg et al. found that youth in 4-H science programs were nearly two times more likely to participate in science, engineering and computer technology programs during OST (Grades 10 - 12). Additionally, girls who participate in 4-H are two times more likely (Grade 10) and nearly three times more likely (Grade 12) to take part in science programs compared to girls in other OST activities (Hershberg, DeSouza, Warren, Lerner, & Lerner, 2014). Other researchers state that STEM education within 4-H can improve science literacy (Smith, Heck, & Worker, 2012) and build problem solving skills (Daniels et al., 2013).The experiences of racial and ethnic minority students in STEM have become an important element to increasing the scientific and technology workforce in this country. A recent monograph by Museus and colleagues (Museus et al., 2011) provided an in-depth overview of America's changing workforce, and focused on the financial and social benefits of increasing the success rates of students, specifically minority students, in STEM fields. In essence, this work outlined how our technologically-driven economy needs the creativity and manpower that can only be filled by engaging a diverse workforce. Other studies have shown that less than half of the three million students who enter U.S. colleges yearly intending to major in a STEM field persist in STEM until graduation and, furthermore, the exit rate is especially high for the so-called "underrepresented majority," women, racial, and ethnic minorities who are underrepresented in STEM majors but collectively make up 68 percent of college students in the United States (Seymour & Hewitt, 1997). An overwhelming body of research has suggested that underrepresented racial minorities, women, and students of low socioeconomic status persist at lower rates in STEM fields of study than their white, male, and more socioeconomically advantaged counterparts (Bailyn, 2003; Blickenstaff, 2005; Kulis, Sicotte, & Collins, 2002). In addition to the gender and racial disparities in STEM persistence and completion, researchers have highlighted theoretical reasons that students persist in STEM fields of study, such as early exposure to math and science (Adelman, 1999; Kim, Tribal Colleges and Universities Program (U.S.), & Systemic Research Inc., 2006); quality high school curriculum (Elliott, Strenta, Adair, Matier, & Scott, 1996); advanced courses in math and science (Ellington & Prime, 2011); and diverse information on STEM careers (Fadigan & Hammrich, 2004).References:Adelman, C. (1999). Answers in the tool box : academic intensity, attendance patterns, and bachelor's degree attainment. Washington, DC. Education Publications Center, U.S. Dept. of Education.Bailyn, L. (2003). Water quality research and localized field verification of fertility recommendations provide more specificity on nutrient use and conservation topics for farmers to consider as they modernize practices. Extension's ability to provide research, education and demonstration on this topic empowers farmers to collect and analyze their own data and learn from work done on other farms when presented in educational sessions and materials. It is important for farmers to understand and adapt to using improved practices, and the general public is also benefitted by this through improvement of water resources. Rural populations are especially benefitted by this work because of extensive use of groundwater as water supply and surface water for recreation and other water needs. There are no civil rights factors and implications related to this issue, it affects all populations equally.

ISSUE: There are 23 Towns, 2 Villages and 3 Cities within Oconto County. Each has a Plan Commission of 5 to 7 members in addition to their governmental body of 3 to 5 members. Each election period there is roughly a turnover of 1/3 membership. Interviews detailed how not knowing the job duties makes it difficult to perform duties competently and with confidence. I work with County staff in the Planning and Zoning Department and with State Land Use Specialists providing assistance and trainings to these officials. Additionally, all governments have a Comprehensive Land Use & Economic Development Plan which governs local land use decisions and retains local control. ALL within Oconto County will be out of compliance in 16 months as mandated by the State of Wisconsin. These plans need to be routinely reviewed and updated a minimum of once a year, minor updates once 5 years, and a major update with latest Census information once every 10 years. INVOLVEMENT 20%: UWEX is expertly equipped at providing the facilitated Official's Trainings, and has done so for the last decade. I have a Master's Degree in Urban Planning and have co-taught with Center of Land Use Education in the past. Co-leading with Planning Department will ensure a well thought out approach to meeting state mandates regarding adopting land use plans for each municipality.EQUITY: Rural communities have few dollars to spend on large "ticket" mandates such as Land Use planning. Assisting smaller communities identify ways and methods to complete the work themselves will go a long ways in accomplishing the mandate as well as staying affordable. Training local officials on how to conduct themselves and do business will enable them to feel confident in all that they do.Priority Project #1 is the Plan Commission Official TrainingPriority Project #2 is County Wide Planning

Adult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 9,650 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2018, volunteers reported on average they donated over 58 hours per year. Approximately 72% of Wisconsin 4-H volunteers are female and 28% are male. Nationally, women continue to volunteer at a higher rate than men. (Bureau of Labor Statistics U.S. Department of Labor.) In Wisconsin 4-H, approximately 97% of the volunteers are white. WI 4-H Youth Development volunteers currently do not reflect the demographics of most counties.In 2018, Columbia County had 95 adult and 81 youth volunteers. The demographics of volunteers were 75 % female and 25 % male with approximately 99 % of the volunteers being white. Columbia County demographics indicate there is a potential audience of volunteers who reflect Hispanic and Black or African American racial and ethnic groups who are currently not volunteering in 4-H Youth Development.Volunteers play a critical role in the delivery of quality educational programs. In a survey completed January 2015, 4-H Youth Development staff identified Volunteer Development as an area in need of program support. Additionally, a WI 4-H Youth Development Survey was conducted in February 2014 of over 1500 volunteers. Adult volunteers in 4-H indicated relatively low awareness and understanding of some of the educational principles (Essential Elements and the Experiential Learning Process) that are central to the work of 4-H Youth Development. In the 2014 survey, volunteers expressed an interest in learning through not only face-to-face modalities; but also through online-learning such as webinars and podcasts. The 2017 Strategic Plan released by USDA NIFA and National 4-H Council outlines a 4-H Youth Development Vision for 2025. Nationally the following goal has been established "Youth are surrounded with competent, prepared staff and volunteers." This goal includes the following outcomes:? "The 4-H program is supported by a well-trained volunteer force."? "4-H staff and volunteers engage in meaningful professional development."In addition, there is a responsibility of volunteers to ensure access, equity and opportunity. The National 4-H Strategic goal states "All youth engage in program and opportunities." To that end it has been identified that "4-H volunteers and staff are skilled, knowledgeable and prepared to work with all members of their community." Effective August 15, 2018, a new Columbia County staffing model went into effect when a Positive Youth Development Extension Educator position was filled and the 4-H Program Assistant position was removed. In a late 2017 priority planning process, the Columbia County 4-H Leaders Association identified the following four categories as needing attention: acceptance/welcoming of new families; hands-on learning opportunities; speaking skills and other life skills development; and community service opportunities. In addition, new volunteers and families are requesting meaningful training as well as mentoring families.

Wisconsin faces a number of pressing issues that come up swiftly with need for response. Examples of such issues include Foxconn (Kures et al 2018), housing (Deller et al 2018), the labor shortage (Conroy et al 2018; Kures et al 2018), and trade (Deller et al 2018). Our Extension educators and local leaders need to be able to learn about issues quickly and share their knowledge in their communities.

Adult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. The 4-H program aims to deliver a research-based program to help youth develop citizenship, leadership and life skills. The 4-H Youth Development Program researchers have identified key elements and approaches that have proven to be effective, and have designed the structure and curriculum of the program around these elements and approaches. These include the Essential Elements of positive youth development, the Experiential Learning Model, and life skills development. All three elements are key factors in successful positive youth development programs. The Essential Elements of positive youth development programming includes:Belonging - Youth need to know they are cared about by others and feel a sense of connection to others in the group.Independence- Youth need to know that they are able to influence people and events through decision-making and action.Mastery- In order to develop self-confidence youth need to feel and believe they are capable and they must experience success at solving problems and meeting challenges.Generosity- Youth need to feel their lives have meaning and purpose (Kress, 2004).Within each 4-H club, project, and activity, these four elements should be embedded across the learning experience. In 2019, Ozaukee County 4-H will focus on two key areas related to "belonging". These include evaluating the club environment to determine how it can be more welcoming to new members, and incorporating these principals into camp staff training. In addition to the Essential Elements, Experiential Learning is a key approach to life skill development in youth development programs. Within each 4-H project, a supportive adult helps youth experience learning in their chosen project area. Together they use Experiential Learning to pursue a deeper understanding of the subject, and apply what was learned to other life situations. In 4-H clubs and activities, youth work with an adult mentor to develop life skills through participation and leadership in club events and activities.4-H youth programs promote life skill development through use of a five-step Experiential Learning Model. Experiential Learning occurs when youth are involved in a project or activity in which they:look back at their experience criticallydetermine what was useful or important to rememberuse this new information in real life situationsare encouraged to think, work harder and ultimately learn more thoroughly than is possible through just showing or telling (Pfeiffer & Jones, 1983).A statewide survey of 4-H Leaders was conducted in 2014 to evaluate the degree to which the Essential Elements and Experiential Learning Models were being used to help youth develop life skills. In Ozaukee County, 81 of the 285 registered leaders responded to the survey. The results were as follows: Question: Strongly Disagree Disagree Not Sure Agree Strongly Agree Total Responses I can describe the Essential Elements of Positive Youth Development 10 25 19 23 4 81 I can describe how Life Skills are developed through 4-H projects, activities, and events 4 10 11 41 15 81 I can describe how Experiential Learning is used to work with you in projects, activities or events. 7 18 28 20 8 81 It is clear from the results of the survey that Ozaukee County 4-H Volunteers need to be educated about the key elements and approaches that should be used to effectively help youth develop through the 4-H Youth Development Program. Ongoing training of 4-H Leaders is the key to having the program delivered to youth in the way it was intended. All new 4-H Leaders are trained by the 4-H Youth Development Educator when they initially enroll as a leader. The training is good for life and does not need to be repeated. Of the survey respondents, 68% have been a leader for 5 years or more, and 30% have been a leader for 20 years or more. Many of these leaders were trained in 4-H fundamentals before the Essential Elements and Experiential Learning Models were created. On a positive note, the Ozaukee 4-H Leaders were in the top 5% of response rate to the statewide survey. It is clear from the survey results that ongoing training is needed.References:2014 Survey of WI 4-H Volunteers 4-H Youth Development A 2025 Vision - Source 2017 USDA NIFA and National 4-H Council https://nifa.usda.gov/sites/default/files/resources/National%204-H%20Strategic%20Plan%202017.pdf Kress, C. (2004) Essential Elements of 4-H Youth Development. National 4-H Headquarters, CSREES UDSA, Retrieved from www.national4-hheadquarters.gov/library/Essential_Element-Satellite.ppt National 4-H Headquarters at USDA, (2007). Retrieved from www.nationalhheadquarters.gov/about/4h_elements.htm Pfeiffer, J. W., & Jones, J. E., Eds. (1983). Reference guide to handbooks and annuals (revised). San Diego: University Associates Publishers.

Portage County and several of the municipal government units in the area have recently expressed interest in pursuing SolSmart certification. This basically entails updating local provisions planning and permitting to provide greater certainty as to where and how development of solar energy should occur, and to allow for ease of investment and development. Concurrently, several business and community leaders in Plover have expressed interest in emerging financing options available for renewable energy and efficiency projects, possible updates to community plans that may further encourage such investments, and prospects for new housing development that might showcase state-of-the-art design with respect to efficiency. It is estimated that customers located in Plover spend nearly $18 million in a year (2013) on natural gas and electricity. Meanwhile, the 2017 LIFE Report for Portage County indicates that the number of crisis payments via the Wisconsin Home Energy Assistance Program have starkly risen in 2016 and remained quite high in 2016. The report also observe that affordable home energy is a health and safety issue.

The Master Gardener Program (MGP) was created nationally in the early 1970's as a way for an extension educator to serve a broader audiences' need in obtaining answers to their gardening questions. The first records of the MGP training in WI appear in the late 70's/early 80's. Since that time, the program has expanded beyond diagnostic services; today's master gardener volunteer activities include establishing native environments and protecting valuable pollinator areas; participating in beautification projects in communities, parks and business districts to aid in placemaking; partnering with our FoodWIse educators to educate low income families on how to grow food; giving educational public presentations on various gardening topics; planting and maintaining gardens that demonstrate science-based gardening recommendations; and doing horticultural therapy-type programming in conjunction with health care, correctional, educational facilities. County MGP coordinators (educators) recruit community members as volunteers, train individuals to increase their capacity on a topic (horticulture), and leverage volunteer efforts to address our educational priorities.To achieve success in this program, educators:? Recruit and train volunteers to increase their capacity in addressing horticultural related issues on behalf of UWEX. ? Support and engage volunteers and leverage their efforts via volunteer development principles, developing community partnerships, and creating/approving projects to assist UWEX address our educational priorities.
