As Richland County continues to see changes in demographics and funding there has been a primary change to the role of the Agriculture agent in Richland County. The county decided to reduce the position to a half time position. Also with in that same time frame Crawford County had a vacancy in its agriculture position. It was then agreed upon to move to a split position were 50% time was in Richland and 50% time in Crawford. The two counties are very similar with regards to its agricultural community. According to the 2012 Census of Agriculture Data, Richland County has 1,260 farms and Crawford County has 1,105. Both counties showed a trend down from the 2007 census. While the number of farms has been decreasing, the average size has increased. Land used for agricultural production is predomantly used for crop production in both counties, with 45% and 49 % percent of Crawford and Richland County's Ag land devoted to crop production. The census data also shows us that market value of the products sold is increasing on Richland County farms as well. As a County, the market value of agricultural products sold in 2012 was $115,451,000 up 37% from the 2007 Census of Agriculture. Looking at the breakdown, Richland County is still heavily reliant on sales generated by livestock and their products (72% of the agricultural sales). While Crawford County is more balanced with 50% of its agricultural sales coming from Livestock sales. A quick overview of the agricultural sector in Richland County shows us that the top agricultural commodities in Richland County by sales are: Milk, Grain, Cattle & Calves, Fruits/ Tree nuts / Berries, and Vegetables. Top Commodities for Crawford County are: Cattle & Calves, Grains, and Hogs and Pigs. While being focused on livestock production, Richland and Crawford Counties offer very diverse landscape with many very small agricultural operations. Utilizing the farm finical data offered by USDA, 70% of Richland County farms and 68% of Crawford County Farms had less than $25,000 in gross sales (2012). Sales of agricultural products in this range are an indication that these producers are not utilizing agriculture as their primary income, and agriculture as a part of their lifestyle. Lifestyle producers view agriculture as a way to supplement their land base, add extra income or enhance their quality of life. From the increase in the number of calls and office visits; it is evident that basic animal husbandry, market development and environmental resources are needed.

Adult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 9,650 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2018, volunteers reported on average they donated over 58 hours per year. Approximately 72% of Wisconsin 4-H volunteers are female and 28% are male. Nationally, women continue to volunteer at a higher rate than men. (Bureau of Labor Statistics U.S. Department of Labor.) In Wisconsin 4-H, approximately 97% of the volunteers are white. WI 4-H Youth Development volunteers currently do not reflect the demographics of most counties.In 2018, Door County had 56 adult volunteers. The demographics of volunteers were 80% female and 20% male with approximately 98% of the volunteers being white. Door County demographics indicates there is a potential audience of volunteers who reflect additional racial and ethnic groups who are currently not volunteering in 4-H Youth Development.Volunteers play a critical role in the delivery of quality educational programs. In a survey completed January 2015, 4-H Youth Development staff identified Volunteer Development as an area in need of program support. Additionally, a WI 4-H Youth Development Survey was conducted in February 2014 of over 1500 volunteers. Adult volunteers in 4-H indicated relatively low awareness and understanding of some of the educational principles (Essential Elements and the Experiential Learning Process) that are central to the work of 4-H Youth Development. In the 2014 survey, volunteers expressed an interest in learning through not only face-to-face modalities; but also through online-learning such as webinars and podcasts. The 2017 Strategic Plan released by USDA NIFA and National 4-H Council outlines a 4-H Youth Development Vision for 2025. Nationally the following goal has been established "Youth are surrounded with competent, prepared staff and volunteers." This goal includes the following outcomes: "The 4-H program is supported by a well-trained volunteer force." "4-H staff and volunteers engage in meaningful professional development."In addition, there is a responsibility of volunteers to ensure access, equity and opportunity. The National 4-H Strategic goal states "All youth engage in program and opportunities." To that end it has been identified that "4-H volunteers and staff are skilled, knowledgeable and prepared to work with all members of their community." With the generational changes occurring in the volunteer world, the needs and face of volunteers have been shifting. Today's volunteers are no longer the long-term volunteers who are committed solely to one organization. Busy parents and the vast number of volunteer opportunities make recruiting and retaining volunteers more challenging. Training volunteers in this new world also poses challenges. Volunteers are looking for training that is relevant to their role, but also flexible to allow for delivery at a time and place that is convenient for them. A research study from Ouellette et al. (2014) sampled 4-H volunteers in 19 states and found that online instruction was an effective delivery format for introducing information to new volunteer leaders, who appreciated the flexibility and accessibility of the virtual training modules. Another advantage of online instruction modules is that consistent information can be presented to all new and current volunteers on globally important topics, including youth development, teaching and learning, parliamentary procedure, and so forth (Ouellette et al., 2014).By considering flexible training methods, and analyzing new roles for volunteers, 4-H Youth Development can continue to grow and increase the reach of the educational programs.

Washburn county population demographics, as reported by the 2017 American Community Survey (ACS), indicate the following: 94.7% white; 1.6% Hispanic/Latino; 1.4% American Indian/Alaskan Native; 1.2% 2 or more races indicated; 0.6% Asian; 0.5% Black, with a total population count of 15,494. Our comprehensive poverty rate as obtained from the same data source is 12.8%. The 2010 US Census data reports that 20.3% of the population is >65 year old; 58.4% of the population is between the ages of 18-64; and 21.2% are <18 year old. There are 4 public school districts within the county and 1 private school. The public schools reported free & reduced lunch rates in 2017 ranging from 47.26% - 62.88%, according the WI DPI WISHDash online database.The WI Food Security project data from the 2011-15 report indicates that 16.8% of the population lives in the urban areas within the county; 20.71% of our children live in poverty; 22% of the population rents their home and of those renters 41.86% pay >30% of their income for rent. In addition this report notes that 6% of the eligible population does not own a vehicle; 30% of adults are obese and our county ranked 68th (out of 72) in the County Health rankings for health outcomes and 51st (out of 72)for health factors.According to the WI ACE's study with data from 2011-2015 - 20% of the residents of Washburn County have and ACE score of 4 or more; we have on average 61 hospitalizations from opioid use annually, 46% of the county are classified as "asset limited, income constrained, employed (ALICE)". According to the County Health Rankings and Roadmaps organization, a Robert Wood Foundation, "these ALICE households often live paycheck to paycheck; have little or no savings; struggle to make ends meet and easily are bankrupted by a single medical bill". In addition 31% of our children live in single parent households and according to the same organization "adults and children in single-parent households are at risk for adverse health outcomes," including an increased likelihood of mental illness, substance abuse and depression. The ACS report also notes that we have 239 grandparents living with grandchildren under the age of 18 and of those 239, 117 are responsible for their grandchildren in Washburn county.All of the data above clearly paints the picture of the high level of stress faced by many of the families living in Washburn County. In addition to the data above the following information has been obtained from stakeholder conversations:There are limited parent education opportunities available for families - as shared by Health and Human Services, both the Head Start programs in the county, and the Family Resource Center. There are no programs to support individuals struggling with their finances to work towards greater independence - Washburn Christian Outreach & Indianhead Community Action Agency (ICAA).In contrast to other areas of the state we have a methamphetamine, marijuana, and alcohol epidemic which is impacting our jail population, schools, families, and is taxing all of our county resources. - County Jail Administration, Sheriff's Department, Health and Human Services, Spooner, Shell Lake, and Northwood School District.Mental Health resources are extremely limited and individuals requiring services often only seek them when in crisis - transportation issues compound the limited access - Washburn Co. Mental Health Task Force, Health and Human Services DirectorBased on the data and stakeholder conversations it is apparent there are two primary issues facing Washburn County: the need for parent, family and relationship based education as well as financial skills education across the lifespan. UW-Extension has a unique position in this county with broad reaching support for comprehensive programming to support the needs of the county residents. The vast amount of resources coupled with our extensive efforts to avoid duplication of services and our efforts to identify gaps in programming has established credibility and high levels of engagement with a wide variety of stakeholders and partners throughout the county. The remaining sections of this document will highlight the work that has been identified as key components in the larger picture of addressing the needs expressed in the data and conversations.

The demographics of the farmers I program with continues to change. The number of active dairy farms is decreasing, while those remaining are either increasing their herd size or diversifying. Farm stress is elevated in Wisconsin and in Taylor County. Due to the current oversupply of milk, dairy processors have stopped accepting milk from Grade B farms and have discontinued accepting milk from some Grade A farms. Prices paid to farmers for milk, meat, corn and other commodities are flat and below their costs of production. Dairy farmers are either looking to exit or to add other enterprises, including cross- breeding their cattle to beef to capture higher prices for marketing beef feeder calves. Some dairy farms are also considering feeding dairy or dairy- beef cattle for the finished beef market.

Document_Name: Farm Safety - Mental and Physical Health
Segment: Overall Situation StatementOutagamie County is home to a large population of 180,430 people. The large urban population is mostly centered in the Fox Cities and the surrounding area. The rural areas are close by, just minutes in any direction. We have a thriving agricultural county, whereas in 2016 we had 37,000 cows producing 27,500 pounds of milk per cow. This rates our county in the top 10 milk producing counties in Wisconsin. In 2016, we had a total of 204 herds of dairy cattle, 95% being grade A.Because of this great agriculture base, we have many food processors and agricultural related businesses, which help support our communities, by generating thousands of jobs and millions of dollars of business. Our county residents enjoy the positive impact this has on their household income and local tax revenues. We are diversified in race and ethnicity with residents being 88.6% white, 3.93% Hispanic, 3.19% Asian, 1.57% native, and 1.47% of more than one ethnicity. Spanish is the most common foreign language with 5,489 speakers, followed by a large Hmong population of 3,192 speakers. In 2014, 85.9% of our farms were owned by individuals or families, 7.0% of our farms were owned by family partnerships, 4.9% of our farms were owned by family-owned corporations, and lastly 2.2% of our farms were owned by non-family corporations. Our county is largely family owned farms. The UW-Extension Outagamie County Dairy/Livestock Educator' main programming will focus on dairy, with additional programming reaching out to the needs of the livestock owners. In addition to the species specific programming needs, the general agriculture community will benefit from programming or educational material presented on dairy farm profitability, livestock producer education, and possibly programming on farm stress and farm succession. Along with programming, I reach out to the community, and bring agricultural awareness and education as much as possible. We are at a time in history, whereas most people are 50 years removed from agriculture. To preserve our agriculture lands and lifestyle, I reach out and teach the public about agriculture, answer questions, giving all opportunities to see, touch, smell, and hear everything on a farm. The primary production agriculture focus will be on milk quality, farm modernization or expansion, farms and roads, farm safety, farm profitability and farm succession. I will work with dairy and livestock farms and focus on their specific needs. Sources: United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), National Agricultural Statistics Service (NASS)Data USA: Outagamie County, WisconsinUW-Extension, 2014 Outagamie County Agriculture: Value & Economic Impact

Adult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 9,650 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2018, volunteers reported on average they donated over 58 hours per year. Approximately 72% of Wisconsin 4-H volunteers are female and 28% are male. Nationally, women continue to volunteer at a higher rate than men. (Bureau of Labor Statistics U.S. Department of Labor.) In Wisconsin 4-H, approximately 97% of the volunteers are white. WI 4-H Youth Development volunteers currently do not reflect the demographics of most counties.In 2018, Barron County had 180 adult volunteers. The demographics of volunteers were 69 % female and 31% male with approximately 99% of the volunteers being white. Barron County demographics indicates there is a potential audience of volunteers who reflect other racial and ethnic groups who are currently not volunteering in 4-H Youth Development.Volunteers play a critical role in the delivery of quality educational programs. In a survey completed January 2015, 4-H Youth Development staff identified Volunteer Development as an area in need of program support. Additionally, a WI 4-H Youth Development Survey was conducted in February 2014 of over 1500 volunteers. Adult volunteers in 4-H indicated relatively low awareness and understanding of some of the educational principles (Essential Elements and the Experiential Learning Process) that are central to the work of 4-H Youth Development. In the 2014 survey, volunteers expressed an interest in learning through not only face-to-face modalities; but also through online-learning such as webinars and podcasts. The 2017 Strategic Plan released by USDA NIFA and National 4-H Council outlines a 4-H Youth Development Vision for 2025. Nationally the following goal has been established "Youth are surrounded with competent, prepared staff and volunteers." This goal includes the following outcomes: "The 4-H program is supported by a well-trained volunteer force." "4-H staff and volunteers engage in meaningful professional development."In addition, there is a responsibility of volunteers to ensure access, equity and opportunity. The National 4-H Strategic goal states "All youth engage in program and opportunities." To that end it has been identified that "4-H volunteers and staff are skilled, knowledgeable and prepared to work with all members of their community." Youth leadership requires development programs and tools to educate young people to reach their full potential and be successful. Wisconsin 4-H offers programs to aid in this process. In order for this process to be successful, adult volunteers and community members need to work together to sustain these programs in order to help youth grow and learn.Barron County had 208 4-H Adult Volunteers in 2017. This number has dropped in 2018 to 180 adult volunteers. While some of the drop in numbers can be attributed to an increased amount of confusion about the background check process, this information does create an opportunity to engage new volunteers and re-educate the existing long term volunteers. Barron County has always been a volunteer strong county with 4-H programming. Just to name a few, this past year we celebrated 50, 30, and 25 year mile stones with some of our volunteers. Traditional 4-H runs deep with many of our volunteers and families. We can also celebrate new adults volunteering with 145 of the 180 volunteers in 2018 celebrating 1 or 5 year involvement with the 4-H program compared to only 20 volunteers in 2017 celebrating 1 or 5 year involvement. This data shows that new adult volunteers are becoming involved and need to have quality training and engagement to help shape our youth and stay connected with the Wisconsin 4-H Mission. Between community clubs and special interest programs, 486 youth were enrolled in 4-H. Adult volunteers lead training sessions, programs, project activities, and leadership events to support 4-H youth in the Barron County Community. Connecting the dots from the 4-H Adult Leaders to our 4-H Youth is an important role for Wisconsin 4-H to play.To create the strongest youth/adult partnership for our program, it is important that adults are provided with the knowledge, training, and skills to help youth be as successful as possible. In order to meet this goal, thorough communication and education are vital in this process. Finding the best ways to communicate with leaders and ensure that they are provided the best education for the 4-H Youth is imperative.

Document_Name: Fostering Health & Wellness in Waukesha County
Segment: The World Health Organization defines health as "a state of complete physical, mental, and social well-being and not merely the absence of disease or infirmity."1 A multitude of factors influence the health behaviors and environment that affect the health of both the individual and the community at large. The Social Ecological Model will provide the framework for considering the educational programming being provided.2 The Social Ecological Model explains how personal health choices are influenced by factors at multiple levels, and how efforts directed solely at changing a person's behavior may not be effective. All people are exposed to relationships, worksites and institutions, and communities that may or may not support healthy lifestyle choices. When programming provides supportive influences at multiple levels (i.e. personal knowledge/belief systems, interpersonal, organizational, policy), also known as a systems approach, greater success towards more positive health behaviors can be achieved.Located just west of Milwaukee County, Waukesha County is the third largest county, by population, in Wisconsin. Waukesha County has a number of very positive socioeconomic and health indicators. Residents' median household income ($78,689) is the second highest in the state. (It should be noted that minority households have a markedly lower median income: Black households $31,865 & Hispanic households $55,123.) Waukesha County has a high school completion rate of 94%, compared to 88% for the state of Wisconsin. Additionally, 80% of adults ages 25-44 reporting some post-secondary education. Unemployment (3.8%) is lower in Waukesha County than for the State of Wisconsin (4.6%). The poverty rate in Waukesha (4.7%) is also lower than the State (12.0%) poverty rate. Waukesha County has a lower ratio of primary care physicians and dentists per resident than the state as a whole. The vast majority of Waukesha County residents also have some form of health insurance, with only 5% being uninsured, compared to 10% for the state (County Health Rankings and Roadmaps).Waukesha County is also changing rapidly. Between 2000 and 2010 the minority populations approximately doubled in the county. The Hispanic population grew from 9503 residents to 16,123 residents. The Black population increased from 2646 residents to 4914 residents, and the Asian population increased from 5381 residents to 10,721 residents. This increase in minority populations is also highlighted by the decrease in percentage of the white population in the county. In 2000, 95.8% of the county residents were white, whereas in 2010, 93.3% of the population was white (US Census Bureau). Similar to the state and nation, Waukesha County is rapidly aging. In 2010, approximately 1 out of 7 (14.7%) of residents in Waukesha County was age 65 or older (US Census Bureau). It is projected that by 2030, nearly one in four (24.6%) will be age 65 years or older (Applied Population Laboratory). This demographic trend has multiple noteworthy implications related to an aging population base including health issues (particularly chronic disease), social issues (e.g., social isolation), housing, transportation, and long-term care. Of particular concern is the high rate of fall fatalities among residents age 65 and older in Waukesha County. According to data cited by the County Health Rankings and Roadmaps, Waukesha County has a fall fatality rate for older adults (ages 65+) of 165 per 100,000 population, as compared to the State of Wisconsin, which has a fall fatality rate of 123 per 100,000. Only Milwaukee County has more total fall fatalities than Waukesha County, and only six other Wisconsin counties have a higher fall rate. As with the rest of the nation, obesity is a significant health issue among Waukesha County residents. According to recent data from the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) of the CDC, 28% of adult Waukesha County residents are obese.3 While there are no data for Waukesha County, nationally both adults and children with disabilities have higher obesity rates than adults and children without disabilities (CDC, https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/disabilityandhealth/obesity.html). According to the County Health Rankings and Roadmaps, 93% of the population has access to exercise opportunities, but 16% of the adult population reports engaging in no leisure time physical activity. According to statistics from the CDC, non-Hispanic white adults are more likely to meet the 2008 Physical Activity Guidelines than non-Hispanic black adults and Hispanic adults. However, the rate of physical activity even among non-Hispanic whites is still very low, with only 23% meeting the Physical Activity Guidelines nationally. Multiple entities have conducted community needs assessments in the county. The following table lists the date of the most recent needs assessment and the resulting priority areas that each organization is targeting.Organization Year of Report Priority Areas Waukesha County CHIPP (County Health Improvement Plan Process) 2016-2020 2017 Mental health Opioids Nutrition & physical activity Aurora Medical Center Summit (Summit, WI) 2015 Access and coverage, including mental health Chronic disease - hypertension, obesity, diabetes, and alcohol/substance use Cancer prevention and treatment Injury prevention - falls prevention and workforce development Community Action Coalition for South Central Wisconsin 2013 For those living in poverty the needs are: Affordable housing Education/skills training Access to healthcare Transportation to work Food assistance Community Memorial Hospital of the Froedtert & Medical College of Wisconsin (Menomonee Falls, WI) 2015 Access to care and navigation Mental health/alcohol and other drug abuse Chronic disease management ProHealth Care (Waukesha, WI) 2016 Needs of the elderly   Mental health issues including depression, dementia, and Alzheimer's disease   AODA -adverse effects from polypharmacy   Prevalence of chronic conditions   Accidental injury   Social vulnerability and isolation   Obesity   Access issues including scarcity of providers specializing in gerontology AODA issues   Binge drinking   Prescription drug overdose/misuse   Heroin and opioid deaths/hospitalizations   Access including scarcity of providers Mental health   Suicide rate   Alzheimer's disease   Depression   Access including scarcity of providers Center for Urban Population Health (located in Milwaukee, but prepared for Waukesha County from funding from Aurora Health Care, Children's Hospital of Wisconsin, Columbia St Mary's, Froedtert Health, ProHealth Care, & Wheaton Franciscan Health) 2015 Mental Health Alcohol & Drugs Chronic Disease Access to Health Care Physical Activity Education Financial Stability Individuals feel better about themselves, have fewer health issues, and have greater ability to handle life's challenges when they are physically active and eating well. Developing the capacity to purposefully and mindfully manage life's stressful situations has been shown to positively affect an individual's mental/emotional and physical health. Additionally, the senior population in the county continues to increase, mirroring the booming senior population nationwide. Educational programming in the area of health and wellness, with an emphasis on supporting the aging population's health and quality of life, will complement other initiatives in the county that are working to produce a healthier, more resilient population with fewer health, mental health, and AODA issues. 1 Constitution of the World Health Organization. Rock County 4-H volunteers are essential to the success of our county's 4-H program. More than 330 4-H volunteers partner with 4-H youth to lead, teach, involve, mentor and guide clubs, projects, activities and serve as officers in the county's adult leaders' chartered organization. The vision that today's 4-H volunteers embrace will provide 4-H members the opportunity to build skills, confidence, empathy, independence and relationships with others in 4-H and our worldwide community. 4-H members model 4-H volunteers' actions; therefore, it's imperative that all 4-H volunteers have the opportunity to engage in professional educational development to enable them to help provide the best education opportunities for the youth involved in Rock Co. 4-H. Currently, many 4-H club volunteers struggle with meeting deadlines as well as completing required paperwork to apply for 4-H Club Charters. Project leaders at the club and county levels don't know what the expectations are for their roles. Leadership in the county's adult leaders' organization continues to be a top-down model instead of partnering with youth and local clubs. Therefore, all aspects of 4-H volunteer leader roles and education are a top priority for me to provide educational opportunities for Rock Co. 4-H volunteers.

The second priority area focuses on strengthening communities and families, with a focus on both one-time interventions (e.g. workshops and classes) as well as collaboration with family-serving agencies in the county for greater impact.Parenting classes will be important to support parents and caregivers' ability to understand child development and to face stressors such as poverty and single parenthood need support to cope. Parental stress has been linked to negative child outcomes, including child abuse. Last year, Waupaca County had 50 cases of child abuse, a prevalence rate of 4.3%. Child abuse affects the physical and mental health of a child and has long-term detrimental outcomes. Parent-child relationships are important to address. Curriculum such as Raising a Thinking Child, Strengthening Families and other family/relationship workshops are a common response to community needs in Extension work. Thus, the target audience will primarily be parents and caregivers with limited resources.Addressing well-being means taking into consideration factors influencing families in a larger context, including greater collaboration with other program areas and the community. The FLE has strong relationships with stakeholders through coalition work. She will continue to network and collaborate with area coalitions such as Mission of Hope-Waupaca and the Suicide Prevention Coalition to share resources, offer evidence-based information and the perspective of an Extension educator. Finally, another new relatively new program that has been a significant portion of Liang's work is Building Bridges across Communities, an initiative to build leadership in the growing Latino/Hispanic families in Waupaca County. Waupaca County's Latino/Hispanic population has grown significantly over the past decade, and is estimated to be around 3% (US Census, 2010). In the past year, the county office decided to make a concerted effort to build trust with the Latino/Hispanic community. Project "Building Bridges across Communities" seeks to build trust between UW-Extension, non-profits, and underserved audiences through cross-cultural family-centered programming.

In recent years there has been a resurgent cultural interest in learning how to cook and an increasing number of community-based food preparation (cooking) classes occurring across the country. Cooking meals in the home is associated with healthier dietary choices, such as increased fruit, vegetable, and whole grain consumption, than meals consumed outside of the home.1,2 This is especially relevant for individuals with limited incomes as they are more likely to have poor diet quality, and poor diet quality is a risk factor for obesity and other adverse health outcomes.3 Numerous cooking skills programs target children and parents with limited incomes and research indicates that these programs increase confidence in cooking, improve fruit and vegetable consumption, and improve vegetable variety and home availability of vegetables.4,5 While many programs target parents and/or children independently, the combination of parents and children learning and preparing meals together may further enhance cooking self-efficacy and diet quality for both children and parents.6 In addition to short- and medium-term positive outcomes, there is evidence that adequate cooking skills in adolescence predicts long-term indicators of nutrition, such as preparing meals in the home, frequent family meals, greater vegetable consumption, and lower fast food consumption.7In response to this research and increased interest from FoodWIse colleagues, FoodWIse state specialists Betsy Kelley, Gayle Coleman, and Emily Latham developed and delivered a hands-on food preparation training to all FoodWIse Coordinators and Educators in the summer of 2017. The overall goal of the training was to provide all FoodWIse staff with a baseline knowledge of food preparation and to equip them with the skills to facilitate food preparation activities as part of direct education. In FY18, food preparation activities were limited to youth in grades 6-12, utilizing the curriculum Teen Cuisine, and to parents and caregivers of young children. Over 700 FoodWIse participants were engaged in hands-on food preparation lessons and over 500 participants were reached using Teen Cuisine. A revised and updated version of Teen Cuisine was made available in the fall of 2018 and statewide funding was provided for every educator to purchase cooking equipment, thus an increase in the number of participants engaged in hands-on food preparation is expected in FY19.FoodWIse state specialists acknowledge the need to continue to support and expand efforts to reach new audiences with hands-on food preparation activities. Specifically, engaging elementary age children and families in experiential nutrition education that includes cooking. References:1. Mclaughlin C, Tarasuk V, Kreiger N. An examination of at-home food preparation activity among low-income, food-insecure women. J Am Diet Assoc. 2003;103(11):1506-1512.2. Lachat C, Nago E, Verstraeten R, et al. Impacts of a vegetable cooking skills program among low-income parents and children. J Nutr Educ Behav. 2018;50:795-802.6. Jarpe-Ratner E, Folkens S, Sharma S, et al. An experiential cooking and nutrition education program increases cooking self-efficacy and vegetable consumption in children in grades 3-8. J Nutr Educ Behav. 2016;48:697-705.7. Utter J, Larson N, Laska MN, et al. Self-perceived cooking skills in emerging adulthood predict better dietary behaviors and intake 10 years later: a longitudinal study. J Nutr Educ Behav. 2018;50(5):494-500.

The national Master Gardener Program (MGP) was created in the early 1970's as a way for an Extension educator to serve broader audiences' needs in obtaining answers to their gardening questions. The first records of MGP training in WI date back to the late 1970's/early 80's. Since that time, the program has expanded beyond diagnostic services; today's volunteer activities also include establishing native environments and protecting pollinator resources; creating beautification/green space projects in communities, parks, schools and business districts to aid in placemaking and create outdoor classrooms that demonstrate science-based gardening recommendations; partnering with FoodWIse educators to educate low income families on how to grow food; giving public educational presentations on various gardening topics; and doing horticultural therapy-type programming in conjunction with health care, correctional, educational and homeless/low income housing facilities. I recruit community members in Dane County as volunteers, train individuals to increase their capacity regarding horticultural topics and techniques, and leverage volunteer efforts to address Extension's educational priorities.

Access to "adequate, appropriate, and safe foods and nutrition" means the regular and sufficient consumption of nutritious foods across the life span. Common health concerns related to food and nutrition include food security (hunger), overweight/obesity rates, and food safety.According to the most recent United Way L.I.F.E. (Leading Indicators for Excellence, 2018) findings, nearly 8% of Fond du Lac residents experience poverty. The American Community Survey (2013-2017) report an 8.5% poverty rate. This number is higher for children, at 11% (ACS, 2017.) The Wisconsin Food Security Project (2018) has a predicted food security rate for Fond du Lac County of 10% for the total population and 16% for children. The most recent community health assessment found that 6% of surveyed adults reported hunger in the past year. Fifteen percent of Fond du Lac residents participate in FoodShare and 41% of the student population are eligible for the free/reduced lunch program. There is a growing body of evidence proving the connection between food insecurity and obesity. The Food and Research Action Center (2015) explains the "coexistence of food insecurity and obesity is expected given that both are consequences of economic and social disadvantage." While all segments of the population are affected by obesity, low-income individuals are especially prone to the health effects associated with lack of healthy foods. According to the L.I.F.E. report, Fond du Lac County experienced a significant increase from 2010 to 2015 when looking at low income and low access to supermarkets. Equitable access to healthy foods is an even bigger concern in Fond du Lac County than in the past.

The City of La Crosse, a frequent partner with the La Crosse County CRD educator, has requested assistance from Extension-La Crosse County to assist in the development of a series of data sets to help influence the 2020 comprehensive plan. Historically, the City hired a consultant for this work. However, many data sets developed by the CRD educator have influenced City of La Crosse policy on issues such as rental registration and single family occupancy in neighborhoods.

This area of emphasis focuses on youth cultivating the habits and skills necessary for political participation in a democratic society and taking individual and collective action to identify and address issues of public concern.4-H Youth Development prioritizes learning by doing to maximize positive youth development outcomes. Successful strategies include: building youth/adult partnership practices into community decision-making, whether within the 4-H organization or in other community settings, from community coalitions to organizational boards and committees. Resources to inform these practices can be found at https://fyi.uwex.edu/youthadultpartnership/ facilitating action planning processes, by which youth can address community issues, either in youth-led spaces with adult coaching or in partnerships with adults working on the same issues. Resources for action planning have been developed for the Tech Changemakers program (https://fyi.uwex.edu/wi4hcitizenship/research-resources/) and the FoodWIse/4-H Youth Development Youth Action for Community Health project) creating opportunities for youth input and decision-making including Teen Courts where youth enact restorative justice, opportunities for youth to serve as advisors on local government boards (Youth in Governance), etc. where they can build relationships with and inform adult decision-makers, youth input into community development through participation in planning process, etc. These opportunities help youth to build understanding of community issues and their civic roles.Youth who participate in these types of opportunities develop habits that make civic participation as adults much more likely. In Wisconsin, we have also seen evidence that youth develop an appreciation for the communities where they live and develop supportive relationships with community adults. Outcomes for communities of youth civic engagement include greater economic and social development that includes young people in all aspects of community life. Key practices developed by the Engaging Young People to Sustain Communities include empowering more diverse community leadership, increasing social capital, and strengthening sense of community and sense of place (see, for example, https://blogs.ces.uwex.edu/engaging-youth/files/2015/02/EYP-White-Paper-February-2015.pdf). These outcomes are particularly important for groups that are marginalized from community leadership due to race, class, or other characteristics.In the most recent Youth Risk Behavior Survey, 62.7% of youth strongly agree or agree that they feel like they belong at their school. 72.1% of students who reported having at least one teacher or other adult in their school that they can talk to if they had a problem. In the most recent general election, Marathon County had 85% of registered voters vote. (Marathon County). 62% of the voting age population voted. In the recent Marathon County LIFE Report, 55% of respondents said they were satisfied or very satisfied with how welcoming the community is. Also, only 3.7% of the 2017 LIFE Survey respondents stated that civic engagement created a sense of connectedness to community.

Recent research indicates that the prevalence of childhood obesity is not declining as some reports previously suggested.1 In fact, there has been a significant increase in severe obesity among children ages 2-5 years old.1 Additionally, the prevalence of obesity among African American children and Hispanic children is significantly higher than that of White children.1 Diet quality also remains a concern for children, particularly those under the age of 12 years. While fruit intake increased over the past five years, children are not eating vegetables as frequently.2 For children from low-income households, both fruit and vegetable consumption decreased over the past five years.2 It is important that children ages 2-11 achieve a healthy weight by developing healthy eating habits and engaging in physical activity.3 Encouraging children to accept and consume new foods can take as many as 10 repeated exposures.4In addition, 61% of young children ages 3-6 years old who are not yet in kindergarten are in center-based care arrangements (2012).5 The high percentage of children in early care and education (ECE) settings presents an opportunity to influence healthy eating and physical activity behaviors. In fact, ECE settings are proven to be effective settings for obesity prevention interventions.6 Specifically, research illustrates that nutrition education programs, such as Color Me Healthy, increase fruit and vegetable consumption among children ages 4-5 years old.7 Additionally, the Nutrition and Physical Activity Self-Assessment for Child Care (NAPSACC) is a policy, systems, and environmental change intervention aimed at improving the nutrition and physical activity environments of child care centers and is associated with a reduction in children's body mass index.8Historically, reaching children under the age of five years with direct education in ECE settings was not a focus for FoodWIse. However, in Fiscal Year 2018, 7.8% of FoodWIse's total participants were under the age of five years. This percentage is much higher than would be expected given our program delivery models. Education with this audience is occurring in ECE settings (32%) and in schools (62%), possibly through 4K programs. Additionally, education with children under the age of five is reaching a much higher percentage of Black/African American (FY17: 15.76%) and Hispanic (FY17: 21.07%) children than is represented statewide by the Wisconsin Demographic Data from the U.S. Census (6.6% and 6.7% respectively). FoodWIse is uniquely situated to reach diverse children from low-income households with nutrition education and policy, systems, and environmental change projects to increase acceptance and consumption of healthy foods and to improve the food and physical activity environment in ECE settings. In early 2018, a short needs assessment was sent out to 48 individuals consisting of dairy farmers, beef farmers, vegetable and fruit producers, government agencies, and private agriculture industry. Ten replies were returned. Although the response rate was low two themes of land conservation practices and pasture management practices emerged from the needs assessment.In the 2007 USDA Census of Agriculture, 22% of the farms in Langlade and 18% of the farms in Lincoln reported using some sort of conservation practice. Presently farmers are becoming more aware of the need for soil conservation as concern from the general community grows regarding non-point pollution sources of nutrients to public waters. With the short growing season and the unpredictability of fall weather, further examination of which cover crop, timing of planting, and method of planting needs to be completed in order to make recommendations that fit within the area's growing season and cropping rotations. To aid in this I am currently assisting AgSource Cooperative with their cover crop research trials at the Langlade County Research Station and presented at the annual Antigo Flats Producer Group meeting in 2017 and 2018. I am also working with the University of Wisconsin Nutrient and Pest Management Program to develop studies to further examine which cover crops fit the growing season and rotation and if there are other uses for the covers such as forage. Additionally, teaching farmers to use nutrient management plans, specifically SNAP Plus computer software, to assist them in making decisions on crop rotations and tillage practices are best used to reduce soil erosion and nutrient runoff. According the USDA Census of Agriculture, from 2007 to 2012 the percentage of cropland acres receiving fertilizer increased 3% in Lincoln County and 7% in Langlade County. During the same time period, Lincoln County had a 16% increase in the number of acres receiving manure and Langlade County a 22% increase in acres with a manure application. The Wisconsin Department of Agriculture, Trade, and Consumer Protection reported in 2012, Lincoln County had 9% or 3442 of cropland acres and Langlade County has 45% or 32,891 cropland acres in a nutrient management plan. As of 2018, the percent of cropland acres has increased to 18% in Lincoln County and 70% in Langlade County. To continue the growth in acres I partnered with the Langlade County Conservation Department in 2018 to nutrient management planning workshops. During the workshops I presented on concepts of nutrient management planning and worked one on one with producers to assist them in writing and submitting a finished nutrient management plan. Further programming in nutrient management planning needs to continue to serve as a tool for farmers to use as they plan their tillage and fertilizing strategies for the next growing season.Although many may not think of grazing as a conservation practice, in an October 2015 eXtension article titled "Pasture Management for Small Farms" it stated that "manure ultimately will either be incorporated into the pasture soil or if the pasture is poorly vegetated it may be a runoff risk." One method a producer may use to promote vegetation to prevent runoff is to implement a managed grazing system. Managed grazing moves the animals through paddocks to allow the forage grasses and legumes time to rest and restore energy which in turn improves forage quality and persistence. The USDA Census of Agriculture reported that from 2007 to 2012 permanent pasture acres increased 6% in Lincoln County with 7196 acres and Langlade County with 6528 acres. During that time period Lincoln County reported a decrease from 112 to 88 farms using a managed grazing system. Langlade County also reported a decrease from 70 to 38 of farms using a managed grazing system. Langlade County reported to the USDA Wisconsin National Agriculture Statistics Service an increase of 15% cattle and calves from 17,000 to 19,900 and a 5% increase of dairy cattle from 7500 to 7700 from 2012 to 2018. In that same time period Lincoln County a decrease in dairy cattle but a 3% increase in cattle and calves from 11,800 to 12,100. As cattle numbers continue to increase programming on pasture management will need to be developed to assist these producers in producing high quality forages that will utilize the nutrients supplied through manure deposited and supplemental fertilizer applications. In 2018, I collaboration with the Langlade County Conservation Department and the USDA Lincoln and Langlade Counties Natural Resources Conservation Office to develop and host pasture walks throughout the growing season. I lead the discussion proper soil testing methods for pasture systems, methods on how to measure pasture yield, and manure management while winter feeding cattle using round bales.

Kenosha County sits in the southeastern corner of Wisconsin; it is a fairly central location in between Milwaukee, WI and Chicago, IL and considered to be part of the Chicago metropolitan, Chicagoland, area. In the recent and coming years, Kenosha County has seen and will continue to see marked growth of population. The population of Kenosha County was estimated to be 168,521 in 2017[1] and is currently projected to be 200,620 by 2030.[2] It is important to address current health issues within the existing population, as well as think about the coming influx of residents. In 2018, Kenosha County ranked 59 of 72 Wisconsin counties for Health Outcomes (length and quality of life) and 66 of 72 for Health Factors (health behaviors, clinical care, social & economic factors, and physical environment). [3] As the county's population continues to expand, addressing facets to enhance the overall health of our residents is imperative. Kenosha County has fairly defined lines and areas that can be described as 'urban,' 'suburban,' and 'rural.' Understanding these portions of the county exist are important in ensuring all sectors of the population are reached, as lifestyles within these areas have a lot of variance.Well-being is a driving force of a person's ability to cope with and prosper in life. There are many elements which contribute to the overall well-being of an individual, family, and community. Behavioral health of the community can set the stage for residents' success and safety within the area. Kenosha County is in the midst of reframing their Community Health Improvement Plan (CHIP), 'Healthy People Kenosha County' for the coming years of 2020-2025. In late 2018, one of the three identified areas of concern was determined to be mental health. This topic has emerged to be an understood important facet of a strong community. Behavioral health has recently been identified as a program area for the Health & Well-Being Institute, with underscores of mental health (social/emotional well-being) and substance use prevention.Attaining financial well-being is a personal state and is not only defined by measurements. It is having financial security and freedom of choice. Cost of living in Kenosha as it is now and in the future has been a concern for residents living close to or under poverty thresholds. Kenosha County's median prices for homes and rental units continues to climb, as the county population and demand for housing climbs. Standards say only 30% of income should go toward collective housing costs; however, area median rent is $884 and rising. In 2016, Kenosha County had an eviction rate of 3.47%, which was the second highest county rate in the state, only behind neighboring Racine County. [4] Rent burden and general financial security holds people back from being able to plan for emergencies, save money, pay household bills, repair credit, among other things. Food is a necessity of life for everyone. It is the fuel that contributes to the ability to learn, work, and play. Food insecurity is the lack of assured access to enough food for a healthy and active life and is tied to a person's financial security in many ways. According to the UW-Madison Applied Population Lab, Wisconsin Food Security Project, Kenosha County holds an 11.2% rate of food insecurity of its residents, with an 18.6% rate for children specifically.[5] These rates are slightly higher than state rates of 11% and 17% respectively. UW-Extension has a history in working to strengthen food security across the state. The foundation for food security includes: communities that support economic well-being, strong federal food and nutrition programs, adequate access to and availability of safe, healthy, and affordable food, and a strong and accessible emergency/charitable food safety net. Meeting with potential partners and stakeholders in the community has been imperative, as Kenosha County's Extension office did not previously have an equivalent position (formerly Family Living) for a number of years and many did not have a frame of reference for possible programming. Through gathering input from community stakeholders, participating in the Area 22 Developmental Situational Analysis, and input from Kenosha County's Extension Education Committee, initial programming areas have been identified to be social/emotional well-being, financial security, and food security. County Health Rankings, Kenosha County, WI. http://www.countyhealthrankings.org/app/wisconsin/2018/rankings/kenosha/county/outcomes/overall/snapshot[4] Eviction Lab. https://evictionlab.org/map/#/2016?geography=counties&bounds=-88.685,42.434,-87.612,42.819&locations=55059,-88.066,42.609[5] Applied Population Laboratory, WI Food Security Project. https://foodsecurity.wisc.edu/mapping

Outreach has included Caregiver cafes' , resource fairs and other outreach method to reach families and individuals that are seeking resources to enhance their family needs. Specific community outreach has occurred in local communities. Working with the Village of Hortonville, there has been specific attention given to more resources being made available to seniors. Transportation issues, Food accessibility and outreach to community partners to increase resources to Seniors. For the past four years we ahve also coordinated a Senior Autumn Fest that has included a resource fair and keynote speaker.

Fertile soils have allowed Columbia County to be in the top 10 for production for corn grain. The fertile soils support a variety of enterprises - from large cash grain operations of 1,000 plus acres to 10 acre fresh market vegetable producers. Included in these totals are 109,200 acres of corn grain, 21,800 acres of corn silage, 49,000 acres of soybeans, 2,800 acres of oats, 7,400 acres of winter wheat, 19,800 acres of alfalfa hay, plus many acres of pasture, potatoes, sweet corn peas, carrots, onions and other vegetables according to the 2018 Wisconsin Agricultural Statistics. Survey results from Columbia County Corn growers identified the need for updated information to be able to adopt new techniques and practices available to them to achieve high levels of production and also to adapt to a changing market environment in order to maintain high profitability. Columbia County Land Conservation Department provides stipends for farmers to receive Nutrient Management update training each year and stipends for new farmers to be trained to write their own nutrient management plans, to assist with UW-Extension Educational Programming.

Thirty-one percent of adult residents in Wisconsin are obese (County Health Rankings, 2018.) Fond du Lac County has surpassed the state with 37% adult obesity and 73% adult overweight, which both have increased since 2014. The 2017 Fond du Lac County Community Health Assessment found the increasing rates of obesity and percentage of overweight as one of the 10 most pressing health concerns in the county.Among all of the health issues facing society today, obesity has clearly become one of the most pressing. It has been directly linked to increased rates of chronic disease, premature death and increased medical costs. Studies have shown that specific health behaviors have been clearly linked to obesity prevention. They include: consumption of fruits and vegetables, limiting consumption of sugar-sweetened beverages, limiting consumption of large portion sizes and energy-dense foods, and physical activity. Overall health behaviors for Fond du Lac County ranked 30 out of 72 (1 being the healthiest; 72 the unhealthiest) (County Health Rankings, 2018.)There are several social, economic, physical and environmental health determinants related to obesity, including access and quality of food, levels of physical activity, and health behavior. The Public Health Department's Healthy 2020 Steering Committee and Living Well Coalition are current local prevention efforts in Fond du Lac County. Most recently, these groups have taken special interest in examining the effects that social and economic indicators have on health (e.g. food insecurity and access, poverty, race/ethnicity, etc.) by identifying Social Determinants of Health as an overarching priority.

Research shows that high quality programs are more likely to foster positive youth developmental outcomes. High quality programs are characterized by 4 key elements: (1) safe, inclusive, and welcoming environment, (2) supportive and caring adults, (3) content that simultaneously challenges and sparks passion and interest, and (4) high levels of youth voice in program decision making. Together, these elements promote youth engagement, and in turn, the developmental and practical skills for youth to succeed. Regardless of the type of program (in-school, after-school, on-going, or sporadic), programs that focus on maximizing each of the high quality elements are more likely to be engaging for participants.These key elements are especially important for 4-H and Extension-based Positive Youth Development programs because each element is within the control of program educators and participants. The elements can change and improve over time. By monitoring and evaluating each of the key elements, program leaders can adapt and improve the program to maximize positive youth development outcomes for all participants. Research with 4-H members nationally has shown that programs that implement these elements contribute to positive developmental outcomes including: 1) academic motivation and success, 2) social competence, 3) personal standards, 4) contributions to others, 5) connections to others, and 6) personal responsibility. In turn, these developmental outcomes in the longer term contribute to increased academic and vocational success, civic engagement, economic stability, and overall wellbeing.https://health.oregonstate.edu/sites/health.oregonstate.edu/files/thriving-model/pdf/2018-thriving-model-summary-booklet.pdf

Agriculture is an integral part of Dodge County and ranks 6th in the state for the total value of agricultural products. The market value of livestock, poultry, and their products sold in Dodge County is $202.5 million, accounting for 54% of the $373.4 billion total agricultural products sold in the county. The Dodge County agricultural accounts for $2.86 billion in economic activity, 34% of the counties total economic activity. Every dollar of sales from agricultural products generates an additional $0.44 of economic activity in other parts of the county's economy. Agriculture additionally contributes $761 million to the counties total income (21.7% of the counties total income), and pays $37.1 million in local and state taxes. According to the 2012 Census of Agriculture, there were 2,012 farms in the Dodge County, of which the principle operators are 92% male/ 8% female, with the average age of the principle operator being 57.6 years old. 85.7% of farms are owned by individuals or families, 7.7% by family partnerships, 4.2% by family owned corporations and 2.4% by non-family corporations and other business enterprises. Meaning 97.6 % of Dodge County farms are family owned. Farmers own and manage 402,021 acres, or 72% of the land in Dodge County. 54,060 acers are used for forage land including all hay, haylage, grass silage, and green chop. One hundred and fifty five Dodge County farms generate $1,303,000 in direct-marketing sales to customers. Agriculture provides jobs for 9,855 county residents, about 19% of the county's 49,743 workforce. DairyDairy is the major agricultural industry in Dodge County, consistently ranking as one of the top ten milk-producing counties in Wisconsin. In 2012, the market value of the on-farm production and sale of milk accounted for $149.2 million. On-farm milk production accounts for 918 jobs, and dairy processing provides 3,870 jobs in Dodge County. In 2017, there were 241 dairy farms in Dodge County a decrease from 257 herds in 2016. 99% or 239 herds are grade "A" certified herds. These farms contained on average through the year 40,000 cows producing an average of 25000 pounds of milk per cow. While cow numbers in 2017 remained stable compared to 2016, milk production per cow was up 1,200 lbs. resulting in 1 million lbs. of milk produced in Dodge County. On-farm milk production accounts for 918 jobs, and dairy processing accounts for 3,870 jobs. Many Dodge County dairy farms are on the forefront of the dairy industry, with multiple farms utilizing robotic milkers, and value added productions. Dodge County is home to seven milk plants - producing retail milk, Ice cream, a variety of cheeses, cheese spreads and snack dips. The county is home to the Dodge County Dairy Herd Improvement Association, and East Central Select Sires. The county Holstein association also supports a very active and competitive Junior Holstein Association. LivestockDodge County consistently ranks among the top five for livestock such as hogs and pigs, and chukars. Additionally, it ranks in as one of the top ten counties in cattle and calves and pheasants in Wisconsin. In 2017, Dodge County is home to 105,000 cattle and calves an increase of 5,000 from 2016, 19,000 hogs and pigs. Dodge County farmers also raise; chickens, alpacas, bees, whitetail deer, and aquaculture. An area of interest and concern for dairy and livestock producers in Dodge County is remaining profitable. In a needs assessment done in 2016-2017 Dairy producers indicated that animal wellbeing / herd health, nutrition, herd management / record keeping, dairy facilities, heifer development, and reproduction/genetics were viewed as areas farmers were interested in receiving additional education. While livestock producers indicated nutrition, animal wellbeing / herd health, herd management / record keeping, housing / facilities, and quality assurance. All the elements of a farm listed previously are essential to creating a profitable/ long lasting farm business. Therefore, this agent will focus on providing support and education to producers looking to create a profitable farm business. Efforts for programming will focus on animal wellbeing, young stock development (genetics, reproduction, and health), herd management, and facilities.

Situation Statement: Agriculture in Oconto and Marinette Counties:Agriculture is a key contributor to Oconto and Marinette Counties' economy. According to "Oconto County Agriculture: Value and Economic Impact" (Deller, 2014), agriculture provides 4,193 jobs and $126.4 million to the county's income. Dairy is Oconto County's leading agricultural sector. In 2012, 154 dairy farms housing 20,100 dairy cows, contributed $97.3 million to the local economy in on-farm milk production and milk sales. In addition to dairy production; grain, cattle and calves, and vegetable production drive approximately $1.3 billion in economic activity in Oconto County (United States Department of Agriculture National Agriculture Statistics Survey (USDA NASS, 2012)). During the same time period, Marinette County had 66 dairy farms housing 11,800 dairy cows and contributing $55.1 million to the local economy in on-farm milk production and milk sales (USDA NASS, 2012).Oconto and Marinette Counties have a formal specialization agreement allowing the county's agriculture agents to specialize in dairy and livestock (Oconto County) or agronomy and horticulture (Marinette County). The agents collaborate on educational programming where appropriate. The specialization agreement provides farmers, home gardeners, and agribusinesses in both counties specialized technical advice and assistance in solving complex production, management, and environmental challenges.Program Needs Assessment:In spring 2014, I conducted a local needs assessment, distributing surveys to 788 farmers and agribusiness professionals in Oconto and Marinette Counties. One hundred thirty-nine usable surveys were returned (17 percent response rate). Respondents were asked to rate agricultural topics based on individual educational needs (Likert scale, 1=no need to 5=high need). Highest ranked animal health topics included: calf/heifer management (2.74), dairy modernization (2.68), milk quality (2.65), and dairy facilities (2.55). Top farm management educational needs were: farm succession (3.11), financial management (2.88), and use of technology (2.76). The survey results, in addition to my educational background and experience in veterinary medicine, were used to guide and prioritize my educational programming in Oconto and Marinette Counties.Current and Emerging Issues:   Economic Hardship in the Dairy IndustryDairy farms have encountered tight margins over the past few years with low milk prices, low commodity prices, and high input costs. The outlook for dairy farmers is not predicted to change as low milk prices are forecasted throughout 2019. Many factors are driving the market price of milk in the United States: large national dairy herd, declining domestic demand, reduced global exports with imposed tariffs, and a strong dollar. Some dairy farms within the last few years have struggled financially finding themselves a statistic in the market downturn. Farms will be faced either mandated via creditors or voluntarily selling their farm business(es) to meet their outstanding debts. According to the Wisconsin Department of Agriculture, Trade and Consumer Protection, Wisconsin lost 691 farms in 2018, a calendar loss of 7.9%.Farms will continue to monitoring expenses tightly, but will also face emotional and mental stress due to the inability to pay monthly bills. Farm related suicides are double that of veteran suicides. Wisconsin farm families are seeking information to assist in discussing this topic in addition to ways to communicate family budget concerns with their children, and ways to take care of themselves.Farmers will also be exploring job opportunities off the farm to meet family expense needs. These individuals will be seeking opportunities to understand the private sector hiring, creation of resumes, and proper interview techniques. Individuals may be seeking alternative options to add income from their farm businesses such as a value-added product, or utilizing their current resources in other manners.  Dairy Replacements Dairy replacements, or young animals that will ultimately become lactating animals in the herd, are the foundation for genetic progress and improvement of the herd. Raising productive and successful dairy replacements is the second highest expenditure on Wisconsin dairy farms, behind feed costs, when all factors of milk production are considered (Hagedorn et al., 2013). It is estimated to cost $2,377 to raise a single replacement animal from birth to calving (Hagedorn et al., 2013). This cost can increase significantly if young animals are taxed with diarrheal diseases, which can reduce animal growth and productivity, require treatment, and/or lead to death. The USDA National Animal Health Monitoring System estimates 23.9 percent of pre-weaned heifers are treated for diarrheal diseases (NAHMS, 2007), with diarrhea cited as the leading cause of death of dairy heifers of all age groups (NAHMS, 2011).  Animal Well-Being Animal welfare concerns exist regarding painful procedures performed on young dairy animals. In January 2019, People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA) released an undercover video from a Marinette County heifer raiser on their practices of dehorning animals. This video is a vivid example of the need for continued education on the proper technique for pain mitigation in dehorning. Public perception of these procedures has resulted in greater scrutiny of all animal management practices. The average population is three-generations removed from an agrarian lifestyle.  Farm Succession/Transfer According to the 2012 Census of Agriculture, the average age of farmers in Oconto and Marinette Counties was 56.4 and 58.3 years of age, respectively. Currently, there are 129 and 66 dairy farms in Oconto and Marinette Counties, respectively. Across the country, the USDA estimates 70 percent of farmland will change hands in the next 20 years (National Institute of Food and Agriculture, 2017). Therefore, successfully transferring farms to the next generation will be a necessity to ensure the vitality of the agriculture industry. Farm succession is a complex, multi-faceted process, requiring consideration of a variety of topics such as profit margins, land value, farm size, and tax rates. Farm succession is often a laborious process, requiring strategic planning and open communication between all parties.  Alternative Dairy/Livestock: GoatWisconsin is known as "America's Dairyland". It is a widely accepted fact, Wisconsin is the leader in the dairy cow industry; however, Wisconsin is the leader in the nation of milk goat animals according to a United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) National Agriculture Statistics Survey on January 2016. From the January 2016 USDA report, Wisconsin has 44,000 head of milking goats. Most of the milk from these animals is used for making award-winning cheese which appeals to consumers across the nation. Dairy goat herds in northeast Wisconsin continue to grow both in number and size. Goat farmers are looking for educational resources from reliable sources.The Wisconsin dairy industry is a strong economic driver for the state. However, if current economic trajectories persist, farm profit margins will continue to tighten without strong educational interjections to improve production and financial efficiencies. As an educator with University of Wisconsin-Madison Division of Extension, I play a unique and key role to continued farm success by providing relevant, research-based information to decrease farm production costs, decrease costs associated with animal health, and streamline farm inputs, as evidenced by the impacts of my on-farm research, one-on-one farm consultations, and educational programming efforts. I will continue in developing both current and future educational program efforts in animal health and well-being and farm financial health and management to meet the needs of my clientele.My outreach educational programming will focus on the following emphasis areas: 1) animal health and well-being and 2) farm financial health and management. The scope of my educational work in animal health and well-being focuses on calf and heifer management, facilities management, milk and meat quality, and alternative dairy and livestock production. My work in farm financial health and management focuses on farm succession, financial management, and farm efficiencies achieved through farm modernization.

Since joining the Local Government Center in 2008 I have worked to provide Local Government Law resources, information and training fo county extension offices, other local government organizations and directly to local government officials and the public.
