Situation StatementMy work plan is largely driven by community leaders and their priorities in Sauk County. I have developed a respected reputation throughout the region, and I am routinely invited to be engaged and help lead key community and economic development efforts. I have more requests for educational programming than I can provide so I select my work priorities based on my strengths, UWEX resources and potential impacts. Placemaking Sauk County is focused on supporting its unique communities in order to help them create and maintain places where people choose to live and work. The following situation statement is an excerpt from the 2017 "Making Sauk: A Place Plan":Change is the only constant. Places are continuously changing. Communities grow and evolve and natural events alter the characteristics of the landscape. Changes to infrastructure, technology, and the economy influence how decisions are made, and people involved in the process make choices that influence what a place looks like far into the future. Settlements that were started in 1940 in the Sauk Prairie area focused on wheat farming and raising hops, but quickly evolved with the influence of the railroad a mere 20 years later. As dairy and row crop production expanded, the landscape of Sauk County began to change into what it is today, ultimately influenced by the introduction of industry and tourism throughout the twentieth century. The landscape of Sauk County will continue to evolve; decisions made now will heavily influence what this place looks like far into the future. People, businesses, organizations and municipalities across Sauk County are actively engaged in conversations about the future of this amazing place. These conversations often focus on quality of life, sustainable growth, and the abundance of rich resources that this area has been blessed with. These resources include vast natural, agricultural, and cultural resources that distinguish Sauk County from the other 71 counties in the state. It also includes a strong community of hardworking people who focus their daily efforts on improving the communities around them. Sauk County has so much to offer, not only to its residents and the people who grew up here, but to the world. As the gateway to the Driftless region, Sauk County is unlike any other place, but it is difficult to gauge how many people recognize that. There is evidence that Sauk County needs be more progressive in its approach to attract and retain people: businesses have available jobs sitting empty; world-class organizations are experiencing declining numbers of patrons walking through their doors; and school districts have declining enrollments.

Washburn county population demographics, as reported by the 2017 American Community Survey (ACS), indicate the following: 94.7% white; 1.6% Hispanic/Latino; 1.4% American Indian/Alaskan Native; 1.2% 2 or more races indicated; 0.6% Asian; 0.5% Black, with a total population count of 15,494. Our comprehensive poverty rate as obtained from the same data source is 12.8%. The 2010 US Census data reports that 20.3% of the population is >65 year old; 58.4% of the population is between the ages of 18-64; and 21.2% are <18 year old. There are 4 public school districts within the county and 1 private school. The public schools reported free & reduced lunch rates in 2017 ranging from 47.26% - 62.88%, according the WI DPI WISHDash online database.The WI Food Security project data from the 2011-15 report indicates that 16.8% of the population lives in the urban areas within the county; 20.71% of our children live in poverty; 22% of the population rents their home and of those renters 41.86% pay >30% of their income for rent. In addition this report notes that 6% of the eligible population does not own a vehicle; 30% of adults are obese and our county ranked 68th (out of 72) in the County Health rankings for health outcomes and 51st (out of 72)for health factors.According to the WI ACE's study with data from 2011-2015 - 20% of the residents of Washburn County have and ACE score of 4 or more; we have on average 61 hospitalizations from opioid use annually, 46% of the county are classified as "asset limited, income constrained, employed (ALICE)". According to the County Health Rankings and Roadmaps organization, a Robert Wood Foundation, "these ALICE households often live paycheck to paycheck; have little or no savings; struggle to make ends meet and easily are bankrupted by a single medical bill". In addition 31% of our children live in single parent households and according to the same organization "adults and children in single-parent households are at risk for adverse health outcomes," including an increased likelihood of mental illness, substance abuse and depression. The ACS report also notes that we have 239 grandparents living with grandchildren under the age of 18 and of those 239, 117 are responsible for their grandchildren in Washburn county.All of the data above clearly paints the picture of the high level of stress faced by many of the families living in Washburn County. In addition to the data above the following information has been obtained from stakeholder conversations:There are limited parent education opportunities available for families - as shared by Health and Human Services, both the Head Start programs in the county, and the Family Resource Center.There are no programs to support individuals struggling with their finances to work towards greater independence - Washburn Christian Outreach & Indianhead Community Action Agency (ICAA).In contrast to other areas of the state we have a methamphetamine, marijuana, and alcohol epidemic which is impacting our jail population, schools, families, and is taxing all of our county resources. - County Jail Administration, Sheriff's Department, Health and Human Services, Spooner, Shell Lake, and Northwood School District.Mental Health resources are extremely limited and individuals requiring services often only seek them when in crisis - transportation issues compound the limited access - Washburn Co. Mental Health Task Force, Health and Human Services DirectorBased on the data and stakeholder conversations it is apparent there are two primary issues facing Washburn County: the need for parent, family and relationship based education as well as financial skills education across the lifespan. UW-Extension has a unique position in this county with broad reaching support for comprehensive programming to support the needs of the county residents. The vast amount of resources coupled with our extensive efforts to avoid duplication of services and our efforts to identify gaps in programming has established credibility and high levels of engagement with a wide variety of stakeholders and partners throughout the county. The remaining sections of this document will highlight the work that has been identified as key components in the larger picture of addressing the needs expressed in the data and conversations.

DemographicsAccording to the SNAP-Ed Assessment Site Pepin County has a population of 7,349 people. 23% of the population is under 18, 61% of the population is between 18 and 65 years of age and 18% are over age 65. 965 people are currently living at the 100% Federal Poverty Rate, 12%, compared to the state average of 13%. 2061 of Pepin County individuals live at the 185% Federal Poverty Rate, 29%, compared to a state average of 28%. Data from the Wisconsin Food Security Project shows that poverty has risen in the past ten years in Pepin County. In 2000, Pepin County's poverty rate was 9%. An increase of 2%. Five Year Estimate from 2011-2015 shows that 20% of children live in poverty in Pepin County, compared to a state rate of 17.5% and 10% of adults live in poverty, versus 11.3% statewide.Data from the SNAP-Ed Assessment Site shows that 344 households in Pepin County receive FoodShare benefits, 12 % of the total population compared to 13% statewide. According to the Wisconsin Food Security Project data, in 2000 only 3 % of Pepin County's total population participated in Food Share, showing an increase of about 9% in participation. The free or reduced price school lunch eligibility in Pepin County Public Schools grew from 24% in 2000 to 32% in 2012 and is now at 37% in 2017, a total of 1196 students. The state average of free and reduced price participation is 42%. (SNAP-Ed Assessment Site). The Durand High School Alternative School is one school in Pepin County currently eligible for FoodWIse programming. Based on data from the County Health Rankings site, predicted food insecurity rates for Pepin County is 10%, versus the state rate of 11%.Nutrition and Physical Activity BehaviorsAccording to the SNAP Ed Assessment 31.85% of Wisconsin, adult SNAP-Ed participants consume less than 2 servings of vegetables per day. 29.35% of adults in Wisconsin who are SNAP-Ed participants consume 2 or more servings of fruits per day. Fruit and especially vegetable consumption are two focus areas in FoodWIse program efforts.Another focus area for Pepin County FoodWIse is to decrease sugar sweetened beverage consumption. The Master Gardener Program (MGP) was created in the early 1970's as a way for an extension educator to serve a broader audiences' need in obtaining answers to their gardening questions. The first records of MGP training in WI appear in the late 70's/early 80's. In Marinette County, the MGV training was first conducted in 1992 and has continued to be offered consistently since then. The program has trained residents of Marinette and Oconto Counties in Wisconsin and Menominee and Delta Counties of Michigan, most of which have become members of the Northern Lights Master Gardener Volunteer Association if they have continued on as active MGV's. Local MGV's conduct many educational workshops, assist in individual horticultural diagnostic services, and manage & plan most of the demonstration activities conducted within the Marinette County owned Harmony Arboretum Demonstration Gardens. Continued changes to duties of the Marinette County Agriculture/Horticulture Agent position and nearly full turnover of the leadership of the Northern Lights Master Gardener Volunteers' Association (NLMGA) in the last year have created both challenges and opportunities. The most significant challenge is forging new, clear communication channels; as well as creating clarity on the roles of UW-Extension staff and volunteers in the different aspects of continuing education for MGV's, NLMGA activities & guidance/oversight, and meeting the new or changing volunteer management needs of MGV's at the state-wide and local levels. To achieve success in this program, educators:Recruit and train volunteers to increase their capacity in addressing horticultural related issues on behalf of UWEX. Support volunteers and leverage their efforts via volunteer development principles, developing community partnerships, and creating/approving projects to assist UWEX address our educational priorities.

Adult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 9,650 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2018, volunteers reported on average they donated over 58 hours per year. Approximately 72% of Wisconsin 4-H volunteers are female and 28% are male. Nationally, women continue to volunteer at a higher rate than men. (Bureau of Labor Statistics U.S. Department of Labor.) In Wisconsin 4-H, approximately 97% of the volunteers are white. WI 4-H Youth Development volunteers currently do not reflect the demographics of most counties.In 2018, Rusk County had 55 adult volunteers. The demographics of volunteers were 51 % female and 49% male with approximately 100% of the volunteers being white. Rusk County demographics indicate there is a potential audience of volunteers who reflect 1.9% Native American and African American racial and ethnic group who are currently not volunteering in 4-H Youth Development.Volunteers play a critical role in the delivery of quality educational programs. In a survey completed January 2015, 4-H Youth Development staff identified Volunteer Development as an area in need of program support. Additionally, a WI 4-H Youth Development Survey was conducted in February 2014 of over 1500 volunteers. Adult volunteers in 4-H indicated relatively low awareness and understanding of some of the educational principles (Essential Elements and the Experiential Learning Process) that are central to the work of 4-H Youth Development. In the 2014 survey, volunteers expressed an interest in learning through not only face-to-face modalities; but also through online-learning such as webinars and podcasts.The 2017 Strategic Plan released by USDA NIFA and National 4-H Council outlines a 4-H Youth Development Vision for 2025. Nationally the following goal has been established "Youth are surrounded with competent, prepared staff and volunteers." This goal includes the following outcomes: "The 4-H program is supported by a well-trained volunteer force." "4-H staff and volunteers engage in meaningful professional development."In addition, there is a responsibility of volunteers to ensure access, equity and opportunity. The National 4-H Strategic goal states "All youth engage in program and opportunities." To that end it has been identified that "4-H volunteers and staff are skilled, knowledgeable and prepared to work with all members of their community."Rusk County is devoted to offering high quality positive youth development programming to the youth in Rusk County, these programs are offered with the support of the Rusk County 4-H volunteers. Historically, in the last 5 years, Rusk County has had limited critical leaders that have been volunteering for several years, fulfilling most of the volunteering roles and supporting new 4-H volunteers. The Rusk County 4-H program continues to recruit new skilled volunteers to offer learning experiences to Rusk County youth that were not offered as a leader lead projects in the past. With this historical knowledge and perspective of 4-H and a new eagerness for providing more high quality positive youth development learning experiences, Rusk County 4-H will need to provide more training opportunities/experiences to the volunteers.

UW Discovery Farms is a farmer-led, research and outreach program that was designed to gain a better understanding of agricultural impact on water quality in Wisconsin. Since 2001, UW Discovery Farms has performed research on privately owned farms throughout the state and has accumulated a robust dataset. Once this data is collected and understood, it is my responsibility to develop and distribute lessons learned back to Wisconsin's farmers and ag community to aid in the development of practical solutions to water quality concerns.

Many people employed in the green industry do not have the basic educational background to provide sound horticultural services. This Short Course is one of the few opportunities for green industry personnel to receive continuing education. The goal of the Landscape ad Grounds Maintenance Short Course is to provide timely information and education that will allow Green Industry professionals the opportunity to improve the quality of service and profitability of their horticultural businesses. Master Gardener Volunteers help people in the community better understand horticulture, natural sciences and the environment. They also serve as a way to help extend the horticultural resources of Extension to wider audience with the community. Master Gardeners helps build community.

UW Discovery Farms develops on-farm and related research to determine the economic and environmental effects of agricultural practices on a diverse group of Wisconsin farms. The Discovery Farms program is a farmer led program that focuses research on topics farmers feel are their biggest challenges. Project/research is directed by what is deemed priority issues by farmers. This process guides our research to address industry concerns. Discovery Farms meet with farmers and a steering committee to discuss the specific concerns and together determine how to move forward. Research projects are a team effort, and work within these projects is determined by location and the strengths of each of the Discovery Farms personnel.Understanding tile drainage water quality is a priority subject in the agriculture industry. It is important to understand tile drainage systems and how management practices in the fields affects water quality in tiles.

Farm and financial/risk management skills are important for those farm owners/managers to improve upon regardless of their longevity in the agriculture industry. Volatility in agricultural commodity markets along with ever-changing input costs creates a need for farm owners/managers to manage their farm operation or business' profit margins. For example, crop farm owners/managers have seen lower commodity prices for the last three years and have requested programming related to marketing so that they can determine their cost of production and seek additional profit when market prices are above their breakeven price. In addition, the agricultural landscape in Dunn County continues to change and flexibility will be needed to address emerging farm management issues, such as land rent and budgeting for non-traditional farm enterprises. Farm owners/managers and agricultural service providers continue to request programs that focus on improving farm record-keeping skills as well as comparing the financial records with those of others in their industry. Also, with an aging farm operator population, more farm owners/managers are seeking information regarding farm succession planning and their next step in their farming career.Due to ongoing economic conditions in agriculture, many farms are facing significant financial challenges, resulting in questions regarding the viability of the businesses. Based on the Economic Research Service's latest farm income forecast, farm income has now been in general decline for the past four years and seems to be headed for a fifth in 2019. The downturn has clearly started to take a toll, financially and mentally for many farms, farm families and rural communities which depend on agriculture. Farms are experiencing challenges in their ability to successfully transfer the business to the next generation, and others will need to consider an exit strategy, and off-farm employment.

Kewaunee and Door Counties have an informal specialization agreement involving the duties of both Agriculture Educators. This educator will be responsible for planning and implementing educational programs and services directly relating to Dairy and Livestock Management in the dual-county area.Kewaunee County's economy is heavily dependent on agriculture, mainly the dairy industry. Kewaunee County's 48,000 cows are expected to produce over 1.276 billion pounds of milk in 2018. Since this educator started with UW-Extension in 2007, the county herd average has increased from 28,000 to 49,000 cows. The county's herd total has decreased slowly over 12 years, however still has 130 herds averaging 356 cows, an increase of 235 cows per herd since 2007. Agriculture generates nearly $380 million of economic activity annually and provides over 21 percent of the eligible workforce with jobs in Kewaunee County.An initial needs assessment was done in Kewaunee and Door Counties in 2007. That needs assessment showed farm management (milk quality, herd health, reproduction), employee management, profitability, and modernization were top priorities for producers in both counties. Since 2007, formal and informal needed assessments have been sent via Qualtrics (email) and post card in 2010, 2013, and 2015. Results from follow-up needs assessments show producers continue to desire programming in the general farm management areas with additional emphasis on farm employee management. This small shift in programming needs is most likely due to the increase in herd size and more farms hiring employees to help with the day-to-day work. Those producers responding to livestock production requested programming on dairy beef production (dairy steers). The current trend with dairy steers is the shift to using beef sires on low-end dairy cows to produce a value-added by product of the dairy industry. The use of beef sires on dairy cows is more common due to the increased adoption of genomic testing in the herd.Kewaunee County hosted the 2017 Wisconsin Farm Technology Days show for the first time in the show's history. This educator initiated the application for Kewaunee County to host and is served as the Executive Secretary of the show.

Overview of Upham Woods and Current TrajectoryBackground: Upham Woods Outdoor Learning Center is an informal science learning (ISL) center that is a part of the University of Wisconsin System, currently a part of the UW- Extension's Natural Resources Institute. Over the last four years, Upham Woods Outdoor Learning Center's increasingly vibrant outdoor classroom and dynamic statewide outreach program have strengthened the quality, diversity, and reach of environmental education in Wisconsin. Fast Facts:  Founded in 1941 318-acre facility- including a 200 acre state natural area Served 12,019 youth and adults in 2017 from 49 Wisconsin counties; served over 500,000 Wisconsinites since 1941 Programming includes:  on-site group visits from schools, 4-H programs, scouts, etc.  open enrollment summer camps open to youth statewideo outreach learning experiences across the state to school, scout, and 4-H groupsCurrent Trajectory Established by Renewed Outreach Efforts and Use of Technology 2014-2018:   Over $1.92 million in cumulative program revenue generated Over $1.01 million investment in capital projects in collaboration with UWEX administration Acquisition of over $1.45 million in extramural support grants for building environmental education capacity and expanding access to programs at Upham Woods as well as to statewide environmental education opportunities, including Digital Observation Technology Skills (DOTS):  Framework developed at Upham Woods and used statewide for integrating modern, mobile technology into outdoor, experiential science educationo 13,602 (and counting) youth and adults have used DOTS since 2014o Generates hands-on engagement with technology in the context of a classic outdoor learning settingo Digital tool kits are assembled, distributed and supported by Upham Woodso Resulted in 19 peer-reviewed articles authored or co-authored by Upham staff. Upham Woods programming reach has increased 28% in the last 4 years and revenue is up 15% in the same time period. Furthermore, our reach in 2017 was the largest in 32 years and our revenue is the highest in center history.Embracing Technology Rooted in Heritage of Upham WoodsWhen the University of Wisconsin received the donation of land that would become Upham Woods in 1941, Wakelin McNeel served as the Center's first superintendent. McNeel was also known as "Ranger Mac", a persona he created for a Wisconsin Public Radio show that he hosted. As part of his show, he invited youth and adults from across Wisconsin to explore, observe, engage, and conserve the state's wonderful natural resources. On the program, he often noted that "If you didn't take a walk yesterday, you missed out on many things that may not come again" (Matkin-Rawn 2004). Today, we share these same sentiments with our students, encouraging them to observe their surroundings and ask questions that enable them to better understand the world they inhabit. While Ranger Mac worked at Upham Woods in the 1940s and 1950s, many parallels exist between his service to the state and the direction Upham is headed today. Ranger Mac used the technology of the era radio to connect a statewide audience to the environment. By using a resource that was both pervasive and accessible, he drew youth and adults to issues in our natural world and encouraged them to explore Upham Woods. Today, we accomplish these same objectives through the Digital Observation Technology Skills (DOTS) program and web-based mobile resources. Ranger Mac's approach focused on observation and wonder in the outdoors. Today, we use terms such as informal science learning (ISL), inquiry-based instruction, project-based learning and place-based education to describe this same approach. Although there have been many changes in the last 76 years at Upham Woods, it continues to serve a crucial statewide presence in environmental education outreach by leveraging an effective blend of technology and youth development, within a context of vibrant natural resources and scenic beauty.Confidence in this Well-founded ApproachThe National Research Council's research shows that ISL is guided by student inquiry about the natural world, data collection related to their inquiry, and opportunities to present their findings to peers and community members (National Research Council, 2009). Further, the National Research Council states that informal learning environments are, in principle, accessible to all learners, and evidence suggests they have potential for supporting learners from non-dominant groups (National Research Council, 2009). In addition to providing experiential learning opportunities grounded in environmental concepts, ISL centers like Upham Woods expand the network of educators and facilitators engaged in environmental education and provide students with "direct access to compelling phenomena in the natural world" (National Science Foundation, 2011).While ISL centers, such as camps and nature centers, have historically had programming legacies rooted in the natural sciences, their educational practices can be in tension with the emphasis on the adoption of modern technology that often guides contemporary STEM education (Cuthbertson, Socha, & Potter, 2004). Yet using technology in outdoor education settings holds great promise in deepening scientific connections to local places through data collection. As an example, data collection within a context of location, community, and inquiry provides a place-based approach to education that contributes to active and engaged citizens (Hougham & Kerlin, 2016; Sobel, 2004). In modern science classrooms and careers, most scientific tools are digital. Consequently, adopting digital tools requires ISL centers to strike a careful balance between retaining the connection to place that outdoor, experiential learning promotes and serving youth and educators with modern STEM curricula. Connecting this further, place-based education like that promoted at Upham Woods has been shown to connect learners' STEM engagement to their experiences in informal settings, develop their acute observation skills, and increase their capacity to care about the environment around them (Land & Zimmerman, 2015; Greenwood & Hougham, 2015).

Strong relationships between parents and children can steer young people away from dangerous behaviors such as underage alcohol or drug use. A reduction in alcohol and drug abuse can save the county money relating to alcohol related treatment as well as incarceration. Programs are needed to enhance family relationships, parenting, child development and family well being. Many new parents do not have the knowledge or proper parenting education. According to the University of Wisconsin Population Health Institute (http://www.countyhealthrankings.org), in 2018 the teen birth rate in Barron County was 23 out of 1,000, 30% of children were being raised in single parent homes. Access to parent education in Barron County is limited by barriers such as transportation and child care. Research indicates that children with an incarcerated parent have a 70% greater chance of going to jail themselves. This assures that taxpayers will be paying for the incarceration of a new generation of inmates for years to come. Incarceration costs approximately $25,000 per inmate annually according to Barron County Judge James Babler. The Barron County Jail Program Coordinator has indicated that she doesn't have the time, resources or expertise to provide the education necessary. No other department in Barron County Government has the staff time available and the research-based curriculum to provide this program. Without my involvement in this program the necessary education surrounding families would be lost. This too is an undeserved audience that can thrive from the opportunity to gain education.Another major way that children are affected is by parents' divorce when they are exposed to conflict between their parents. In fact, parental conflict affects children negatively regardless of whether their parents' divorce or not. These effects can be observed by researchers for years prior to the divorce taking place. Problems brought on by parental disagreements can appear in different ways  a drop in school performance, behavior problems at school, anxiety and depression.According to the most recent report Wisconsin Department of Health Services Report published in May 2015, 52% of all Wisconsin divorces in 2014 involved families with children under 18 years of age. Among divorces involving children, an average of 1.9 children were affected by each divorce. In 2014 Barron County granted 143 divorces; of those divorces 137 children were affected.Families perform a variety of key functions that contribute to both the mental and physical health of individuals as well as the public health and functioning of society. Throughout all developmental stages, from the prenatal period to the last years of life, strong healthy relationships help families effectively and efficiently raise healthy children, care for vulnerable members, and sustain productive workers and contributing community members. Children who are born into and raised in an environment of positive relationships have a strong foundation that can help them develop into healthy adults and productive citizens. This environment of relationships involves not only parents and children but also extended family and social networks, schools and childcare providers, and others who engage with the family. Stable, nurturing relationships have a powerful protective impact on children. They help prevent exposure to multiple risks and stressors, including family violence and neglect, parental incarceration, and mental illness. Exposure to these stressors is associated with numerous poor outcomes, some of which are commonly seen across multiple generations within families and are very costly to society. In addition to contributing to prevention, safe, stable, nurturing relationships with parents and other caregivers serve as a buffer to help mitigate the damaging impacts of toxic stress. Healthy relationships help children thrive. Adult health and well-being also depend in great part on the quality and success of relationships. Adults in stable relationships have better health outcomes, greater financial stability, a greater sense of well-being and improved capacity to provide care for vulnerable family members, including children and older adults. It has long been understood that a strong parent/child relationship is a key factor in preventing negative outcomes for children. More recent research suggests that strong relationships between parents and other adults, including romantic partners, friends and extended family, can help prevent child maltreatment and improve the capacity of adults to parent effectively. Healthy relationships help adults nurture.

Washington County Agriculture & Dairy Industry: "Agriculture works hard for Washington County every day. Family-owned farms, food processors and agriculture-related businesses generate thousands of jobs and millions of dollars of economic activity while contributing to local income and tax revenues. Washington County agriculture is diverse, which adds to its strength. Dairy leads the way, but grain, greenhouse and nursery, livestock, vegetable and farm-direct markets are also very important. Washington County's diverse agricultural atmosphere is a vital part of the area's culture, communities and economy. Residents find that this rural urban mix adds value to their quality of life. Employers find that it helps recruit high quality employees.Washington County agriculture provides 4,353 jobs, or about 7 percent, of the county's workforce of 66,760. Production jobs include farm owners and managers and farm employees. Agricultural service jobs include veterinarians, crop and livestock consultants, feed, fuel and other crop input suppliers, farm machinery dealers, barn builders and agricultural lenders, to name a few. Processing jobs include those employed in food processing and other value-added industries that support food processors. Every job in agriculture generates an additional 1.18 jobs in the county.Agriculture contributes about $435 million to county income Washington County agriculture accounts for $434.9 million, or 7 percent, of the county's total income. This includes wages, salaries, benefits and profits of farmers and workers in agriculture-related businesses. Every dollar of agricultural income generates an additional $0.85 of county income.Washington County agriculture generates $1.43 billion in economic activity, about 25 percent, of the county's total economic activity. Every dollar of sales from agricultural products generates an additional $0.41 of economic activity in other parts of the county's economy. Here's how agriculture stimulates economic activity:  The direct effect of agriculture equals $1.2 billion and includes the sale of farm products and value-added products.   Purchases of agricultural and food processing inputs, services and equipment add another $320.5 million in economic activity. For example, this includes business-to-business purchases of fuel, seed, fertilizer, feed and farm machinery, as well as veterinary services, crop and livestock consultants and equipment leasing.  This business-to-business activity then generates another $92.2 million in economic activity when people who work in agriculture-related businesses spend their earnings in the local economy.Economic activity associated with Washington County farms and agriculture related businesses generates $22.8 million in local and state taxes. This figure does not include all property taxes paid to support local schools. If it did, the number would increase dramatically.Dairy is a key Washington County industry. Dairy farming is the major agricultural industry in Washington County. On-farm production and milk sales account for $82.2 million. Processing milk into dairy products generates another $431.7 million.  Seven plants process dairy products in Washington County.  On-farm milk production accounts for 437 jobs, and dairy processing accounts for 1,012 jobs.  At the county level, each dairy cow generates $4,377 in on-farm sales to producers.  At the state level, each dairy cow generates about $34,000 in total sales.Source: S. Deller, 2014 Washington County Agriculture: Value & Economic ImpactCurrent & Emerging Issues: The agriculture industry is a very dynamic industry, with new technologies and practices being developed, managing income and expenses with an ever-changing markets, and an aging population.  Dairy farmers faced tight margins for the past couple years with 2019 milk prices predicted to raise slightly, but farm income is not expected to improve for the year. With a large national dairy herd, declining domestic demand, reduced exports due to large global outputs of milk, and a strong dollar, prices for commodities such as milk are negatively affected. Prices for other commodity crops such as corn and soybeans are also expected to remain low which, and farm income for grain producers is projected to go negative for 2019. Lower milk checks and grain prices mean reduced income for the farm to pay expenses related to the farm business, as well as living expenses. Farmers have to watch where they spend every dollar more carefully. With long-term low commodity prices, farmers and their families are emotionally and mentally affected through stress, and more farmers are considering exiting the industry or enterprise. When it comes to managing a farm business operation, production, herd health, animal well-being, and sound financial management can have a substantial impact on profitability. Based on the educational priorities identified in the needs assessment as well as current and emerging issues within the overall agriculture industry and community, this educator will conduct outreach for the 2019 programming year through two major program priorities: 1.) Farm Business Management and 2.) Animal Agriculture. Please see the following Plan of Work for details.

Wisconsin is consistently listed as one of the least, if not the least entrepreneurial (Kauffman, Conroy and Deller 2016) and dynamic (Economic Innovation Group) states in the country. Further, the state has a strong manufacturing legacy and because of the pressures of globalization and technological advancement, this sector is losing employment power (Conroy 2018). These factors are directly related to economic performance of the state, including the slow jobs recovery and tepid wage growth. These factors are important to the quality of life of Wisconsin residents, particularly in rural areas which have been struggling more than urban areas.

ISSUE: Within the County there are 28 municipalities and six school districts. The County has 8% poverty rate and an 8% adult illiteracy rate. In recent memory there existed TEEN COURT within the county to address alternative means of dealing with youth offenders while building upon youth as leaders while positively transforming the community. The vast size of the county and lack of resources has had TEEN COURT operating in the past under 4-H on a limited budget. With the discontinuation of a 4-H Agent the Community Development Agent and Family Living Agent have taken on the program. School districts, municipal Judges, Police Chiefs, Sheriff Office and Circuit Court Judges along with health & Social Services staff have strongly expressed a need for this program (needs assessment 2018-2019) as teen delinquency, drug use, and other offenses have increased within the county of 38,000 people.INVOLVEMENT10%: UWEX is expertly equipped at providing the facilitated TEEN COURT, and has done so for the last six months with a longer history within the county and across the State.

Research is clear that strong family relationships significantly contribute to the health and well-being of individuals across the lifespan. Safe stable, nurturing relationships and environments have a powerful protective impact on children and are fundamental to healthy brain development. They help prevent exposure to multiple risks and stressors, including family violence and neglect, parental incarceration and mental illness. Children who are born and raised in an environment of positive relationships have a strong foundation that can help them develop into healthy adults and productive citizens. In addition, safe, stable, nurturing relationships with parents and other caregivers serve as a buffer to help mitigate the damaging impacts of toxic stress. Childhood exposure to toxic stress is associated with numerous poor outcomes, some of which are commonly seen across multiple generations within families and are very costly to society.In Ashland County, compromised social and economic factors contribute to toxic stress for families and children. According to County Health Rankings & Roadmaps (CHRR), in 2018 Ashland County ranked very low compared to other Wisconsin counties for Social and Economic Factors, at 59 out of 72. The factors used to determine this ranking include community safety, education, employment, family & social support, and income. Ashland County families are experiencing high poverty, with the latest figures from the US Census Bureau indicating that 15.% of residents live below the poverty line, compared to a Wisconsin average of 12.%. An alarming 22% of children under 18 living are living in poverty, as opposed to 16% of children statewide. Unemployment rates in Ashland County are 5.6%, above the state average of 4.1%. One-third of children in Ashland County live in single parent households.To address sources of toxic stress, Ashland County Human Development and Relationships programming will focus on education and community supports to strengthen families. These efforts are framed around the Center for Study of Social Policy's Strengthening Families Protective Factors, which have been shown to enhance child development and reduce the likelihood of child maltreatment. Building on these factors promotes the well-being of children, their families and their communities.

According to the SNAP-Ed Assessment Site Buffalo County has a population of 13,319 people. 22% of the population is under 18, 62% of the population is between 18 and 65 years of age and 19% are over age 65. 1500 people are currently living at the 100% Federal Poverty Rate, 14%, compared to the state average of 13%. 3767 of Buffalo County individuals live at the 185% Federal Poverty Rate, 29%, compared to a state average of 28%. Data from the Wisconsin Food Security Project shows that poverty has risen in the past ten years in Buffalo County. In 2000, Buffalo County's poverty rate was 7.5%. An increase of 2%. Five year estimate from 2011-2015 shows that 13% of children live in poverty in Buffalo County, compared to a state rate of 17.5% and 10% of adults live in poverty, versus 11.3% statewide.Data from the SNAP-Ed Assessment Site shows that 598 households in Buffalo County receive FoodShare benefits, 10 % of the total population compared to 13% statewide. According to the Wisconsin Food Security Project data, in 2000 only 5 % of Buffalo County's total population participated in Food Share, showing an increase of about 6% in participation. The free or reduced price school lunch eligibility in Buffalo County Public Schools grew from 25% in 2000 to 35% in 2010 and is now at 34% in 2017, a total of 1959 students. The state average of free and reduced price participation is 42%. (SNAP-Ed Assessment Site). Gilmanton Elementary is the only school in Buffalo County currently eligible for FoodWIse programming. Based on data from the County Health Rankings site, predicted food insecurity rates for Buffalo County is 11%, Same as the state rate of 11%.Nutrition and Physical Activity BehaviorsAccording to the SNAP Ed Assessment 31.85% of Wisconsin, adult SNAP-Ed participants consume less than 2 servings of vegetables per day. 29.35% of adults in Wisconsin who are SNAP-Ed participants consume 2 or more servings of fruits per day. Fruit and especially vegetable consumption are two focus areas in FoodWIse program efforts.Another focus area for Buffalo County FoodWIse is to decrease sugar sweetened beverage consumption. State data shows that 35.78% of adults who are SNAP-Ed participants consume excessive sugar sweetened beverages. Health OutcomesBuffalo County overall health outcomes have varied over the past three years. In 2015 Buffalo County ranked 31 out of the 72 counties in Wisconsin, and in 2016 ranked 9 out of 72. According to 2017 County Health Rankings data Buffalo County ranks 33 out of the 72 counties, with an adult obesity rate of 33% compared to the state average of 31%. According to the SNAP Ed report data for Buffalo County between 25% and 30% of youth are overweight or obese compared to the WI child obesity rate of 22% (according to the State of Obesity report for Wisconsin)Diabetes rates in Buffalo County are at 10% compared to the WI diabetes rate of 9.8% that would be 470,136 cases in 2010 in Wisconsin. (State of Obesity report for Wisconsin)Hypertension rates for Wisconsin are about 30% or 1,130,359 cases in 2010. (State of Obesity report for Wisconsin)Physical Activity EnvironmentAccording to the 2017 Health Ranking report for Buffalo County, 25% of the county residents are physically inactive, compared to 20% statewide. 57% of Buffalo County have access to exercise opportunities, compared to a Wisconsin rate of 81%. Food EnvironmentThe southern half of Buffalo County is consider a food dessert, people have to travel 10 or more miles to the nearest food access, according to USDA Economic Research. Service SNAP-Ed Report findings: According to the 2017 Health Rankings report 7% of residents of Buffalo County have limited access to healthy foods, with Wisconsin having 5%. The SNAP-Ed Report shows that Buffalo County has 40% of the population with no healthy food outlet, state data shows 35.94%. 0% of Buffalo County has high food access, Wisconsin has an 8.35% rate. There are 9 SNAP-Ed retailers in Buffalo County, In 2017 two schools had farm to school programs, neither of those qualify for FoodWIse programing. Only one school qualifies for FoodWIse programming with a free and reduced lunch rate over 50%. There is one farmers markets in Buffalo County, statewide there are 312. None of the farmers markets accept SNAP benefits, none that know of accept WIC and the senior vouchers.

In addition to the traditional methods of publishing and speaking about our research, our Outreach Program uses our website to identify ourselves and demonstrate our value. This online presence is supported by social media.

Kewaunee and Door Counties have an informal specialization agreement involving the duties of both Agriculture Educators. This educator will be responsible for planning and implementing educational programs and services directly relating to Dairy and Livestock Management in the dual-county area.Kewaunee County's economy is heavily dependent on agriculture, mainly the dairy industry. Even though dairy is the main agriculture industry in Kewaunee County, there are an estimated 4,400 cow/calf (beef) pairs and market steers in the county. In addition to beef, there are an estimated 2,200 hogs sent to market from Kewaunee County annually. Agriculture generates nearly $380 million of economic activity annually and provides over 21 percent of the eligible workforce with jobs in Kewaunee County.An initial needs assessment was done in Kewaunee and Door Counties in 2007. That needs assessment showed farm management (milk quality, herd health, reproduction), employee management, profitability, and modernization were top priorities for producers in both counties. Since 2007, formal and informal needed assessments have been sent via Qualtrics (email) and post card in 2010, 2013, and 2015. Results from follow-up needs assessments show producers continue to desire programming in the general farm management areas with additional emphasis on farm employee management. This small shift in programming needs is most likely due to the increase in herd size and more farms hiring employees to help with the day-to-day work. Those producers responding to livestock production requested programming on dairy beef production (dairy steers). The current trend with dairy steers is the shift to using beef sires on low-end dairy cows to produce a value-added by product of the dairy industry. The use of beef sires on dairy cows is more common due to the increased adoption of genomic testing in the herd. Kewaunee County hosted the 2017 Wisconsin Farm Technology Days show for the first time in the show's history. This educator initiated the application for Kewaunee County to host and is served as the Executive Secretary of the show.

Meetings with key stakeholder groups in 2018 identified the need for a series of facilitated community conversations around selected topics. Individuals representing human-service non-profits, local chambers, and local municipalities all identified the need for housing at a wide variety of price points, improved public transportation, and more workers across a broad range of industries. Members of each group offered a unique perspective on these three issues and have been working individually or within a topic-specific coalition. There is an interest in bringing the larger community together for focused conversations, but no structures exist for such conversations to occur. In addition, the Area 15 Situational Analysis identified the need for an in-depth, county-wide needs assessment. The Situational Analysis relied on existing research and the abbreviated timeline did not allow for meaningful stakeholder engagement. As part of rebuilding the Community Development program area after a two-year vacancy, a thorough and inclusive needs assessment is essential so that future programming focuses on the priority needs.

At the local level, residents in Door County have reported feelings of isolation, social withdrawal, and lack of community support 1. Community members also state that geographic isolation is a barrier to access of support services and education. Likewise, the numbers of children partaking in free and reduced lunch continue to rise (28%) 3, access to quality childcare is referred to as a "county crisis" 1, and parents are also reporting high levels of stress as barriers to their own as well as their children's success 4. Perhaps, unsurprisingly, early childhood suspensions are continuing 5 and an increased need for social and emotional learning programs is present 4. "Research shows that when families build strong relationships within supportive communities many sources of stress are reduced and outcomes for children, families and society improve." -HDFR State Team One way, Extension programming can support these families is by utilizing the Protective Factors Framework, created by the Center for the Study of Social Policy. According to the National Alliance of Children's Trust and Prevention Funds, Protective Factors are "Characteristics that make a parent, child, or family more likely to thrive and less likely to experience a negative outcome." These include: social connections, knowledge of parenting and child development, concrete support in times of need, social and emotional competence of children, and parental resilience. Resiliency can be defined as having the ability to cope, accept, and grow amidst change and hardship. Those with a strong sense of resiliency (a skill that can be both nurtured and learned), may be better positioned to address adversity when it arrives 6. In rural Door County, the need for resiliency is matched by the high numbers of adverse childhood experiences reported by residents, as 15-20% report 4+ adverse childhood experiences 7 (ACEs). ACEs matter in terms of health and well-being, as higher ACE incidents (4+) correlate with a greater likelihood of experiencing impaired childhood brain development, risky lifestyle behaviors (drug and alcohol misuse, unhealthy relationships, etc.), as well as liver disease, cancer, and/or diabetes 8. While ACEs have lasting health impacts for both adults and children, Harvard's Center for the Developing Child (2016) states, "the single most common factor for children who develop resilience is at least one stable and committed relationship with a supportive parent, caregiver, or other adult" for it is within these relationships, children learn the essential life skills of behavior/emotion regulation, empathy, problem-solving, and connection. Still, it is important to remember that each child works in synergy with his/her surroundings and relationships; it is both a child's biology and environment that can support or halt resiliency development 6. Therefore, healthy resiliency may be threatened if an individual's surroundings do not cultivate attitudes, cultures, and beliefs that nurture its development and support trauma-informed care practices. Thus, coalitions and programs that support Door County families may be of essential need. By working together to increase the community's capacity for change, communication may increase, redundancies may be reduced, and awareness may arise. Likewise, research-based programs that support and empower caregivers, reduce stress, and strengthen problem-solving skills may change household dynamics leading to stronger family relationships. Also, finding creative ways to counter issues of isolation and social withdrawal, may also greatly benefit all age groups, as social support has been found to increase resiliency as well as overall well-being. 1. Document_Name: Soil Health and Nutrient Management to Improve Crop Production
Segment: Clark County is home to 160,000 cattle and calves, of which 69,000 are dairy cows, producing an average of 899 million gallons of manure annually. Livestock sales contribute $310 million annually or 80% of the total sales for agriculture production in Clark County (2012 Census of Agriculture). Agriculture in Clark County contributes more than $401 million to the local economy.Surface and ground water quality is a concern in the county. Clark County manure ordinance requires farmers to use best management practices to prevent manure contamination of surface and ground waters of the county. A needs assessment identified manure and nutrient management programming as a need in the county.

State WAHCE Liaison PD identifies the position provides professional guidance and counsel to the WAHCE State Board, focused on organization building and volunteer development through appropriate media formats. As the Extension model moves forward and merger with UW Madison solidifies, there will be a need to provide orientation to newly employed Extension Educators who will be point of contacts in the county for the county WAHCE subordinate organizations. Continued work to address Extension/UW Madison reorganizational change with relation to the WAHCE organization's affiliation - 501c3 organizational functions, Wisconsin Bookworms, the State Educational Programs supplied by Extension faculty/Staff will be addressed in 2019 State WAHCE organization leadership development achieved through inclusiveness done through board development opportunities and volunteer leadership trainings

Successful local governments routinely undergo processes to help its communities understand future trends, prepare and adapt to new circumstances, enhance quality of life and economic development opportunities, operate efficiently, and better serve their constituents. These deliberative efforts can lead to more resiliency within the local system, which is compulsory to respond to transitions in the economy, workforce, energy sources, the environment, and societal needs and desires. The development of strategic plans are tools that should define the future aspirations and the steps needed to achieve them. Strategic planning involves deliberative processes by an organization's representatives and often, external stakeholders. In addition to providing direction, with meaningful conversations, the act of planning spurs creativity and can help to strengthen the cohesion within an organization.

According to The National Endowment of Financial Education, Latinos have the highest labor participation, lowest retirement security, and have a longer life expectancy than any other demographic in the nation.[1] Moreover, the U.S. is home to 52 million Latinos and the number is projected to grow to 133 million by 2050 and represent 30% of the U.S. population. Moreover, in many Latino-immigrant families, Latinas are expected to be income contributors and are the managers of household finances. They are also more likely than Latino men to liquidate pensions and savings when changing jobs or facing an emergency.In Wisconsin, specifically, according to the US Census, Latinos are now the largest minority group with the largest increases since 2000 occurring in Milwaukee County, Dane County, and Brown County. The latest "Latinos in Wisconsin: A Statistical Overview" reports that[2]:Median household and family incomes in 2010 were vastly less for Latinos than for the total population (72% and 59% of the total populations' medians, respectively).34% of Latino households earned less than $25,000 in 12 months prior to 2010 compared with 25% of total population households.The gender gap in earnings between male and female Latinos was smaller than in the total Wisconsin population the time of the 2010 ACS The earnings gap between Latino and total population males was over $14,000. Between Latinas and total population females, the earning gap is over $8,000.2010 ACS measures suggest that more than one fourth of the Latino population lived in poverty. The combination of lower earnings and larger family size contributed to a greater risk of poverty for Latinos.The 2010 Latino men and women had rates of unemployment that were roughly one-and-a-half times those of their counterparts in the total Wisconsin population.The population increase tied with these findings, and interest expressed from Latino community organizations demonstrate that there is a definite need for financial literacy programming within the Latino communities. Equally importantly, as the study "Latinas: Hungry for Financial Education, Challenged by Cultural Stereotypes," Latinas and Latino households are hungry for financial education and recognize the need to improve their financial stability.[1] Golden, Paul. Families perform a variety of key functions that contribute to both the mental and physical health of individuals as well as the public health and functioning of society. Throughout all developmental stages, from the prenatal period to the last years of life, strong healthy relationships help families effectively and efficiently raise healthy children, care for vulnerable members, and sustain productive workers and contributing community members.Children who are born into and raised in an environment of positive relationships have a strong foundation that can help them develop into healthy adults and productive citizens. This environment of relationships involves not only parents and children but also extended family and social networks, schools and childcare providers, and others who engage with the family. Stable, nurturing relationships have a powerful protective impact on children. They help prevent exposure to multiple risks and stressors, including family violence and neglect, parental incarceration, and mental illness. Exposure to these stressors is associated with numerous poor outcomes, some of which are commonly seen across multiple generations within families and are very costly to society. In addition to contributing to prevention, safe, stable, nurturing relationships with parents and other caregivers serve as a buffer to help mitigate the damaging impacts of toxic stress. Healthy relationships help children thrive. The Family Living Educator works closely with family serving agencies in the county to identify community needs that impact the well-being of families. The educational role of the Family Living Educator includes identifying the best use of existing resources and working collaboratively with these agencies to achieve intended outcomes by feasible target dates. The Family Living Educator also links the family organizations to UW-Extension expertise by using the concepts of evidence-based resources and strategies. The Family Living Educator's evaluation guidance and development promotes the importance of accurate data collection for a specific project as well as the future direction of the program.Today's parents can benefit from technology to support their parenting. Married couples with children who are younger than age 18 have higher rates of internet and cell phone usage, computer ownership, and broadband adoption than any other households (Kennedy, Smith, Wells, & Wellman, 2008). Usage of social networking, e-readership, video chat, tablets, and smartphones for parenting purposes is increasing at an astonishing pace as well (Pew Internet & American Life Project, 2011). Access to digital devices and the Internet is no longer limited to middle class families; the clear majority of parents, including those from low-income and vulnerable populations, are now connected.Available web-based knowledge and programs can both stand-alone and supplement face-to-face programs. Increasingly, the web has become the initial point of contact where parents seek out and access information. It also functions as the "front door" through which parents learn about and connect to local and county resources, including face-to-face education and assistance. Having a prominent online presence is critical to successfully reaching and educating parents in the 21st century. As participants in the 2017 pilot of eParenting Little Ones, the Head Start coordinator, school district 4K coordinator and one child care center director all felt that the program was easy to use, information was accurate, interesting and appropriate for the parents.

The population of Dane County in July of 2017 was 536,416 and is currently the fastest growing county in the state. A key way to help ensure healthy communities in Dane County is to ensure that the local non-profits are vibrant and able to work at their mission to the best of their ability. Dane County has over 4000 non-profits including many that serve the entire state of Wisconsin. This educator invests time in assisting organizations build their capacity to do their work. Organizational capacity building also extends to government agencies too. Being the county that has the capital city, many governmental bodies reside here. Dane County UW Extension is well suited to assist local organization's build their capacities, plan for the future so that they are strategically positioned and ready for change, and strengthen their leadership. As an Extension faculty member who has been trained in systems thinking and analysis, conflict, communication, facilitation, change processes, leadership, and organizational development make me well positioned to assist Dane County's organizations and local governments to help ensure community vitality. As a natural resources educator I will focus most of my work with either local governments or environmental organizations.The rapid county growth also brings additional stresses to the county's water and land resources. The Situation Analysis completed after a review of current plans and interviews or focus groups for Dane County in 2018 identified protection of natural resources, climate change, and working to maintain ground and surface water quality as 3 of the 14 high priority issues for the county. Groundwater provides all the water for domestic and industrial water use and recharges locally. Water quality is a problem as 25-35% of the county's approximate 23,000 private wells have nitrate-nitrogen levels that exceed the state and federal standards for safe drinking water and pesticides have also been found in well water and chloride levels have been rising in municipal wells due to winter salt use. Runoff pollution in urban, rural and transitional areas also threatens the county's surface water. The majority of the streams and 37 lakes are eutrophic or overly nutrient rich. Storm water increases in both quantity and water quality problems as impermeable surfaces grow with development. Storm water runoff causes significant problems to the county's surface water resources. Along with this is the need to protect shore lands and open spaces as the pressures of growth emerge. The county also has developed a Pollinator Protection plan as pollinators have been in decline throughout the state, nation and world. The county is actively trying to encourage pollinator habitat protection and creation. The Federally endangered Rusty patch Bumblebee has been found at various locations in Dane County. This has put even more emphasis on protection of our local pollinators.There is an ever increasing need for local governments and all citizens to become active stewards in protecting our natural resources. Dane County's natural environment - its forests, soils, water, wildlife, and scenic beauty provide a significant contribution to our quality of life. It supports agriculture, forestry, tourism, surface mining and many other industries. It provides recreational opportunities, waste disposal sites and the place we call home.Many current Dane County plans have identified protecting our environment as one of the top three concerns in Dane County. The County Executive and the County Board both have initiatives focused on conserving and protecting our land, water and other natural resources.In collaborative efforts with other natural resource agencies, this Extension Natural Resource educator will help plan and implement programs and projects that address these local natural resource issues and enhance local stewardship of the natural environment. Efforts will be made to help local community leaders and citizens including youth to learn how to increase their understanding of the environment and enhance their ability to be good stewards of the natural environment.Finally 20% of my time is currently bought out by the Dane County Environmental Council as staff for the Council to oversee their work. As much as I can I try to integrate educational work of the Council with my Extension work such as my pollinator protection work. I also leave about 30-40 % of my time unplanned so that I can be nimble and responsive to the quickly changing needs of the county. This has enabled me to have the time available to be part of important emerging issues and assist with county task forces and other projects that rapidly arise in Dane County.

Marquette County is an active outdoor recreation community. Gardening is an outdoor activity that many residents of the county participate in. Home horticulture is a popular activity with both year-round and weekend or seasonal residents. There is an active Master Gardener Volunteer (MGV) Association located within the county to help address home horticulture education and activities.

Green County is fortunate to have a strong county-wide economic development entity (Green County Development Corporation), which means my efforts in economic development are very specifically targeted to bringing in UW-Extension specialists and specific resources and data. These targeted efforts contribute to Green County having a strong approach to economic development initiatives. In 2019, my work around economic development is anticipated to focus specifically on the City of Brodhead, with some follow-up evaluation work from some work I have completed in the Village of Belleville.

In the previous year an agriculture needs assessment survey was conducted and analyzed. It was very helpful in assisting me with what the needs were for my agriculture producers that I created a horticulture needs assessment. Since the assessment was not created until later in 2018 I plan to continue that survey through out this year (2019). Analyzing the data I did collect has indicated that the top five programming they would be interested in was the Master Gardener Level 1 and Level 2 training, pruning, pest and disease management, sustainable horticulture, and environmental protection. This may change as the needs assessment is conducted further but for this year my focus will be on advancing horticulture education through the Master Gardener program and interested horticulture groups.

Dairy is the largest agricultural sector in Wood County, accounting for 60-70% of total on-farm agricultural receipts. In addition there are large sectors of the area economy that rely on the dairy industry including dairy processing, dairy equipment, forage and crop equipment, lending, accounting, insurance, health care and many other direct and support industries. The dairy industry is currently in financial distress with record numbers of dairy producers exiting the industry after four years of below average prices. The industry is consolidating with fewer and larger farms, but regardless of size, profitability has been difficult to establish.Dairy producers are considering new technologies and seeking efficiencies wherever possible to improve their enterprise. The situation is very similar across Central Wisconsin where I partner with other Extension Educators to support the dairy production system.

Almost 20 years ago, a task force of Extension agents, local university educators, directors from area chambers of commerce, and other local organizations, associations and agencies, identified a lack of leaders in Southwest Wisconsin and by enhancing the number of engaged leaders in our communities, they will be better able to address the declining numbers of volunteers serving on and leading committees, boards, planning teams and work groups in the community. The task force members recognized that a formal leadership development program was needed to build the knowledge and skills, motivation and confidence, and capacity of the citizens of the region to serve as change agents and leaders, to ensure the health and vitality of the region's communities. After researching other leadership programs, the Task Force decided that a collaborative effort, rather than a single community-based program would make it more sustainable - drawing on resources and participants from a larger geographic area.

A. Marquette County, WIData indicate, and key leaders affirm, that preventing substance abuse remains a high priority in Marquette County. Pregnant women smoking is nearly twice that of the state average; cancers, especially lung, are uncommonly high in Marquette County. The 2017-2022 Marquette County Health Assessment lists alcohol, tobacco and other substance abuse in its top three priorities.[1] Substance abuse and unhealthy lifestyle choices are rooted in family practices, community norms, and societal influences. Tackling entrenched high-risk behaviors requires decades of focused, collaborative action grounded in the evidence of "what works," which includes using a combination of practices, programs and environmental change. Although there is still much more to achieve, efforts to reduce and prevent youth substance abuse over the past fifteen years in Marquette County are paying off: youth alcohol use and tobacco smoking were reduced by half since 2003.[2] High school students have significantly decreased heavy drinking. However, high school students increased frequent marijuana and e-cigarettes use, and driving under the influence of alcohol. Adult heavy and binge drinking has decreased, defying state and national trends over the past 10 years.[3] Marquette County's substance abuse prevention coalition is Healthy Communities Healthy Youth (HCHY). HCHY uses multiple data-driven, evidence-based strategies, and multi-sector members participate in regional, statewide, and national professional development. UW-Extension and Health Department provide core leadership for HCHY to prevent substance abuse and promote healthy lifestyle choices. Allen is a certified Wisconsin Substance Abuse Prevention Specialist.B. Opioid Crisis Work GroupWisconsin's opioid crisis includes 916 deaths in 2017 from opioid overdose - more than those who die in car crashes. Overdoses of prescription painkillers by people ages 10-14 have increased dramatically in recent years - by over 200%. Extension educators can and are contributing to the prevention of opioid abuse and overdose in Wisconsin, and can learn more about their roles and resources in 2019.[1] Marquette County Community Health Improvement Plan 2017-2022, Marquette County Health Department. http://www.co.marquette.wi.us/home/showdocument?id=9819 [2] Marquette County 2015-16 Youth Risk Behavior Survey Report, Westfield and Montello School Districts.[3] Healthy Communities Healthy Youth coalition, 2003-2016 Report to the Community.

Document_Name: Pop-Up-Produce Garden Kits for Low-Income Families (2019)
Segment: Marathon County has an estimated population of 135,732. The Marathon County Jail was reported to be 70% over capacity with most of those convicted due to drugs or drug related activities. Currently, occupant overage is vetted to other counties, which is an expensive practice. The impact on families of those incarcerated is devastating. Youth are sometimes placed in foster care or shelter homes. The extreme amount of stress associated with this for Marathon County families is immeasurable. Marathon County strives to be the healthiest, safest, and most prosperous county in the State. To this end, collaboration among community leaders, our elected County Board of Supervisors, and Marathon County employees has led to development of a 2018-2022 Strategic Plan, identifying area of focus in the coming years (http://www.co.marathon.wi.us/Portals/0/Departments/CAD/Documents/StrategicPlan_2018-2022.pdf).As a UW-Extension Horticulture Educator, my unique contribution to addressing Marathon County's Strategic Plan, thus far, has been to identify target populations where therapeutic horticulture could improve well-being. After lengthy review of the 2018-2022 plan, there are three populations on which I have been focusing my efforts: 1) jail inmates, 2) county youth, and 3) individuals in addiction recovery or those living with mental illness. For 2019, my plan of work centers mainly upon county jail inmates and community youth, although there is some overlap here with individuals in addiction recovery or those living with mental illness. Based on numerous studies conducted across the globe, it is likely that therapeutic gardens and horticulture programs will positively impact the physical, intellectual, emotional, social and spiritual well-being of individuals in these target populations (American Horticulture Therapy Association, 2018).Upon my hiring, I reached out to stakeholders across Marathon County, and specifically within the City of Wausau where our county jail is located. I provided a series of four public informational sessions to raise awareness of therapeutic horticulture as a viable treatment option for individuals across diverse populations and added two additional programs to more specifically inform Master Gardener Volunteers in Marathon and Portage Counties of our community engagement efforts. Approaches in therapeutic horticulture vary by population and programming provided in 2019 will be research-based. I continue to be told that even if we reach only ONE person through this initiative, we will have made a difference! By not engaging in this situation, UW-Extension will fail to do its part in supporting positive mental and physical health for youth and adults in Marathon County.

The poverty numbers within Chippewa County are in line with the current need for financial supports throughout the state. The statistics within the 2015 FINRA Financial Capability Survey suggests an ongoing financial insecurity in Wisconsin, signaling the need for supportive educational programming (Family Financial Security Team Plan of Work, 2016). In Chippewa County, poverty, trauma, substance abuse, and isolation reach many families. The poverty rate in Chippewa County is 11.3%, with the food insecurity rate at 14.3% (Clark, Johnson, Malual, Walsh, Tarter, & Fastner, 2016). According to the ALICE (Asset Limited Income Constrained Employed) report, 42% of families in Chippewa County make under the amount needed to afford their basic needs. Based on this 2014 point in time data, the ALICE report shows that the towns of Chippewa Falls, Stanley, and Cadott contain the highest count of families struggling in Chippewa County (Alice in Chippewa County, 2017). This data suggests a need for programming in financial education, capability, and stability. Too many individuals experience financial crisis due to lack of income, inadequate savings, too much debt, and making non-informed spending choices. Education is needed to help families make better financial choices with the monies they have. Education can help families meet their future needs by addressing the basics of earning, spending, saving, investing, and housing.
