Research shows that high quality programs are more likely to foster positive youth developmental outcomes. High quality programs are characterized by 4 key elements: (1) safe, inclusive, and welcoming environment, (2) supportive and caring adults, (3) content that simultaneously challenges and sparks passion and interest, and (4) high levels of youth voice in program decision making. Together, these elements promote youth engagement, and in turn, the developmental and practical skills for youth to succeed. Regardless of the type of program (in-school, after-school, on-going, or sporadic), programs that focus on maximizing each of the high quality elements are more likely to be engaging for participants.These key elements are especially important for 4-H and Extension-based Positive Youth Development programs because each element is within the control of program educators and participants. The elements can change and improve over time. By monitoring and evaluating each of the key elements, program leaders can adapt and improve the program to maximize positive youth development outcomes for all participants. Research with 4-H members nationally has shown that programs that implement these elements contribute to positive developmental outcomes including: 1) academic motivation and success, 2) social competence, 3) personal standards, 4) contributions to others, 5) connections to others, and 6) personal responsibility. In turn, these developmental outcomes in the longer term contribute to increased academic and vocational success, civic engagement, economic stability, and overall wellbeing.https://health.oregonstate.edu/sites/health.oregonstate.edu/files/thriving-model/pdf/2018-thriving-model-summary-booklet.pdf 4-H programming in Chippewa County currently centers around caring adult volunteers and the programs the adults in our program feel the youth need. The creation of new 4-H programming stalled over the last few years through burn out of volunteers, volunteers suffering from founder's syndrome and changeover in staff. The last new event/program created came in 2016 with a 5-8 grade educational experience. Chippewa County 4-H according to the Leader's Council Executive Board survey has become a place where we check things off a list that the event is done, rather than consistently "making the best, better." A term coined for this county is "4-H blindness." This means that volunteers believe our program is the best, yet lack the 4-H worldview that there are other neat programs offered in neighboring counties or states. Our youth do see this as they attend State Fair, Fall Forum, and the other great educational opportunities offered by WI 4-H. Through high quality programming, provided by youth leadership, the face of Chippewa County would shift from people who perceive themselves as the experts on youth to the youth who are experts on what they/their peers need.

Between 1990 and 2007 Census of Ag, (2018 Census of Ag is being completed) farm numbers increased in Iowa County, driven largely by farms being split into smaller retirement and weekend farms by urban development pressure from Madison and Dubuque, Iowa. The farms in the middle are disappearing, some getting larger, others selling the farm at retirement into smaller units. Grant, Iowa and Lafayette Counties rank 1, 2, and 3 respectively in Wisconsin for beef production. Grant County is also ranked 1 for swine. Although National Ag Statistics Service no longer keeps county level data, the last year this information was available (2000), 25% of the sheep population was also located in the 5 southwestern counties. Dairy and meat goat operations are concentrated within the southwest region, and recently dairy sheep operations are increasing. While cow dairy is still a significant part of the agriculture landscape, age of operator and economics are resulting in fewer farms milking more dairy cows, or small dairy enterprises transitioning to grazing and/or organic management. Since beginning in the role of Ag educator in 2009, 100 dairy (30%) have ceased operating in Iowa County. The transition to non-dairy livestock will likely continue.Livestock production is a significant part of the local ag economy, producers purchase inputs, hire veterinarians, trucking and other services. Ruminant livestock require forage, the cost of which, until recently, was being pulled higher by increases in the grain market. Currently being pulled higher still by 2nd lowest supply in 70 years. The loss of pasture and hay ground to grain may have stabilized with the decrease in grain prices, most of this converted land should not be in row crop production. The forecasts are for improved profit potential for livestock over the next several years and consumer demand for artisan dairy, goat and sheep milk cheeses continues to outpace production, even in the current year of excessive dairy production. Farms and farmers have a resource base. Farms may have vacant facilities that can be converted to livestock from dairy. They often have a forage base in hay acres and harvest equipment as well has acres that are most suitable to grazing. Farmers themselves possess knowledge and husbandry skills that can be transferred to other species such as beef, sheep or goats. Success in livestock comes down to managing costs, primarily feed but also in labor efficiency. Some producers will adapt strategies which lower their cost of production, they may have the scale to invest in technologies which improve feed and/or labor costs. Smaller producers (livestock and dairy)may need to consider alternative products and markets, including grass based, organic, and tapping into regional food systems. Iowa County in Southwest Wisconsin sits within a circle of some 75 million consumers within a 5 hour drive. There are ag products and services which we can offer this group of people. There may be alternative ag enterprises with higher profit margins that require smaller acreages that can fit into a local or regional food system. A study by the Center for Integrated Ag System at UW-Madison highlighted the lack of federally inspected processing facilities needed to access large population markets outside of Wisconsin.

Winnebago county is comprised of suburban, urban, and rural areas. According to the 2015 U.S Census data, Winnebago County has a population of 169.546 residents. Winnebago County is comprised of a mix of cities (5), towns (16), villages (2) and unincorporated communities (8). Winnebago county is largely populated by white/non-Hispanic individuals (92.7%). Of note, however, between 2010 and 2015 other racial and ethnic groups represented the largest growth in population changes in our area. For example Black/African American representation grew from 1.8% to 2.1% (14.3% increase) and our Asian, Hispanic/Latino and American Indian populations continue to grow at rates of more than 10%. This changing landscape of people creates a strong pull to continue to be responsive, respectful seekers of cultural competence and connection.Winnebago County residents report a median household income of $52,018 with 12.0% of residents living in poverty. This is a 12.5% increase from 2015-2015. Living in poverty has major impacts on one's overall well-being. While reviewing the data and scanning the environment major themes have emerged in response the the challenges that our families face.Challenges Facing Winnebago County Families:Disconnection: Research shows that "when families build strong relationships within supportive communities stress is reduced and outcomes for children, families, and society improve" (HDFR Impact Report). The national Research Council also reports that more than 50% of premature deaths are attributable to non-medical factors such as where one lives. Strengthening connections between people increases their hope, sense of belonging and resilience to adversity. People who have strong connections to each other are more likely to seek help before a crisis occurs. Research also indicates that parents who have strong social connections are less likely to abuse/neglect their children (Child Welfare Information Gateway). Parenting is a difficult task, and if attempted without the buffer of supportive relationships both the parent and child will suffer undue stress. We know that there are many barriers to connection (lack of awareness, poorly developed social-emotional skills, poverty, poor mental health and transportation) with support and encouragement we can work together as a community to build stable networks of families who support each other physically, emotionally, spiritually and economically.Poverty/HousingIn Winnebago county 16% of household live below the poverty line. According to the Annie E. Casey foundation (2015) on average families need an income of roughly twice the official line to cover the entire cost of basic expenses of a household; this represents food, shelter, clothing, health care, food and child care. " Poverty has a profound negative impact on a children's development, academic success, health, safety, and life achievement" (State of the Fox Valley Child Report)Out of Home Living Placement for Children:In Winnebago County approximately 6% of children live with someone other than their parents (2325 total children) according to the 2010 census data. For grandparents in particular, this presents a multitude of parenting challenges. Aging, lack of connection to parenting-peers, financial challenges and the grieving process are all present with these families. Children who are also raised by non-biological parents require additional supportive strategies to ensure healthy trajectories into adulthood. Trauma and Adversity in Childhood:The brain is wired to thrive in the environment that it is constructed. When a brain is wired to adapt and respond to repeated stressors or traumatic experiences, it shapes the way that a person responds and adapts to the world. These behaviors, while critical for survival in highly stressful environments can be maladaptive in every day interactions. When we understand that individuals who have been exposed to trauma and stress are responding in the way that feels safe for them, we are able to take a more compassionate approach to their experiences with us. By recognizing these responses as ones that may be a product of stress we can create healthy, safe, predictable environments that allow for individuals to become empowered. As their self-efficacy increases, their brain begins to form new pathways and adaptive behaviors supporting their growth and healthy choices. More than 20% of Winnebago residents report having experienced more than 4 experiences in their childhood that are considered adverse. This study, is not comprehensive to include other toxic experiences such as poverty or neighborhood violence (short sample). We know that trauma is pervasive. We cannot tell by just looking at someone if they have a trauma history or if they have or are experiencing toxic stress do it is critical to work as a coordinated community to increase awareness and create a compassionate response that allows for individuals to live their best lives.Mental Health Concerns:According to the 2016 Youth Risk Behavior Survey 19.4% of Winnebago County high school students reported seriously considering attempting suicide (WI average 13.2%). Additionally, more than 20% of Winnebago county residents have more than 4 or more ACEs (Wisconsin Child Abuse and Neglect Prevention Board). these traumas in childhood are likely to create lasting negative outcomes in all domains of wellness. According to the County Health Rankings Report; adults report an average of 3.4 poor mental health days per month.

When considering the importance of science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) education, many reports speak of job opportunities and economic drivers in a global environment. Research strongly suggests that STEM educational initiatives are not just creating scientists and engineers, but producing STEM literate persons in all areas of the workforce. Eighty percent of the fastest growing occupations in the U.S. require STEM adequacy, and science and technology jobs are projected to grow by 20.6 percent through 2020, more than doubling the 10.1 percent overall U.S. labor force's projected growth (Beatty, National Research Council Committee on Highly Successful Schools or Programs for K-12 STEM Education, National Research Council Board on Science Education, & National Research Council Center for Education, 2011). Additionally, in middle-skill jobs (jobs that require more than a high school diploma, but less than a four year degree), over 67% of openings require, at a minimum, proficiency in productivity software such as Microsoft Excel or Microsoft Word and typically other digital literacy skills (Burning Glass Technologies, Captial One, 2015). Overall, it seems clear that middle-skills work has shifted decisively and is now digitally intensive.As a mission mandate, the impacts of STEM educational programming within 4-H have been investigated. Hershberg et al. found that youth in 4-H science programs were nearly two times more likely to participate in science, engineering and computer technology programs during OST (Grades 10 - 12). Additionally, girls who participate in 4-H are two times more likely (Grade 10) and nearly three times more likely (Grade 12) to take part in science programs compared to girls in other OST activities (Hershberg, DeSouza, Warren, Lerner, & Lerner, 2014). Other researchers state that STEM education within 4-H can improve science literacy (Smith, Heck, & Worker, 2012) and build problem solving skills (Daniels et al., 2013).Trempealeau County is a rural area with a rapidly growing Latino population in western Wisconsin. In 2000, the Latino population made up less than 1% of the total population. By 2010 the Latino population had risen to 5.8 percent of the population (Applied Population Lab, 2014). This has had a dramatic impact on the makeup of school populations with some districts having a Latino population of 41% of their entire student population. Trempealeau County is also relatively poor with most districts reporting a population that is between 40-50% economically disadvantaged with the highest being 55.7% (DPI school report cards 2013-2014). This unique population is regularly underrepresented when it comes to STEM education with only 2.2% of Latinos having earned a first university degree in the natural sciences or engineering by age 24 (ref fed strategic plan)On a local level our counties businesses, schools, and libraries have all recognized an education in the sciences as valuable to both individuals and communities and are looking for programs that can meet their needs in this area. According to the DPI school report cards 6 out of 7 school districts in Trempealeau County fell below the Wisconsin average in either mathematics achievement or mathematics growth, scores are much lower for Latino students. Female students are also marginalized with overall lower test scores on the county level in mathematics. This is another population that is underrepresented in the STEM fields. Women make up the majority of all college students and 46 percent of the American workforce but represent less than one fifth of all bachelor degree recipients in the areas of computer science and engineering and hold less than a quarter of all STEM jobs (ref fed strategic plan). These test scores and national trends indicate a clear issue that needs to be addressed.Two school districts in the county have established 21st Century Learning Centers as a means to meet the growing demand for quality afterschool programming that uses STEM education as a foundation. These centers are regularly searching for programming that can meet the needs of their students and the UW-Extension has shown itself as a valuable partner. Interviews with local librarians have indicated the strong desire to integrate STEM literacy into their programming as a core need of the people they serve. It is through these local agencies, who have also identified the need and are ready and willing for help, that we can work in partnership to extend the reach of 4-H science and UW-Extension programming and ensure effective and impactful STEM education programs.Evaluations from previous STEM programs implemented in Trempealeau County indicate that these programs fill a need for science curriculum in elementary education and have been both effective and popular. Surveys taken from afterschool and summer camps indicate that students who complete the program have a much higher interest in science and engineering, have gained foundational STEM comprehension, and developed problem solving and critical thinking skills. Of all total respondents 93% stated they would encourage their child to participate in another UW-Extension science camp and 86% stated they were 'very likely' to recommend Extension science programs to other families.The need for STEM education is critical to the success of the young people in Trempealeau County and across the country. The diverse and unique population of Trempealeau County shows a clear need for supplemental STEM education to meet the needs of all students. Educators, organizations, businesses, and communities have made it clear that they see the need for STEM education. If these needs are not met our young people will graduate from school unprepared for further education and without the tools they need to navigate an increasingly complex and technologically sophisticated world. The UW-Extension has a unique skill set and opportunity to teach, provide resources to, and partner with existing stakeholders to ensure STEM education is available to all and taught with fidelity in Trempealeau County.

Situation Statement (it's okay to list two different situation statements)Overview of Upham Woods and Current TrajectoryBackground: Upham Woods Outdoor Learning Center is an informal science learning (ISL) center that is a part of the University of Wisconsin System, currently affiliated with UW-Madison, Division of Extension. Over the last four years, Upham Woods Outdoor Learning Center's increasingly vibrant outdoor classroom and dynamic statewide outreach program have strengthened the quality, diversity, and reach of environmental education in Wisconsin. Fast Facts:  Founded in 1941 318-acre facility Served 11,237 youth and adults in 2018 from 49 Wisconsin counties; served over 500,000 Wisconsinites since 1941 Programming includes:  on-site group visits from schools, 4-H programs, scouts, etc.  outreach learning experiences across the state Current Trajectory Established by Renewed Outreach Efforts and Use of Technology 2014-2018:   Over $1.92 million in cumulative program revenue generated Over $1.01 million investment in capital projects in collaboration with UWEX administration Acquisition of over $1.45 million in extramural support grants for building environmental education capacity and expanding access to programs at Upham Woods as well as to statewide environmental education opportunities, including Digital Observation Technology Skills (DOTS):  Framework developed at Upham Woods and used statewide for integrating modern, mobile technology into outdoor, experiential science educationo 14,591 youth and adults have used DOTS since 2014o Generates hands-on engagement with technology in the context of a classic outdoor learning settingo Digital tool kits are assembled, distributed and supported by Upham Woodso Resulted in 19 peer-reviewed articles authored or co-authored by Upham staff. Upham Woods programming reach has increased 28% in the last 4 years and revenue is up 15% in the same time period. Furthermore, our reach in 2018 was the largest in 32 years and our revenue is the highest in center history.Embracing Technology Rooted in Heritage of Upham WoodsWhen the University of Wisconsin received the donation of land that would become Upham Woods, Wakelin McNeel served as the Center's first superintendent. McNeel was also known as "Ranger Mac", a persona he created for a Wisconsin Public Radio show that he hosted. As part of his show, he invited youth and adults from all across Wisconsin to reflect on, observe, engage, and conserve the state's wonderful natural resources. On the program, he often noted that "If you didn't take a walk yesterday, you missed out on many things that may not come again" (Matkin-Rawn 2004). Today, we share these same sentiments with our students, encouraging them to observe their surroundings and ask questions that enable them to better understand the world they inhabit. While Ranger Mac worked at Upham Woods in the 1930s and 1940s, many parallels exist between his service to the state and the direction Upham is headed today. Ranger Mac used the technology of the era radio to connect a statewide audience to the environment. By using a resource that was both pervasive and accessible, he drew youth and adults to issues in our natural world and also enabled them to explore Upham Woods. Today, we accomplish these same objectives through the Digital Observation Technology Skills (DOTS) program and web-based resources. Ranger Mac's approach focused on observation and wonder in the outdoors. Today, we use terms such as informal science learning (ISL), inquiry-based instruction, project-based learning and place-based education to describe this same approach. Although there have been many changes in the last 76 years at Upham Woods, it continues to serve a crucial statewide presence in environmental education outreach by leveraging an effective blend of technology and youth development, within a context of vibrant natural resources and scenic beauty.Confidence in this Well-founded ApproachThe National Research Council's research shows that ISL is guided by student inquiry about the natural world, data collection related to their inquiry, and opportunities to present their findings to peers and community members (National Research Council, 2009). Further, the National Research Council states that informal learning environments are, in principle, accessible to all learners, and evidence suggests they have particular potential for supporting learners from non-dominant groups (National Research Council, 2009). In addition to providing experiential learning opportunities grounded in environmental concepts, ISL centers like Upham Woods expand the network of educators and facilitators engaged in environmental education and provide students with "direct access to compelling phenomena in the natural world" (National Science Foundation, 2011).While ISL centers, such as camps and nature centers, have historically had programming legacies rooted in the natural sciences, their educational practices can be in tension with the emphasis on the adoption of modern technology that often guides contemporary STEM education (Cuthbertson, Socha, & Potter, 2004). Yet using technology in outdoor education settings holds great promise in deepening scientific connections to local places through data collection. As an example, data collection within a context of location, community, and inquiry provides a place-based approach to education that contributes to active and engaged citizens (Hougham & Kerlin, 2016; Sobel, 2004). In modern science classrooms and careers, most scientific tools are digital. Consequently, adopting digital tools requires ISL centers to strike a careful balance between retaining the connection to place that outdoor, experiential learning promotes and serving youth and educators with modern STEM curricula. Connecting this further, place-based education like that promoted at Upham Woods has been shown to connect learners' STEM engagement to their experiences in informal settings, develop their acute observation skills, and increase their capacity to care about the environment around them (Land & Zimmerman, 2015; Greenwood & Hougham, 2015).

Successful local organizations benefit from facilitated conversations to refine their missions, goals, and capacity. Some organizations benefit from assistance with a SWOT analysis, others need to develop capacity through leadership training. These efforts can help organizations become more focused on their missions.

Document_Name: Addressing Nitrate Contamination of Groundwater in Rural Areas
Segment: Nitrate contamination of groundwater is an increasing problem in agricultural areas throughout the state. High-intensity row crop production, particularly in regions of susceptible soils (e.g., sandy texture, shallow groundwater), coupled with the loss of pasture-based livestock agriculture have exacerbated the problem. Groundwater quality data shows a continuing upward trend in contaminant concentrations. This has serious health implications for rural populations that rely on untreated groundwater for drinking water.

Beginning beekeeping classes in Metropolitan Milwaukee presented by non-profit organizations are not very comprehensive. To maintain a beehive in many municipalities, new beekeepers are required to have taken a certified beekeeping class. Our focus groups indicated that research based beekeeping information is important for both our new and existing beekeepers. The focus groups also specifically liked the UIWEX hands-on, in the apiary, class experience. Although UW does not maintain a "bee lab" like the University of Minnesota, we find and share university information to help our beekeepers maintain quality hives. The program began in response to the concerns of our community gardeners in 2005, who related to us that they had low yields of squash and cucumbers. Because bees provide 100% of pollination of vine crops, we now maintain seven apiaries with forty hives in our large community gardens to help with pollination. The forty-six acre UWEX Kohl Farm Community Garden now has three apiaries and about 20 bee hives. Our high quality season-long course gives new students a chance to explore this opportunity without the risk of a substantial investment of bees and materials before they commit to this discipline. We plan to train 25 new certified beekeepers to help them comply with their local ordinances.

Document_Name: Building Strong Mental and Physical Wellbeing in Chippewa Count
Segment: Many of Chippewa County Families are directly impacted by opioid and methamphetamine use. The rapid rise of these toxic drugs has increased the cases of Child Protective Services throughout the county from 28 cases in 2014, to 92 cases in 2016. This increase has impacted our schools, legal communities, service providers, public health department and Department of Corrections. Babies are affected before birth and they continue to be affected through the adverse childhood trauma that they experience (Winter, L. 2016).The impacts of poverty, isolation, drug use and incarceration have been seen throughout the community by all members of the community and suggests a correlation to the top needs of the county. The results of the 2014-2015 Community Health Needs Assessment, 2017 Chippewa County Community Health Survey, and 2017 Chippewa County Youth Survey, indicate that the top health priorities in Chippewa County are mental health, substance abuse, alcohol misuse, healthy growth and development, and healthy nutrition. The data further indicates that Chippewa is above the state and/or national level in: Opioid-related and drug-related hospitalizations, driving deaths with alcohol involvement, excessive drinking, violent crimes, injury hospitalizations, hospitalizations for self-inflicted wounds, number of mentally unhealthy days, suicide death rate, obesity, and lacking in adequate access to food (Chippewa County Community Health Assessment, 2014-2015, Chippewa County Youth Survey, 2017, and Chippewa County Community Health Survey, 2017).Survey data indicates that there is a need for University of Wisconsin- Division of Extension to provide research-based/evidence based programs and provide education to inform policy development. The community needs help dealing with the occurrence and outcomes of alcohol use, drug abuse, physical wellbeing, and mental health issues that are being seen in families. Furthermore, building strong leaders in our community is important to help shape the direction of tomorrow.References2017 Chippewa County Community Health Survey, (2018).2017 Chippewa County Youth Survey, (2018).ALICE by County - United Way of Wisconsin. Document_Name: Workforce development among under/unemployed residents in Racin
Segment: Demographics: Kenosha County is comprised of 13 municipalities (1-City, 7-Villages, 5-Towns) with a total population of just over 167,000. Racine County is comprised of 17 municipalities (2 Cities, 9 Villages, 6 Towns) with a total population of 196,000. The City of Kenosha is the fourth largest WI city with a population of just over 100,000. City of Racine follows closely behind at 77,500. Kenosha and Racine County populations are projected to grow between 30% to as much as 60% by the year 2050 according the Southeastern Wisconsin Regional Planning Commission's 2010 Comprehensive Plans. This population will also grow increasingly diverse demographically with respect to race and ethnicity as the white, non-Hispanic population drops off from over 70% of the current population in 2017 to just over 55% in 2050. This also reflects a growing trend of individuals speaking English as a Second Language. Natural Environment: The region has a recent legacy of poor air quality; recording the second highest number of daily alerts of WI counties between 2007 and 2013 with hazardous levels of ozone and particle pollution (WI Dept. of Natural Resources). Regional personal vehicle miles total over 4 million daily (VMT) according to WI DOT 2011 wherein nearly 43,000 daily commuters leave the county for work (US Census). These environmental impacts are exasperated by land use planning, urban sprawl, insufficient public transportation infrastructure and heavy commercial trucking. Renewable fuel sources such as wind power, hydroelectricity, and solar power, which are pollution-neutral, comprise less than one-half of one percent of our region's energy portfolio. Both Racine and Kenosha County have formidable challenges with respect to land use, wetland conservation, air quality, water quality and rapidly depleting space at their landfills due to the rapid growth and development throughout the region.Economy: Broad-based, equitable economic development also remains key to Racine and Kenosha County sustainability as both rebound from unemployment rates that in the recent recession peaked at over 10% (WI DWD Annual Unemployment Rates, 2005-2010), and is at a rate of 3.6% and 3.7 respectively in March 2018 (statewide averages at the same time were 3.2). Since the 1970s industrial productivity has slowed nationally, lending way to all-together new employment patterns. This shift was acutely felt in Kenosha and Racine through the 1980s as major employers eliminated local production facilities: Redevelopment of sizable brownfield redevelopment projects and significant workforce development and retraining needs exist. In 2017 signs of the New Economy are shaping the nature of employment, job creation and the practice of economic development with emphasis on business retention, creativity and innovation, entrepreneurship and digitization. (Kaufmann Foundation State New Economy Index). Since 2008, SE Wisconsin began a strong recovery from economic recession, and has outpaced most regions nationally to become one of the most attractive distribution/ logistics and manufacturing locations in the US. With a tight labor market of eligible employees and skill gaps across Kenosha and Racine Counties, the region has struggled to meet workforce development demands. But that was so even prior to the 2018 announcement of Wisconsin's largest economic attraction deal in state--and United States history, with Taiwanese electronics manufacturer Foxconn. This current challenge requires the region to shore up eligible employees to fill the 13,000+ net new technology jobs and reshape the built environment with a capital investment of $10 billion of private funds. And Foxconn, while hugely significant, is only one employer. The region is laden with legacy employers that will continue to grow and require a talent pool to compete. And the region will likely see many complimentary industries emerge through business high profile relocations (Haribo) and corporate expansions (Uline, Amazon). Taken together, the resulting demographic shifts, environmental impacts and infrastructure enhancements will be staggering. These will require an unprecedented degree of coordination, expertise and informed decision-making.

Through a competitive selection process, CCED was awarded grant funding from the Department of Commerce's Economic Development Authority for the purpose of establishing a University Center. The grant supports a partnership based in the UW Extension Center for Community & Economic Development and includes researchers and staff from the Center and the UW Madison Department of Agricultural and Applied Economics. The EDA University Center funding, a total of $750,000 over five years, is for applied research, education, outreach and professional development opportunities focusing on specific aspects of the state's regional economic development. The University Center is intended to advance research and community assistance specifically by focusing on entrepreneurship, innovation, labor markets and economic resilience. 2019 will encompass the third and fourth years of the grant.

Document_Name: Cropping Systems, Resource Protection and Cover Crops
Segment: Situation: There is an on-going need to utilize cropping procedures that protect water quality by reducing the amount of nutrients and sediment impacting both surface water and groundwater. Cover crops produce vegetative biomass that increase organic matter, protect soil aggregates, improve water infiltration, and help to recycle plant nutrients from one year to the next. This need is clearly identified by: Local Planning and Conversation Departments, DNR and numerous conservation groups concerned about water quality and climate change issues. The primary focus area of work includes the Sheboygan and Milwaukee River Watersheds. The Research Team includes: UW -Extension Sheboygan County, UW-Madison - Soil Science Department, Nutrient & Pest Management Program, NRCS, Planning & Resources Department, Local Soil and Water Conservation Departments and The Nature Conservancy. Through my leadership the partnerships were expanded starting in 2016 to include the Milwaukee Metropolitan Sewerage District, The Conservation Fund and Sweet Water Milwaukee.

A clean and dependable supply of water is critical to ensure a high quality of life and maintain a strong economy. Groundwater is of particular importance to Wisconsin since nearly 95% of communities and all rural residents rely groundwater as their principal water supply. While municipal water supplies are subject to strict guidelines and water quality testing to ensure that water meets the criteria for safe drinking water; the estimated 900,000 households that rely on private wells (~42% of Wisconsin Residents) are not routinely tested. While drinking water standards are not enforceable for private wells, they serve as guidelines for well owners to decide whether or not to drink the water. Data collected by Extension shows that nearly 10% of wells are considered unsafe with respect to nitrate. Fifteen to twenty percent have detectable coliform bacteria which may indicate problems with the well that could allow harmful pathogens into the well. Approximately 3% and 5% contain unsafe levels of arsenic and lead, respectively. Private well owners must act as their own water utility manager, however this group often know little about the quality of their well water, where to send a sample to get tested, or what to do if there is a problem. Characteristics of rural audiences include less formalized networks, fewer interactions among the population, fewer shared activities, horizontal accountability, less specialization and more egalitarian allocation of resources; all of which can make it more challenging to effectively target messaging or implement policy changes to assist this audience. This Extension research and programming is designed to provide support and services that increase the capacity of rural residents to provide clean drinking water to their families.

Other researchers state that STEM education within 4-H can improve science literacy (Smith, Heck, & Worker, 2012) and build problem solving skills (Daniels et al., 2013). Through the Emmett Project and the 4-H Digital Ambassadors, youth leaders will be trained as spokespeople and trainers. They will expand their voice with in the communities by providing workshops or program in STEM+C or Digital Literacy with both youth and adults. 4-Her's serve as trusted voice and have many long-standing relationships within their communities. Provided the youth with effective training they can build the relationships as leaders within the communities. The Emmett Project will serve the youth in Lincoln and Langlade counties. This STEM+C program will be open to all youth in the communities not just 4-H. Flyers were given out to local schools, the Boys & Girls Club, and local libraries. While Langlade was identified as county with a large digital divide with need for the digital literacy program. 4-H youth will become team leaders that will take their knowledge into the community for both youth and adults to learn from.

Families in Wisconsin struggle to make end meets, with 17% of our children living in poverty [1] and 31% of these children live in single parent households.[2] There are 286,829 families with 405,611 young children. In Wisconsin, 43% (172,526) of young children live in low-income families. (National: 45%)[3] We know that families perform a variety of key functions that contribute to both the mental and physical health of individuals as well as the public health and functioning of society. Throughout all developmental stages, from the prenatal period to the last years of life, strong healthy relationships help families effectively and efficiently raise healthy children, care for vulnerable members, and sustain productive workers and contributing community members. Despite recent reports of overall improvement in employment and gains in median incomes, the economic recovery in Wisconsin has been uneven. Many families continue to face challenges from low wages, depleted savings, and the increasing cost of basic household goods.Children who are born into and raised in an environment of positive relationships have a strong foundation that can help them develop into healthy adults and productive citizens. This environment of relationships involves not only parents and children but also extended family and social networks, schools and childcare providers, and others who engage with the family. Stable, nurturing relationships have a powerful protective impact on children. They help prevent exposure to multiple risks and stressors, including family violence and neglect, parental incarceration, and mental illness. Exposure to these stressors is associated with numerous poor outcomes, some of which are commonly seen across multiple generations within families and are very costly to society. In addition to contributing to prevention, safe, stable, nurturing relationships with parents and other caregivers serve as a buffer to help mitigate the damaging impacts of toxic stress. Healthy relationships help children thrive.It has long been understood that a strong parent/child relationship is a key factor in preventing negative outcomes for children. More recent research suggests that strong relationships between parents and other adults, including romantic partners, friends and extended family, can help prevent child maltreatment and improve the capacity of adults to parent effectively. My work will focus on strengthening families and enhancing relationships by: Offering Raising a Thinking Child (RTC) and I Can Problem Solve (ICPS) throughout Wood County.Using media technology as a means to reach and connect with busy families today, providing evidence and research -based information about child development and parenting practice in a digital format. Provide parents, grandparents and caregivers with education as how they can use digital media to support their parenting practices. [1] http://www.countyhealthrankings.org/sites/default/...[2] http://www.countyhealthrankings.org/sites/default/...[3] http://www.nccp.org/profiles/WI_profile_8.html

Document_Name: Produce safety program oversight and delivery
Segment: The FDA Food Safety Modernization Act (FSMA), the most sweeping reform of our food safety laws in more than 70 years, was signed into law in 2011. It aims to ensure the U.S. food supply is safe by shifting the focus from responding to contamination to preventing it. Food safety is an important issue for every farm. Contamination by food borne pathogens can make customers ill and have devastating impacts for farm business. In addition to being the right thing to do, food safety is increasingly becoming a required part of doing business. Many buyers require some form of food safety audit. The federal Food Safety Modernization Act also requires increased food safety regulations on farms of various sizes. FSMA establishes science-based standards for growing, harvesting, packing and holding produce on domestic and foreign farms. In Wisconsin, over 80,000 acres of fresh market vegetables, tree fruit and berries are produced in Wisconsin according to the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) Census of Agriculture. This produce is sold directly to the public and/or wholesale to grocery stores, restaurants and schools. Farmers are expected comply with the Food Safety Modernization Act (FSMA) Produce Safety Rule to mitigate the risk of food borne illness. Complying with this rule requires produce growers to understand and mitigate risk related to food borne pathogens in all aspects of their operations from the beginning of the growing process to the sale. To enable produce growers to improve food safety on their farms and comply with the food safety rule, they require education relevant to their operations. Fortunately, proper harvesting and handling techniques will minimize the risk of contamination as well as increase the shelf life and marketability of your products. Implementing food safety practices is simply good farming.The Produce Safety Alliance (PSA) has developed a curriculum, approved by the FDA; and is a collaboration between Cornell University, FDA, and USDA. The PSA's mandate it to prepare fresh produce growers to meet the regulatory requirements included in the United States Food and Drug Administration's Food Safety Modernization Act (FSMA) Produce Safety Rule. UW-Extension was granted a contract with Wisconsin Department of Agriculture to provide farm safety training, using the PSA curriculum to Wisconsin growers.

In Kenosha County, the disparities in reading & math proficiency, graduation, and college readiness are most serve with students of color across the board. In 2016 African-Americans only represented 7% of the total Kenosha County population, and Hispanics made up 13%. Students of color (23% Hispanic & 11% African-American) make-up only 34% of the 28,813 pre-K - 12th grade Kenosha County students. African Americans hold the highest poverty rate in Kenosha County at 43%. Youth that grow up economically disadvantaged face many challenges which may cause them to be unrepresented, underestimated, undervalued, and marginalized when it comes to their academic success and overall opportunities. There is tremendous need for positive youth/adult partnerships, lifeskills, pre-college preparation & post-secondary, and career exploration programming for underrepresented students of color in Kenosha County. School administrators and staff are oftentimes over exhausted with the number of students they have at their particular schools to meet the unique needs of underrepresented students. If students are not developing the necessary skills needed in reading & math, they will not be prepared for post-secondary education or have the skills needed to go directly into the workforce.The goal of Extension is connecting UW-Colleges to the local community, through resources and expertise from the various institutions. UW-Extension Kenosha County can contribute to the greater good of Kenosha County through bridge-building access to quality enrichment opportunities for local underrepresented youth & young adults through various programming. As there is no single point of these disparities, strides can be made through the facilitation of new programming, collaborations and partnerships i.e. academic enrichment, tutoring, and social-emotional development programs, pre-college and post-secondary awareness, and career exploration. Combined with increased parent involvement, the aforementioned engagement activities have proven to have direct impact on the achievement gap. Utilizing student-centered programming and approaches that will effectively address disparities that exist among student's unrepresented youth in Kenosha County.The cost of not engaging this population of youth will continue to widen the academic achievement, which will have a domino effect on the gap in post-secondary attainment, and the economic and workforce shortfall.

Encouraging Community Economic Development by increasing activity and connectivity within Regional Food System of Ashland and Bayfield CountiesFood and agriculture are integral to the economic, social and cultural fabric of Ashland and Bayfield Counties. Over the past decade, there has been significant focused effort put forth by many stakeholders to to build regional wealth, vitality and social equity through the development the regional food system.Within the last 10 years, there have been several new additions and expansions within the local food system including: new small diversified vegetable and fruit farms; new wineries, distilleries, and cideries; new restaurants focused on buying locally and offering local food on their menus; a new food producers cooperative that has branched out into a broader regional markets; new local food-related events for both community members and visitors; consistency and growth at farmers markets; presence of multiple CSAs; growth in programs providing access to local fresh fruit and vegetables for low-income community members; a growing presence of food sovereignty in the region; growth in capacity of organizations providing emergency food to populations in need; an new food center with commercial kitchen and co-packing capacity; growth in micro-loans available to producers; increase in quantity of local foods stocked at grocery stores; growth in commitments to purchase local food from cornerstone institutions; and a new degree program at the local college for sustainable farming and food systems. A 2018 Local Food Survey conducted by the Center for Rural Communities at Northland College notes the following: "a large majority of households share values related to access to healthy food, a regional culture of small farms, and water quality in Chequamegon Bay. 92 percent of households would like more of the food they purchase to be produced in Ashland and Bayfield Counties. A majority of households are willing to pay more for food produced locally. Over 45 percent of households are willing to contribute to community programs that support wider distribution and greater affordability of local food.... Taken together these values and beliefs suggest that there is support for growing the local food economy and making sure that households across the income spectrum are able to participate and benefit from its development."Despite these numerous recent developments and significant public support, the food system of the greater Chequamegon Bay Area has not yet matured to become economically sustainable or self-perpetuating. CSA sales have declined, value added producers are facing continued challenges with growth and distribution to broader markets, and local food is still out of reach for many local residents due to both real and perceived barriers. While great effort has been put forth, success has been modest. Many of the expected benefits, including sustainable livelihood creation, increased entrepreneurship, and increased access to local food, and other useful "spillover effects" have yet to be realized. This has left key stakeholders questioning whether food is a viable economic driver for this geographically isolated region with such a small population.

Title: Energy Development and PolicySituation statement (Why): Energy systems, economics, policy and opportunities are increasing complex and fluid. Wisconsin energy stakeholders are continuously seeking applied research, outreach and advisory from UW (trusted sources) in order to better understand options and technical/transactional issues related to effectively deploying projects/programs. Regional, national and global drivers, including environmental, economic and policy, have advanced the state-of-art and opportunity in such a manner that energy system innovation is a necessary requirement for all involved stakeholders - if for no other reason than to remain competitive and relevant in this "space."

Outagamie County Family Court systems continues to see a major request for co-parentng classses for both mandated and non-mandated family members. Extension has been and continues to be a co-presenter for this monthly event. Along with this, there has been a documented need for education for never-married couples who are raising children together in two households. The Co-parenting classes are offered on a monthly basis. Extension is the key coordinator of evaluation for end of program and a follow-up evaluation process.Besides this class, there are also numerous adults responsible for providing a home for children who's parents are not in the picture due to drug addictions, incarceration of mental health issues. The number of adults in this role is increasing.As a result a support group for families entitled, "It's All Relative" has been developed to offer monthly family suppers, child care activities and adult support programs. Extension has worked with the Department of Health and Human Services to offer this monthly support group.

Although current indicators show that the state of the economy is on the upswing, there are still many individuals and families in Madison and surrounding Dane County that struggle to manage their household finances. Reduced earning power due to racial income disparities, layoffs, reduction in work hours and decreased salary and benefits, results in families having to pay more out of pocket for basic needs. For many families and individuals, just one shift in the flow of financial resources (e.g., loss of a job, death of a breadwinner, divorce, or long-term illness) can be detrimental to financial stability and, if persistent, will impact financial security. Low income families are particularly vulnerable because they typically have little or no saving reserves to fall back on when unforeseen expenses arise.As the number of Dane County children growing up in poverty continues to grow, it is highly likely that their care-givers are not financially capable to consistently provide food on a daily basis. According to the United Way, over 16,000 children are food insecure in Dane County. Low income family care-givers struggle to make ends meet as a result of job insecurity; rising food and housing costs and decreasing public assistance programs, and the impact on their children's long-term health and ability to succeed in school is severely jeopardized.

Demographically, the United States continues to grow more diverse and this demographic trend is even more apparent nationwide with the youth population (Chart 1).Chart 1 (Child Trends, 2016)Wisconsin's racial minority population increased 500 percent between 1970 and 2013 including significant increases in Latino/Hispanic, Black/African American and Asian populations (Gordon, 2016). Similarly, the growing number of foreign-born youth and families provide opportunities for 4-H youth development to grow its membership base and reach new audiences. In 1990, census figures showed the foreign-born population at about 121,500; in 2015, that number had increased to nearly 279,000. This represents an increase of 130% over the 25 year span (Long, Jones, & and Ewald, 2017). These audiences are historically underserved by 4-H Youth Development. Families and individuals may lack familiarity with 4-H (knowledge barrier) or unable to access 4-H programs by traditional means (organizational barrier). 4-H Youth Development can benefit by welcoming youth and volunteers from diverse backgrounds. As an organization, UW-Extension needs diversity in its staff, volunteers and learners to effectively participate in an intercultural and global world.The Wisconsin 4-H Community Club program had 29,912 youth (grades 5K-13) enrolled in 2017. Of those youth enrolled in 4-H Community Clubs, 94.7% identified as White (4-H Youth Development State Office, 2018). Given that Wisconsin's population is 86% White according to Census 2010, it is clear that the community club program does not reflect the state's demographic profile (United States Census Bureau, 2010).In 2017, 10,787 adults had been certified as 4-H Youth Development volunteers of those 97.1% of these adults self-identified as White (4-H Youth Development State Office, 2018).In addition to the 4-H Community Club, 4-H Youth Development in Wisconsin offers programs for youth that include 4-H Afterschool programs, in-school enrichment programs, and group educational experiences at camps, demonstrations, library programs and more. In 2017, 27,392 youth participated in these experiences across the state and 82.3% of these youth were identified as White (4-H Youth Development State Office, 2018). Although gains have been made in delivering educational programs to underserved youth through these types of modalities, more effort must be made to provide racially and ethnically diverse 4-H participants with all the opportunities available through 4-H club programs, including staff support, awards, educational trips and scholarships.In April of 2016, National 4-H launched a new campaign aimed at rebranding 4-H as a strategy to increase the number of ethnically and racially diverse youth participating in the program. National 4-H has set their goal high. By 2025, 4-H wants to add 4 million new members and in so doing double the number of African American and Hispanic youth engaged in the program. This goal is especially pertinent in Wisconsin where the state's youth of color face extreme racial disparity across all measures of well-being and could benefit greatly from quality youth development programs. According to the 2016 KIDS COUNT Data Book, Wisconsin ranked 12th among the 50 states in overall child well-being, but persistent challenges hinder children living in immigrant families and children of color, especially African-American, Latino and American Indian children (The Annie E. Casey Foundation, 2018; Kids Forward, 2018). Black children and American Indian children in Wisconsin are more than four times as likely to live in poverty as White non-Hispanic children, and Hispanic children are nearly three times as likely as White children (Kids Forward, 2018). In 2015, a 24/7 Wall Street Special Report listed Wisconsin as the worst state in the nation for Black Americans. Authors citied home ownership, unemployment, and incarceration rates as key indicators of extreme racial inequality (Frohlich, Sauter, & Stebbins, 2015). According to a 2002 study conducted at the Institute for Applied Research in Youth Development, Tufts University, researchers discovered that, compared to their peers, youth involved in 4-H programs excel in several areas. 4-H Youth are:Four times more likely to make contributions to their communities (Grades 7-12);Two times more likely to be civically active (Grades 8-12); Two times more likely to make healthier choices (Grade 7);Two times more likely to participate in Science, Engineering and Computer Technology programs during out-of-school time (Grades 10 - 12); and4-H girls are two times more likely (Grade 10) and nearly three times more likely (Grade 12) to take part in science programs compared to girls in other out-of-school time activities (Tufts University).Adapting what works in 4-H Youth Development programming to the needs of emerging and underserved audiences is a major goal of the Expanding Access Team. We know from recent focus groups conducted with diverse stakeholders that parents are interested in these programs and willing to assist with programming in their communities. In April 2017, 4-H Youth Development was reviewed for Civil Rights Compliance by a team from NIFA-USDA (Hicks, 2017). The review was conducted to determine whether UWEX was complying with the provisions of the U.S. Civil Rights law and USDA's Civil Rights rules and regulations. The team found significant areas for improvement. Serious civil rights concerns include: the ability to collect participant datainequitable access to participate in activities and opportunitiessupporting a diverse and inclusive volunteer basethe absence of a strategic plan for expanding accessthe lack of a diverse and demographically representative advisory group *********************************************************************************UW-Extension and its 4-H Youth Development program are charged with making "all reasonable efforts to reach protected audiences (women and people of racial and ethnic minority groups) with special outreach activities" by Title VI of the Civil Rights Law of 1964, and "expanding access to 4-H opportunities, services and education to groups or segments of the community that have traditionally not been served or are currently not being served by an organization to the same extent as other groups or segments have been or are being served" (Civil Rights Leadership Team, 2012). This law, in and of itself, requires staff to continuously seek ways to reach and make welcome new, diverse audiences. In Walworth CountyReaching Latino/Hispanic audiences is a high priority, particularly in the Delavan-Darien and Whitewater School Districts where they reside in larger numbers than elsewhere. 2012-2013 district demographic data shows that 44.4% of the Delavan-Darien School District students are Latino/Hispanic. Greatschools.org reports that about 32.3% of the Whitewater Unified School District students identify as Latino/Hispanic. The overall Walworth County population is 29.5% Latino/Hispanic.We are fortunate to house the Wisconsin School for the Deaf, which poses unique programming opportunities.Seven school buildings in three communities county-wide serve populations in which 50% or more qualify for free and reduced lunch.With the exception of the past year, during which the Walworth County community club program enjoyed an increase in membership of approximately 50 youth, the trend has been a very slow decline in membership during the last decade. The county 4-H Expansion & Review Committee and county 4-H leadership have set goals to increase community club membership while continuing to reach new diverse youth in creative new ways.Substantial interest in the 4-H community club program exists as evidenced by participation in the county's annual Back-to-4-H Night open house event for potential new families. Participation in 2018 = 101 4-H age youth. Participation in 2017 = 199 4-H-age youth. Efforts to make Spanish-speaking families feel welcome have included making a Spanish language interpreter available throughout the event each year since 2016, and noting the availability of the interpreter on the marking materials directly beginning in 2018. The 4-H Science Lab program was initiated in 2011 and has been a successful means of exposing otherwise untapped audiences to 4-H while establishing credibility as an effective and valued educational partner in the schools; since its inception, the 4-H Science Lab program has resulted in 8871 contacts, 23% of which have been Hispanic/Latino; the program is also one that the Wisconsin School for the Deaf has taken advantage of participating in.The 4-H Ag Technology Day program, held twice in 2014, and once in 2018 creates a welcoming environment for Delavan-Darien School District 4th and 5th graders. As noted previously, district demographic data from 2012-2013 shows that 44.4% of students report as Latino/Hispanic.The Elkhorn OPtions Homeschool Program has a strong presence in Walworth County and has been a proponent and avid user of 4-H outreach in past years.Several summer school programs, a 21st Century Learning Community afterschool program, and several park district and day care programs exist in Walworth County and have reached out to 4-H staff in the past for programming; they remain potential programming partners. WGNHS Strategic Plan requires we "Provide practical learning and training opportunities for the students and teachers of Wisconsin"

Nationally, minorities and immigrants start new businesses at higher rates than non-Hispanic white people despite the fact that minority entrepreneurs face a wide range of challenges, including barriers in accessing information, technical supports in terms of business planning, and financial resources necessary for business startup and growth (Bonds, 2007; Erdmann, 2016; Freeland & Keister, 2016; Kopkin, 2017). Many factors (cultural and social) affect the ability of minority entrepreneurs to interact with and use services offered by public and private organizations such as economic development corporations and financial institutions (Garcia-Pabon & Klima, 2017; Moon et al., 2014; Zarrugh, 2007). These organizations, on the other hand, fall short of adequate in recognizing and reaching out to minorities partly because they are largely staffed by non-Hispanic white employees with limited intercultural experience and communication skills to effectively engage business owners from different racial and ethnic background (Brown & Parkins, 2015; Valdivia et al., 2012). This results in alienation of minorities, disconnecting them from available services in their communities (Hohn 2005; Kelderhouse, 2002; Lamie, 2003).While Wisconsin is not a top immigrant-receiving state nor among the most diverse by race and ethnicity of residents, minority business ownership is skyrocketing here. In 2007, minority residents represented 14.6% of the total population and owned 6.2% of all firms in the state (Obuko & Planting, 2015). From 2002-2007 the number of MBEs in WI increased by 47.5% and their gross receipts increased 77.5%, while the minority population as a whole increased only 13.6% (Obuko & Planting, 2015). The largest number of minority-owned businesses (11,276) in WI were owned by African-Americans (Obuko & Planting, 2015). In spite of these impressive growth statistics, there is no statewide effort to accurately track the numbers or performance of minority-owned businesses. The WI Department of Administration manages the WI Supplier Diversity Program which invites women-owned, racial- and ethnic-minority-owned, and disabled veteran-owned businesses to bid for government services contracts. However, this is voluntary and only benefits certain types of businesses. There are only a few peer-reviewed research efforts that document minority business efforts in WI (Bonds, 2007; Erdmann, 2016; Squires &  'Connor, 2001). Minority ownership data by county exists (2012 Survey of Business Owners, U.S. Census) but has not yet been compared to the working adult population to find parity. Locally, Extension in Fond du Lac County is a founding member of IGNITE! Business Success, an entrepreneurship development system (Lichtenstein & Lyons, 2001) of 16 entities united in a collaborative since 2014. At that time, none of the partners were routinely serving minority-owned businesses, even though they were quite visible in the area and well-established. The partners were also unaware of the scope of demographic change taking place in the county. Specifically, the white population increased by one percent between the last two Census counts (2000 and 2010) while the number of Latino (120%), African-American (43%), American Indian (19%), and Asian (33%) residents of the area increased by double-digit percentages (U.S. Census Bureau). This trend is expected to continue, with all area school districts reporting a minimum of five percent students of color, and 24 percent in the largest district (Department of Public Instruction, 2016). To respond to this situation, I have already:  Coordinated a research project which obtained interviews from 35 minority owners in 2014-2015,   Begun raising issues of equity, access, and race in IGNITE! conversations, teaching the white economic development professionals about the importance of a racial equity lens in our programming Built relationships with additional entrepreneurs of color and begun programming specifically for their needs   Supporting the Regional People of Color Business Association (RPOCBA) based in Oshkosh which has led to opportunities to work with business owners in Outagamie, Winnebago, & Brown Counties.  Submitted an article for publication in the journal Community Development, co-authored by Dr. Joseph Malual (Chippewa, Baron, & Eau Claire Counties). It is still in review as of 2.1.19.As a result of a deeper collaboration with Dr. Tessa Conroy (Madison), Ihave learned that wide and supportive networks are a key to minority- andwomen-owned business success, more than content-based programming. I will framemy work in 2019 from this perspective.

Document_Name: Workforce Preparation and Life Skills Development
Segment: National Data: From the 1990s on, critical job skills identified by employers have included a mix of soft skills and technological acumen. Research shows that cognitive skills like reading, writing and arithmetic and non-cognitive skills such as responsibility, independence, and initiative are important in predicting academic and employment success. These non-cognitive skills are also called "enabling", "soft", "interpersonal", "applied", "workforce", "life", "knowledge economy", "career", or "21st Century" skills depending on which sector is defining them (Garcia 2014). They also need to be independent, learn things on their own, and manage themselves without relying on others. Many students leave high school with the skills to work in jobs that are no longer available in our country. Only one third of graduating students are ready for college, yet in order to earn a decent wage, most will need at least some postsecondary education (Wagner 2008).The American Management Association (AMA), the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) are both national and international in focus. The Definition and Selection of Competencies Project, created by OECD (an organization of 30 industrialized nations) and the Partnership for 21st Century Skills (a group that is comprised of representatives from the business community, education leaders and policy makers) say it is critical for young people to develop 21st Century skills in order to function effectively in today's knowledge-focused economy (AMA 2015) (P21 2015) (OECD 2005).In an article from the Journal of Instructional Psychology, 13 job critical job skills were rated by numerous Fortune 500 companies, with survey response from 1970 and 1997 reported. Topping off the list for 1997 were: 1) teamwork, 2) problem solving, 3) interpersonal skills, 4) oral communication, and 5) listening (Cassel and Kolstad 1998).The 2010 American Management Association Critical Skills Survey Executive Summary reports "employees need to think critically, solve problems, innovate, collaborate and communicate more effectively at every level within an organization." (AMA 2010). A survey conducted by Pennsylvania State University in 1992 to 1993 identified the following qualifications as rating of top importance among 700 employers: oral and written communication skills, interpersonal skills, proficiency in field of study/technical competence, demonstrated ability for teamwork, and demonstrated leadership (Davis & Miller, 1996). A trend noted by Davis and Miller in their research is that businesses are relying more and more on people working in teams.More recent research has also shown teambuilding and communication skills to be of utmost importance to employers, along with problem-solving, decisiveness, and workflow prioritization (Adams, 2014). Ku generalizes the most sought after skills as fitting into three broad categories: life skills, literacy skills, and learning skills, and identifies three popular career tracks as computer systems analysis, computer software development, and civil engineering (Ku 2014). An article in U.S. News & World Report identifies seven skills employers are looking for; these are: social media literacy, critical thinking, sales experience, project management, writing, problem solving, and fluency in computer languages (Graves 2013).A key difference in the expectations of employers going forward revolves around literacy. For today's (and tomorrow's) employers, literacy no longer refers to one's ability to read and write, but also their ability to navigate online communication platforms. Today's youth are born into a world where technology is part of how they learn, communicate, and experience life (Ku 2014).Wisconsin Data: In Wisconsin, the Governor's office has established workforce development goals that serves as the basis for local/regional responses to economic development and workforce needs, including a plan for youth (Department of Workforce Development 2013). The soft skills/life skills previously identified align with the Governor's goals for Wisconsin's "emerging workforce" - youth (Western Wisconsin Workforce Development Board, Inc. 2014).4-H Data: Students gain many skills during school, which is typically a small part of their day. As an out-of-school-time program, 4-H Youth Development has been preparing youth for a successful future for years. With changes in the economy, types of available jobs and technology, 4-H Youth Development can make a valuable impact to successfully prepare youth for postsecondary education and future employment by being intentional about integrating workforce development skills in programs (Cochran et al 2010).Pierce County is a part of the Twin Cities Metropolitan Statistical Area and due to its close proximity to this area there are numerous opportunities to expose young people and adults to a wide variety of job settings. 4-H is a large program in the county and this closeness to the Twin Cities combined with the large numbers of members taking projects and volunteers who work in the Twin Cities area will provide an excellent path for teaching about workforce preparation and how to use life skills wisely to ease into the world of work.
