Topping off the list for 1997 were: 1) teamwork, 2) problem solving, 3) interpersonal skills, 4) oral communication, and 5) listening (Cassel and Kolstad 1998). -The 2010 American Management Association Critical Skills Survey Executive Summary reports "employees need to think critically, solve problems, innovate, collaborate and communicate more effectively at every level within an organization." (AMA 2010).  -A survey conducted by Pennsylvania State University in 1992 to 1993 identified the following qualifications as rating of top importance among 700 employers: oral and written communication skills, interpersonal skills, proficiency in field of study/technical competence, demonstrated ability for teamwork, and demonstrated leadership (Davis & Miller, 1996). A trend noted by Davis and Miller in their research is that businesses are relying more and more on people working in teams. -More recent research has also shown teambuilding and communication skills to be of utmost importance to employers, along with problem-solving, decisiveness, and workflow prioritization (Adams, 2014). Ku generalizes the most sought after skills as fitting into three broad categories: life skills, literacy skills, and learning skills, and identifies three popular career tracks as computer systems analysis, computer software development, and civil engineering (Ku 2014). An article in U.S. News & World Report identifies seven skills employers are looking for; these are: social media literacy, critical thinking, sales experience, project management, writing, problem solving, and fluency in computer languages (Graves 2013). -A key difference in the expectations of employers going forward revolves around literacy. For today's (and tomorrow's) employers, literacy no longer refers to one's ability to read and write, but also their ability to navigate online communication platforms. Today's youth are born into a world where technology is part of how they learn, communicate, and experience life (Ku 2014). Wisconsin Data: In Wisconsin, the Governor's office has established workforce development goals that serves as the basis for local/regional responses to economic development and workforce needs, including a plan for youth (Department of Workforce Development 2013). The soft skills/life skills previously identified align with the Governor's goals for Wisconsin's "emerging workforce" - youth (Western Wisconsin Workforce Development Board, Inc. 2014).Milwaukee County Data:The challenges that many individuals and families in Milwaukee face are complex, with roots in historical segregation and racism, generational poverty, low-quality educational systems and more. Many young people in Milwaukee's most distressed neighborhoods grow up with trauma as a daily reality due to violence, emotional and physical abuse, addiction, lack of support from parent/role model. Additionally, the public school system often does not prepare young people with the skills and/or confidence they need to identify and pursue post-secondary goals. The segregation and lack of understanding of/empathy towards other communities and cultures, as well as what is portrayed by the media, perpetuate stereotypes and misunderstandings that contribute to an overall sense of apathy and hopelessness for too many young people in Milwaukee. It is estimated that 33% of children in Milwaukee County live in households where income in the past 12 months was below poverty level, and 63% of children qualify for free or reduced lunch (www.countyhealthrankings.org/app/wisconsin/2015/measure/factors/24/data). 83% of children in Milwaukee Public Schools meet the federal qualifying standard to receive free or reduced lunch (http://mps.milwaukee.k12.wi.us/MPS-English/CFO/Bud...). Extreme disparities exist when comparing data from Milwaukee Public Schools (MPS) to data for the state. Students attending MPS schools are five times as likely to be truant. 62% of MPS students graduate in four years, compared to 89% at the state level. Of those 62%, only 57% go on to a two or four-year college, compared to 74% at the state level. 13% of teachers in MPS do not hold a license for their assignment, compared to 1.6% for the state. Only 3.5% of FTE in MPS have five or more years of experience, compared to 75.2% at the state level. The suspension rate in MPS is 13.6%, compared to 3.9% for the state. And of those 13.6%, only 59.1% of those that are eligible to return actually come back to school (wisedash.dpi.wi.gov/Dashboard/portalHome.jsp).A Community Needs Assessment (21 stakeholder interview, 4 focus groups with teens) conducted in 2018 revealed the following data/information:  -There are significant gaps in programming for young people between the ages of 18 and 24; most programming ends at age 18 or high school graduation, though many young people are not prepared to pursue post-secondary goals at that point and would benefit from continued programming/support.  -Young people want (and need) programming that focuses on social and emotional development (skills including communication, teamwork, responsible decision making, goal setting, critical thinking, etc.) and job skills.   -Young people want and need connections to both their own communities and communities outside of their neighborhoods; programming needs to expose young people to diverse experiences, people and post-secondary options.   -Strong and trusting youth-adult partnerships are critical to effect and impactful programming.  -Youth voice needs to be infused into program development and implementation.  -Resources and support around mental health need to be available for both young people and youth-serving staff alike. -Greater resources and opportunities need to be dedicated to professional development and training for direct-service staff, including how to develop social and emotional skills through programming, mental health, positive communication, and self-care (particularly for staff).

Ashland County has many local governments, nongovernmental organizations, associations, and civic clubs; many are experiencing decreasing participation as current members age or retire from their roles. Many are looking for new members, new or enhanced functions to attract interest in their missions, and local governmental officials are often unopposed in their elections. These kinds of groups need help finding new roles, new members, fundraising, and enhanced leadership capacity to accomplish goals.

Document_Name: Community & County-based Correctional Systems and Families
Segment: Children learn in the most expected places. For many children, classrooms, childcare settings, and their own homes provide safe and friendly learning environments. Yet, for increasing numbers of young children, unexpected spaces in criminal justice-related settings such as county jail visiting areas are learning spaces. Too often, the learning that occurs in these less than child-friendly environments can be frightening and harmful. These children of incarcerated parents remain largely an invisible population despite being at risk for a host of negative outcomes.Our recent collaboration with UW-Madison and U-MN Pediatrics Department on ground-breaking NIH research studying young children with jailed parents found that young children (aged 3-8) visiting their parents in county jails had increased emotional and conduct problems, hyperactivity, and peer problems than the national norm. Our study also revealed that these young children had delays in developmental milestones, particularly in reading, talking, and listening skills, and waited 24 minutes in the jail lobby before the visit with their parent, and astonishingly, some children waited over 80 minutes.Bringing more literacy and language-rich resources into these children's lives is critical to their wellbeing. Poor readers are more likely to drop out of school and poor literacy undermines job success. And, parents whose literacy abilities are compromised are less likely to be able to help their children succeed academically. Interventions that support the language and literacy skills of children with incarcerated parents are critical.

Volunteers are Forest County's most valuable asset in strengthening the cultural, natural and built systems of Forest County. Expanding the capacity of the volunteer base to include the delivery of quality youth-led, adult guided programs to connect our youth to these systems is necessary to encourage mental-health well-being of both adults and youth of Forest county. In 2018, Forest County had nine adult volunteers registered as 4-H leaders. The demographics of volunteers were 89% female and 11% male with 100% of the volunteers being white. Forest County demographics indicates there is a potential audience of volunteers who reflect several racial and ethnic groups who are currently not volunteering in Youth Development programs including members of the Forest County Potawatomi community and the Sokaogon Chippewa community.The 2018 Forest County Youth Risk Behavior survey states that "31% of Forest County high school students reported that they felt so sad or hopeless almost every day for two weeks or more in a row that they stopped doing some usual activities. This figure represents a 10% increase over the 2016 report."1In addition, Forest County ranked 70 out of 72 in the state of Wisconsin's Quality of Life outcome with adults in Forest County reporting 3.9 days in the past 30 days that their mental health was not good. 2Research has found that "participation in voluntary services in significantly predictive of better mental and physical health, life satisfaction, self-esteem, happiness, lower depressive systems, psychological distress, and mortality and functional inability." Public health experts agree that volunteering should be promoted "as a kind of healthy lifestyle, especially for the social subgroups of elders, ethnic minorities, those with little education, single people and unemployed people". 31. 2018 Youth Health Profile. Forest County Partnership Coalition. 2. Forest County, Wisconsin. University of Wisconsin Population Health Institute. School of Medicine and Public Health. (2018) Retrieved from: http://www.countyhealthrankings.org/app/wisconsin/2018/rankings/forest/county/outcomes/overall/snapshot3. Yeung, Jerf W. K., Zhuoni Zhang, Tae Yeun Kim, Zhuoni Zhang, and Tae Yeun Kim. 2017. "Volunteering and Health Benefits in General Adults: Cumulative Effects and Forms." BMC Public Health 17 (July): 1. Document_Name: Grain Crop Management with an emphasis on Pest Management (2019
Segment: University of Wisconsin-Extension in Door and Kewaunee Counties have an informal agricultural educator specialization agreement whereby the Door County educator provides programming for crops and soils in both counties, and the Kewaunee Agent covers dairy and livestock. Although neighbors, the agricultural environment in Door and Kewaunee County is quite different. Door County is more than twice the size of Kewaunee County, yet Kewaunee County has 45% more acres of harvested agricultural land (86,505 ac in Door County and 134,654 ac in Kewaunee County; USDA Census of Agriculture 2012). Consequently, in Door County, farmers steward 43% of the county's land, whereas in Kewaunee County, farmers steward 81% of the land (S. Deller, Value and Economic Impact, 2012). The types of crops grown in the two counties also varies. In Kewaunee County, dairy farming is the primary form of agriculture, generating $190 million in milk sales. Door County also has a significant dairy industry ($38.5 million in milk sales) and many farmers grow cash crops, but there is much more diversity in the crops grown. Fruit and berry sales generate $4.4 million towards Door County's economy, compared to the $0.36 million in Kewaunee County. Despite these differences, the similar climatic and geological environment, especially between Kewaunee County and Southern Door County makes many Extension programs and research projects relevant to both counties. In 2016, this agriculture educator conducted a needs assessment survey sent to farmers in Door and Kewaunee County regarding their crop and farm management needs. One hundred fifty six surveys were returned (34% response rate), with exactly 2/3 of the responders from Door County and the remaining 1/3 from Kewaunee County. Overall, the number one issue identified was weed management. Disease and insect management were also in the top ten, making pest management overall a top priority. In this survey, farmers were also asked to mark all crops that they grow. Of the 156 returned surveys, 63% of the responders indicated that they grow corn, 60% grow alfalfa, 53% grow wheat, 44% grow oats, and 44% grow soybeans. After that the next highest crop that was marked on the survey was 11% of the farmers indicating that they grow apples and many other specialty crops were listed after that. While many of the agronomic crops are grown for forage, these survey results point out the importance that grain crops (corn, wheat, oats, and soybeans) have to this area. For this reason, it is important to do programming specific to the needs of grain crop production including information on pest management, profitable farming, as well as soil health, agricultural risk management, and marketing. Additionally, the first confirmed finding of glyphosate-resistant waterhemp in Door County in 2017 will make efficient and informed weed management critical to prevent herbicide resistant weeds spreading throughout the county. Given current crop prices, farm stress management is also an emerging priority.

Clark County is a large rural farming county with 92% of its population living in rural environments. Approximately 47% of its births in 2018 were of Amish/Mennonite faith.The isolation and strong rural traditions are a tremendous opportunity for UW-Madison's Division of Extension to become the resource for current information in the county. The mission of UW-Cooperative Extension is to extend the knowledge and resources of the University of Wisconsin to people where they live and work. When people are isolated, the mission becomes even more relevant to the residents lives. Demographic data indicates that Clark County is struggling in some key areas. It is the sixth poorest county in the state which results in a high percentage of children living in poverty. The county has a low high school graduation rate and Clark County also has the lowest percent of individuals age 25-44 with some post-secondary education (43.1%) in the state. In the 18-24 population it is estimated that 37.3% of the population has less than a high school graduation. Only 2.7% of that population has a college degree or higher (U.S American FactFinder, 2015) . The lack of a diploma leads directly to severely diminished opportunities for individuals as well as an estimated $260,000 in lost earnings, taxes and productivity. (Annie E. Casey Foundation, 2010) By 2020, 65% of all jobs, compared to 28 % in 1973, will require some form of post-secondary education, according to a new report from the Georgetown University Center on Education and the Workforce.While these factors warrant action in any regard, Clark County's situation was more pressing for the following reason. Clark County is the state's leading dairy producer. This accomplishment is both good and bad news, for the county's prosperity is invested in a single changing industry and therefore vulnerable, as we saw recently. When Canada changed policy and refused to accept super refined milk from the United States, the county instantly saw more than a dozen local dairy farms on the brink of bankruptcy. Clearly an economy that rests on one leg is vulnerable to any change in the environment. While an economically diverse economy brings stability and new forms of employment, it is also clear that our modern agribusiness is increasingly data and technology driven. Preparing children for educational success by promoting nurturing and healthy environments is crucial to future careers. Reading proficiency among fourth-grade youths across the United States has become a major concern. Approximately two thirds (66%) of all fourth-grade students and 80% of all low-income fourth-grade students in the United States are not reading at their grade level (U.S. Department of Education, 2013). Reading proficiency at an early age is not only vital to improving the quality of life for children in general and at-risk children specifically, it is crucial for sustaining the nation's workforce. The nation's workforce must be composed of literate citizens who have the skills and education required to function in society. However, according to Manyika, Lund, Auguste, and Ramaswamy (2012), the United States is expected to have a shortage of 1.5 million workers with college degrees yet a surplus of 6 million unemployed individuals without high school diplomas by the year 2020. In order to sow the seeds for children's future economic prosperity and societal well-being, a long term goals involving community action towards what I call "Future Ready Families" needs to be initiated. There are three educational vectors that are addressed. Focus on school success and readiness through increased exposure to early literacy and to parenting techniques found in healthy families. Academic achievement is positively associated with the degree to which the parent-child relationship is characterized by parental acceptance, nurturance, encouragement, involvement and responsiveness to the child's needs.  Establish financial literacy in families, because these are correlated to family stability, school success, and post-secondary education probability. Promote lifestyle actions through evidence based programs that help build protective factors and strengthen families and create optimal child development.

Evaluations have indicated that most boaters are already taking action to prevent the spread of AIS. More than 90% of boaters indicate that they are aware of AIS regulations and take action to stop the spread of AIS. However, with new invasions still appearing on the landscape, this means that not everyone is being persuaded by our message. In order to reach that group of water users, new messages and new methods are needed.

In the City of Milwaukee, 28% of people of that an overwhelming 41% of children live below the federal poverty line. In 2017, nearly 43% of children in Milwaukee County received FoodShare (food stamps) and a full 86% of Milwaukee's public school students were determined to be economically disadvantaged. Since 1972 Milwaukee County Extension has provided garden space and educational resources to help all families that seek space to garden. The benefits of community gardening extend beyond food security. Physical Activity has been shown to reduce the risk for chronic health conditions including cardiovascular disease, diabetes, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, osteoporosis, and certain types of cancer (1, 2). In addition, physical activity helps with weight management, improving mental health, and strengthens muscles and bones (1, 2). Physical inactivity has also been associated with increasing the risk for chronic disease (3). According to County Health Rankings, only 86% of Wisconsinites report having access to physical activity, with reporting of the lowest access to exercise opportunities at 2% and the highest at 99%. In addition, 21% of Wisconsin residents report that they get no leisure time physical activity (4).As a member of the Active Communities team, I will strive to increase physical activity opportunities for all members of the community using Active School and Active Communities Strategies, StrongWomen and other evidence-based programs. By using evidence-based programs to increase physical activity in schools and communities, and by increasing access to physical activity opportunities, individuals will have the knowledge and ability to be more physically active to improve their health. In Price County, I will enhance and improve physical activity levels across the community and thus, improve the health and overall quality of life of Price County residents.

Research shows that high quality programs are more likely to foster positive youth developmental outcomes. High quality programs are characterized by 4 key elements: 1) safe, inclusive, and welcoming environment, 2) supportive and caring adults, 3) content that simultaneously challenges and sparks passion and interest, and 4) high levels of youth voice in program decision making. Together, these elements promote youth engagement, and in turn, the developmental and practical skills for youth to succeed. Regardless of the type of program (in-school, after-school, on-going, or sporadic), programs that focus on maximizing each of the high quality elements are more likely to be engaging for participants. These key elements are especially important for 4-H and Extension-based Positive Youth Development programs because each element is within the control of program educators and participants. The elements can change and improve over time. By monitoring and evaluating each of the key elements, program leaders can adapt and improve the program to maximize positive youth development outcomes for all participants. Research with 4-H members nationally has shown that programs that implement these elements contribute to positive developmental outcomes including: 1) academic motivation and success, 2) social competence, 3) personal standards, 4) contributions to others, 5) connections to others, and 6) personal responsibility. In turn, these developmental outcomes in the longer term contribute to increased academic and vocational success, civic engagement, economic stability, and overall wellbeing.In Richland County, there are eleven community clubs and one afterschool 4-H club, with a current enrollment of 271. With a new 4-H club starting in February 2019, enrollments will be slightly over the 278 members in 2018. Although membership remains fairly constant, participation in county and statewide 4-H programs has increased during the past 3 years.During the past two years, 50% (10 out of 20) 4-H club co-leaders are new in that role.

With 29.3% of the population being under the age of 18, Clark County ranks second in the state in this category (County Health Rankings, 2017) According to the Clark County Health Department, currently 42% of all new births are to members of the Amish/Mennonite community. This indicates that the community has a large percentage of families with children or families with many children. However, Clark County cannot be simply classified as a "young" county because of its unique age distribution The County substantially exceeds the state in the share of population under 18 years old (29%) and share of population 65 and over. To put it simply, Clark County has a lot of children and a lot of elderly compared to the rest of the state. Part of this unique and somewhat strange dynamic is caused by a tangible Amish population. The Amish are generally associated with high birth rates and consequently, a young population. The high share of a population 65 or older is typical of rural counties.Clark County is the sixth poorest county in the state. The median household income is $43,147 which is $10,000 less than the state of Wisconsin average income with 14.9% of the population living below the Federal Poverty Line. The percentage of children in poverty is significantly higher than the state average (rank: 61 of 72) with 22% of children living in poverty and 38% of children eligible for free lunch program. Clark County is 95.9% white with a small but growing Hispanic population in the north eastern parts of the county. This number is still lower that the state of Wisconsin's average of 6.2% Hispanic population. The county shows its interesting diversity with the statistic it is ranked second in the state for percent (14.6) speaking language other than English at home just behind Milwaukee County. The other language is primarily German spoken in the Amish homes.Overall, Clark County residents face barriers to professional, quality care that other Wisconsinites do not. Brain health in children is also being recognized as a critical issue in our country. Research indicates that poor children are disproportionately exposed to factors that may impair brain development and affect cognitive, social, and emotional functioning. These risks include environmental toxins, inadequate nutrition, maternal depression, parental substance abuse, trauma and abuse, violent crime, divorce, low-quality child care, and decreased cognitive stimulation (stemming in part from exposure, in infancy, to a more restricted vocabulary).As of 2017 Clark County only had one psychiatrist for its 34,713 residents. Clark County has been designated as a mental health shortage area by the state of Wisconsin Health Department. Residents have also voiced concern. Clark County residents expressed their concern for mental health/behavioral health in the community health improvement planning process (CHIPP) where residents chose mental health as one of its priority areas of work. This is most relevant since farm stress and suicide rates have risen over the past few years as the farm economy has continued to suffer low profits due to issues outside of their control. This financial stress is felt throughout the family unit.

A Community Food System Team was launched in 2012 for two complementary reasons. First, Extension leadership saw it as a topic amenable to interdisciplinary work that might break down the "silos" dividing our four Program Areas at that time. Secondly, Extension staff statewide were responding to constituents who were passionate about solving food-related problems. Many understood that these problems had systemic causes, and that solutions required collaboration across boundaries delineating traditional academic disciplines as well as public vs. private entities; urban vs. rural communities; and those who have power from those who don't. Furthermore, the Team brought together colleagues who focused on different elements of the food supply chain: food production, processing, distribution, marketing, consumption, and waste management. Unfortunately, Extension's "team" structure has always had great limitations. Typically, team leaders volunteer their time in small, sporadic increments. There are usually no expectations or incentives for them to pursue external funding to support team programming. Without funds to support new products and activities, it can be difficult to keep colleagues, partners and constituents engaged. A notable exception was the Emerging Agricultural Markets (EAM) Team of the former ANRE Program Area, which garnered nearly $700,000 over ten years via a Senate appropriations process that is no longer tenable. The highly flexible funding attracted consistent participation from both ANRE and CNRED staff, plus specialists from DATCP's Marketing Division. The team trained 26 Agricultural Innovation Counselors; published a 135-page Guide for Direct Market Meat Producers and a 109-page Guide for Agricultural Entrepreneurs; sponsored an annual statewide conference; and supported a score of county-specific initiatives. Even with significant funds, EAM Team leaders often lacked the authority or status to engage with other institutional entities. The time they could give to team leadership was constrained by other duties. Leadership turnover also became a problem. These limitations have hampered other teams throughout Extension.The "graduation" from Team to Program offers tremendous potential for Community Food System programming. Having a dedicated Manager, with decision-making authority and outcome expectations, should provide the consistent leadership that has eluded the Team structure. As an official unit of Extension, the Program should enjoy opportunities to partner with other campus and external entities in grant proposals. Furthermore, if a needs assessment and/or strategic planning process is undertaken in 2019, and truly engages campus, county and regional Extension colleagues, it could articulate a concrete vision for CFS programming that will guide our collective work for years to come. Notes from two meetings at last December's Extension conference, and dozens of private conversations with colleagues over the past six months, are my evidence that this new Program is sorely needed and highly anticipated. I expect it will enjoy a period of generous participation by colleagues and external partners who have long seen the need for Extension to step up its role in developing food systems that more effectively meet the needs of people living and working in communities throughout Wisconsin.

Multiple layers of wellness choices make up a healthy life - healthy eating habits, physical fitness, positive social interactions and relationships, a healthy and balanced inner life, and the avoidance of risky behaviors. Each of these layers is connected to and impacts the others. For young people, the ability to maintain a healthy life is further influenced by internal beliefs and personal practices as well as their environment - the community, school and home in which they live.  Acknowledging the interconnectedness of all layers of health to make up a healthy life, the Living Healthy Team operates in three primary areas:   Nutrition and physical activity - including fitness, nutrition, safety, sexual responsibility, general hygiene, and adequate sleep Social-emotional well-being - including youths' sense of confidence, self-efficacy, emotional regulation, self-reliance and optimism, empathy, connection, contribution, ability to lead a team, teamwork, appreciation of cultural diversity, and civic responsibility Furthermore, the nationwide mission mandate of 4-H Youth Development is to expand participation among youth and their families in the dynamic process of healthy living, so they are physically, socially, and emotionally prepared to meet the challenges of the 21st century.Nutrition & Physical ActivityNationally, in 2015, 13.9% of high school students were considered obese while an additional 16% were overweight, based on body mass index. More than 14% of high school students got less than 60 minutes of physical activity, with significantly higher rates of sedentary lifestyles among females (17.5%) than males (11.1%). Nearly half (45.6%) of high school students indicated they were trying to lose weight at the time of the survey. The rate is much higher (60.6% among females). Screen time is a significant factor. Time spent playing video games or on computers for more than 3 hours per day has increased to 41.7% in 2015, up from just 31% in 2011. Looking at nutrition, in 2015, during the 7 days before the survey was administered, 14% of high school students did not eat breakfast, 5% did not eat fruit or drink 100% fruit juice, and 7% did not eat vegetables. Since 2005, drinking of both milk and soda declined. However, in 2015, only 78.5% of high school students reported drinking milk and 73.8% reported drinking soda. The 2017 Wisconsin Youth Risk Behavior Survey shows that student rates in each of these areas are consistent with the national statistics. According to The Trust of America Health Project, in 2016 the combined overweight and obesity rate for children between the ages of 10 - 17 is 29.5%, raking 31 of the 50 states. (Centers for Disease Control & Prevention, High School Youth Risk Behavior Survey (2015): https://www.cdc.gov/healthyyouth/data/yrbs/results.htm and Trust for Americas Health https://stateofobesity.org/states/wi)Finding ways to support healthy habits including good nutrition and physical activity starts at an early age. Young people in 4-H Youth Development programs explore a range of food choices and learn more about how exercise can help their bodies grow strong and healthy. Furthermore, older youth take on leadership roles in teaching about and advocating for healthy options. They become camp counselors and leaders in other programs where they can encourage younger children to live an active lifestyle.Pepin County has ranked in the top ten counties in the past 3 years on its health rankings, although has dropped in the past three years. In 2015 Pepin County ranked 2 out of the 72 counties in Wisconsin, and in 2016 ranked 5 out of 72. According to 2017 County Health Rankings data Pepin County ranks 8 out of the 72 counties, with an adult obesity rate of 34% compared to the state average of 31%. According to the State of Obesity report for Wisconsin the data for Pepin County between 25% and 30% of youth are overweight or obese compared to the WI child obesity rate of 22% According to the 2017 Health Ranking report for Pepin County, 26% of the county residents are physically inactive, compared to 20% statewide. 59% of Pepin County have access to exercise opportunities, compared to a Wisconsin rate of 81%. Diabetes rates in Pepin County are at 12% compared to the WI diabetes rate of 9.8%, that would be 470,136 cases in 2010 in Wisconsin. (State of Obesity report for Wisconsin)Physical Inactivity in Pepin County has increased from 2004 to 2014, from 21% to 26%. When that is compare to Wisconsin they are higher, Wisconsin which is 20% in 2004 to 21 % is in 2014. (University of Wisconsin Population Health Institute-Health Rankings)Positive youth development is a crucial element in developing life skills including communication, conflict resolution, and personal management as well as critical ways of being such as self-esteem, self-responsibility, and managing feelings. Youth development programming that intentionally builds confidence and competence in these life skills helps prepare young people to make healthier choices for themselves and their bodies

"Families are a cornerstone for raising responsible children who become caring, committed contributors in a strong democracy, and competent workers in a sound economy[1]." In one statement, Karen Bogenschneider, former director of Wisconsin's Family Impact Seminars, summarizes decades of research about the significance of families in our American culture. The Center for Study of Social Policy[2] reports five research-based protective factors that lead to stronger families, optimal child development and reduced child abuse and neglect. These five protective factors are parenting knowledge and skills, social connectedness, parental resilience, concrete supports in times of need, and the social-emotional competence of parents and children. Families are not responsible to create or ensure these protective factors entirely on their own. The environment or community and societal context in which families exist also play a major role in strengthening families by promoting protective factors. This is supported by Bronfrenbrenner's ecological theory of human development[3] which outlines the impact of interpersonal primary relationships, connections between home and primary community settings (school, work, etc.), partnerships between and among community entities that support families, and the effects of many systems, policies and cultural or contextual factors. In addition, individual biological factors such as mental illness or chronic disease, and even temperamental traits, can influence how parents navigate their roles as manager, nurturer and child developer.Strengthening families who are raising children in Marquette County and Wisconsin is a core concern of Extension's Human Development and Relationships Institute. In Marquette County, key informant interviews affirm the need for Extension efforts to sustain existing parent education and support efforts and develop new ones as capacity allows. Parent leaders, parent program participants, and professionals working with parents increasingly look to Extension for parenting resources, information and education. Marquette County Human Services provides one full-time in-home parent mentor and one-half time community response worker. Marquette County Health Department offers well-baby visits. Head Start, the public schools and a few churches offer occasional educational programs. Childcaring, Inc. is the lead agency for Parent Cafs. These efforts, and Extension's efforts to strengthen families by addressing protective factors across the ecology of child development, constitute the sum total of parenting education resources in the county.The low-income nature of Marquette County and the rural, relatively isolated geographic location make it challenging to develop additional programs and services that would strengthen and support families, such as family resource centers, afterschool programs, mentoring programs, and home visitation. Marquette County has no hospital, limiting access to hospital-sponsored parenting programs to those who will travel out of county. Marquette County has no community foundation, no United Way, and no private foundations that award grants of $20,000 or more. To complicate this further, U.S. Census data indicate that the majority of Marquette County residents living in poverty are our younger population, including children and young adults in their developmental years, and adults bearing and raising children. Of our 1,362 households with children under age 18, 13-19% are living in poverty[4]. Poverty is major risk factor for child abuse and neglect and puts children at risk of achieving optimal development. Two hundred and two (202) grandparents are raising their grandchildren under age 18, largely due to parents' incarceration, mental illness or substance abuse disorders. Twenty-five (25) of these parents live under the poverty line[5]. The United Way of Wisconsin's 2016 ALICE (Asset Limited, Income Constrained, and Employed) report indicates that approximately 41% of Marquette County households struggle to afford the basic necessities of housing, healthcare, childcare, food, and transportation.[6] These include households that earn more than the Federal Poverty Level, but less than the basic cost of living for Marquette County.Because many basic parenting programs and supports would be missing in Marquette County without Extension, the situation must reflect the need for Extension to sustain existing efforts and look for ways to partner or fund new programs. Digital parenting educational resources are available, but Marquette County Extension's capacity to implement these are hampered by time constraints. Nevertheless, parent use of technology to access parenting resources is critical and will be addressed as time allows this year.[1] Bogenschneider, K. Demographically, the United States continues to grow more diverse and this demographic trend is even more apparent nationwide with the youth population (Chart 1).Chart 1 (Child Trends, 2016)Wisconsin's racial minority population increased 500 percent between 1970 and 2013 including significant increases in Latino/Hispanic, Black/African American and Asian populations (Gordon, 2016). Similarly, the growing number of foreign-born youth and families provide opportunities for 4-H youth development to grow its membership base and reach new audiences. In 1990, census figures showed the foreign-born population at about 121,500; in 2015, that number had increased to nearly 279,000. This represents an increase of 130% over the 25 year span (Long, Jones, & and Ewald, 2017). These audiences are historically underserved by 4-H Youth Development. Families and individuals may lack familiarity with 4-H (knowledge barrier) or unable to access 4-H programs by traditional means (organizational barrier). 4-H Youth Development can benefit by welcoming youth and volunteers from diverse backgrounds. As an organization, UW-Extension needs diversity in its staff, volunteers and learners to effectively participate in an intercultural and global world.The 4-H Community Club program had 29,912 youth (grades 5K-13) enrolled in 2017. Of those youth enrolled in 4-H Community Clubs, 94.7% identified as White (4-H Youth Development State Office, 2018). In 2017, 10,787 adults had been certified as 4-H Youth Development volunteers of those 97.1% of these adults self-identified as White (4-H Youth Development State Office, 2018). Given that Wisconsin's population is 86% White according to Census 2010, it is clear that the community club program does not reflect the state's demographic profile (United States Census Bureau, 2010).In addition to the 4-H Community Club, 4-H Youth Development in Wisconsin offers programs for youth that include 4-H Afterschool programs, in-school enrichment programs, and group educational experiences at camps, demonstrations, library programs and more. In 2017, 27,392 youth participated in these experiences across the state and 82.3% of these youth were identified as White (4-H Youth Development State Office, 2018). Although gains have been made in delivering educational programs to underserved youth through these types of modalities, more effort must be made to provide racially and ethnically diverse 4-H participants with all the opportunities available through 4-H club programs, including staff support, awards, educational trips and scholarships.In April of 2016, National 4-H launched a new campaign aimed at rebranding 4-H as a strategy to increase the number of ethnically and racially diverse youth participating in the program. National 4-H has set their goal high. By 2025, 4-H wants to add 4 million new members and in so doing double the number of African American and Hispanic youth engaged in the program. This goal is especially pertinent in Wisconsin where the state's youth of color face extreme racial disparity across all measures of well-being and could benefit greatly from quality youth development programs. According to the 2016 KIDS COUNT Data Book, Wisconsin ranked 12th among the 50 states in overall child well-being, but persistent challenges hinder children living in immigrant families and children of color, especially African-American, Latinx and American Indian children (The Annie E. Casey Foundation, 2018; Kids Forward, 2018). Black children and American Indian children in Wisconsin are more than four times as likely to live in poverty as White non-Hispanic children, and Hispanic children are nearly three times as likely as White children (Kids Forward, 2018). In 2015, a 24/7 Wall Street Special Report listed Wisconsin as the worst state in the nation for Black Americans. Authors citied home ownership, unemployment, and incarceration rates as key indicators of extreme racial inequality (Frohlich, Sauter, & Stebbins, 2015).According to a 2002 study conducted at the Institute for Applied Research in Youth Development, Tufts University, researchers discovered that compared to their peers, youth involved in 4-H programs excel in several areas. Adapting what works in 4-H Youth Development programming to the needs of emerging and underserved audiences is a major goal of the Expanding Access Team. We know from recent focus groups conducted with diverse stakeholders that parents are interested in these programs and willing to assist with programming in their communities. In April 2017, 4-H Youth Development was reviewed for Civil Rights Compliance by a team from NIFA-USDA (Hicks, 2017). The review was conducted to determine whether UWEX was complying with the provisions of the U.S. Civil Rights law and USDA's Civil Rights rules and regulations. The team found significant areas of improvement. Serious civil rights concerns include:  the ability to collect participant data inequitable access to participate in activities and opportunities supporting a diverse and inclusive volunteer base the absence of a strategic plan for expanding access the lack of a diverse and demographically representative advisory groupIn Washburn County, about half of the students in public schools are economically disadvantaged. Over half of the students in Washburn County school districts have been economically disadvantaged at least three of the last five years (Northwood School District) or four of the last five years in the other three districts (Department of Public Instruction WiseDash School District Data, 2018). Race and ethnicity data show that the number of non-white students has grown over the last five years in each district, while there are fewer total white students in all but the Shell Lake school district. Of non-white students in the public schools, youth of Hispanic descent are the most prevalent with 68 (3%) accounted for in the most recent data, and American Indians are the second most prevalent with 48 (2%.) 120 students (5%) in the county are two or more races. Employees with the St. Croix tribe have indicated that not all youth with Native American descent are accounted for in this data because the tribe requires a person to be 1/8 blood quantum to claim Native American ancestry. There are students that report that they are fully white because of this. There is also a larger population of Native Americans (24%) in the Hayward School District; while Hayward schools are located in neighboring Sawyer County, the school district services also Washburn County youth. Looking at the traditional 4-H Community Clubs, two youth identify as Asian, one identifies as Hispanic, two identify as two or more races, and three are unreported, of 103 youth registered for 4-H clubs in 2017-2018 . 3/36 adults chose not to identify their race and the rest were white. The community clubs program doesn't represent the growing diversity of race and ethnicity that Washburn County has.

Segment: (Due to having one month remaining on my contract, it was suggested I write a one page summary of my work plans for Feb. The one page plan is under the Action Plan heading.)

Each year one in six Americans get sick and 3,000 die from food borne illness. Some of the most common food borne illnesses include E.Coli, Salmonella, Listeria and Norovirus. Statewide tracking and reporting systems, such as the Wisconsin Public Health Profiles, have information on communicable disease, including food borne illness, by county. According to the most recent profile (2017), Salmonellosis and Campylobacter enteritis were the most commonly reported food borne illnesses in Fond du Lac County. Food borne illnesses are primarily prevented through proper hand washing, food handling and preparation and food storage.

Dane County is home to a growing diverse population that faces many challenges. Between 2000 and 2010, the county's total African American population increased by almost 50%. The 2013 Race to Equity Report outlined drastic disparities between segments of the county's population. For example, 74% of Dane County's children of color were poor, compared to 5.5% of white children. Dane County's juvenile justice numbers also show disparities that are wider than those found elsewhere in the state or nation. Teens of color in Dane County are six times more likely to be arrested than whites. Similar disparities apply to many other statistics including academic performance, unemployment, and health rates between residents of color and white residents. Dane County is also home to a large segment of Wisconsin's Hispanic population that has increased by 127.8% from 2000 to 2015. Spanish-speaking residents also face many socioeconomic disparities related to lack of services opportunities provided in their primary language.Dane County UW-Extension is uniquely situated to engage in programming to support underserve Dane County's residents. Many local organizations rely on UW-Extension's partnership for access to direct education, community connections, and other resources to carry out programs that reach underserved populations. It is likely that UW-Extension will make a difference to address racial disparities due to its track record of partnering with organizations to carry out programming year after year. By creating capacity for local organizations to provide programming to the community, UW-Extension extends its impact in the community to provide educational programs to underserved populations.

In 2014, University of Wisconsin-Extension gathered feedback from Oconto County community members by executing a Family Living visioning process. The top critical needs identified and challenges facing Oconto County residents include; economic uncertainty, poverty and underemployment. The objective of financial security begins with establishing stability, or ability for a family to make ends meet. For many families and individuals, just one shift in the flow of financial resources (e.g., loss of job, death of spouse, divorce, or chronic illness) can lead to significant negative financial suffering. Evidence that there is a need for financial education programs to improve financial capability sills is shown in Wisconsin based on the 2015 FINRA Financial Capability Survey, which collected data from people in each state to measure financial behaviors, attitudes and knowledge (See http://www.usfinancialcapability.org/results.php?region=WI).  47% find it very/somewhat difficult to cover expenses and pay billso 51% do not have 3-month emergency savingso 28% pay the minimum due on credit cardso 21% have past due medical billso 16% spent more than earned over past yearThese statistics suggest there is ongoing financial insecurity in the state, potentially signaling the need for supportive educational programing. However, Wisconsin is not alone in this respect, in general people in this state reflect regional and national trends. Family Financial Security programming will help people to improve their financial management capability. This will enhance the financial security of families in the state, which will benefit communities by boosting economic stability and contributing to a foundation for economic growth.

The coterminous boundary of Menominee County/Reservation delineates 235,000 acres total, 233,000 of these acres in trust status. 217,000 acres are in commercially forested lands - the majority of which is under sustainable forestry management practices. It is home to four unincorporated rural communities, to include Native Americans and non-native residents who live on fee land. Flowing wildly through Menominee land, the Wolf River is known for its waterfalls and pristine waters. Lakes and wetlands are integral to the landscape. Menominee is rich with the Native tradition of respect for the land.The population of Menominee County is approximately 4,615 according to the 2018 US Census QuickFacts. 82.4% is Native American, 11.7% White, .9% African American, 2.6 Asian, and 2.5% Two or more races. Although this is a relatively small population, there is an abundance of needs in the community that can be addressed through UW-Extension Family Living Programs. Traditionally, family and social organization is very important in the Menominee culture. Children are considered to be gifts and are cherished as such. Elders in the Native American community are valued for their wisdom and are often given a place of honor in ceremonies and community gatherings. They hold the aspects of the culture within them and are the teachers of the "old ways", including speaking and teaching traditional Menominee language. Situation 1: Unfortunately, there are other factors at play within the Menominee County/Nation community, including startling health statistics - 39% of births for which the mothers smoked during pregnancy, the impact of ACE's (Adverse Childhood Experiences) and historic trauma with an estimate from the Menominee Indian School District of many youth having an ACE score of 7 or higher, alarming levels of alcohol and drug abuse, 36% of adults smoking (Z-score was capped at -3.0/3.0 due to population <20,000), 43% of adults obese, and teen pregnancy (highest teen birth rate at 101 per 1,000 births). These and other statistics have led to Menominee County consistently ranking 72nd out of 72 counties in overall health outcomes (University of Wisconsin's Public Health Institute).This educator and the 4-H Youth Development Educator held a series of Talking Circles in 2018 to discover what parents and caregivers felt their greatest needs were. Talking Circles are a local practice that is used to share, get ideas, and solve problems openly. Trends emerged through these talking circles - parents and grandparents need support in parenting strategies and coping with the stress of parenting, caregivers and youth need support in the area of social-emotional health, youth need additional opportunities for safe physical activity and recreation, families need opportunities to learn and play together to support family relationships, alcohol and other drug abuse are a serious community issue, and youth need to learn Menominee language and culture. UW-Extension is uniquely poised to address many of these issues through health related and family relationship programming.

The 2017 estimated population of Grant County is 51,999 people, with 96.5% being white, 1.4% Hispanic, and 1.4% black. It has a slightly higher percentage of people aged 65 and older (15.6%) than Wisconsin as a whole and a lower percentage under 18 (21.3%) as compared to Wisconsin as a whole (23.6%). It is a rural county with a population density of 43 people per square mile and experienced a minimal (0.42%) growth rate in the last decade. Grant County has a poverty rate of 15.4%, higher than the 12.5% state average. The medium household income is $49,067, which is well below the national average of $56,516. The child poverty rate is 17%, also higher than the Wisconsin rate of 16%. In Grant County, the proportion of the population receiving FoodShare increased from 2.8% in 2000 to 14.7% in 2015. In Grant County during the same period, the share of school-age children certified for free or reduced price meals grew from 27% to 45%. These economic statistics along with priority issues determined by Grant County UW-Extension needs assessment completed in 2015/16 has assisted in setting a framework for the Grant County Family Living Program.In 2015-2016 Grant County UW Extension partnered with the Survey Research Center (SRC) at the University of Wisconsin at River Falls to conduct a county wide needs assessment. Programming priorities on topics related to the family are more evenly distributed than for any of the other Extension programming areas. There are no clear top priorities for family-focused programming, but the overall average level of importance attached to these topics was higher than all other Extension programming areas. There several topics that about half or more of the respondents felt were very important: personal finances (saving/investing for the future, budgets, debt, credit reports, etc.), child development, identity theft, caring for aging family members, healthy lifestyles (nutrition, physical activity, social and emotional health), coping with family transitions, communication and relationship building. In a comparison with the 2015/16 needs assessment over previous efforts ranked a higher awareness or concern in regards to health & well-being over parenting practices gathered from open ended questioning as noted in the following bullet points.  Discuss and plan how to deal with incursion of drugs, gangs, and crime in Grant County.   Expand substance abuse programs possibly through the court system.  Mental illness treatment for Grant County residents.   Programming for healthy living, lifestyle behavior change, and healthy decision making.  Promotion of health of all aspects i.e. food, physical, mental, relationship, etc.  Find out why cancer is so prevalent in this county.  Healthy lifestyles.After careful consideration of priorities and needs of Grant County, the determined priority program efforts will focus on building community capacity supporting and building family financial security and economic well-being, building family strengths, improving parenting supports and practices, and promoting healthy lifestyles while strengthening the collaborative efforts of all agencies serving families improving outcomes for children, families and society.The profound influence of families on society makes evident the importance of supporting and strengthening families. Issues' relating to parenting or the strengthening of families is nothing new for Grant County UW Extension, but often takes on new forms as parenting issues change with the times. Whether looking at families seeking basic parenting skills, support and prevention of AODA issues or child abuse, families struggling with divorce, couple relationships, connecting to community, or spending quality time together; citizens of Grant County are concerned about families enduring ongoing challenges that remain a fact of life. It is also apparent within Grant County that even though families remain the primary place where children are raised there is increasing evidence that the task is shared by others, and that "care giving is everyone's business."Program Priority #1As highlighted in the Family Financial Security State Team Plan of Work financial security is the goal for many Americans. Financial security is defined as an individual's or family's ability to meet short-term needs and to prepare for the future. The path to financial security requires accessible and accurate information, as well as financial competency in setting goals, earning, spending, saving, borrowing, and protecting. But it is not enough to just provide learners access to these concepts. Families would benefit from an increased ability to manage cash and credit so that they may not only make ends meet day to day, but also begin to set aside resources for emergencies and to reach future goals. However, access to financial education and information is still limited for many households. In addition, many seminars provided by financial services are not affordable for low- to moderate-income families and individuals, nor do they provide objective unbiased information. While about half of Wisconsin schools offer personal finance, most do not require it and few adults graduated at a time when schools offered such programs. Evidence that there is a need for financial capability skills is shown in Wisconsin based on the 2015 Financial Capability Survey from the FINRA Foundation. Beyond efforts in public schools, families critically need support during "teachable moments" such as when starting a new job, taking out a loan, buying a house, or beginning retirement. This is continually communicated throughout Grant County Family Living Agents communications across the county with parents, teachers and agency partners. Many wanting an easy one time fix, however as noted in the state plan of work, one recent report highlights the limited impact of financial education on increasing positive financial behaviors, while suggesting financial coaching as an approach to increase behavior change. Grant County Family Living Educator has incorporated financial coaching techniques working with learners in order to facilitate self-guided learning resulting in increased personal awareness and positive financial capability behaviors. More work needs to be done to refine how to access Grant County consumers during these key times and to develop better forms of delivering information for various audiences. Over the years the Grant County UW Extension Family Living has successfully partnered with organizations across the county leading to building financial capacity as a way to improve their household financial management capability enhancing their personal financial security benefiting communities by boosting economic stability contributing to a foundation for economic growth.One standing partnership includes a tri county planning team of 11 School Districts (Belmont, Benton, Cuba City, Fennimore, Highland, Iowa Grant, Lancaster, Mineral Point, Platteville, Potosi, Southwestern) in the annual SWIFLE Event (Southwest Wisconsin Financial Literacy Event). This interactive event involves youth participating in accounting, financial literacy, etc. courses in the 2018/19 school year in the above mentioned schools. Over 60 volunteers are utilized at the individual stations from choices on housing, purchasing a car, groceries, paying child care, utilities, investments, etc. - the volunteers keep it real making it fun and interactive. The event allows youth to get a glimpse at what lies ahead in the "real world." UW Extension Family Living Agent's role at this time is the continued yearly planning partnership, assisting in updating station sheets, attaining volunteers, and facilitating the event.Other partnerships and referrals include the Work n Wheels program through SWCAP & Head Start, Department of Social Services Wisconsin Home Energy Association Program (WHEAP), Family Promise of Grant County, Inc., the Grant County OWI/Drug Court, Unified Community Services, Grant County Taskforce on Homelessness, as well as individual referrals. Financial coaching skills are strategically utilized and the online UW Extension Financial Building Blocks Money Matters as part of the new pilot group under increasing individual credit worthiness - https://fyi.uwex.edu/moneymatters was newly incorporated in the fall of 2017.

The need for this project is demonstrated by data compiled by the Kindergarten Readiness Network (KRN) of Higher Expectations for Racine County Youth. The Network maintains a dashboard of the PALS (Phonological Awareness Literacy Screener) to determine the number of children enrolled in RUSD's 4K program who meet or exceed spring literacy benchmarks.According to Wisconsin DPI, "Wisconsin teachers use PALS to identify students at risk of developing reading difficulties, diagnose students' knowledge of literacy fundamentals, monitor progress, and plan instruction that targets students' needs." Based on the findings, not all students are coming in ready for kindergarten - both academically and social-emotionally.In the spring 2016-17 school year, approximately 68% (1,015) of all RUSD 4K students entered kindergarten ready to learn. Wide disparities of literacy achievement existed based on race/ethnicity and income level. For example, 85% of White, non-Hispanic students met the literacy benchmark compared to only 49% of African American/Black students and 57% of Hispanic students. Only 56% of economically disadvantaged students met the literacy benchmark compared to 87% of non-economically disadvantaged students. As a result, the Network is looking at ways to improve kindergarten readiness in RUSD so that 98% of 5K students enter kindergarten ready to learn.

The County Health Rankings and Roadmaps rank Menominee County as the least healthy county in the State of Wisconsin. This tool ranks length of life, quality of life, health behaviors, clinical care, social & economic factors, and physical environment for all 72 counties in Wisconsin. The following variables show the community and health disparities in Menominee County as compared to the State of Wisconsin according the 2018 County Health Rankings and Roadmap:Variable Menominee County Ranking Wisconsin Ranking Premature death 15,000 6,000 Adult obesity 45% 31% Children in poverty 41% 16% Access to exercise opportunities 2% 86% These rankings have impacted the community positively as they have created a sense of urgency. Service providers are motivated by the rankings and with help from the University of Wisconsin Madison, created the Menominee Wellness Initiative. The Menominee Wellness Initiative is a partnership between local service providers and UW-Madison and the group uses a collective impact approach to addressing the need. Language, culture, and traditional food systems are increasingly being recognized as a different approach to overall wellness. In response to work that is being accomplished by the Menominee Wellness Initiative, UW-Extension applied for and received a Center for Disease Control grant that focuses on local systems changes to address obesity. This innovative grant provides support for addressing the built environment, policy changes, and the creation of a food hub within Menominee County and the Menominee Indian Reservation. The grant addresses work that the Menominee Wellness Initiative has been discussing and has not had the resources to address. This educator's work will focus on specific outcomes of this grant for the next five years.

St. Croix County continues to attract Twin Cities residents in pursuit of the rural lifestyle. Most own small acreages and work off the farm. Demand for information on beef, sheep, goat, and other livestock enterprises is growing with these small farms. These livestock enterprises also complement cash grain enterprises, and are transition enterprises for exiting dairy farms. Per the 2012 Census of Agriculture, St. Croix County is home to 353 beef farms, representing over 6,000 head (updated census data expected in 2019). Close proximity to the Twin Cities offers direct marketing opportunities, but also creates challenges in legally crossing state lines with product. Many of these smaller enterprises, and non-dairy enterprises, do not draw as significant interest from private agri-business. This dynamic can create more demand from Extension to support these enterprises. Dairy continues to be an important sector of the local ag economy. A prolonged downturn in dairy prices has placed significant financial pressure on local dairy farms. Wisconsin Ag Statistics service reports indicate St. Croix County lost on average one dairy farm per month in 2018. Challenges with the quality of feed harvested in 2018, particularly corn silage, is reducing daily milk production at this time. Many new rural landowners don't know what ag enterprise they want to pursue, and do not know the harsh realities of the farm business. As the agricultural landscape changes in St. Croix County flexibility will be needed to address emerging farm financial management issues, such as land rent and enterprise budgeting. Farm management concepts often times require one-on-one teaching efforts. With an aging farm operator population, more producers are looking for information on farm succession planning and/or exit strategies during challenging financial times. As St. Croix County experiences continued urban development, urban / rural conflicts will increase. At this time allowable land uses (ag vs. housing, agri-tourism is not permissible in much of the county) and water quality are the leading issues. Forage production and grazing are closely related production topics for animal agriculture. These are topics I intend to continue being involved in, although not necessarily as a primary program affiliation.

According to Michael Delli Carpini of the Pew Foundation, in the past three decades, two thirds of our American 18-25 year olds do not even vote (excepting the last 3 presidential elections). Carpini argues that habits of citizenship and civic engagement develop early in life, and are hard to change later on. The danger of this is that a disengaged youth becomes a disengaged adult. Thus, a thirty year decline in civic engagement bodes ill for our local and our national community. Locally, this trend manifests itself in aging boards and councils. In addition, a majority of seats in our local elections go uncontested. In order to counter the trend pointed out above, in accordance to UW-Extension and 4-H youth development goals, and in response to the wishes of the Ashland County Ag and Extension committee and community leaders, it is imperative that Ashland County youth be given opportunities and encouragement to develop public leadership skills and experience. UW-Extension Youth Development and 4-H have echoed both the concerns and the importance of focusing on youth leadership development among other top priorities for educational programming. Since 2006, Ashland County UW-Extension 4-H Youth Development has developed and implemented the following programs to provide leadership development and opportunities for local youth to lead:  Teen Court Program Superior Days Legislative forum in Madison School-based leadership training program (3-12th grade, longitudinal, average 3 program contacts per year for 345 students in the Ashland School District)  4-H Ambassadors leadership training program, including leadership training for volunteer camp counselors at 4-H Summer Camp, a 4-H Winter Camp, and other programs including opportunities to run workshops for younger students and opportunities to speak to 21 grade school classes each spring.This is just a sample of leadership development programs that have been put into place during my tenure as the Ashland County 4-H Youth Development Educator. This past year I added planning for, supporting and guest teaching in a full-year, 1 credit high school leadership class at Ashland High School. The need for the class was determined by a group of concerned school administrators, teachers, coaches, and community leaders (including UW-Extension) who met for 18 months to explore the need and establish an educational response. The planning and execution of the class includes teaching the skills outlined in the 4-H life skills model for leadership development, and opportunities to practice leadership taken from the new Illinois leadership competencies model. UW-Extensions role has become more important in local youth leadership development as school budgets have shrunk over the past 8 years and many or most of the district based leadership development opportunities have fallen by the wayside due to budget cuts.
