The Outreach Staff at Wehr Nature Center have a contract with the Milwaukee County Parks in order to provide Environmental Education programming with in the Metro Milwaukee Area. Pop-Up Nature is a brand new program model that we developed and piloted in 2018. This program was designed to be a drop-in program meant for busy families that still wanted a nature experience. Each Pop-Up Nature is a two hour experience which includes a seasonal-themed hike, hands-on activities, and personal interaction with a staff naturalist. To make Pop-Up Nature more accessible in 2019 it will be offered in five additional park locations.

Document_Name: Supporting Economic Development in the Area
Segment: Our local EEC committee continues to prioritize, direct and support our work in economic development in our region. This is based on the position listening session that was held with key stakeholders for the CRD position here in the county. Juneau County has seen phenomenal changes in key economic indicators in the past 8-10 years in the area of lower unemployment, higher per capita incomes, and in new job creation. In the past the county has had unemployment figures as high as 13-14%, as compared to the current rates of less than 3%. The continuation of business counseling, starting a business classes, assisting in business financing with banks or RLFs funds, and strategic planning for businesses and organizations continue to be key areas of work for the CRD position within the county.

The UWEX ERC AIS Program helps coordinate the work of the larger Wisconsin AIS Partnership, a group of ~75 professionals that work on AIS issues across the state. In late 2016 it was announced that the DNR grant program that funds many of these partners was going to change - instead of fewer larger, competitive grants, the program would shift to more contracts for smaller amounts. This will hopefully provide consistent AIS services across Wisconsin and reduce the patchiness that was previously seen under the competitive grants program. This new program is currently called the AIS Prevention Network.UWEX is in a position to help provide consistent training to AIS Prevention Network and to help existing AIS partners work across jurisdictional boundaries to implement a consistent program. In areas where this is no program, UWEX could provide AIS Prevention Network services.

The number of Green Lake County residents estimated to be living in poverty is 12%. The median household income of the county is at $50,276. The combination of these two data sets contributes to an increased number of 'working poor' in the county. Green Lake County residents are suffering from a higher than [state of Wisconsin] average rate of unemployment (5.0%). Unemployment has been shown to increase unhealthy behaviors related to alcohol and tobacco consumption, diet, and physical activity. In the last eight years, there has been an increase in children living in poverty in Green Lake County (15% to 19%). The Green Lake County Agriculture, Extension Education, & Fair Committee has expressed a high need for financial literacy education within Green Lake County. The needs arises, as students are not receiving this type of education during their schooling, which creates a cycle of generations who do not know how to manage their money or budget properly. Often times, financial instability can have broad health impacts, including increased risk of mortality, poor health, and increased cardiovascular disease risks.

Families perform a variety of key functions that contribute to both the mental and physical health of individuals as well as the public health and functioning of society. Throughout all developmental stages, from the prenatal period to the last years of life, strong healthy relationships help families effectively and efficiently raise healthy children, care for vulnerable members, and sustain productive workers and contributing community members.Children who are born into and raised in an environment of positive relationships have a strong foundation that can help them develop into healthy adults and productive citizens. This environment of relationships involves not only parents and children but also extended family and social networks, schools and childcare providers, and others who engage with the family. Stable, nurturing relationships have a powerful protective impact on children. They help prevent exposure to multiple risks and stressors, including family violence and neglect, parental incarceration, and mental illness. Exposure to these stressors is associated with numerous poor outcomes, some of which are commonly seen across multiple generations within families and are very costly to society. In addition to contributing to prevention, safe, stable, nurturing relationships with parents and other caregivers serve as a buffer to help mitigate the damaging impacts of toxic stress. Healthy relationships help children thrive. Adult health and well-being also depend in great part on the quality and success of relationships. Adults in stable relationships have better health outcomes, greater financially stability, a greater sense of well-being and improved capacity to provide care for vulnerable family members, including children and older adults. It has long been understood that a strong parent/child relationship is a key factor in preventing negative outcomes for children. More recent research suggests that strong relationships between parents and other adults, including romantic partners, friends and extended family, can help prevent child maltreatment and improve the capacity of adults to parent effectively. Healthy relationships help adults nurture.
I was given the task of writing a Strategic Plan for Outreach in 2018 which I have done.

Many of the towns, villages, and cities in St. Croix and Polk Counties are struggling to attract and retain young families and qualified workers. This has become very apparent from discussions and work done by economic development organizations in the region (e.g. Momentum West, St Croix EDC, Pierce Co. EDC, Polk Co EDC, Chambers of Commerce, and education institutions. This presents a two-sided problem: 1) have accurate and timely information to effectively market a location, and 2) have the right information and data to diagnose and correct local problems related to economic development goals. While several data dashboards exist that focus on socio-economic data, I have seen few that do it with an explicit purpose in mind and none that interpret the data in a meaningful way. This program aims to rectify this problem. It will draw upon similar existing programs in Extension services in other states, different data guidelines form various EDOs, and internal knowledge and expertise within UW Extension. The output will be an education program that will teach local economic developers, government leaders, and businesses learn about sources of data, interpretation of data, and effective use of data. In addition, this education program will aim to produce regular education materials that focus on various topics related to economic development which maybe use in newspaper articles, teaching events, or marketing campaigns. The outcome will be local municipalities that can better understand and manage their situations to become more prosperous and experience desired growth.

Document_Name: Family Economic Security and Financial Literacy
Segment: Financial security is the goal for many Americans. Financial security is defined as an individual's or family's ability to meet short-term needs and to prepare for the future. The path to financial security requires accessible and accurate information, as well as financial competency in setting goals, earning, spending, saving, borrowing, and protecting. But it is not enough to just provide learners access to these concepts. The long run objective of financial security begins with establishing financial stability, or the ability to make ends meet. For many families and individuals, just one shift in the flow of financial resources (e.g., loss of a job, death of a breadwinner, divorce, or long-term illness) can be detrimental to financial stability and, if persistent, will impact financial security. These shocks to resources can be the impetus for significant negative financial outcomes including, in some severe circumstances, personal bankruptcy. Families would benefit from an increased ability to manage cash and credit so that they may not only make ends meet day to day, but also begin to set aside resources for emergencies and to reach future goals. However, access to financial education and information is still limited for many households. In addition, many seminars provided by financial services are not affordable for low- to moderate-income families and individuals, nor do they provide objective unbiased information. While about half of Wisconsin schools offer personal finance, most do not require it and few adults graduated at a time when schools offered such programs. Evidence that there is a need for financial capability skills is shown in Wisconsin based on the 2015 Financial Capability Survey from the FINRA Foundation.Beyond efforts in public schools, families critically need support during "teachable moments" There is a shortage of objective financial education on cash and credit management and risk management. One recent report highlights the limited impact of financial education on increasing positive financial behaviors, while suggesting financial coaching as an approach to increase behavior change.[1] UW-Extension financial educators are encouraged to use financial coaching techniques with learners in order to facilitate self-guided learning resulting in increased personal awareness and positive financial capability behaviors. Barron County stakeholders have identified theses teachable moments and the lack of financial education and success. Participants working through the drug court program are required to get a job and for many this is the first time they have held a job that was needed to support their families. Along with Drug Court incarcerated individuals have also been identified as an opportunity to provide financial education and change. Without my engagement in this education these programs would be lacking financial education. In many cases these are under served audiences and my involvement allows education to those who might not otherwise seek it out.The current need for financial supports in the state is evidenced by the 2015 FINRA Financial Capability Survey, which collected data from people in each state to measure financial behaviors, attitudes and knowledge (See http://www.usfinancialcapability.org/results.php?region=WI).  47% find it very/somewhat difficult to cover expenses and pay bills 51% do not have 3-month emergency savings 28% pay the minimum due on credit cards 21% have past due medical bills 16% spent more than earned over past yearThese statistics suggest there is ongoing financial insecurity in the state, potentially signaling the need for supportive educational programming. Wisconsin is not alone in this regard; in general, people in this state reflect regional and national trends.

Multiple layers of wellness choices make up a healthy life - healthy eating habits, physical fitness, positive social interactions and relationships, a healthy and balanced inner life, and the avoidance of risky behaviors. Each of these layers is connected to and impacts the others. For young people, the ability to maintain a healthy life is further influenced by internal beliefs and personal practices as well as their environment - the community, school and home in which they live. Acknowledging the interconnectedness of all layers of health to make up a healthy life, the Living Healthy Team operates in three primary areas:  Nutrition and physical activity - including fitness, nutrition, safety, sexual responsibility, general hygiene, and adequate sleep Social-emotional well-being - including youths' sense of confidence, self-efficacy, emotional regulation, self-reliance and optimism, empathy, connection, contribution, ability to lead a team, teamwork, appreciation of cultural diversity, and civic responsibility  Prevention of alcohol, tobacco and other drugs (ATOD) Furthermore, the nationwide mission mandate of 4-H Youth Development is to expand participation among youth and their families in the dynamic process of healthy living, so they are physically, socially, and emotionally prepared to met the challenges of the 21st century.Social-Emotional HealthSuicide is the 2nd leading cause of death for young people ages 10-24[1] and the national suicide rate among all ages has been rising for more than a decade. For every suicide death in Wisconsin, there are 11 hospitalizations or emergency department visits for self-inflicted injuries. Wisconsin's teen and young adult population have the highest rates for self-inflicted injury.[2] Statistics like these point to low social and emotional wellness among young people. A further concern is that many of the counties with the highest suicide rates coincide with those having the highest numbers of Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs).[3] Many of those counties are rural as well, just one of many indicators of a growing rural health disparity.According to the 2017 Wisconsin Youth Risk Behavior Survey,[4] reports of electronic bullying are increasing - 16.6% in 2011 to 18.4% in 2017. Likewise, 27% of high school students reported feeling sad or hopeless for more than 2 weeks in a row, up from a low of 20.4% in 2009. Nearly 1 in 5 (17%) high school students reported having hurt themselves purposely without wanting to die, self-harm being a coping strategy for many young people who don't have other, healthier strategies available to them.Alcohol, Tobacco and Other DrugsChallenges with high ACE scores and poor mental health have a significant impact on the choices young people make around alcohol, tobacco, and other drugs. According to the Wisconsin Youth Risk Behavior Survey (YRBS), the smoking rate has decreased from 29% in 2005 to 11% in 2017. Similarly, the rate of marijuana use has also decreased from 7% in 2005 to 5% in 2017. However, a growing trend is the use of electronic vapor products, which was at 11% in 2017. Similarly, youth rates of alcohol use has decreased overall, but the early age of onset (having their first drink of alcohol other than a few sips before age 13) increased from 14.6% in 2013 to 15.5% in 2017, the first increase since 1999. Youth rates of prescription drug misuse - an important precursor to use of street drugs like heroin - have also decreased; yet 1 in 10 youth report having taken prescription pain medications differently than the doctor's recommendation. While the use of alcohol, tobacco and other drugs in Wisconsin is reportedly decreasing, trends within these statistics must be addressed. Local Situation StatementIn Buffalo County the local situation is similar to that of the state and national data. A developmental situational analysis conducted in UW-Madison's Division of Extension Area 9 (Buffalo, Jackson, Pepin and Trempealeau Counties) yielded a top priority for mental health and drugs (particularly opioids and meth). These findings mirror those that contributed to a 2017 Comprehensive Health Improvement Plan (CHIP) in Buffalo County focusing on increasing mental health screenings and trainings for QPR and mental health first aid. In addition Buffalo County's newer developed Criminal Justice Services Department and Coordinating Council have placed increased emphasis on the connections between mental health, addition and recidivism; introducing more opportunities for restorative justice measures with the adult population. Buffalo County school districts also received mental health grants in 2018-2019 academic year to focus on trauma-informed education, including mindfulness, social emotional learning and wrap-around services. Moreover, in 2018, an estimated 25% of youth enrolled in summer programming in Buffalo County in 2017 had at least one adverse childhood experience with the top ACE's being drug addition, neglect, poverty and witnessing family violence. There has also been a reported uptick in self-harm with elementary and middle school youth and an increase in students seeking school psychologists (all of which are contracted services at schools in Buffalo County).The data from the aggregated Buffalo County 2017 Youth Risk Behavior Survey for both middle school and high school illustrate a growing need for mental health services and use of meth and opioids among students. Buffalo County UW-Extension, Law Enforcement, Social Workers and their coalition have contributed to the kNOw Meth campaign in 2018 and plan to expand resources and educational experiences in 2019. The extent of meth use in Buffalo County has more than quadrupled in the last three years and there has been an evidenced increase in child neglect and child placements in foster care as result of meth use in Buffalo County. The prevalence led the department of Human services to hire two new social workers in 2018 and The use of e-cigarettes among young people has also risen significantly nationally and in Buffalo County. A student survey of vaping/juuling use indicated that nearly 75% of middle and high school students know a friend that vapes. The number of vaping teen court referrals rose from zero in 2017 to fourteen in 2018. There has been a direct ask for Buffalo County Extension Educator to work in collaboration to tackle what the CDC has labeled as an "epidemic."Similarly, local school administration and human services have sought out the expertise of Buffalo County Extension Educators in digital photo sharing and social media safety. As "sexting" has implications for young people as a risk behavior that significantly contributes to mental health, this continues to be an area of concern and programming in Buffalo County. Wisconsin is shifting its AIS program to focus on invasion pathways as opposed to individual species. This shift will help identify how AIS are moving into and throughout the state while helping the WI AIS Partnership develop actions to reduce the number propagules in transport. Historically, AIS programs have spent most of their effort addressing the recreational boater pathway and have spent some effort addressing organism in trade (OIT) pathways. This shift in focus should allow Wisconsin to address and close previously unaddressed pathways.Addressing pathways involves a lot of applied research combined with partnership building and collaboration. These are all things that UWEX is in a strong position to help facilitate.

In the Spring of 2018, County Board Chair Sharon Corrigan assembled a team of supervisors and staff to develop a plan of action to guide the County Board's efforts in inclusive engagement. The initiative is called "Engage Dane". The goal of Engage Dane is to put in place a variety of approaches for regular and inclusive engagement across the continuum from awareness to partnership. County government is responsible for many and diverse services, including public safety, human services, lake management, planning, and transportation. County Board members must be conversant in both a variety and a changing range of issues. EngageDane will provide fact sheets with background information to share with constituents at meetings or via newsletters or social media. County Board members will also be trained in inclusive engagement, and provided with resources to use inclusive engagement strategies. The 2019 inclusive engagement plan is to focus on select issues and develop skills and practices in inclusive engagement: a) County jail, b) Youth Justice, c) Lake Levels/Flooding, d) Biogas, e) Human services (Department highlight), f) Water Quality/nutrient management. Extension Dane County (2 Educators - Sharon Lezberg & Mindy Habecker) have been involved in the development of the initiative and drafting the initial report and toolkit worksheets. We will continue to be engaged in the pilot project implementation throughout 2019. The role that this educator will play in the initiative is detailed under action plan.

Historically in Iron County, a northern county bordering Lake Superior and the Upper Peninsula of Michigan, the most popular forms of outdoor recreation included motorized and sportsman activities. Today the Iron County Department of Forestry hires a trail coordinator as well as two recreations maintenance staff, and collectively their primary responsibilities are maintaining motorized trails and county parks. However, in recent years the Forestry Department has shown some interest in non-motorized trails, the first project being a set of groomed trails near a county park. This development occurs alongside the establishment of a nonprofit group called the Iron County Outdoor Recreation Enthusiasts (ICORE) which serves to promote silent sport activities and opportunities throughout Iron County. Infrastructure projects require significant amounts of time and energy, and involve multiple years and partners to achieve outputs. With the development of Michigan's statewide non-motorized Iron Belle Trail just outside the eastern edge of Iron County, the City of Hurley aims to extend this non-motorized trail through its downtown and westward into the neighboring City of Montreal. There is also a set of non-motorized trails in the City of Montreal that is in need of new leadership and maintenance as of January 2019. Extension Iron County has an opportunity to support these developments by facilitating necessary processes, connecting and recruiting engaged stakeholders, and building general community awareness on the benefits and possibilities of non-motorized trail development in the Iron County area.

The Coastal Training Program is dedicated to providing opportunities for local decision-makers to learn about the factors that influence coastal systems, think critically about the role that they play in coastal management, and cultivate skills and confidence that will allow them to be intentional about taking actions that result in mindful management of our estuaries and Western Lake Superior coast. In alignment with Reserve priority issues, CTP is broadly supportive of coastal programming around habitat and water quality, climate change adaptation, land and development impacts on water, and enhancing connection to coastal places and spaces. Program development for CTP is driven in part by opportunistic partnerships, but core program themes are thoughtfully guided by needs assessment work and Reserve priorities, which are reflected in the program's Strategic Plan, the Reserve Management Plan, and various NOAA reporting metrics. A gap analysis of programs was conducted as part of the 2012-2016 needs assessment and a survey of programmatic and informational needs was administered to the target audience in March 2017. This needs assessment work has provided a baseline for the program's topical focus areas, delivery methods, and an understanding of participant motivations.The findings of the 2017 survey revealed that decision-maker stakeholders are most concerned about climate change impacts, adaptation and resilience; water quality issues; overdevelopment of shorelines and habitat; erosion; and invasive species. They also identified financial constraints, organizational capacity, and social and cultural resistance to change as the largest barriers to making progress on coastal community issues in their work. Professional development opportunities that address how to work with the public to create behavioral changes, how to incorporate scientific research into policy development, and how to access data, graphics and information were of highest interest to respondents. The most convenient training formats are online courses, webinars, demonstration programs and field trips, and seminars. Expert speakers, networking opportunities, informational materials, and certification are the most effective incentives for encouraging participation.

According to the ALICE report compiled by United Way (https://www.uwiw.org/sites/uwiw.org/files/ALICE%20Report%20Wisconsin.pdf), 15 % of Walworth Counties residences were living in poverty and 29% are considered ALICE (Asset Limited, Income Constrained, Employed). The report breaks down a bare-minimum budget (without savings) that would be needed to survive in Walworth County. For a single person to survive in Walworth County, the person would need to make $25,968. This is far above the $11,670 that is allowed to be considered at the Federal Poverty Level. A family of 4 (two adults, one preschooler and one infant) would need to make $58,836 to survive in Walworth County. Again this is far above the Federal Poverty Level budget of $23,850. In addition, economic conditions were ranked in three core areas with an index of 1 (worse) to 100 (best). Walworth County Ranked in the "poor" category for each of these conditions: housing affordability (score of 30), job opportunity (score of 50) and community resources (score of 38). Walworth County residence understand that without a good knowledge of basic financial capability many of these families are not able to meet basic needs. In February 2015, Walworth County UW-Extension worked with UW-River Falls to conduct a needs assessment. Eight of the top ten issues were the same in the public respondents and volunteer/client respondents, albeit in a somewhat different order. Both groups identified issues related to economic wellbeing (financial skills, job training/development, workforce readiness), family issues (cyberbullying, family financial management) and personal well-being (fitness, outdoor activities, emotional health). The #1 rated item by the public and volunteer/client respondents was financial skills for the future. Family financial management was rated at #7 by public and #8 for volunteer/client respondents. Among the "Home and Family Issue" questions, the number one rated issues was family financial management, the fourth was affordable housing (rated 28 by the public and 35 by volunteer/client respondents overall) and the seventh was landlord/tenant relations (rated 47 by the public and 52 by volunteer/client respondents overall).Our financial security team's plan of work has outlined the importance of financial security for families. Financial security is defined as an individual's or family's ability to meet short-term needs and to prepare for the future. The path to financial security requires accessible and accurate information, as well as financial competency in setting goals, earning, spending, saving, borrowing, and protecting. But it is not enough to just provide learners access to these concepts. The FFS Team promotes financial capability more broadly, which includes how learners apply what knowledge they have combined with access to financial products and services, prior experiences, attitudes and behaviors. (See Figure 1)Families would benefit from an increased ability to manage cash and credit so that they may not only make ends meet day to day, but also begin to set aside resources for emergencies and to reach future goals. However, access to financial education and information is still limited for many households. In addition, many seminars provided by financial services are not affordable for low- to moderate-income families and individuals, nor do they provide objective unbiased information. While about half of Wisconsin schools offer personal finance, most do not require it and few adults graduated at a time when schools offered such programs. Evidence that there is a need for financial capability skills is shown in Wisconsin based on the 2015 Financial Capability Survey from the FINRA Foundation. Adult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 10,500 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2017, volunteers reported on average they donated over 54 hours per year. Approximately 70% of Wisconsin 4-H volunteers are female and 30% are male. Nationally, women continue to volunteer at a higher rate than men. (Bureau of Labor Statistics U.S. Department of Labor.) In Wisconsin 4-H, approximately 97% of the volunteers are white. WI 4-H Youth Development volunteers currently do not reflect the demographics of most counties.Locally, Brown County is home to a total of 17 active 4-H Community Clubs, making 4-H a strong part of the fabric of the community. Total enrollment, in both traditional and special interest clubs throughout the county, in 2017-18 over 1,100 youth, with 60% of the members participating in community clubs. Aside from community club programming significant programming began to be offered in 2013 in an additional area: school enrichment /afterschool programming, STEM Saturday programming and summer camps. In 2017-18, more than 480 students participated in 4-H programming in the afterschool/out of school time programming. In 2018, Brown County had 169 youth and adult volunteers. Brown County demographics indicate there is a potential audience of volunteers who reflect significant and multiple racial and ethnic groups who are currently not volunteering in 4-H Youth Development (ES-237 Data, 2013-14). In Brown County, the volunteer-to-member ratio is 1:15. Without the valuable contributions of volunteers, the 4-H Youth Development program simply would not exist.As programming options for Brown County 4-H Youth Development have expanded, so have the needs to recruit, retain and engage volunteers in different capacities. Brown County 4-H Youth Development brought on new volunteers to engage in community clubs, but also hired part time, limited term employees to be the liaison between 4-H Youth Development and the 4-H Afterschool program, with employees being trained in youth development and afterschool curriculum, and them being the face of the afterschool program. Taking a new and fresh look at Youth Development, specifically in an urban setting, various levels of adult involvement and staffing patters are required. 4-H Youth Development, however, is not the only organization in Brown County that relies on local volunteers to develop and implement programming. With over hundreds of non-profit, tax exempt organizations throughout the county, volunteers are in high demand. Moreover, qualified and trained volunteers are increasingly important. The face of the volunteer is changing, as well. Volunteers in the past were long-term volunteers, many of whom helped to start the programs they volunteer in. The world of volunteering has changes in the past 10 years, and to remain competitive, organizations need to adjust the way they recruit, train and manage volunteers. As reported by the U.S Bureau of Labor Statistics (2015), volunteer participation rates nationwide have declined steadily over time, showing only 24.9% of adults indicate they are volunteering. That is nearly 1 percentage points since 2013, leaving This is the lowest volunteer rate reported since the survey and data were collected, beginning in 2002. In addition, the research shows that men are less likely to volunteer (21.8%) versus women (27.8%)Thus, the demand on volunteers in any program have shifted and become more taxing and demanding. To fully address the needs of current volunteers, organizations, including UW-Extension and 4-H Youth Development, need to provide adequate training, support and materials to allow volunteers the ability to fulfill their changing expectations and demands. In addition, organizations must adjust recruitment strategies and techniques to appeal to the shorter-term, busy volunteers that are willing to help, but not necessarily commit one's life to an organization. Research by Thomas McKey, a published author on volunteerism, indicates that volunteers in the 21st century demand flexibility, the use of technology and competence. In addition, volunteers are busy and want to be assured that by taking time out of their schedule will not just make a contribution, rather, will make a difference.The value of volunteers is recognized throughout Wisconsin, the nation and internationally. When organizations consider the economic value of a volunteer, the time donated by volunteers is astronomical. The dollar value of a volunteer hour in Wisconsin is $24.69 (Independent Sector, Value of Volunteer Time, 2018). If a typical volunteer donates 50 hours per year to an organization (many of them donate many more hours), the value of time given to Brown County 4-H Youth Development is nearly $208,630 annually. As the program success of 4-H Youth Development program depends on the building and maintenance of volunteers, time and effort need to be dedicated to volunteer recruitment, development, training and support. As detailed in the 2008 National Learning Priorities: Volunteer Development for the Next Generation Knowledge and Skill Rubric and Syllabus paper (Pleskac et al, 2008), "building the individual capacity for volunteerism in paid staff will lead to increase organizational capacity". In addition, "educating and empowering volunteers to assume or accept service or volunteer roles will help improve and build volunteer capacity and competencies" (2008). The philosophy of volunteer and staff development can be seen in practices throughout Wisconsin 4-H, including professional development opportunities for staff, volunteer leader training and development, and statewide volunteer forums for education, support and recognition of 4-H Youth Development volunteers. However, it is also noted that the amount of time staff actually has and dedicated to volunteer development and management is less than it should be to be most effective and prepared for the needs of volunteers. Volunteers play a critical role in the delivery of quality educational programs. In a survey completed January 2015, 4-H Youth Development staff identified Volunteer Development as an area in need of program support. Additionally, a WI 4-H Youth Development Survey was conducted in February 2014 of over 1500 volunteers. Adult volunteers in 4-H indicated relatively low awareness and understanding of some of the educational principles (Essential Elements and the Experiential Learning Process) that are central to the work of 4-H Youth Development. In the 2014 survey, volunteers expressed an interest in learning through not only face-to-face modalities; but also through online-learning such as webinars and podcasts. The 2017 Strategic Plan released by USDA NIFA and National 4-H Council outlines a 4-H Youth Development Vision for 2025. Nationally the following goal has been established "Youth are surrounded with competent, prepared staff and volunteers." This goal includes the following outcomes:"The 4-H program is supported by a well-trained volunteer force.""4-H staff and volunteers engage in meaningful professional development."In addition, there is a responsibility of volunteers to ensure access, equity and opportunity. The National 4-H Strategic goal states "All youth engage in program and opportunities." To that end it has been identified that "4-H volunteers and staff are skilled, knowledgeable and prepared to work with all members of their community." Youth experiences in an organization are directly affected by adult leader relationships and expectations. As non-profit organizations, and to ensure they are fulfilling the mission of Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development, and effectively be a catalyst for positive community youth development, organizations should be welcoming, inviting environments where learning and growing can occur. To strengthen the effectiveness of volunteers throughout Brown County, volunteers must be confident and well-equipped with essential tools, resources, and knowledge to teach and lead activities that strengthen the youth development experience (Wisconsin 4-H Volunteer Leader Development, 2008)

Since 1992, UW-Extension's Local Government Center has been considered the go-to resource for local officials seeking information and guidance on the proper rules, procedures and policies for doing the position they have been elected or appointed to. This work is highly regarded by the Institution, county-based educators and the three major local government associations in the state.

The Center for Community and Economic Development was designated as a U.S. Department of Commerce Economic Development Administration University Center (UC) in 2016. In 2019, I will continue pursuing the work plan that we submitted as part of our designation. Part of this research agenda is detailed under my major program titled: "Addressing Labor Force Quantity and Quality in Wisconsin." Another major component of this work plan includes addressing the need for understanding regional industry concentrations and diversity. This research component is based on the demand from regional economic development organizations (EDOs) and the Wisconsin Economic Development Corporation (WEDC) in researching opportunities and challenges related to industry clusters. Specifically, WEDC and regional EDOs all base components of their economic development strategies on understanding how they can assist specific categories of industries to become more successful and sustainable. As with labor force issues, we can address this need using our research capacity and educational programs.

Talking Circles are a culturally responsive spiritual method of gathering input from community members while providing opportunities for safe-space sharing. Four Talking Circles were held with 19 participants in various locations on the reservation with 5 mothers, 2 non-mothers, and 12 grandmothers. 4-H Youth Development Educator and UWEX colleagues discovered the following themes regarding inter-generational families who are active members in the Menominee 4-H Clubs on the reservation and local community members:  Need for Cultural Programming - traditional Native American arts & crafts, storytelling, songs, dances Youth leadership opportunities   Addressing trauma and bullying through Native healing practices   Sustain Menominee 4-H through fundraisers and promotional events   Provide opportunities for low-cost physical activities with active parent engagement- sports, tournaments, revitalizing swimming and park areas Promote family based activities - Outdoor movie nights in the park and game nights Address transportation barriers with low-income families   Partner with local organizations to support 4-H Find ways to address negative issues facing the Menominee community - AODA, DV, homelessness, young mothers

Document_Name: Nitrogen Use Efficiency Field Trials and Educational Workshops
Segment: Discovery Farms established its nitrogen use efficiency (NUE) Project in 2015, and from 2015-2017, we collected NUE data from over 50 participating farms across six regions of WI. Through this time, we refined field methodology and results messaging while working with farmers and their corn production practices. This process provided participants with individualized insights into how corn nitrogen (N) management can be altered to achieve economically efficient yields while reducing N losses to the environment. Additionally, over time, this project accumulated enough data to create WI NUE benchmarks, which are now used so that farmers can assess how their individual NUE values compare to those in WI and determine how they can improve their NUE.The goal of the NUE Project is to transform NUE into an effective and viable self-evaluation tool of nitrogen management for farmers, crop consultants, advisors and other agricultural and water specialists. One way to accomplish this was to partner with local extension and natural resources agencies to teach them the NUE field trial methodology and monitor NUE with partnering farmers. In 2018, Discovery Farms began a three year-long partnership with local agency in Sauk, Pepin and Dunn counties for NUE monitoring. These NUE field trials will continue into 2019. Additionally, the NUE project is launching an NUE workshop series, which will be held in 4-6 locations throughout WI. These workshops are designed to train farmers, crop consultants and advisors on how to implement NUE self-evaluations on their fields, analyze their results and determine future management decisions. The workshop series serves both as a research and an educational tool, as it will facilitate the collection of more NUE data which will add to Discovery Farms' NUE dataset to make benchmarks more representative and accurate, and will share important findings related to NUE and N management with our target audience.
