To that end it has been identified that "4-H volunteers and staff are skilled, knowledgeable and prepared to work with all members of their community." At the November 2017 Waushara County Annual Leader Training: "Cultivating an Environment for Growing True Leaders", only 25% of the 35 volunteer leaders in attendance were familiar with the Essential Elements: Mastery, Independence, Belonging and Generosity. At the November 2018 Waushara County Annual Leader Training: "All Together, Not All The Same", there has been improvement as 40% of the volunteer leaders in attendance were familiar with the Essential Elements.

Many regional groups exist to coordinate the work of AIS programs. I am currently the second term co-chair of the Mississippi River ANS Panel, a member of the Great Lakes ANS Panel Outreach Committee and participate in their "Blue Accounting" working group for demonstrating collective impact, I help coordinate the NCRWN AIS Working Group, and I am a member of the Great Lakes Sea Grant Network AIS working group. Being involved in all of these working groups allows for a two-way flow of information that can help us all be more efficient and obtain additional resources to accomplish our goals.

The FLE will continue to focus on financial capability in families this upcoming year. Access to financial education and information is still limited for many households.The support for such programming began the fall of 2013, where a Visioning Session was held to identify community-based issues in Waupaca County. The category, "Family Financial", received the most number of "high priority" votes. In the 2013 Community Health Improvement Plan (CHIP), there was identified need for "free or affordable classes for families with limited resources" such as classes on budgeting, checkbook balancing, and other classes related to long-term financial security. It was also indicated that "limited education has been provided by UW-Extension". The rationale behind the interest in financial security was in part drawn from the 2017 County Health Ranking's data, taking into consideration variables that can affect families and individuals' abilities to make ends meet: 1) percentage of children in single-parent households (245%), 2) percentage of population with at least some college education (55%), and 3) living in a county with an unemployment rate that matches the country average (4.1%). All these factors influence income-earning potential Family Living state teams in Extension have strong financial programming that continues to evolve to fit consumer needs. In Waupaca County, there are no other organizations that offer financial education for the general public. Thus, the FLE can offer many opportunities for community members.

Wisconsin's AIS outreach is largely implemented by the broader Wisconsin Aquatic Invasive Species Partnership. The WI AIS Partnership is a broad group of professionals representing federal, state, and local government, universities, and nongovernmental organizations that all work on AIS issues. Led by the University of Wisconsin-Extension and the WDNR, the Wisconsin AIS Partnership implements AIS outreach programs statewide.A number of key prevention and outreach programs are administered through the Wisconsin AIS Partnership, including:Clean Boats Clean Waters: our education-based watercraft inspection program coordinated by UWEX-Lakes that comprised of paid inspectors and citizen volunteers The Drain Campaign and the 4th of July Landing Blitz: two targeted outreach campaigns coordinated by UWEX that use community-based social marketing principles to inspire boaters to take sustainable behaviors Project RED and Snapshot Day: two citizen science efforts coordinated by the River Alliance of Wisconsin that provides AIS monitoring data on Wisconsin streams Citizen Lake Monitoring Network: a citizen science effort coordinated by UWEX-Lakes that trains citizens to monitor their lakes for AIS and other water quality metrics'The Wisconsin AIS Partnership holds two in-person meetings each year, and has opportunities to meet at the Wisconsin Lakes Convention and during other online meetings. These meetings combined with a Wisconsin AIS Partnership email list and file sharing service are the primary means of communications for the Wisconsin AIS Partnership

During the course of 2018 I sought to engage business owners for feedback in Forest and Vilas Counties as often as I could. Coordinating with the Vilas County Economic Development Director, I conducted 23 business retention visits in eastern Vilas County as a follow up to the survey of 150 businesses that I had done in 2017. I engaged economic development boards of both Vilas and Forest County - including directors, board members and business people as often as possible to gather input on their thoughts about business and economic development. I helped a private citizen - along with a small team - to prepare and hold an event we collectively called the Northwoods Forum, which attracted 88 people, to discuss economic development issues common to Forest, Vilas and Oneida Counties. From all of these gatherings and 'listening sessions' of the people in the region, two major topics emerged that I feel I can contribute much to the region by addressing: workforce development and broadband. The importance of the workforce issue was captured in the statewide Situational Analysis conducted in 2018 by UW-Extension. The desperation felt in rural areas on this issue can best be summed up by the comment of one local business that I visited in Vilas County in 2018. In operation for decades, the owners stated {with the critical problem of not being able to find help in the area}: "this is the issue that is going to put us out of business." Some businesses have cut back on their hours, thus reducing profitability while potential workers remain home, unemployed and in some cases, using opioids. Thus, a serious disconnect exists in our area. Researching Best Practices in Rural Workforce Development is Major Program #1.

Regional Housing Challenges in Bayfield and Ashland CountyLack of adequate housing is a persistent and growing challenge across Bayfield and Ashland counties. Regionally, there is a lack of emergency housing and transitional housing. The strain on current emergency and transitional housing services and providers has been exacerbated by a burgeoning methamphetamine and opioid crisis.There is also a lack of adequate housing to address seasonal workforce needs. This is of particular concern in area of the counties that rely heavily on tourism, including the popular tourist destinations of Bayfield and LaPointe. Businesses report spending time each year seeking out staff housing and an inability to hire employees based on lack of housing options, further exacerbating the growing workforce challenges. Some businesses have begun to purchase employee housing. This practice is not ideal, as it is reported to be risky for the business owner and removes much needed housing stock form the year-round market. In addition to affecting the hospitality, retail and recreation markets, lack of housing is also creating a challenge for regional farms. Migrant and seasonal workers are employed to harvest fruit crops and support regional dairy farms, but adequate housing is not available, resulting in poor living conditions for these vulnerable workers and economic loss to farmers. There is a reported need in both Ashland and Bayfield Counties for more low-income and median-income housing. Housing insecurity is a significant problem, with many residents under the mean income contributing more than 30% of their resources to housing. Recent efforts to develop a mixed-income housing development in the Bayfield County seat of Washburn (including some low-income and permanently affordable units) were thwarted by NIMBYism and a pervasive prejudice against low-income persons, despite the reality that the vast majority of the community would qualify for these units. Further exacerbating the housing problem, Bayfield County reports over 50% second home ownership county-wide. This drives home values out of reach for median income home-buyers, and simultaneously removes quality housing stock no longer serving year-round residents. It should be noted that there are several luxury homes in the region, many concentrated along the lakeshore of Bayfield and Ashland County. The purchase price of these homes, and the incomes of the homeowners, skews data upward and makes data analysis of the problem more challenging.There is a reported lack of quality housing stock. Much of the housing stock is old and quite expensive to maintain and repair. Many of these homes have fallen into disrepair, creating risk for buyers and increasing overall housing insecurity. The large majority of the homes in the region are large single family homes, in need of significant structural and mechanical upgrades. Regional storms and flooding exacerbates these challenges, with common defects in foundations causing basements flood with regularity. There are some programs for homeowners to make upgrades to homes, but homeowners often fall outside the income guidelines or lack sufficient home-equity to access these funds.There is a reported lack of quality rental units in the region. This is particularly challenging for younger and low-income residents and exacerbates the problem of attracting and maintaining younger people in the community. Lack of rental units also forces residents to purchase homes before it is economically sound, or to purchase low-quality, high-risk properties, leading to further housing insecurity. There is some anecdotal evidence that housing co-ops may provide residents with an alternative opportunity to build equity, while simultaneously making use of some of the larger houses on the market. However there is lack of information on these solutions and no local examples of such arrangements or data that points to interest.There is also a lack of homes that can adequately serve the needs of aging populations. Bayfield County is expected to be the "oldest county" in Wisconsin by 2035, with over 40% of residents over 65. There is insufficient housing options to receive these residents interested in downsizing or looking for semi-assisted or maintenance free housing options.Programs to support the development of low and middle-income housing units are few and far between. In a traditional development model, developers apply for tax credits to offset the cost of providing units as below market rates. These tax credits are competitive and size of development (number of units) are core criteria for evaluation. Because of the rural nature of Bayfield County, no one community can absorb a "competitively sized" development (<60 units), rendering these sized-based incentive programs difficult to access for rural communities. There is also a lack of data to understand the scope of the regional housing problem. Anecdotally, housing is considered a significant issue, but few studies have been done to quantify the problem, and none have been performed at a regional scale in the past decade or more.

This area of emphasis focuses on youth cultivating the habits and skills necessary for political participation in a democratic society and taking individual and collective action to identify and address issues of public concern. The ideal in a democratic society is that citizens are actively involved in their own governance and that such participation is based on an informed and critical reflection of political and civic issues (Branson & Quigley, 1998). Therefore, the success of such a system is built on a citizenship that is civically engaged and informed. There is, however, much debate over the balance of civic knowledge, civic skills and civic action. The debate is not pertaining to the importance of these three elements, rather which of these are vital in defining one who is "civically engaged."Many reports express concerns regarding the levels of civic engagement and knowledge in the U.S.. In particular, adolescents' and young adults' knowledge of and engagement in the civic process are below desirable levels (Coley & Sum, 2012). The link between civic engagement and knowledge on the one hand, and political participation on the other, has resulted in a widely documented decline in the political participation of young Americans. There has been a steady decline in voting participation in young adults between 18 and 29 between 1972 and 2014 with only 45% of young adults voting in the 2012 presidential election and only 21.5% voting in the 2014 midterm election ("Center for Information on Civic Learning", n.d.).In addition to a general concern with engagement, knowledge, and participation, some scholars have placed particular emphasis on what has been termed the civic empowerment gap (Levinson, 2010) which describes an inequity among social groups in terms of their political participation and influence. More privileged groups typically have more political voice than other groups. Among those groups that are historically and currently underrepresented in the political process are those with low income and less education (Coley & Sum, 2012) as well as recent immigrants and those with limited English proficiency (Kahne & Sporte, 2008). This empowerment gap is reflected in the civic knowledge of traditionally oppressed groups. Black, Hispanic, and Native American students perform significantly lower than their White peers on assessments of civic education (U.S. Department of Education, 2010).4-H Youth Development prioritizes learning by doing to maximize positive youth development outcomes. Successful strategies include: building youth/adult partnership practices into community decision-making, whether within the 4-H organization or in other community settings, from community coalitions to organizational boards and committees. Resources to inform these practices can be found at https://fyi.uwex.edu/youthadultpartnership/  facilitating action planning processes, by which youth can address community issues, either in youth-led spaces with adult coaching or in partnerships with adults working on the same issues. Resources for action planning have been developed for the Tech Changemakers program (https://fyi.uwex.edu/wi4hcitizenship/research-resources/) and the FoodWIse/4-H Youth Development Youth Action for Community Health project) creating opportunities for youth input and decision-making including Teen Courts where youth enact restorative justice, opportunities for youth to serve as advisors on local government boards (Youth in Governance), etc. where they can build relationships with and inform adult decision-makers, youth input into community development through participation in planning process, etc. These opportunities help youth to build understanding of community issues and their civic roles.Youth who participate in these types of opportunities develop habits that make civic participation as adults much more likely. In Wisconsin, we have also seen evidence that youth develop an appreciation for the communities where they live and develop supportive relationships with community adults. Outcomes for communities of youth civic engagement include greater economic and social development that includes young people in all aspects of community life. Key practices developed by the Engaging Young People to Sustain Communities include empowering more diverse community leadership, increasing social capital, and strengthening sense of community and sense of place (see, for example, https://blogs.ces.uwex.edu/engaging-youth/files/2015/02/EYP-White-Paper-February-2015.pdf). These outcomes are particularly important for groups that are marginalized from community leadership due to race, class, or other characteristics.In 2005 a Youth Risk Behavior Survey was completed with all 7th, 9th and 11th grade students within Sheboygan County in Public School Districts. The survey was repeated again in 2007 with the majority of Plymouth School Districts Students grade 6-12. The survey includes 60-100 questions regarding risk taking behaviors of youth. In addition to the Youth Risk Behavior Assessment, most youth also responded to several questions related to the presence of the 40 Developmental Assets in their lives and among their communities. The results reflected a limited sense of belonging felt by young people in relation to their schools and communities. Results also reflected youth not feeling valued by their communities. In a 2009 study, Civic Measurement Models: Tapping Adolescents' Civic Engagement, several measures of youth civic engagement were captured. These measures tap aspects of adolescent civic behaviors, opinions, knowledge, and dispositions. While the work was focused primarily on measures to capture adolescent civic engagement one response indicated that only 63% of youth felt they were likely to work with a group to solve a problem in the community where they live post high school. In 2018 Sheboygan, Wisconsin rated number 2 on the AARP Livability Index for livability based on housing, neighborhood, transportation, environment, health, engagement and opportunity. Sheboygan got high marks for civic engagement for its voting record: 71.8 percent voted, compared with the national median of 55.6 percent.According to the release, the city promotes civic engagement with numerous neighborhood associations, arts and culture "and plenty of natural trails and parks for those who love to be outdoors." Because of the local needs identified, a key focus of the 4-H Youth Development Educator, according to the Position Description is to provide opportunities for youth to assume leadership roles and responsibilities through group membership, community engagement and increased social capital.

Green Lake County is a rural county in east central Wisconsin with a population of 18,760. The county spans over 349 square miles and is comprised of a variety of ethnic descendants, including Amish communities, that contribute to a unique mixture of cultures and customs. The population is predominately White and non-Hispanic, and the largest "minority" group is Hispanic at 4.9%, or approximately 919 people. Green Lake County residents are obese (37%), and lack engagement in physical activity (25%). Green Lake County residents also have insufficient fruit and vegetable consumption (77.1%). About 14% have reported being in poor or fair health, which is closely compared to the state average of 15%. Adult residents of Green Lake County have reported an average of 3.5 days (of the past 30 days), as physically unhealthy days. Even more days (3.6 days) were reported for poor mental health days in 2018. In Green Lake County, 10% of the adult population reported having frequent physical distress, meaning more than 14 days of poor physical health per month. Finally, 11% of the adult population was reported having frequent mental distress, meaning more than 14 days of poor mental health per month. There are high rates of diabetes (12%) and cancer (415 per 100,000) in Green Lake County. In some cases, both of these chronic diseases are preventable.

Document_Name: People of Color Entrepreneurship Discussion Group
Segment: From EDA WIndicator publication, "...Compared to other parts of the U.S., the share of businesses that are minority-owned seems to be relatively modest in Wisconsin, and those businesses tend to be clustered in a handful of counties in southeastern Wisconsin. Similar to the U.S., minority-owned businesses tend to be smaller than their non-minority owned counterparts. But the absolute growth in the number of minority owned businesses over the past few decades suggest that the minority populations may be a fertile ground for the fostering of entrepreneurial activity. The challenge facing Wisconsin and local communities, is that many of current, and potential, minority business owners have unique social and business networks that areoften independent of mainstream networks. The research on social capital and entrepreneurship is clear; the broader the business owner's network (social and business) the more likely the business is to (1) start and (2) succeed. Parallel to the research on women business owners outlined above, a robust local business climate that fosters successful entrepreneurship must be inclusive to maximize thosenetworks. Because minority business owners, much like women business owners, operate in smallernetworks, attempts to broaden those networks is a necessary first step in building on the entrepreneurial potential of the growing minority population in Wisconsin. "

The World Health Organization considers health a fundamental human right and defines it as "a state of complete physical, mental and social well-being and not merely the absence of disease or infirmity." Leading organizations and scholars agree that to make long-term sustained impact on health outcomes, policy, systems, environmental, and structural changes need to be made on the root causes and social determinants of well-being, in addition to evidence-informed direct education with individuals and families.A variety of factors contribute to the health of Florence County residents. According to the County Health Rankings (2018), Florence County ranks 21 of 72 for heath behaviors with a higher than state average for physical inactivity at 24% compared to 21% and adult obesity at 33% compared to the state at 31%. Including adult smoking at 15% and access to exercise opportunities lower than the state average at 73% compared to 86%. Florence County ranks 24th in the state for physical environment with 92% driving alone to work compared to 81% for the state. There is no reported data on mental health providers in Florence County. As of late 2018, Florence County was excited to welcome a mental health provider. According to the Census Population Estimates, Florence County has 4,456 permanent residents. With a racial and ethnic makeup as follows: 99.7% white, 0.3% two or more races, 0.3% black or African American, 0.9% Hispanic or Latino and 0.3% American Indian and Alaska Native. The median age of Florence County is 52.1. Because of the high aging population, it is a priority of Florence County to offer programming to the aging population.Another factor for additional programming and resources for the aging population is that Florence County only has one public gym available to its citizens. There gym is 24 hours but is often unsupervised which deters the elderly from attending. The citizens live in a rural area, making travel difficult to access workout and health facilities. There are plenty of hiking trails and outdoor amenities that are attractive to younger people. Our aging population would have a more difficult time utilizing these outdoor resources.

Document_Name: Building Protective Factors and Resilience in Families (2019)
Segment: Buffalo and Pepin are adjacent, rural counties and share a combined total of a little more than 20,500 individuals living in 8,759 households (U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts estimates, July 1, 2016), spread across 1,004 square miles. In both counties, agricultural-related activity is the primary economic base. Statistics show that family composition is mixed, with a greater percentage of single-parent households, unmarried parents and stepfamilies, in comparison to two-parent households. (American Community Survey Profile Report: 2011-2015 5-year estimates). Racial/ethnic composition in Buffalo County is 97.7% white alone; Pepin 98.2%. Although a relatively small percentage, Latino is the predominant minority, and I have utilized partnerships for outreach to connect with Latina-led young families for parenting and relationship education. Alcohol abuse, illegal drug use and mental health are top concerns for residents across both counties. (Great Rivers United Way COMPASS NOW 2015 Survey; Buffalo County Community Needs Assessment, 2015; Pepin County Community Health Improvement Plan 2016-2020; Buffalo County Community Health Improvement Plan 2016-2020). According to the National Provider Identification Registry, there were no mental health care providers available in Buffalo County prior to 2015. There are now two part-time mental health providers available in Buffalo and Pepin counties, with a patient to provider ratio of 6,679:1, compared with the WI state average ideal patient to provider ratio of 623:1. The lack of access to mental health services is a problem for families and individuals.Both Buffalo and Pepin counties face a dramatic doubling (from 15% to 30%) of residents age 65 and older by the year 2035. A need to prepare aging-friendly communities has been expressed among local government and agency partners, and will be a part of future programming planning. (This may become a secondary programming priority).Median household income is $50,196 and $49,516 for Buffalo and Pepin counties respectively. However, there are wide disparities between age groups, ranging from $16,917 for younger adults to $63,182 for seniors (U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts estimates, July 1, 2016). And, while unemployment rates are low, so are high-paying "living wage" jobs (livingwage.mit.edu, living wage calculator, 2017). Only 4% of Buffalo County respondents rated the availability of jobs with wages that offer a good standard of living; 74% responded poor or fair (2015 United Way: Buffalo County Random Household Survey). The percentage of high-paying jobs is low and a high household income is not enjoyed by most residents. The UW-Extension 2018 Developmental Situational Analysis process for Area 9 identified AODA and health concerns, and building skills for healthy family relationships, stability and well-being as two of the top five priority needs. This was based on a broad representation of stakeholder/partner input and surveys, and is consistent with results of a 2010 formal Survey of Issues and Themes Impacting WI Families and Communities that I conducted with local partners, as part of a statewide Family Living Program effort. Responses from dozens of partners confirmed my programming focus on education and prevention for family relationships and financial security, especially for vulnerable populations. Local Community Health Improvement Plans, United Way Community Assessments and Youth Risk Behavior Survey data continue to validate these programming priorities.I hold a leadership role within the Institute for Human Development and Relationships by chairing two state efforts: Healthy Relationships, and Correctional Systems Audiences. In order to make the greatest impacts at the local, regional or state levels, it is important that I leverage resources and be clear about my facilitating, research, education, planning and evaluation roles. Where possible, a prevention approach that reached a wide audience has been the foundation of programming efforts and, when necessary or appropriate, intervention strategies have been used. I rely on research and specialist support, as well as multiple sources for assessing current and future community needs. I advance a collective impact with partners and coalitions.Provide educational resources and opportunities about healthy couple, co-parenting and other family relationships parenting, child development, either direct education or contacts, online or through key partners.

The current need for financial supports in the state is evidenced by the 2015 FINRA Financial Capability Survey, which collected data from people in each state to measure financial behaviors, attitudes and knowledge (See http://www.usfinancialcapability.org/results.php?region=WI).  53% answered 3 or fewer questions out of 5 on a financial literacy quiz 47% find it very/somewhat difficult to cover expenses and pay bills 51% do not have 3-month emergency savings 28% pay the minimum due on credit cards 21% have past due medical bills 16% spent more than earned over past year 38% reported their spending broke even 44% of women and 33% of men are able to come up with $2000 for an emergencyThese statistics suggest there is ongoing financial insecurity in the state, potentially signaling the need for supportive educational programing. Wisconsin is not alone in this regard; in general, people in this state reflect regional and national trendsLooking at use of financial products and credit, close to 1 in 10 people in Wisconsin do not have a traditional bank account. About 1 in 5 people have used payday loans, pawn loans, or similar high cost borrowing methods in the last year. About three-quarters of people have a credit card, but 28% pay the minimum due each month, incurring regular interest charges. As many as 1 in 5 people in the FINRA survey have paid credit card late fees in the last year. Clearly credit management and access to financial services remains an issue.Finally, the FINRA data offer some insights into the knowledge and application of knowledge by consumers in Wisconsin. People in Wisconsin performed slightly better than regional or national averages, but still show room for improvement. Notably, the majority of consumers in the state are not actively shopping for credit or monitoring their credit reports.Beyond efforts in public schools, families critically need support during "teachable moments" such as when starting a new job, taking out a loan, buying a house, filing taxes, or beginning retirement. There is a shortage of objective financial education on cash and credit management and risk management. More work needs to be done to refine how to access consumers during these key times and to develop better forms of delivering information for various audiences throughout urban and rural areas in Wisconsin.Financial programming will help people to improve their financial management capability. This will enhance the financial security of families in the state, which will benefit communities by boosting economic stability and contributing to a foundation for economic growth.The United Way has identified, with assistance from UW-Extension, the needs of the ALICE population in the county. ALICE is an acronym that stands for Asset Limited, Income Constrained, Employed. ALICE households earn more than the official U.S. poverty level but less than the basic cost of living. In Washington County, 28.6% of the population is ALICE while 5.6% of the population is at or below the poverty level. According to the Household Minimal Survival Budget researched by United Way, it takes $66,384 for a family of two adults, one infant and one toddler to meet their most basic needs in Washington County. This estimate includes the minimal cost of housing, child care, food, transportation and health care. People who struggle to meet these five basic needs will face difficulty in obtaining and maintaining employment, staying healthy and remaining self-sufficient. According to a basic needs survey conducted by the Greater Milwaukee Foundation in the fall of 2012, there were 13,645 FoodShare recipients in Washington County. FoodShare participation in Washington County had increased. Many students in the county that attend public schools receive free or reduced price lunch. For example, in the West Bend School District, 34.2% of the students were eligible in 2012.Over the past few years, several national organizations - the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau (CFPB) and the Corporation for Enterprise Development (CFED) - released various guides for incorporating financial education into human service programs. UW-Extension Family Living Programs also has Wisconsin-specific training materials being used statewide by several educators. In mid-2016, new standards for inclusion of financial education into workforce development with youth and young adults also took effect in WI and nationally through WIOA or the Workforce Innovation and Opportunity Act.

Document_Name: Crop management information for diversified organic vegetable f
Segment: Diversified organic vegetable farmers need detailed management information that includes cover crops, reduced tillage techniques, and vegetable crop specifics that contribute to farm profitability. They appreciate research based information and want to hear from their farmer peers working in the field. Farmer-to-farmer information sharing is highly prized in the organic vegetable producer community. Sharing experiences and learning from other practitioners working in the field is an essential component of any education program for this group. This information is taken from the FairShare CSA Coalition Annual Survey (completed by over 50 farms per year), the FairShare Grower Education Committee (6 to 8 farmers tasked with proposing educational programming for their farmer peers), ongoing program evaluation surveys, conversations with farmers, and the Area 18 Situational Analysis.

The area I serve has a strong and long-standing economic development program led by the Grant County Economic Development Corporation that primarily focuses on the traditional areas of industrial recruitment and business retention. The potential for tourism based economic development is has the potential for significant growth. Tourism studies by the Wisconsin Division of Tourism indicate that total revenues generated from tourism based activities in Grant County is relatively low when compared to other counties in our region. In addition, the lack of a brand hampers our efforts to establish ourselves as a destination for visitors. The surrounding communities of Galena. IL, Dubuque, IA, and Prairie du Chien have strong and effective tourism based business programs. Cooperating with these 'Tier One' communities is an almost completely untapped resource. And our existing chambers have struggled to make consistent progress in tourism development.

Waushara County is a rural, low-income county in central Wisconsin that is located 80 miles south of Madison, with 24,496 residents. The population is predominantly White and non-Hispanic; the largest minority group is Hispanic, at 6.1% of the population or approximately 1484 people and Black or African Americans at 2.1% of the population or 511 people. 19% of the population is under the age of 18. The Waushara County Average Annual Wage is $31,608 compared to Wisconsin's $46,031. The number of people living in poverty in Waushara County include 32% of single mothers and 16% of children, with 51% of students in the district receiving free or reduced lunch, and 8% of seniors. In the past year 2,112 individuals in 759 households used the Waushara County Commodity Food Pantry on a monthly basis. 66% of them were adults and 34% were children. 2,698 people receive Food Share, with 60% adults and 40% children. Waushara County residents who responded to the 2016 Waushara County Needs Assessment survey, in rating the importance of Family Life Topics, said that Managing Family Income was extremely important and quite important, and was rated second highest in the top ten issues to address through education. In addition, the Vision 2020 workgroup, under the Waushara County Prevention Council, voted that this Extension Faculty chair a dual-county Financial Capability workgroup, Green Lake Waushara Financial Wellness, to increase awareness of Waushara County's economic situation and needs, and provide education to increase financial literacy.

In October 2018, eXtension Foundation contracted with me and UW-Extension to buy out 85% of my time to serve as Innovation Facilitation Manager through December 31st 2019. This Plan of Work encompasses only the 15% of time that I have dedicated to UW-Extension for the year 2019.Wisconsin is home to eleven Federally Recognized Tribal Nations and one additional Tribe (Brothertown) that is seeking Federal recognition. Some of these Tribes (e.g. Chippewa, Ojibwa, Ho Chunk and Menominee) have always called Wisconsin and the woodlands surrounding the Great Lakes their home. Other Tribes (e.g. Brothertown, Oneida and Stockbridge-Munsee) were forcibly removed from their homelands and relocated to Wisconsin. Regardless of the location of their ancestral homelands and history in Wisconsin, all of the Tribes and/or Bands of American Indians in Wisconsin have different customs, cultural teachings, languages and systems of governance. The eleven Federally Recognized Tribes hold one important policy element in common: They are sovereign nations with full authority to govern themselves. Historical trauma is omnipresent in all of Indian country and this certainly holds true in Wisconsin's Tribal communities and among Tribal members regardless of whether they live on the reservation. Centuries of forced removal, assimilation, systematic cultural and language oppression, termination and boarding school abuses have created, among other things, a lack of trust for educational and other institutions. Extension Educators in this state and others, have long documented a need for continuous relationship building to establish trust-based working relationships. For many years, Tribal leaders, members and affiliated Extension Educators have requested and worked to develop culturally appropriate educational programming that is respectful of Indigenous wisdom and ways of thinking and acting. However, when considering the unique needs, languages and cultural practices of each Band and/or Tribe, culturally appropriate curriculum development needs for a variety of topics is significant. Through brief surveys, one-on-one and small group visits with Tribal leaders, members, Extension Educators and Tribal-serving organizations, a few common culturally appropriate programming needs have emerged: Leadership development, organization development, environmentally-based language restoration, and resources to combat the opioid epidemic. While the topics for these needs vary greatly, the educational response is similar: Utilize cultural teachings to transform and heal. In my literature searches thus far, I have discovered that there are few existing curriculum resources and programs that have been designed utilizing Indigenous methodologies. I believe that if Cooperative Extension (CE) were to be successful in designing culturally appropriate responses, CE would make a significant contribution to the work of Tribal communities nationwide. In turn, Tribal leaders, members and communities have much to teach non-Native communities and scholars. By increasing their understanding of sovereignty, indigenous knowledge and cultural teachings, non-Native communities can improve their ability to learn from, live among, work and partner effectively with Tribal communities.For the 15% of my dedicated UW-Extension time in 2019, I will concentrate on addressing leadership and organizational development needs of Tribal nations; specifically, the Tribal Nations Lead Leadership Development Pilot Program that was co-conceived by Michigan and Wisconsin and that received funding from the North Central Region Community Rural Development Program.

Document_Name: Managing Horticultural Crops and Landscapes with an emphasis on
Segment: University of Wisconsin-Extension in Door and Kewaunee Counties have an informal agricultural educator specialization agreement whereby the Door County educator provides programming for crops and soils in both counties, and the Kewaunee Agent covers dairy and livestock. Although neighbors, the agricultural environment in Door and Kewaunee County is quite different. Door County is more than twice the size of Kewaunee County, yet Kewaunee County has 45% more acres of harvested agricultural land (86,505 ac in Door County and 134,654 ac in Kewaunee County; USDA Census of Agriculture 2012). Consequently, in Door County, farmers steward 43% of the county's land, whereas in Kewaunee County, farmers steward 81% of the land (S. Deller, Value and Economic Impact, 2012). The types of crops grown in the two counties also varies. In Kewaunee County, dairy farming is the primary form of agriculture, generating $190 million in milk sales. Door County also has a significant dairy industry ($38.5 million in milk sales) and many farmers grow cash crops, but there is much more diversity in the crops grown. Fruit and berry sales generate $4.4 million towards Door County's economy, compared to the $0.36 million in Kewaunee County. Despite these differences, the similar climatic and geological environment, especially between Kewaunee County and Southern Door County makes many Extension programs and research projects relevant to both counties. In 2016, this agriculture educator conducted a needs assessment survey sent to farmers in Door and Kewaunee County regarding their crop and farm management needs. One hundred fifty six surveys were returned (34% response rate), with exactly 2/3 of the responders from Door County and the remaining 1/3 from Kewaunee County. Overall, the number one issue identified was weed management. Disease and insect management were also in the top ten, making pest management overall a top priority. When the responses were separated based on those who indicated that they grow specialty crops (43 responders of the 156 total (28%) who grow fruit, vegetables, trees, and/or flowers), insect management was the number one issue, disease management was number two, and weed management was number three. Integrated pest management was also a high priority for this sub-group, ranking as the sixth most important need (integrated pest management was the 12th most important need when including all responses). In a targeted survey of 14 cherry growers in Door County, 100% indicated that insect management was their highest concern and disease management was second. Currently there are a number of severe insect pests (e.g. spotted wing drosophila, European chafer, brown marmorated stink bug) that farmers and landowners will need to deal with annually. Farmers and landowners must know what pest(s) they are dealing with, how much damage they can tolerate, and when is the best time to apply treatment measures for effective management. For example, the brown marmorated stink bug was first found in Door County orchards in 2018, so it will be extremely important to continue to monitor where this pest is present. Targeted research trials and scouting reports from Door and Kewaunee Counties, as well as from around the state, can help farmers stay ahead of major issues, and know what steps to take when an issue arises. Door County is also home to the eight largest group of Master Gardener Volunteers based on 2017 memberships. As a partner with UW-Extension, their mission is to make an impact on horticulture in our community through education, community outreach, and stewardship of the environment. The Master Gardener Volunteer's care for an educational garden at the Peninsular Agricultural Research Station that had approximately 8,000 visitors in 2015. They are also involved in many educational projects throughout the entire county and facilitate various educational programs during the winter.

Situation Statement:Adult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 10,500 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2017, volunteers reported on average they donated over 54 hours per year. Approximately 70% of Wisconsin 4-H volunteers are female and 30% are male. Nationally, women continue to volunteer at a higher rate than men. (Bureau of Labor Statistics U.S. Department of Labor.) In Wisconsin 4-H, approximately 97% of the volunteers are white. WI 4-H Youth Development volunteers currently do not reflect the demographics of most counties.In 2018, Polk County had 238 adult volunteers. The demographics of volunteers were 75 male and 160 female with almost all the volunteers being white. Member statics for the same year reflect some more diversity. Of the 667 members, there were 17 Hispanic or Latino; (Up from 7 in 2017), 4 Asians, 3 African Americans, 1 American Indian, 10 youth indicating more than one race, and 23 youth did not self-identify. Volunteers play a critical role in the delivery of quality educational programs. In a survey completed January 2015, 4-H Youth Development staff identified Volunteer Development as an area in need of program support. Additionally, a WI 4-H Youth Development Survey was conducted in February 2014 of over 1500 volunteers. Adult volunteers in 4-H indicated relatively low awareness and understanding of some of the educational principles (Essential Elements and the Experiential Learning Process) that are central to the work of 4-H Youth Development. In the 2014 survey, volunteers expressed an interest in learning through not only face-to-face modalities; but also through online-learning such as webinars and podcasts. The 2017 Strategic Plan released by USDA NIFA and National 4-H Council outlines a 4-H Youth Development Vision for 2025. Nationally the following goal has been established "Youth are surrounded with competent, prepared staff and volunteers." This goal includes the following outcomes: "The 4-H program is supported by a well-trained volunteer force." "4-H staff and volunteers engage in meaningful professional development."In addition, there is a responsibility of volunteers to ensure access, equity and opportunity. The National 4-H Strategic goal states "All youth engage in program and opportunities." To that end it has been identified that "4-H volunteers and staff are skilled, knowledgeable and prepared to work with all members of their community." Over the past many years Polk County has seen a shift from a primarily rural county to a sub-urban/rural county with urban influences from the major metropolitan Minneapolis/St. Paul area. The rural roots of the county remain a strong foundation for the traditional view of 4-H community clubs. Polk County remains a bedroom community with many parents commuting the 70 plus miles to work in the twin cities area which adds challenges to reaching volunteers and youth for face-to-face trainings and educational opportunities. In 2018, the Polk County 4-H program had a large volunteer base of 238 adults and 667 community club members. The large adult volunteer base enables the program to offer many educational opportunities for youth. Oversight for the program is provided by a large board of directors, comprised of one adult and one youth representative from each of the 22 clubs. This broad representation provides an inclusive perspective, however program management with a board this large can be challenging. The Board serves as a valuable resource to assess the needs of the program and guide program development for the Community Club and Youth Leadership Development; being a continuous needs assessment opportunity. A noted change over the past decade shows that volunteers focus their time on one or two areas in the program due to time constraints and additional demands. Likewise, youth are pulled in many directions with extracurricular activities provided by schools almost every day of the week. Youth also have to focus program participation, enrolling in fewer projects and focusing involvement more narrowly.

The Outreach Staff at Wehr Nature Center have a contract with the Milwaukee County Parks in order to provide Environmental Education programming with in the Metro Milwaukee Area. Currently, there is a lot of information being shared about pollinators and their worldwide decline within the media. This broad program is meant to meet the needs that are being asked for by the public who potentially want to improve habitat within their garden, school age children who desire to know more about honeybees, or volunteers who wish to conduct butterfly/bumblebee surveys through a citizen science program.Who cares whether this issue is resolved or not and how did you get their input?Who is your research intended to help?

Document_Name: Improving Socioemotional Health for Youth in Shawano County and
Segment: Mental Health Diseases impact 1 of every 4 people. 1 in every 5 youth will experience a mental health illness. Poor mental health can negatively impact physical health, leading to an increased risk of some health conditions. Stigma is rampant across Northwoods Culture, making the process of seeking health even more difficult than the lack of mental health providers. Compound this with the lack of Mental Health Professionals available to meet our needs: The National Benchmark is 1 provider to 330 people. In Shawano County, we have roughly double that at 1 provider for 650 people (Community Health Rankings.)The suicide rate in Wisconsin is four times the homicide rate. Each year, over 700 Wisconsin residents die by suicide. In addition, approximately 5,500 Wisconsin residents are hospitalized due to intentional, self-inflicted injury. Suicide is the fourth leading cause of years of potential life lost (YPLL) before age 65. Suicide is the 2nd leading cause of death for Wisconsinites who are 15-24 (140 deaths) and 25-32 (134 deaths), and 3rd leading cause of death to those 35-44 (143 deaths). This number continues to trend upward for those who fall in the 15-24 year old age range. Depressive symptoms and suicidal ideation are on the rise, and anxiety is high. Students report greater use of screens, less sleep, and poorer self-reported health. Area 8 boasts high rates of excessive drinking (binge or heavy drinking in the past 30 days). Shawano County reports a rate of 24%. The National Benchmark is 13%. In Shawano County, 28% of all vehicle crashes involved alcohol. We have an issue. As one Shawano County Sheriff reflected during the 2019 Departmental Youth Mental Health First Aid Training, "It sounds like people aren't doing drugs just for fun. This makes me think that folks might be abusing substances as a coping mechanism." One in five teens and young adults live with a mental health condition - half develop the condition by age 14 and three-quarters by age 24. (National Alliance for Mental Illness.) One in five American children ages three through 17   about 15 million   have a diagnosable mental, emotional or behavioral disorder in any given year. Only 20 percent of these children are ever diagnosed and receive treatment; 80 percent   about 12 million   aren't receiving treatment (TODAY via Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.) Health disparities among youth as evident, as were highlighted during Thedacare's Community Health Action Team Process, featuring a plunge into ACES and youth mental health in 2018. During 2018, the CHAT ACES Action team has been diving into data, recognizing that Shawano County is not serving the needs of our youth and families around trauma informed care. The ACEs study found that having adverse childhood experiences was strongly associated with a range of psychological, social and health problems as an adult. Responses to these experiences often manifest in behaviors or conditions that result in involvement with the child welfare and the criminal and juvenile justice system or in difficulties in the education, employment or primary care system.(SAMHSA 2014). Shawano County has a population of workers and residents that have lived through ACES, as well as Native American Tribal members of Menominee, Stockbridge-Munsee, and Ho Chunk, whom have inherited generational trauma. The county is beginning to see that it is necessary to educate workplaces, educational settings, and government systems on the signs and symptoms of ACES, mental health issues, and their connections to child brain development. In addition to serving on the Trauma-Informed Shawano County and ACES Action Teams through Thedacare, I continue to serve as one of two co-organizers of the newly formed Shawano County Alliance for Youth. This coalition brings the community together to empower people through education and resources that support healthy and affordable choices for youth throughout the entire county. Thus far, we have had twelve organizations and 7 school districts represented. There currently is not an AODA Coalition in the area. I continue to address the health needs of young people by serving on the health team that may be formed through the Positive Youth Development and/or Health and Well Being Institutes. I have done state-wide training in Youth Mental Health First Aid, partnering with Jen Park-Mroch, Danette Hoppke, and Tracy Henegar. As individuals and families gain knowledge and skills, and community environments support healthy living, there will be less illness, substance abuse and mental illness. Shawano County and Wisconsin will benefit from these changes through decreased health care costs, increased productivity of our workforce and improved quality of life.

Document_Name: Research Naturalist Programming at Upham Woods
Segment: Overview of Upham Woods and Current TrajectoryBackground: Upham Woods Outdoor Learning Center is an informal science learning (ISL) center that is a part of the University of Wisconsin System, currently affiliated with UW-Extension (UWEX). Over the last four years, Upham Woods Outdoor Learning Center's increasingly vibrant outdoor classroom and dynamic statewide outreach program have strengthened the quality, diversity, and reach of environmental education in Wisconsin. Fast Facts:  Founded in 1941 318-acre facility Served 11,237 youth and adults in 2018 from 49 Wisconsin counties; served over 500,000 Wisconsinites since 1941 Programming includes:  on-site group visits from schools, 4-H programs, scouts, etc.  outreach learning experiences across the state Current Trajectory Established by Renewed Outreach Efforts and Use of Technology 2014-2018:   Over $1.92 million in cumulative program revenue generated Over $1.01 million investment in capital projects in collaboration with UWEX administration Acquisition of over $1.45 million in extramural support grants for building environmental education capacity and expanding access to programs at Upham Woods as well as to statewide environmental education opportunities, including Digital Observation Technology Skills (DOTS):  Framework developed at Upham Woods and used statewide for integrating modern, mobile technology into outdoor, experiential science educationo 14,591 youth and adults have used DOTS since 2014o Generates hands-on engagement with technology in the context of a classic outdoor learning settingo Digital tool kits are assembled, distributed and supported by Upham Woodso Resulted in 19 peer-reviewed articles authored or co-authored by Upham staff. Upham Woods programming reach has increased 28% in the last 4 years and revenue is up 15% in the same time period. Furthermore, our reach in 2018 was the largest in 32 years and our revenue is the highest in center history.Embracing Technology Rooted in Heritage of Upham WoodsWhen the University of Wisconsin received the donation of land that would become Upham Woods, Wakelin McNeel served as the Center's first superintendent. McNeel was also known as "Ranger Mac", a persona he created for a Wisconsin Public Radio show that he hosted. As part of his show, he invited youth and adults from all across Wisconsin to reflect on, observe, engage, and conserve the state's wonderful natural resources. On the program, he often noted that "If you didn't take a walk yesterday, you missed out on many things that may not come again" (Matkin-Rawn 2004). Today, we share these same sentiments with our students, encouraging them to observe their surroundings and ask questions that enable them to better understand the world they inhabit. While Ranger Mac worked at Upham Woods in the 1930s and 1940s, many parallels exist between his service to the state and the direction Upham is headed today. Ranger Mac used the technology of the era radio to connect a statewide audience to the environment. By using a resource that was both pervasive and accessible, he drew youth and adults to issues in our natural world and also enabled them to explore Upham Woods. Today, we accomplish these same objectives through the Digital Observation Technology Skills (DOTS) program and web-based resources. Ranger Mac's approach focused on observation and wonder in the outdoors. Today, we use terms such as informal science learning (ISL), inquiry-based instruction, project-based learning and place-based education to describe this same approach. Although there have been many changes in the last 76 years at Upham Woods, it continues to serve a crucial statewide presence in environmental education outreach by leveraging an effective blend of technology and youth development, within a context of vibrant natural resources and scenic beauty.Confidence in this Well-founded ApproachThe National Research Council's research shows that ISL is guided by student inquiry about the natural world, data collection related to their inquiry, and opportunities to present their findings to peers and community members (National Research Council, 2009). Further, the National Research Council states that informal learning environments are, in principle, accessible to all learners, and evidence suggests they have particular potential for supporting learners from non-dominant groups (National Research Council, 2009). In addition to providing experiential learning opportunities grounded in environmental concepts, ISL centers like Upham Woods expand the network of educators and facilitators engaged in environmental education and provide students with "direct access to compelling phenomena in the natural world" (National Science Foundation, 2011).While ISL centers, such as camps and nature centers, have historically had programming legacies rooted in the natural sciences, their educational practices can be in tension with the emphasis on the adoption of modern technology that often guides contemporary STEM education (Cuthbertson, Socha, & Potter, 2004). Yet using technology in outdoor education settings holds great promise in deepening scientific connections to local places through data collection. As an example, data collection within a context of location, community, and inquiry provides a place-based approach to education that contributes to active and engaged citizens (Hougham & Kerlin, 2016; Sobel, 2004). In modern science classrooms and careers, most scientific tools are digital. Consequently, adopting digital tools requires ISL centers to strike a careful balance between retaining the connection to place that outdoor, experiential learning promotes and serving youth and educators with modern STEM curricula. Connecting this further, place-based education like that promoted at Upham Woods has been shown to connect learners' STEM engagement to their experiences in informal settings, develop their acute observation skills, and increase their capacity to care about the environment around them (Land & Zimmerman, 2015; Greenwood & Hougham, 2015).

Document_Name: Farm Business Managment and Government Policies related to prod
Segment: An overview of Rock County Agriculture: As of the 2012 USDA Census of Agriculture Rock County had over 353,700 acres dedicated to crop production with a market value of products sold exceeding $274,420,000 making Agriculture the leading industry in the county. Agriculture production of soybeans ranked highest in the state, corn production ranked 2nd in the state and overall value of agriculture products ranked 14th. Rock County also ranked 1st in pheasant production and 5th in Sheep production1. Having a large urban population as well as a very productive and diverse agriculture sector creates unique programming opportunities for both agriculture production and agriculture literacy. Situation Statement: There are over 1,500 farms in Rock County with a production level ranking 4th in the state for value of crops grown equaling a market value of $165,875,000 according to the 2012 USDA Agriculture Census data1. The large amount of production agriculture coupled with an increase in the cost of agriculture inputs equals a need for educational programs aimed at utilizing inputs for efficient returns in a way that offers long term sustainability. Additionally commodity markets are at a 10 year low and forecasted to remain stagnant to lower. The average market price for corn in 2015 was $3.70/bu. compared with $4.46/bu. In 2014 and $6.89/bu. In 20132. The decreased profit margins for crop producers is creating a need for programing focused on efficient and profitable production practices. This programing will be accomplished in part by utilizing the Rock County Research Farm to conduct relevant field based research trails in collaboration with state specialist and area agriculture producers aimed at increasing the efficiency of agriculture production in Rock County. Additional programing will be conducted aimed at increasing marketing knowledge and economic tools as decision factors in farm management. Initial needs assessments completed by Rock County Farmers indicate the desire for additional programing in the areas of Crop Production and Soil Health further indicating the need for local programing in these areas. Programing in efficient crop production practices as well as soil health and integrated pest management will provide education aimed at successful and sustainable grain enterprises. These programing efforts closely align with the goals of the Agriculture Natural Resources Education (ANRE) Crops Team which is focused on the economic and environmental sustainability of individual cash grain enterprises. Field based research projects in the areas of Corn Production, Soybean Production, Weed and Pest Management, Cover / Companion Crops, as well as Soil Health will be conducted at the Rock County Farm. 1 Data Referenced from 2012 USDA National Agricultural Statistics Service Census of Agriculture County Profile found at www.agcensus.usda.gov2 Data Referenced from USDA Economic Research Service Feed Grains: Yearbook Tables, U.S. Acreage, Production, Yield and Farm Price found at http://ers.usda.gov/data-products/feed-grains-database/feed-grains-yearbook-tables.aspx#26766

The Ashland County population consists of 20% of its population over age 65 (US Census, estimate, 2017); the median age is almost 42 years old. Most of the local elected officials are over the age of 50; during election years, many of these seats are uncontested, indicating a lack of people willing or able to run for office. The Ashland County Board recommended that the Ashland County Extension community development educator focus on programming that helps build leadership capacity in the county.

Other Menominee statistics are unsettling, 31.7% of residents live below poverty level (compared to 12.4% for Wisconsin 2010 Census data), highest number of children living in poverty (51% per 2017 County Health Rankings), high unemployment rate (9.9% per 2017 County Health Rankings), highest number of single parent households (61% per 2017 County Rankings data), and 78% of children eligible for free lunch (Applied Population Lab, 2014 County Data). According to the 2014 County Health Rankings, Menominee County has a median household income of $33,925 compared to the state of Wisconsin's median household income of $51,063. The community, however, possesses much strength as well with strong cultural traditions and pride. Many of the current financial issues for Menominee County are present in counties across the state. In a visioning session for the Menominee County/Nation Family Living Educator position in October of 2012, Financial Management was identified as the 4th highest priority program area. Related to financial management, job and school readiness was ranked as the number one priority area and Culture and Values, relationships and respect was 2nd. Fortunately, UW-Extension Family Living Programs are well positioned to assist families in addressing some of these issues through education and coaching efforts. Financial security is the goal for many Americans, including Menominee County residents. Financial security is defined as an individual's or family's ability to meet short-term needs and to prepare for the future. The path to financial security requires accessible and accurate information, as well as financial competency in earning, spending, saving, borrowing, and protecting. The long run objective of financial security begins with establishing financial stability, or the ability to make ends meet. Menominee County/Nation families would benefit from an increased ability to manage cash and credit so they can make ends meet, and also begin to set aside resources for emergencies and to reach future goals. UW-Extension Family Living Programs can offer financial education and information right in the community with no cost and give them resources to move forward from some of the crippling statistics that the Menominee County and Nation face.

Document_Name: Nutrition education for racially and ethnically diverse audienc
Segment: According to University of Wisconsin-Madison's Applied Population Laboratory, Wisconsin's demographic trends point to an increasingly older population with greater racial and ethnic diversity than in any previous US Census. Most of the aging population is a part of WIsconsin's population of non-Hispanic Whites, which accounts for 83% of the State, with the biggest age group being in the 45-64 age range. The senior population of Wisconsin is 94.5% non-Hispanic White. People of color and people who identify as multiracial have a younger age structure. People who identify as Asian makeup 2% of the population, with young adults aged 15-29 being up the largest proportion of the demographic. The African-American (6%) and American Indian (1%) populations have large groups of 15-19 year olds. The largest age group for people who identified as Hispanic (5.9%) or multiracial (1.9%) are children in the 0 - 4 year age group, with 5 - 9 year olds being the second largest age group.Wisconsin's poverty rate is also expected to increase, with much of the social and economic disparities associated with poverty disproportionately affecting communities of color. The US Census Bureau defines poverty areas as census tracts with at least 20% of its residents at or below the federal poverty line. Research asserts that the well-being of individuals and families living in areas with concentrated poverty, which often have high crime rates, poor schools, and fewer job opportunities, is compromised. Residents living in high poverty areas are often underserved and excluded from mainstream social and economic opportunities and have worse health outcomes. Identifying underserved communities, building relationships with, and increasing access to healthy lifestyle choices at the individual, community, and policy levels provides greater opportunity for communities to engage in activities that promote positive health outcomes. Learning environments that are reflective of learners' culture, including ways of knowing, world views, and learning preferences, are proven to be more effective than those that do not. As a SNAP-ed and EFNEP funded program, FoodWIse is federally mandated to provide nutrition education to individuals with limited resources. The purpose of my position is to assist our colleagues to provide culturally responsive nutrition education. My focus until April 30 will be to review and develop plans for implementing materials that are intended to be used with learners who have identities originating in Southeast Asian, Native American, Black or African American cultures.

For many families and individuals, just one shift in the flow of financial resources can be detrimental to financial stability and if persistent, will affect financial security. Hispanic population is 4.9% of the 101,968 county population. Median household income is $56,376 and from Census, there are 41,029 households with income and benefits in the county. In comparing the median household income and the number of households with income, there are 18,013 households who earn under $ 49,999 - under the median income or 44%. ALICE provides a framework, language and tools to measure and understand the struggles of the growing households in Fond du Lac County who do not earn enough to afford basic necessities. (https://www.fdlunitedway.org/sites/fdlunitedway.oneeach.org/files/fdl%20snapshot.pdf ) The ALICE report for Fond du Lac County noted based upon 41,938 households, 22% of the households earned more than the Federal Poverty Level, but less than the basic cost of living for Fond du Lac County (the ALICE threshold) Combined, the number of poverty and ALICE households equals the total population struggling to afford basic needs, this number is 33% of the households in Fond du Lac County. Inability to make ends meet financially affects the family beyond the pocketbook as it affects relationships within the family and community due to tough choices are made that affect the family and its members. These choices whether financial or not have long-term consequences for families and communities, which is indicative of future success for all involved.Wisconsin renters currently represent one third of all households in the state. In Fond du Lac County, 28%of occupied housing units are renter occupied. The rental housing market continues to experience strong demand. A record 43.3 million households were renters in 2016, representing a 26.5% increase since 2006 (U.S. Census Bureau, 2017b). Meanwhile, the homeownership rate dropped from 68.8% to 63.4%. As a result of the increased demand for rental housing, the rental vacancy rate in the U.S. declined from 9.8% in the4th quarter of 2006 to 6.9% in the 4th quarter of 2016 (U.S. Census Bureau,2017b). The Consumer Price Index (CPI) for the rental cost of a primary residence rose 31.9% over those ten years, which was higher than overall inflation of 19.1% (U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics, 2017a).Household income has not kept up with the rising cost of rental housing. Researchers at the Joint Center for Housing Studies at Harvard predict additional4.7 million-renter households by 2025 from household growth, even if homeownership rates stabilize (Spader, McCue, & Herbert, 2016). They project far more additional renter households if homeownership continues to decline. Source: Out of Reach 2017, National Low Income Housing Coalition. In Fond du Lac County, 11,613 occupied rental units paying rent were shown to range from less than $500/month to over $3,00 per month with a median rent price falling in at $709 .00 per month (Fact finder Census Gov., 2016). The largest monthly expense families have related to housing costs.
