What's Going On Working to complete community needs assessments in both Columbia and Sauk counties, it is emerging that family dynamics within and across generations is a sociocultural hurdle within communities. Raising children, achieving adulthood, maturing successfully, aging with good health and moving through life with competence and confidence are key areas of struggle for most individuals consistently. What was developmentally true or expected of individuals in previous generations is not necessarily developmentally true of generations today. Extension programming will serve to help individuals to bridge this gap by providing educational programming that is timely, accessible, and up to date. Who Cares and Has a Stake The statewide situational statement conducted across the 72 counties in 2018 found 18 points of common challenge in 5 key themes around the state. Within each of these themes a human relationship-based solution has potential. If the interactions or, relationships, between people or groups of people could overcome these challenges then quality of life for all community members could potentially improve. State and local partners have a joint investment in solving these challenges to improve quality of life across Wisconsin for all residents. As a Columbia & Sauk County Extension educator I will participate in and facilitate the building of coalitions locally to problem solve individual and group challenges to human relationships in daily community life. How was this Identified Nationally, the social and cultural issues we face in Wisconsin are evident across our country. The World Health Organization (WHO)'s action plan through 2020 has amongst its four primary goals to, 1) implement strategies for promotion and prevention in mental health, and 2) to strengthen information systems, evidence and research for mental health. As an Extension educator I can support these national goals through outreach with key community partners to advocate for developmental needs of all residents across the human life span, to keep the integration of ACES/ Trauma Informed programming central to the work undertaken, and to help guide the use of resources effectively and efficiently so that the needs are directed at the right issues at the right time.

Document_Name: Horticulture for Jail Inmates: Gaining Ground Gardens (2019)
Segment: Marathon County has an estimated population of 135,732. The Marathon County Jail was reported to be 70% over capacity with most of those convicted due to drugs or drug related activities. Currently, occupant overage is vetted to other counties, which is an expensive practice. The impact on families of those incarcerated is devastating. Youth are sometimes placed in foster care or shelter homes. The extreme amount of stress associated with this for Marathon County families is immeasurable. Marathon County strives to be the healthiest, safest, and most prosperous county in the State. To this end, collaboration among community leaders, our elected County Board of Supervisors, and Marathon County employees has led to development of a 2018-2022 Strategic Plan, identifying area of focus in the coming years (http://www.co.marathon.wi.us/Portals/0/Departments/CAD/Documents/StrategicPlan_2018-2022.pdf).As a UW-Extension Horticulture Educator, my unique contribution to addressing Marathon County's Strategic Plan, thus far, has been to identify target populations where therapeutic horticulture could improve well-being. After lengthy review of the 2018-2022 plan, there are three populations on which I have been focusing my efforts: 1) jail inmates, 2) county youth, and 3) individuals in addiction recovery or those living with mental illness. For 2019, my plan of work centers mainly upon county jail inmates and community youth, although there is some overlap here with individuals in addiction recovery or those living with mental illness. Based on numerous studies conducted across the globe, it is likely that therapeutic gardens and horticulture programs will positively impact the physical, intellectual, emotional, social and spiritual well-being of individuals in these target populations (American Horticulture Therapy Association, 2018).Upon my hiring, I reached out to stakeholders across Marathon County, and specifically within the City of Wausau where our county jail is located. I provided a series of four public informational sessions to raise awareness of therapeutic horticulture as a viable treatment option for individuals across diverse populations and added two additional programs to more specifically inform Master Gardener Volunteers in Marathon and Portage Counties of our community engagement efforts. Approaches in therapeutic horticulture vary by population and programming provided in 2019 will be research-based. I continue to be told that even if we reach only ONE person through this initiative, we will have made a difference! By not engaging in this situation, UW-Extension will fail to do its part in supporting positive mental and physical health for youth and adults in Marathon County.

The Positive Youth Development (PYD) Institute has not had a learning resources-related position for approximately 10 years. During that time, there was limited capacity for identifying and developing high-quality learning resources beyond the scholarly work of state and county-based colleagues. It was often challenging for educators to make their work accessible to others for use, much less scale it up for broad awareness and use. Internal and external communication strategies have gone through significant changes with limited staff capacity to maintain or update them.In fact, in an interview with a youth leader from Wisconsin Leadership Council, the young person pointed to two things: a communication gap and an understanding gap in Wisconsin 4-H. While she and her club work closely with the local educator, she suggested there was a disconnect between members and information/opportunities beyond the county boundary. She went on to outline an understanding gap about basic 4-H concepts - ideas such as how to use 4HOnline effectively, what 4-H is about, and how to get involved.2These communication and connection challenges make the Institute less efficient and increases burnout among educators. Colleagues - especially those in the counties - are less able to build on the expertise and experience of others, and everyone must "reinvent the wheel" in identifying and/or developing resources to do their jobs effectively. In addition, an influx of new colleagues has taken place in the last year. This group, alongside more experienced colleagues, is in search of accessible lesson plans, teaching tools and curriculum. As expressed many times during the All-Program Conference (APC) in December, 2018, these educators seek consistency of approach, language, and process in many areas. This has been reinforced many times during interviews I've conducted with both new and experienced colleagues as they seek alignment of resources in well-organized digital spaces. That consistency and availability of resources - paper, digital and interactive - supports the flexibility and efficiency they need to implement their local programs with discretion and professionalism. This demand makes many learning resources needs seem urgent.Certainly, some learning resources projects, already in progress, have emerged as straightforward needs with immediate benefits. For example, updates to the 4-H Club Central website was identified as a priority by administration, and work was begun on the project last year. Since this has been a resource gap for several years, the soon-to-be-updated documents and guidance found there will be of immediate value to staff and volunteers alike. Other learning resource needs of similar value and urgency are likely to emerge.However, many other projects needs identified by PYD staff and faculty are urgent, but will take more time to prioritize and develop. Many of the more immediate needs and strategies to focus on are being identified through staff, volunteer and youth interviews. With finite capacity to address all the needs and requests that may arise, efficient, effective, flexible and responsive processes are needed to:1) Identify and vet existing high-quality learning resources that meet the needs of staff, volunteers and youth - many issue discussions during the APC brought this up; this also prevents PYD from wasting resources developing products that already exist.2) Review and prioritize project requests and proposals - allows the Institute to be strategic about where and how staff and financial resources are invested.3) Plan and develop learning resources - minimizes inefficiencies while allowing for creative and thoughtful development within PYD's niche.4) Develop a base of consistent, aligned, easy to access learning resources for staff and volunteers (both youth and adults) to begin to bridge the "communication and understanding gap" that has formed in Wisconsin PYD programs.The resources identified and developed through these processes must serve a wide range of audiences, including but not limited to staff, volunteers, youth and others; people in rural and urban settings; people from a variety of affinity groups - racial, ethnic, religious, gender and sexuality, ability, and more; people with varying interests - 4-H (clubs, projects, and more) and community youth development (civic engagement, workforce development, youth-adult partnerships, health, and more); and as described earlier, both new and experienced colleagues. Emily Style wrote that "no student acquires knowledge in the abstract; learning is always personal. Furthermore, learning never takes place in a vacuum; it is always contextual."2 In her article, "Curriculum as Window and Mirror," she goes on to describe how children (and all of us) must be able to both see ourselves and our experience mirrored in curriculum and to see through a "window" into another experience. In that way, learners' experiences are both validated and expanded upon. Achieving diverse perspectives in learning resources is a crucial element of each of the processes briefly outlined above; learning resources identification and development must support the vision and goals of our Institute, Department and broader institution to break down barriers and make PYD programs - both 4-H and community youth development - welcoming and inclusive of all while addressing specific needs of the audience(s). As a high priority, the processes described above will incorporate structures to help ensure use and development of inclusive learning resources.References:Adams, Holly (2019). Personal phone conversation on February 7, 2019.Style, Emily (1996). "Curriculum as Window and Mirror." Social Science Record. First published in Listening for All Voices, Oak Knoll School monograph, Summit, NJ, 1988. Retrieved from http://www.nationalseedproject.org/images/documents/Curriculum_As_Window_and_Mirror.pdf.

Programs provide environmental education to youth of Metro Milwaukee and surrounding urban/suburban areas with enhanced understanding of our rich natural resources, how to enjoy and care for them.

Each year, Public Library Development (PLD) coordinates a summer reading program on behalf of Wisconsin's public libraries. PLD supports Wisconsin's membership to the Collaborative Summer Library Program (CSLP) and the ability to purchase programs, drop-in activities, and other special events that are common in a summer library program. These programs are expected to promote accessible and exceptional public library experiences for children and families. Wehr Nature Center's Outreach program has been part of this collaboration for over 20 years providing a natural sciences connection to the summer reading theme. The 2019 theme is Space and the slogan is A Universe of Stories celebrating the 50th anniversary of the Apollo Moon Landing.

Document_Name: Dairy and beef animal health, well-being and quality assurance
Segment: The demographics of the farmers I program with continues to change. The number of active dairy farms is decreasing, while those remaining are either increasing their herd size or diversifying. Farm stress is elevated in Wisconsin and in Taylor County. Due to the current oversupply of milk, dairy processors have stopped accepting milk from Grade B farms and have discontinued accepting milk from some Grade A farms. Prices paid to farmers for milk, meat, corn and other commodities are flat and below their costs of production. Dairy farmers are either looking to exit or to add other enterprises, including cross- breeding their cattle to beef to capture higher prices for marketing beef feeder calves. Some dairy farms are also considering feeding dairy or dairy- beef cattle for the finished beef market.Consumers increasingly demand assurances that farmers provide good care of animals and the beef or milk provided to them is safe and healthy to consume. The National 2017 Beef Quality Assurance (BQA) Audit of beef processing facilities identified fresh bruises on cattle arriving at facilities. This indicates the need for cattle transportation training and education about cattle handling and welfare. Beginning January 1, 2020 all transporters of cattle arriving at major processing plants must show a certificate of BQA-Transportation training. As of January 1, 2019, Tyson and other processing plants will only purchase cattle from farms that are BQA certified.My Extension experience and professional knowledge as a veterinarian enable me to self-identify my faculty area of focus as dairy and beef animal health, well-being and quality assurance. My programming is aided by my involvement as a state BQA Coordinator, and my involvement with the Extension Dairy and Livestock Teams and the animal well-being workgroup.

Document_Name: Expanding Capacity for Renewable Energy Infrastructure, Sustain
Segment: Organizations and local governments in Ashland County, two tribal nations, and the Chequamegon Bay area have been working steadily over the last five to seven years to increase the number of private homes, businesses, and local governments that get their power from renewable sources. Solar photovoltaic (PV) panels on homes, farms, and infrastructure is the most common form of renewable energy being developed due to the diligent work of a regional nonprofit group called Cheq Bay Renewables. The former Ashland County Extension Community Development Educator also had a lead role in partnering with this group and others including Bad River Band of Lake Superior Chippewa, as well as Ashland County administration to meet the region's Energy Independent Community goal of generating 25% of energy locally from renewable source by 2025 (advance regional goals that increase the kilowatts of electricity produced by solar power). (Goals 1 and 2)The region has a 15-year history of developing and implementing a wide variety of initiatives that increase sustainable lifeways such as developing food security with local agriculture, water use practices, waste reuse and reduction, rural transport systems, and other efforts. (Goal 3)Both Ashland and Bayfield counties and the Bad River and Red Cliff tribes have developed natural disaster mitigation plans to reduce or eliminate impacts that occur as a result of natural disasters that may or not be caused by climate change. All planning partners in these four plans have expressed a need for help reaching goals and objectives, as well as help with outreach and information campaigns. Several of the mitigation goals can be accomplished through educational programs through Extension and related partners. For example, there's a goal in the Ashland County Mitigation Plan, recently adopted by the County Board, to conduct outreach about human health impacts caused by increasing temperatures and extreme weather events. (Goal 4)

During the past century, the focus on maximizing agricultural production and profitability has centered on technological innovations - improving genetics for disease and insect resistance, herbicide-tolerance, drought and heat tolerance, and higher yields. Traditional yet important agricultural methods, such as building and caring for soil, have gotten less attention. For some farmers, this trend has reduced their long-term sustainability by exacerbating problems such as herbicide resistance, erosion/nutrient runoff, and yield losses from drought and flooding. Soil health improvement can help meet surface and ground water quality goals, reduce soil erosion, and mitigate the impacts of climate change.Recently, farmers, agribusiness, government agencies, and non-profits have begun to recognize the value of soil health and the ecosystem services it can enhance. Implementing a soil health system in the production of food, fiber, and fuel can dramatically impact not only air and water quality, but improve farm economic sustainability and quality of life in rural areas. Investment in research and extension soil health efforts vary widely from state to state, resulting in a wide variation in expertise and support available to farmers and agronomists in the Midwest region. Research has shown that the information agricultural advisors in the public and private sectors are using frequently originates with land-grant universities and extension. With the strong renewed interest in soil health science and practice, it is critical that extension specialists and educators are ready to provide the best science and the best advice for farmers, farm advisors, and the agriculture and food industries.The Soil Health Nexus, an extension-led soil health network, was formed to increasing access to research-based soil health knowledge, extension and resources to extension professionals across the North Central Region, and the audiences they engage. The North Central Region Water Network provides funding support, strategic guidance, communication support, and evaluation support for the Soil Health Nexus, with Rebecca Power, Anne Nardi, and Amber Mase providing primary support.

Document_Name: Program #2  Market Studies and Local Educational Programs
Segment: SAME AS MAJOR PROGRAM #1Extension education in community business development has a unique position between broader regional economic development and individual business development. It is often focused on a specific community and its trade area. Community business development directly impacts quality-of-life as measured by the availability of services, retail, workspaces, housing, and other commercial activities. Our learners are often interested in downtown revitalization, but are not necessarily limited to a downtown district, or a Main Street program area. One issue facing community business development efforts, especially in rural areas, has been the migration of retail and services to larger commercial centers of the state. In addition, significant changes are occurring in the retail sector that are challenging bricks and mortar stores in favor of online commerce. Even chain affiliated stores, located in malls and shopping centers, are facing challenges today. Many are reducing the size of their store footprints and closing stores in less profitable locations.This provides an opportunity for Extension to help community and business leaders understand the market and develop realistic scenarios for strengthening and expanding local businesses, while maintaining a focus on what's important to community residents. This is especially important in multicultural urban neighborhoods, and small rural communities that are underserved by grocery, pharmacy, medical and other essential services.Program #2-Local Market Studies and Educational ProgramsWork directly with communities and local Extension educators to apply the existing DMA toolbox and new research and resources identified in program #1 to Wisconsin communities:  Prairie du Chien market analysis ($) - completed Brodhead market analysis ($) -underway other communities ($) -expected($) Fee charged for intensive services by UWEXRevisit communities that have recently completed a comprehensive Market Analysis and provide them with assistance in implementing their recommendations:Cross PlainsBellevillePrairie du ChienBrodheadRelaunch a series of topical webinar or teleconference discussions that focus on applying existing tools (like the Downtown Market Analysis toolbox) and new research and resources (developed in Program #1). Topics include:  "Repurposing downtowns" teleconference hosted by the Local Government Center - completed January 2019 "Market analysis and free data sources" hosted by Heritage Ohio with invites to Wisconsin Extension educators business attraction, retention, trends in retail, etc.

In Winnebago county more than 20% of adults report having had 4 or more traumatic events in their childhood (Wisconsin Child Abuse and Neglect Board). Science has definitively proven that what happens to us in our childhood has lasting impact on our brain development. The science of resilience also provides a great deal of promise as a response to mitigate the negative effects of a childhood shaped by unmitigated toxic stress. Over the course of the last three years, 13 individual agencies and a funder came together with a continuous improvement coach to create a cross-domain toolkit that will education the community in ACEs and provide them with 5 screener tools to increase their awareness of what Trauma-informed could look like. In 2019, after alpha and beta testing we are ready to being the process of rolling this into the community. This work will eventually be carefully scaled to be used by anyone that might be interested. There is a great deal of education that must take place to build will, change perspective and empower community members to create a compassionate community that recognizes that healing can take place in the foundation of compassionate relationships. BACKGROUNDUNDERSTANDING TRAUMA The brain is wired to thrive in the environment that it is constructed. When a brain is wired to adapt and respond to repeated stressors or traumatic experiences, it shapes the way that a person responds and adapts to the world. These behaviors, while critical for survival in highly stressful environments can be maladaptive in every day interactions. When we understand that individuals who have been exposed to trauma and stress are responding in the way that feels safe for them, we are able to take a more compassionate approach to their experiences with us. By recognizing these responses as ones that may be a product of stress we can create healthy, safe, predictable environments that allow for individuals to become empowered. As their self-efficacy increases, their brain begins to form new pathways and adaptive behaviors supporting their growth and healthy choices.Taken from Toolkit IntroductionINTRODUCTION TO TRAUMA-INFORMED CARE When we adopt this way of doing and being, participants and staff feel more empowered and safe. The perception of safety facilitates a higher level of trust, which creates environments that facilitate healing for those affected by trauma and toxic stress. As a universal-precaution, a trauma informed environment supports healthier environments for all. While this toolkit provides you with checklists, evaluation tools, and surveys, we caution you that Trauma-Informed Care (TIC) is not something to be achieved or completed. TIC is the way that we strive to do business. It is the deeply held belief that a compassionate approach is the best practice in our everyday interactions and is a commitment to continuous learning and improvement. TIC requires ongoing critical assessment of policies, staff, training, and hiring policies. While there is no end to TIC there are many opportunities to evaluate and celebrate successes. We recommend that you take the time to weigh each principle and decide how it fits into your organization, and then integrate the framework into your policy and decision-making efforts.WHY THIS MATTERS We know that trauma is pervasive. We cannot tell by just looking at someone if they have a trauma history or if they have or are experiencing toxic stress. Therefore, as a universal precaution, we want to be trauma-informed with all whom we interact so as not to trigger a trauma response. To fulfill the missions of our agencies and strive for the visions of the work we do, it calls upon us to honestly evaluate how existing processes, protocols, interactions, and environments may unintentionally trigger or turn others away from staying engaged with us (or even prevent others from being able to or wanting to engage with us in the first place). And instead, shifting to practices more focused on what works and what helps. Trauma-informed care is doing our work in a way that brought us all to our fields in the first place - to "do good". And to "do good", we must be willing to creatively, collaboratively, and justly look at how we can challenge the status quo and continually improve to do better.

Ozaukee County is served by a strong network of non-profits, including the human-service non-profits housed at the Family Enrichment Center (FEC). The FEC began as a concept in 1995 with four non-profits co-locating and sharing some services. It expanded to its current form in 1998 when those organizations built a joint building in Grafton and formed the FEC as a separate non-profit to manage the space. The FEC currently houses 10 partner agencies that help build strong families and improve the quality of life throughout Ozaukee County. Several of the partner agencies have requested assistance with team building, staff professional development, and general capacity building. The FEC has also requested board development programming that is open to all 10 partner agencies. The United Way of Northern Ozaukee, which financially supports many of the non-profits housed at the FEC, requested assistance with a facilitated process in 2018. The process is underway and will continue in 2019.

Document_Name: Strengthening Programming to 4-H Clubs in Waushara County
Segment: Research shows that high quality programs are more likely to foster positive youth developmental outcomes. High quality programs are characterized by 4 key elements, 1.safe, inclusive, and welcoming environment; 2. supportive and caring adults; 3. content that simultaneously challenges and sparks passion and interest; 4. high levels of youth voice in program decision making. Together, these elements promote youth engagement, and in turn the developmental and practical skills for youth to succeed. Programs that focus on maximizing each of the high quality elements are more likely to be engaging for participants.These key elements are especially important for 4-H and extension based programs because each element is within the control of program educators and participants. The elements can change and improve over time. By monitoring and evaluating each of the key elements, program leaders can adapt and improve the program to maximize positive youth development outcomes for all participants.Research with 4-H members nationally has shown that programs that implement these elements contribute to positive developmental outcomes including: 1. academic motivation and success; 2. social competence; 3. personal standards; 4. contributions to others,; 5. connections to others; and 6. personal responsibility. In turn, these developmental outcomes in the longer term contribute to increased academic and vocational success, civic engagement, economic stability and overall well-being.In Waushara County, there are (14) community clubs and (286) 4-H youth members in 2019, compared with (285) members in 2018. While the number of 4-H members and leaders has remained constant from 2018 to 2019, participation and engagement in trainings, meetings, activities, programming and workshops has increased.

Document_Name: Volunteer Development (2019) and High Quality Youth Programs (2
Segment: VOLUNTEER DEVELOPMENTAdult volunteers are Wisconsin 4-H's most valuable asset in delivering the quality youth-led, adult guided programs to support youth as they acquire essential life skills. Wisconsin 4-H Youth Development has over 9,650 volunteers who are enrolled as UW-Extension 4-H volunteers working with 30,000 youth enrolled in 4-H programs. In 2018, volunteers reported on average they donated over 58 hours per year. Approximately 72% of Wisconsin 4-H volunteers are female and 28% are male. Nationally, women continue to volunteer at a higher rate than men. (Bureau of Labor Statistics U.S. Department of Labor.) In Wisconsin 4-H, approximately 97% of the volunteers are white. WI 4-H Youth Development volunteers currently do not reflect the demographics of most counties.In 2018, Green County had 204 adult volunteers. The demographics of volunteers were 67% female and 33% male with approximately 2% of the volunteers being white. Green County demographics indicates there is a potential audience of volunteers who reflect a Hispanic ethnic group who are currently not volunteering in 4-H Youth Development.Volunteers play a critical role in the delivery of quality educational programs. In a survey completed January 2015, 4-H Youth Development staff identified Volunteer Development as an area in need of program support. Additionally, a WI 4-H Youth Development Survey was conducted in February 2014 of over 1500 volunteers. Adult volunteers in 4-H indicated relatively low awareness and understanding of some of the educational principles (Essential Elements and the Experiential Learning Process) that are central to the work of 4-H Youth Development. In the 2014 survey, volunteers expressed an interest in learning through not only face-to-face modalities; but also through online-learning such as webinars and podcasts. The 2017 Strategic Plan released by USDA NIFA and National 4-H Council outlines a 4-H Youth Development Vision for 2025. Nationally the following goal has been established "Youth are surrounded with competent, prepared staff and volunteers." This goal includes the following outcomes: "The 4-H program is supported by a well-trained volunteer force." "4-H staff and volunteers engage in meaningful professional development."In addition, there is a responsibility of volunteers to ensure access, equity and opportunity. The National 4-H Strategic goal states "All youth engage in program and opportunities." To that end it has been identified that "4-H volunteers and staff are skilled, knowledgeable and prepared to work with all members of their community."HIGH QUALITY YOUTH PROGRAMSResearch shows that high quality programs are more likely to foster positive youth developmental outcomes. High quality programs are characterized by 4 key elements: (1) safe, inclusive, and welcoming environment, (2) supportive and caring adults, (3) content that simultaneously challenges and sparks passion and interest, and (4) high levels of youth voice in program decision making. Together, these elements promote youth engagement, and in turn, the developmental and practical skills for youth to succeed. Regardless of the type of program (in-school, after-school, on-going, or sporadic), programs that focus on maximizing each of the high quality elements are more likely to be engaging for participants. These key elements are especially important for 4-H and Extension-based Positive Youth Development programs because each element is within the control of program educators and participants. The elements can change and improve over time. By monitoring and evaluating each of the key elements, program leaders can adapt and improve the program to maximize positive youth development outcomes for all participants. Research with 4-H members nationally has shown that programs that implement these elements contribute to positive developmental outcomes including: 1) academic motivation and success, 2) social competence, 3) personal standards, 4) contributions to others, 5) connections to others, and 6) personal responsibility. In turn, these developmental outcomes in the longer term contribute to increased academic and vocational success, civic engagement, economic stability, and overall wellbeing.https://health.oregonstate.edu/sites/health.oregonstate.edu/files/thriving-model/pdf/2018-thriving-model-summary-booklet.pdf

Document_Name: Addressing Labor Force Quantity and Quality in Wisconsin
Segment: The Center for Community and Economic Development was designated as a U.S. Department of Commerce Economic Development Administration University Center (UC) in 2016. In 2019, I will continue pursuing the work plan that we submitted as part of this designation. As part of this work plan, I will continue to address labor force availability in Wisconsin as an issue of both the quantity and quality of workers. Since I submitted my plan of work in 2018, very little has changed in terms of labor force challenges and businesses, economic development professionals and elected officials continue their desire to understand regional labor force conditions and develop strategies to find a sufficient supply of employees. Again, the importance of this issue is not surprising due to structural trends, such as slow population growth and an aging population, that have been documented by UW-Madison's Applied Population Laboratory, the Center for Community and Economic Development, and the Department of Agricultural and Applied Economics. Similar conditions also have been noted by the Wisconsin Department of Workforce Development. We can continue to address this issue using our research capacity and educational programs.

According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, health is a state of complete physical, mental and social well-being and not just the absence of sickness or frailty. A variety of factors influence a person's state of health including biological, socioeconomic, psychosocial, behavioral, or social. Health equity is achieved when all people have "the opportunity to 'attain their full health potential' and no one is 'disadvantaged from achieving this potential because of their social position or socially determined circumstance'." Family life and social support in Lincoln County has shown health disparities among youth as evident during our recent Community Health Improvement Planning process. According to the Wisconsin Child Abuse and Neglect Prevention Board, from 2011 - 2015, Lincoln County was the second highest in the state in prevalence of residents reporting 4 or more ACEs, also known as childhood trauma. The ACEs study found that having adverse childhood experiences was strongly associated with a range of psychological, social and health problems as as adult. Responses to these experiences often manifest in behaviors or conditions that result in involvement with the child welfare and the criminal and juvenile justice system or in difficulties in the education, employment or primary care system.(SAMHSA 2014). As a member of the Live Well Lincoln (formerly Healthy People Lincoln County) partnership committee, I have assisted the Health Department in the development and implementation of Community Health Improvement Process (CHIP) for 2012-17 CHIP and continuing to do so for the current 2018-2023 CHIP. The current plan details goals, objectives and strategies to address the health priorities identified through the assessment process completed in 2017. The priorities identified include Mental Health and Substance Abuse, Nutrition and Healthy Foods, and Oral (Dental) Health. In addition, to the partnership committee guiding the overall plan, each priority area is being worked on by a community coalition - Healthy Minds for Lincoln County, Nutrition Coalition and Healthy Smiles Coalition. Social determinants and health equity are additional overarching target priorities the each coalition and the partnership committee are addressing. In developing their action plan, each coalition utilized the socio-ecological model which provides a framework to think about the complexity of influences on health. At the individual level, age, income, race/ethnicity and the presence of a disability can influence an individual's health. Interpersonal factors include peer and family influences. At the environmental levels (organizational and community), schools, workplaces, recreational facilities, access to resources, and healthcare institutions influence the health choices people make. The social-ecological model can be used to develop, implement and evaluate comprehensive interventions at multiple levels. Efforts to improve health are more likely to be successful when using a coordinated, system-wide approach (U.S. Dept. Agriculture, 2010). (More information about the Live Well Lincoln (CHIP) can be found at http://lincolncountyhealthdepartment.com/healthy-people-lincoln-county-hplc-2/ .)In addition to serving on the Live Well Lincoln partnership committee, I continue to serve as one of two co-organizers of the newly formed Healthy Minds for Lincoln County Coalition. The Healthy Minds for Lincoln County coalition brings the community together to empower people through education and resources to support healthy choices regarding substances and social and emotional well-being. The Lincoln County Drug Free Coalition (I was one of the original organizers of this coalition in 2003 and have served as chair since 2012) and Lincoln County Mental Health Coalition (original member of this coalition) made the decision in early 2018 to combine into this newly merged Healthy Minds for Lincoln County coalition which they officially did on July 12, 2018. Mental Health and Substance Use are related issues and many individuals wish to work on both so forming a new merged group was deemed to be an effective way to proceed. Currently, eighteen agencies and organizations are members of the Healthy Minds for Lincoln County coalition. With the change in my role on September 1, 2018 from the 4-H Youth Development Educator to the Positive Youth Development and Health and Well Being Educator, I continue to address the health needs of young people and am expanding efforts to address the health needs of residents across the age spectrum. This expanded programming includes oversight for the existing Strong Bodies program that reaches 150 individuals in Merrill and Tomahawk, partnering with Pine River School for Young Learners on social emotional well-being programming, offering the Taking Care of You - stress reduction program; and joining the Live Well Lincoln Nutrition Coalition, Lincoln County Parent Support Network, Lincoln County Youth Justice Collaborative and a new Aging Coalition being formed by the Aging Disability Resource Center. Beyond Lincoln County, I serve as a Board member for the Northwoods Coalition (https://northwoodscoalition.org/ ), serve as a member of the UW-Extension Opioid Task Force (https://blogs.extension.wisc.edu/opioids/ ), and will consider serving on health teams that may be formed through the Positive Youth Development and/or Health and Well Being Institutes. As individuals and families gain knowledge and skills, and community environments support healthy living, there will be less illness, obesity, chronic disease, substance abuse and mental illness. Lincoln County and Wisconsin will benefit from these changes through decreased health care costs, increased productivity of our workforce and improved quality of life for all Wisconsin residents including Lincoln County.

In order for citizens to develop a deeper sense of place and participate in informed coastal stewardship and landscape protection, they require access to information about emerging issues in the Lake Superior watershed and the St. Louis River Estuary. In response, content related to climate impacts such as flooding, increased temperature and turbidity, and harmful algae blooms as well climate remediation and mitigation strategies should be incorporated into Estuarium exhibits, public programs and NOAA's Teachers on the Estuary/K-12 Estuary Education programs. In accordance with the Great Lakes Marine Debris Action Plan, conservation action education programming can support both marine debris prevention and removal in the St. Louis River estuary and Lake Superior. The Reserve education program provides support for partner efforts in elevating traditional ecological knowledge and biocultural wellbeing as important means of understanding, connecting to and restoring the landscape of the St. Louis River.

Document_Name: Addressing Family Financial Capability in Iowa County
Segment: Iowa County is located in southwest Wisconsin, just west of Madison and Dane County. According to data from the American Community Survey (http://factfinder2.census.gov), the population estimate in 2017 was 23,715 in 9,500 households. About 7,000 residents live in our two cities of Dodgeville and Mineral Point and the balance live in our several small villages and in the rural areas. Just over 60% of our households are made up of married couples, 1/3 of our households have children, and 25% of our households are adults living alone. The racial and ethnic makeup of Iowa County has changed slightly over the decades. The 2017 population estimate is 96% White, 0.7% Black or African American, 0.7% Asian, and 1.1% Two or More Races. The ethnicity in Iowa County is 1.8% Hispanic or Latino which is a 459% increase from 2000. In numbers, the Iowa County Hispanic or Latino population increased from 75 in 2000 to a 2017 estimate of 344. Similar to Wisconsin data, 94% of Iowa County residents over age 25 have graduated from high school and 25% have a bachelor's degree or higher. The Iowa County mean household income was $77,000 compared to the Wisconsin mean household income of $74,000. Our primary employment was related to education/health care/social assistance (21%), retail trade, specifically Lands' End (19%), and manufacturing (13%). Although we appear to be a very rural county, only 7% of our employment is related to agriculture. Our per capita income has increase almost 15% since 2010 while the state per capita income increased 11% in that same time period. Eighty percent (80%) of Iowa County parents with children under age six were in the workforce compared to 74% of Wisconsin parents with children the same ages. The unemployment rate in Iowa County peaked in 2010 at 11% and in October 2018 it was 2.1%. Wisconsin's unemployment rate is currently 3.2%. According to the 2016 Point-in-Time Data from the United Way ALICE Report for Wisconsin (Asset Limited, Income Constrained, Employed), 10% of Iowa County households are living in poverty and 24% of our households are considered ALICE. Both of these percentages are slightly below the state data. Our senior citizen poverty rate is 10% with another 32% of senior households considered ALICE (https://unitedwaywi.site-ym.com/page/2018ALICEbyCounty ). Homeowners make up 76% of the households in Iowa County with 24% of the households being rentals. Of the Iowa County and Wisconsin homeowners with a mortgage, 23% are spending more than 1/3 of their monthly income on housing and related homeowner costs. Thirty-five percent (35%) of Iowa County renters are spending more than 1/3 of their income for housing. In January 2019, the Community Development & Human Development Extension Educators in Iowa County developed a financial education survey with the cooperation of a partner agency from Dodgeville. Although the survey is still open, we have collected 88 responses and learned that: 47% of respondents don't always feel they have control over their day-to-day or month-to-month finances56% don't know if they would have a cushion for on unexpected expense or emergency42% don't feel they have the flexibility to have money for occasional extra spending60% are not sure they would be able to meet a financial goalMore than half of respondents would like to learn more about managing their money, saving their money, investing their money, and protecting their money. About one-third of respondents want to know more about making money and accessing retirement accounts with minimal tax consequences. 60% of respondents selected 3 or more of the 8 topics to learn about80% of respondents are interested in attending in-person classes on these topicsThe data indicates that Iowa County families have financial resources but many of them are also facing challenges. They are also eager to learn. My primary work in Iowa County for 2019-2020 will focus on responding to those interests and needs related to financial well-being with education and partnerships that intended to enhance the ability of individuals and families to manage their resources and support their families.

Document_Name: Parent and Relationships Education Plan of Work 2019
Segment: Research is clear that strong family and other interpersonal relationships significantly contribute to the health and well-being of individuals across the lifespan. Family strengthening programs and policies help build strong relationships within supportive communities, improving outcomes for children, families and society. Families perform a variety of key functions that contribute to both the mental and physical health of individuals as well as the public health and functioning of society. Throughout all developmental stages strong healthy relationships help families effectively and efficiently raise healthy children, care for vulnerable members and sustain productive workers and contributing community members. Research shows that when families build strong relationships within supportive communities many sources of stress are reduced and outcomes for children, families and society improve. Children thrive in school and life. Parents and caregivers are better prepared to provide sensitive and responsible care: The negative effects of incarceration, conflict, and other family stressors decrease. Lifelong mental, physical and emotional health is promoted. (2018 Human Development and Family Relationships State Team Plan of Work). Sometimes families need extra help in creating healthy relationships and experiences for their children which Extension addresses through education and community collaborative work designed to build family strengths. Fond du Lac County has a population of 101,968 residents, with the median age of 41 years. Ninety five percent of the county are Caucasian, with 2% Black or African American and almost 2 % Asian with one percent from some other race. Hispanic population is 4.9% of the 101,968 county population. Median household income is $56,376 and from Census, there are 41,029 households with income and benefits in the county. In comparing the median household income and the number of households with income, there are 18,013 households who earn under $ 49,999 - under the median income or 44%. There are 4,114 families with SNAP benefits in the past 12 months- 10% of households. (https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml# )In 2017, United Way Asset Limited, Income Constrained, Employed (ALICE) survey was released. ALICE provides a framework, language and tools to measure and understand the struggles of the growing households in Fond du Lac County who do not earn enough to afford basic necessities. (https://www.fdlunitedway.org/sites/fdlunitedway.oneeach.org/files/fdl%20snapshot.pdf ) The ALICE report for Fond du Lac County noted based upon 41,938 households, 22% of the households earned more than the Federal Poverty Level, but less than the basic cost of living for Fond du Lac County (the ALICE threshold) Combined, the number of poverty and ALICE households equals the total population struggling to afford basic needs, this number is 33% of the households in Fond du Lac County. Inability to make ends meet financially affects the family beyond the pocketbook as it affects relationships within the family and community due to tough choices are made that affect the family and its members. These choices whether financial or not have long-term consequences for families and communities, which is indicative of future success for all involved. Fond du Lac County families are integral to the county's population and looking at the youngest county members, there are 5,695 children less than five years of age. (https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml# ) Consistent, nurturing relationships are of vital importance to healthy development of children in Fond du Lac County. Strong supports are needed throughout the family lifecycle especially when there are outside forces which affect the family- opioid addiction, mental health challenges, foster parenting and incarceration are present in Fond du Lac County and the families who live here. Supporting families through outside challenges requires collaborative community supports to build resiliency and strength in families as they address challenges and strive to support a healthy relationship for their family and its members. Additionally, when a family goes through divorce, separation, and foster care placement it can be difficult to adjust to the changes. Education and resources offer strategies to educate parents and children about the impact of the family transition and adjustment to their new life as co-parents. Further, co-parenting education and resources are needed by families that have children, yet were not married to one another and foster care parents co-parenting with biological parents need assistance co-parenting as well. More than 14,000 Wisconsin children experience their parents' divorce each year; this number does not include children of unmarried parents who separate, or those who never lived together. Exposure to conflict is the single biggest factor affecting children as they transition from one household to two. In 2018, Fond du Lac County had 566 Marriages, 314 Divorces, 182 Divorces w/minor Children (57.96%) and 102 Paternity cases. This statistic for the county has been consistent for the past 3 years. On average, 300+ individuals attend the Co-Parenting and Paternity Co-Parenting classes held in Fond du Lac County annually.

Situation Statement: Youth leadership requires development programs and tools to educate young people to reach their full potential and be successful. Wisconsin 4-H offers programs to aid in this process. In order for this process to be successful, adult volunteers and community members need to work together to sustain these programs in order to help youth grow and learn. Adult volunteers lead trainingsessions, programs, project activities, and leadership events to support 4-Hyouth in the Pepin County Community. Not only do the 4-H Adult leaders play apart in the success of our youth, but the community plays a vital role.Connecting the dots from the community to our 4-H youth is an important rolefor Wisconsin 4-H to play. To create the strongest youth/adult partnership for our program, it is important that adults are provided with the knowledge, training, and skills to help youth be as successful as possible. In order to meet with goal, communication and collaboration are vital in this process. Maintaining and creating community partnerships which will strengthen and grow the program are necessary in Barron county. Finding the best ways to communicate with leaders and community partners is also imperative to the success in youth programming.

Document_Name: FOSTERING WELLNESS THROUGH PROGRAMMING AND LEADERSHIP DEVELOPME
Segment: National: Improving health outcomes has been at the forefront of National, State and County awareness for many years. Extension specifically has seen the value in supporting programs to address the wide array of health indicators. The National Cooperative Extension system realized the need to intentionally address this emerging field of health in 2010 and subsequently created the National Framework for Health and Wellness in 2014. Wisconsin: UW Extension updated their strategic priorities in 2017. UW-Extension's mission is "Through UW-Extension, people of Wisconsin and beyond can access university resources and engage in learning, wherever they live and work". And one way UW Extension has planned to fulfill its mission is by "Addressing the changing needs of the state and society by conducting, applying, and conveying relevant university research." UW-Extension has had health related goals and plans prior to in 2015. The anticipated public value of doing this work can be found in the 2018 Healthy Living Team Plan of Work. https://blogs.ces.uwex.edu/flpteams/healthylivingteam/ UW-Extension has a unique role in responding to the above needs at the community and state level. We are positioned in countries with direct links to community partners, stakeholders and residents. We have links to University data and research. UW-Extension can better develop and support community-academic research partnerships, translate health interventions for dissemination for community leaders, and directly teach and create policy to better impact community health. UW-Extension's statewide current plans of work include: Food & Culture WorkGroup Plan of Work: "A healthy population is critical to a prosperous and productive Wisconsin. Based on information from County Health Rankings, Community Health Improvement Process (CHIP) & Community Health Needs Assessment (CHNA) data, as well as State Surveillance data, we find a high prevalence of overweight or obesity children and adults, poor dietary patterns, continuing food insecurity, and the prevalence of food assistance programs and use of food pantries. According to findings from the Survey of the Health of Wisconsin (SHOW), the state's obesity rate is 4.5 percent higher than the national average obesity rate of 34.9 percent. Obesity rates are higher in persons who are older, poor, less educated, minorities, or those who live in a community with high economic hardship. Additionally, more than 1 in 9 Wisconsin households are food insecure, meaning they lack access to sufficient foods to support a healthy and active life. A 2014 Feeding America Hunger Study found that nearly 2 in 3 low-income Wisconsin households plan for a charitable food assistance as a part of their monthly household budget. Food insecurity has negative impacts on health, including nutrient deficiencies, low birth weight and premature birth, and chronic stress." Active Communities Plan of Work: "Physical Activity has been shown to reduce the risk for chronic health conditions including cardiovascular disease, diabetes, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, osteoporosis, and certain types of cancer. In addition, physical activity helps with weight management, improving mental health, and strengthens muscles and bones. Physical inactivity has also been associated with increasing the risk for chronic disease. According to County Health Rankings, 83% of Wisconsinites report having access to physical activity, with reporting of the lowest access to exercise opportunities at 7% and the highest at 99%. In addition, 21% of Wisconsin residents report that they get no leisure time physical activity (4). The Active Communities team strives to increase physical activity opportunities for all members of the community using Active School and Active Communities Strategies, StrongWomen and other evidence-based programs. By using evidence-based programs to increase physical activity in schools and communities, and by increasing access to physical activity opportunities, individuals will have the knowledge and ability to be more physically active to improve their health. Efforts of the Active Communities team will enhance and improve physical activity levels across the state and thus, improve the health and overall quality of life of Wisconsin residents." Health Equity Plan of Work: "Leading public health practitioners and researchers agree that to improve health, we must advance health equity. Health equity occurs when all people have the opportunity to achieve their full potential for health and well-being (CSDH, 2008). Health inequities are differences in population health status and health outcomes that are systemic, unjust, and actionable, they are not random or caused by individuals who become ill (Whitehead, 1992). Internationally, health inequities prevent many countries from reaching optimal population health outcomes (Marmot et al., 2008). Inequities not only impact individuals directly but also impact the communities where those individuals live. All parts of communities' experience ripple effects from infectious diseases, consequences of alcohol and drug misuse and abuse, and the occurrence of violence and crime that tend to increase as inequities increase (Woodward & Kawachi, 2000). Moreover, health inequities are incredibly costly. Between 2003 and 2006, the combined costs of health inequities and premature death in the U.S. was estimated at $1.24 trillion (LaVeist, Gaskin, & Richard, 2009)." The state of Wisconsin continues to address health via many different venues and departments. The Department of Health and Human Services most recent WI Health Improvement Plan includes health improvement needs in the areas of nutrition/physical activity and alcohol/drugs/tobacco use. Rock County: As the years have gone by, I continue to keep current with local data, population trends, and emerging issues. Rock County is unique in its population, demographics, and distribution of resources. Rock County's current population is 162,309 and continues to rank among Wisconsin's most populous counties. Demographically, Rock County is 91% White, 9% Latinx, and 5% African American. Rock County is a combination of urban and rural. It also has pocket areas of high poverty and low socioeconomic status. As the population is trending upward, so are the number of families living in poverty and experiencing health disparities, specifically in African American and Latinx communities. There are many needs in Rock County. Data that Rock County is in very poor health compared to the state and national averages cannot be ignored. The County Health Rankings suggest that in 2018 Rock County was ranked 69 out of 72 counties for Quality of Life and 66 out of 72 counties for Poor Health Behaviors (i.e., unhealthy weight, physical activity, nutrition/food environment index, smoking, excessive alcohol drinking, sexually transmitted infections). Document_Name: Parents / Caregivers play a key role as their child's first tea
Segment: Parents/caregivers of young children play an important role as their child's first teacher. This includes fostering early learning and continuing to play a critical role in their child's academic success after they enter school. Racine County Extension seeks to improve parent/caregiver understanding of child development and increase support of families by offering workshops about child development, kindergarten readiness, reading and literacy, social emotional development, and other topics that respond to the needs of families.

Document_Name: Education Program Request, Booking, and Invoice Systems For Weh
Segment: Wehr Nature Center and Wehr Outreach provide environmental education programming for PreK-12th grade youth in the metro-Milwaukee area. As part of this programming, we provide an online program request plan for teachers to serve as an aid to them in booking and receiving a program which fits their classroom's needs. An antiquated program using Access and later Google forms has proven cumbersome for staff and teachers to use. In summer 2018, the education staff of Wehr Nature Center and Wehr Outreach began the task of creating a new system for booking programs.

Document_Name: (2019) Opioid Capacity Building for UWEX staff
Segment: The misuse of and addiction to opioids is a serious national health crisis that has grown to epidemic status. In 2016, the national rate of opioid related deaths was 13.3 deaths per 100,000. The rate of drug overdose deaths has steadily increased in the last decade. In 2016, national rate of drug overdose deaths was more than three times the rate in 1999.In Wisconsin, the drug overdose death rate is higher than the national average. Wisconsin has a rate of 15.8 deaths per 100,000 or (865 people). This statistic refers to only opioid related deaths. Countless more Wisconsin residents are affected by opioid addiction from those who are currently addicted, to children in foster and kinship care due to neglect and/or abuse associated with their parents' drug addiction. The fallout from addiction includes eviction, homelessness, criminal history, unemployment, adverse childhood experiences (ACES), among many others. These rates are expected to soar with the rise in opioid use.

Document_Name: Family Economic Security and Financial Literacy (2019)
Segment: Families in Wisconsin struggle to make end meets, with 17% of our children living in poverty and 31% of these children live in single parent households. There are 286,829 families with 405,611 young children. In Wisconsin, 43% (172,526) of young children live in low-income families. (National: 45%) We know that families perform a variety of key functions that contribute to both the mental and physical health of individuals as well as the public health and functioning of society. Throughout all developmental stages, from the prenatal period to the last years of life, strong healthy relationships help families effectively and efficiently raise healthy children, care for vulnerable members, and sustain productive workers and contributing community members. Despite recent reports of overall improvement in employment and gains in median incomes, the economic recovery in Wisconsin has been uneven. Many families continue to face challenges from low wages, depleted savings, and the increasing cost of basic household goods. The total number of Wisconsin households that cannot afford basic needs increased 5 percent between 2010 and 2016. The 2016 ALICE report noted 24% of Wood County residents qualified as Asset Limited Income Constrained and Employed. This is consistent with the UWSWAC Financial Stability survey results from Fall of 2017 that noted 69% of participants reported never having been taught how to manage their money and 49% in the Fall of 2018 reported not having an emergency savings. Financial security is the goal for many Americans. Financial security is defined as an individual's or family's ability to meet short-term needs and to prepare for the future. The path to financial security requires accessible and accurate information, as well as financial competency in setting goals, earning, spending, saving, borrowing, and protecting. But it is not enough to just provide learners access to these concepts. The Wood County Family Living Educator, promotes financial capability more broadly, which includes how learners apply what knowledge they have combined with access to community partners and services, prior experiences, attitudes and behaviors.Work will focus on helping families build their financial literacy capacity by: Providing tools to increase their knowledge of financial concepts and strategies of budgeting, creating a spending plan and maintaining good credit. Providing financial capability programs to address increasing or rebuilding credit worthiness and individual financial capacity.[1] http://www.countyhealthrankings.org/sites/default/...[2] http://www.countyhealthrankings.org/sites/default/...[3] http://www.nccp.org/profiles/WI_profile_8.html

Document_Name: Financial capabilities: Changing the landscape for young famili
Segment: The lower median income and educational attainment rates in Richland County suggest a need for financial education programming. I am a leader and key connector, both in providing direct financial education and organizing local partnerships. In the 2016 Community Health Needs Assessment, residents identified the top 3 social issues as: Housing, Household Financial Stability, and Jobs & Economy. Richland County has many young families and is close to the state average when it comes to percentage of children under 5 and children under 18. In Richland County, 19.5% of children live in poverty, compared to 18.5% statewide. The Richland School District has 53% of 2015 students receiving free or reduced lunch, up from 51% in 2011. It is clear that many families with children are low income, which combined with geographic isolation, suggests greater need to be connected to community opportunities and positive resources to assist with family functioning, including financial management.

Document_Name: Community Wealth and Household Financial Stability (2019)
Segment: Extensive local collaboration on the 2017 LIFE Report for Portage County has expanded recognition of the need for the community to continue to focus on financial stability and housing affordability in Portage County. These were key calls to action in the report that numerous leaders and knowledgeable people in the community will be collaborating to address. As a summary of these calls to action observes: more than a third of Portage County households struggle to afford basic necessities, and the number of households that report spending more than 30% of their income on housing has increased in recent years as rental rates have been rising. Ownership can be more affordable than renting in Portage County, and offers the benefits of building equity. Yet as indicated in the 2018 ALICE report for Wisconsin, "that is only an option for those who can afford a down payment and real estate taxes and who qualify for a mortgage". Costs of other basic needs have also risen substantially. Comparing the overall household survival budgets as estimated in the 2016 and 2018 United Way ALICE Reports for Wisconsin, the cost of basic needs for a family of four in Portage County has increased by roughly $7,000 over a two-year period (between 2014 and 2016). This represents an average annual growth rate of about 6% per year. Several community members are presently engaged in a series of meetings aimed at figuring out a way to address such concerns, and this group has acknowledged a need to learn more about existing models. Community-based development strategies for us to explore would include those that may help to hold down costs of living and expand opportunities for more people to gain financial stability.

What's Going On Working to complete community needs assessments in both Columbia and Sauk counties, it is emerging that family dynamics within and across generations is a sociocultural hurdle within communities. Raising children, achieving adulthood, maturing successfully, aging with good health and moving through life with competence and confidence are key areas of struggle for most individuals consistently. What was developmentally true or expected of individuals in previous generations is not necessarily developmentally true of generations today. Extension programming will serve to help individuals to bridge this gap by providing educational programming that is timely, accessible, and up to date. Who Cares and Has a Stake The statewide situational statement conducted across the 72 counties in 2018 found 18 points of common challenge in 5 key themes around the state. Within each of these themes a human relationship-based solution has potential. If the interactions or, relationships, between people or groups of people could overcome these challenges then quality of life for all community members could potentially improve. State and local partners have a joint investment in solving these challenges to improve quality of life across Wisconsin for all residents. As a Columbia & Sauk County Extension educator I will participate in and facilitate the building of coalitions locally to problem solve individual and group challenges to human relationships in daily community life. How was this identified Nationally, the social and cultural issues we face in Wisconsin are evident across our country. The World Health Organization (WHO)'s action plan through 2020 has amongst its four primary goals to, 1) implement strategies for promotion and prevention in mental health, and 2) to strengthen information systems, evidence and research for mental health. As an Extension educator I can support these national goals through outreach with key community partners to advocate for developmental needs of all residents across the human life span, to keep the integration of ACES/ Trauma Informed programming central to the work undertaken, and to help guide the use of resources effectively and efficiently so that the needs are directed at the right issues at the right time.

Demographic changes in Green County has resulted in identified need to build leadership and increase community engagement across generations. This need arises in multiple community plans and is expressed by business, local government, and community leaders. It is of particular concern because many of the current business, government, and community leaders are older. For these reasons, it's important to build leadership skills among younger leaders to "deepen" the leadership bench in Green County. At the same time, demographic data indicates that Green County is aging and becoming more racially diverse.

Document_Name: Improved Health for Richland County Youth & Families
Segment: Residents of Richland County face several health challenges. According to the data collected in the 2016 Community Health Needs Assessment, the top health needs are: Substance abuse prevention & treatment, Overweight/obesity prevention & treatment, and Mental health care. Coalitions to address health needs allows for resources to be leveraged and to avoid service duplication. The high overweight/obesity rate (1 in 3 adults) led to the creation of the Richland Fitness in Total (FIT) coalition in 2011. I serve in a leadership role as coalition co-chair and participant in the Healthy Wisconsin Leadership Institute. For Substance Abuse Prevention, the Richland County Children and Families Advocacy Council is a nonprofit coalition well positioned to take on the challenge, but requires support in data analysis, planning, leadership development, and evaluation. Additionally, I can offer educational programming to build the metal resilience and coping skills of residents, including the Raising a Thinking Child parenting program.

Document_Name: Extension Responds to Farm Businesses' Economic Challenges
Segment: Due to ongoing economic conditions in agriculture, many farms are facing significant financial challenges, resulting in questions regarding the viability of the businesses. Based on the Economic Research Service's latest farm income forecast, farm income has now been in general decline for 4 years and seems to be headed for a fifth in 2019. The downturn has clearly started to take a toll, financially and mentally for many farms, farm families and rural communities which depend on agriculture. Farms are experiencing challenges in their ability to successfully transfer the business to the next generation, and others will need to consider an exit strategy, and off-farm employment. At the same time, UW-Extension currently faces the challenge of bringing a number of new educators on board with the organization. Many educators come to UW-Extension with a formal education and professional experience in their field (for example, production agriculture). However, working with farmers, farm families, and rural communities, given current challenges, can involve difficult and emotional conversations, which Extension educators may have little experience or training.

Document_Name: Addressing Leadership and Organizational Development Challenges
Segment: This program was prioritized based on the continued need to raise the majority of my salary and benefits from sources outside of the UW-Madison Division of Extension's budget (with grants, contracts and fees for educational services). This is my 15th year operating within this type of budgeting plan. In 1999, UW-Extension began working with urban neighborhoods adjacent to downtown Waukesha. Current efforts sponsored by Greater Milwaukee Foundation support outreach in Dunbar Oaks, located directly south and Tower Hill, directly west. These are Middle Neighborhoods: affordable, racial/socioeconomically diverse and on the edge of growth or decline. Both neighborhoods' land use is primarily affordable single and multifamily housing options. This location is within walking distance to the downtown riverwalk, parks, schools, numerous eating and drinking places, professional services and retail establishments. These neighborhoods have the youngest median age group in the county with over 50% low -to-moderate income households and older housing stock in established neighborhoods with many amenities. Key issues in the focus areas include the deterioration of affordable housing stock and the lack of a formalized Community Development Corporation to lead/sustain revitalization efforts with these low-income, underserved and distressed neighborhoods. This targeted area that has the largest concentration of housing built before 1960 in Waukesha County. Through neighborhood outreach efforts, housing maintenance and curb appeal improvement are continually identified as key issues to address. To retain and improve this existing housing stock, and influence new housing in-fill, a collective effort is needed with a focus on neighborhood housing.Community Development Educaotrs will pursue a collective effort that engages community partners to connect homeowners with housing resources to help them improve the physical conditions of their homes and strengthen Neighborhood Leadership/Organization Development to sustain quality of life neighborhood efforts.

Document_Name: Master Gardener Program - A joint Waukesha/Milwaukee County Ext
Segment: The Master Gardener Program (MGP) was created in the early 1970's as a way for an extension educator to serve broader audiences' in obtaining answers to their gardening questions. The first records of MGP training in WI appear in the late 70's/early 80's. Since that time, the program has expanded beyond diagnostic services. Today's Master Gardener volunteer activities include establishing native environments and protecting valuable pollinator areas; participating in beautification projects in communities, parks and business districts to aid in placemaking; partnering with our FoodWIse educators to educate low income families on how to grow food; giving educational public presentations on various gardening topics; planting and maintaining gardens that demonstrate science-based gardening recommendations; and doing horticultural therapy-type programming in conjunction with health care, correctional, educational facilities. County MG program coordinators (educators) recruit community members as volunteers, train individuals to increase their capacity on a topic (horticulture), and leverage volunteer efforts to address our educational priorities.To achieve success in this program, educators:Recruit and train volunteers to increase their capacity in addressing horticultural related issues on behalf of UWEX. Support volunteers and leverage their efforts via volunteer development principles, developing community partnerships, and creating/approving projects to assist UWEX address our educational priorities. On a local level, Milwaukee and Waukesha counties have worked together to offer the master gardener program. This two county program ignores county borders and provides training and volunteer opportunities in both counties giving master gardeners the option to choose the location that is convenient for them. Both the Milwaukee County Extension Horticulture Educator and the Waukesha County Extension Horticulture Educator co-lead the program. In addition, all program records and MG support staff are employed and housed in the Milwaukee County Extension office. In January of 2018, the Milwaukee County Horticulture Educator retired. At that time, it was arranged that I would coordinate the MG program in both counties until the Milwaukee County horticulture educator position was refilled. Position descriptions were developed for Milwaukee, Racine, and Waukesha Extension Horticulture Educators. Two new positions serving all three counties were agreed upon. One position would coordinate the Master Gardener program in Racine and Kenosha and co-coordinate with me for the Waukesha/Milwaukee County MG program. The other would be a horticulture outreach specialist position and would serve Racine, Kenosha, and Milwaukee counties.
