Many communities depend on a sustainable forest products industry. As harvesting from industry-owned land decreased, to ensure a continuous timber supply the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources (DNR) looks toward those who own nearly 70% of the 16 million acres of forested land   private woodland owners.Traditionally only a small percentage of woodland owners participate in learning events, and only about 25% have a management plan for their forests. Of these, 16% turned to extension for advice and Cooperative Extension is taking up the task of identifying and reaching those among the state's estimated 414,000 non-industrial private forest landowners who are seeking technical assistance to manage and transfer their woodlands to the next generation with active management on the 6,197,990 family-owned acres yet to be covered (DNR, 2013).

The Wisconsin Master Naturalist Program is a growing network of well-informed citizens dedicated to conservation, education and service within their communities. The program is entering its seventh season and the growth of volunteers, instructors and partner growth is becoming exponential. In six short years, 868 individuals have taken the volunteer training course and115 instructors representing 51 organizations are trained Master Naturalist instructors. The Master Naturalist Volunteer Training Course provides 40 hours of coursework in natural history, interpretation, and conservation stewardship from partner organizations throughout the state. Wisconsin Master Naturalist volunteers perform at least 40 hours of volunteer service each year and receive 8 hours of additional training each year to maintain certification. From 2013-2018, over 80,376 service hours were self-reported representing a value of $1.98 million.  The current website and on-line volunteer management system need to be upgraded to meet the needs of volunteers, instructors and the program. With the integration of Extension within UW Madison, there is a need to create a consistent mechanism for managing volunteers at an Extension level. The program has grown to include aspects that were not part of the first curriculum. The curriculum needs to be updated and revised on a rotational basis.  Volunteers report 2-3 times that amount of required hours for advanced training. This demonstrates a need and desire for additional understanding of Wisconsin's natural resources and stewardship of our precious resources.

Document_Name: Community Engaged Leadership: Emphasis on Youth Leadership #2
Segment: Youth leadership development programs provide skill development and the opportunity to apply applying learned leadership skills. University of Illinois Extension (Diaz et al, 2015) has identified six action areas where youth leaders develop competency in 4-H Youth Development: 1) planning, 2) promoting, 3) teaching, 4) mentoring, 5) advocating, and 6) advising. Program examples and outcomes in each of these six areas were highlighted in a 2016 Wisconsin 4-H impact report: https://fyi.uwex.edu/4h/files/2014/06/2016-Wisconsin-4-H-Foundational-Topics-Report.pdfThe 2010 Wisconsin 4-H Youth Leadership study found that all older 4-H youth demonstrated individual growth in life skills, youth participating in the program's intentional leadership practices (club officers, committee members, camp counselors, leadership training workshop participants, teen court panelists, etc.) had more opportunities in group and teamwork development. Intentional leadership activities give many opportunities to lead and work with both youth and adults. The study identified key program practices that contributed to leadership skill development, including: - Youth are working on meaningful issues and have significant responsibilities- Program structure provides a scaffold for youth leadership- Shared vision and commitment fosters teamwork- Youth/adult partnershipThe strongest outcomes in the 2010 Wisconsin 4-H study were in community connectedness and self-efficacy (beliefs about one's capabilities to produce effects). The strongest skill outcomes were related to communication, decision-making and problem-solving skills.In 2018, Polk County had 308 teens in grades 7-13 participating in the 4-H Community Club program. These teen leaders have opportunities to expand their leadership skills and practice through being: Club Officers, Youth Representatives on the 4-H Leaders Federation Board, club and county committee members and chairs, 4-H Ambassadors, Camp Counselors, Junior Directors, and experiences beyond the county. Helping youth connect with these opportunities and experiences is key to their gaining the necessary skills for mastery and leadership competencies.

Document_Name: Financial Capability for Families and Community Agencies
Segment: Poverty and financial instability is a key source of stress in Bayfield County for families and individuals. The percent of children in poverty in the county is 22% compared with a statewide rate of 16%. (County Health Rankings and Roadmaps). The region faces the challenges of a rural economy with few high paying jobs. According to the Dec 2018 WI Dept of Workforce Development report, Bayfield County had the highest unemployment rate among counties in the state. Median household income is $50,110, compared to the state median of $56,759. According to the MIT Living Wage Calculator a Bayfield County family of two children and two working adults must earn $64,788 annually to meet basic living expenses without assistance programs. A single parent must earn over $59,056. These wages are well above median earnings and the wages offered in the typical service industry, hospitality, farming and support positions most commonly available in the county. Many financially stressed families face difficult decisions in trying to prioritize bills and extend limited resources to meet monthly expenses. Sometimes, without adequate information, poor decisions can lead to costly additional expenses and consequences, such as utility disconnect/reconnect fines, late payment fees, and high interest resulting from poor credit. Without careful planning families and individuals sometimes rely on payday loans and other high-cost lending options, spending extremely high amounts on interest. These extra financial burdens compound an already challenging situation. In addition, some families and individuals are unaware of community resources to help or may feel a stigma in accessing resources. Financial education can help provide families and the agencies that serve them with information to make informed decisions. This can help extend limited resources while reducing the excess costs of fines, fees, high-cost lending and other expenses. It can also empower individuals to set their own financial goals and work toward them through realistic steps with the support of an educator or financial coach. Bayfield County Human Development & Relationships programming is framed around the Center for Study of Social Policy's Strengthening Families Protective Factors: These five factors: Parental Resilience, Social Connections, Social Emotional Skills, Parenting Knowledge and Concrete Support in Times of Need are shown to enhance child development and reduce the likelihood of child maltreatment. They are also important to the well-being of all families, not just those at risk. Financial education contributes to two of these five factors: Parental Resilience and Concrete Support in Times of Need.

Segment: Through service, individuals and groups in 4-H Youth Development contribute to the community now and build the skills, habits, and relationships to continue to contribute in the future.Service is an important way in which individuals and groups in 4-H Youth Development build positive skills and habits, connect to others in their communities, and learn about the needs of others in their communities. If designed intentionally, community service can be connected to other projects to create opportunities for application and deeper learning. Creating opportunities for youth to determine issues, plan responses, carry out a project, and reflect on their experience can more community service into service-learning. It was deduced that the after school directors have little time to put the effort into connecting the youth in their programs with service learning projects. They are looking for guidance and assistance in doing this outreach with their students and would like to develop a model. The United Nations measures the Human Development Index which captures human progress combining information on people's health, education, and income. Yet, the simplicity of the HDI leaves much unsaid, and despite progress, large pockets of poverty, exclusion, and inequality exist. The United States HDI is a .924, however, when inequalities, like health, education, poverty, and having a voice are factored in, the score drops to .796 (Human Development Report, 2016). The State Wellbeing Score measures each states wellbeing, looking at purpose, social, financial, community, and physical wellbeing. Wisconsin has a score of 62.4 (National Score is 61.7) placing at thirteenth out of the 50 states. While, Wisconsin measures well in this assessment, it places at 31st in both purpose and social wellbeing (Gallup Healthways Wellbeing Index 2015). The COMPASS Now Report, a community health and wellbeing assessment facilitated by Great Rivers United Way for La Crosse County and five surrounding counties, indicated that the five top issues La Crosse County faces are: a need for more livable wage jobs, increased access to mental health, increased inclusion of socially diverse people, decrease of alcohol and drug misuse and abuse, and improved wellbeing of children and youth (Gromoske, 2018).Through community assessments and informal interviews of strategic stakeholders in La Crosse County, ACEs (adverse childhood experiences) are a factor in many issues affecting wellbeing including health, life expectancy, education, relationships, mental health, substance abuse, and financial wellbeing (Centers for Disease Control, 2016). Not only is trauma history an important issue that affects wellbeing in La Crosse County, but historical trauma, cultural differences, and socioeconomic differences are also issues that affect wellbeing of all community members as well as participation in services, programming, and having a voice. Research has indicated that being culturally, trauma, and socially/emotionally responsive improve wellbeing, participation, and social emotional learning for all community members. Improving wellbeing has been researched at an individual level, looking at methods to improve resilience, decrease stress, and increase happiness (Lyubomirsky, 2013). Further, the United Nations promotes six pillars of human development: equity, sustainability, productivity, empowerment, cooperation, and security. Initiatives like the Full Frame Initiative, positive psychology like wholebeing, and cultural and trauma responsivity, combine the academic pillars with tools and skills to improve relationships, organizations, systems, and communities to shift their fundamental focus from fixing problems to fostering wellbeing and relationships and looking holistically at people, policy, and community. Document_Name: Building Capacity in Local Justice Systems for a Family and Fut
Segment: Buffalo and Pepin are adjacent, rural counties and share a combined total of a little more than 20,500 individuals living in 8,759 households (U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts estimates, July 1, 2016), spread across 1,004 square miles. In both counties, agricultural-related activity is the primary economic base. Statistics show that family composition is mixed, with a greater percentage of single-parent households, unmarried parents and stepfamilies, in comparison to two-parent households. (American Community Survey Profile Report: 2011-2015 5-year estimates). Racial/ethnic composition in Buffalo County is 97.7% white alone; Pepin 98.2%. Although a relatively small percentage, Latino is the predominant minority, and I have utilized partnerships for outreach to connect with Latina-led young families for parenting and relationship education. Alcohol abuse, illegal drug use and mental health are top concerns for residents across both counties. (Great Rivers United Way COMPASS NOW 2015 Survey; Buffalo County Community Needs Assessment, 2015; Pepin County Community Health Improvement Plan 2016-2020; Buffalo County Community Health Improvement Plan 2016-2020). According to the National Provider Identification Registry, there were no mental health care providers available in Buffalo County prior to 2015. There are now two part-time mental health providers available in Buffalo and Pepin counties, with a patient to provider ratio of 6,679:1, compared with the WI state average ideal patient to provider ratio of 623:1. The lack of access to mental health services is a problem for families and individuals.Both Buffalo and Pepin counties face a dramatic doubling (from 15% to 30%) of residents age 65 and older by the year 2035. A need to prepare aging-friendly communities has been expressed among local government and agency partners, and will be a part of future programming planning. (This may become a secondary programming priority).Median household income is $50,196 and $49,516 for Buffalo and Pepin counties respectively. However, there are wide disparities between age groups, ranging from $16,917 for younger adults to $63,182 for seniors (U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts estimates, July 1, 2016). And, while unemployment rates are low, so are high-paying "living wage" jobs (livingwage.mit.edu, living wage calculator, 2017). Only 4% of Buffalo County respondents rated the availability of jobs with wages that offer a good standard of living; 74% responded poor or fair (2015 United Way: Buffalo County Random Household Survey). The percentage of high-paying jobs is low and a high household income is not enjoyed by most residents. The UW-Extension 2018 Developmental Situational Analysis process for Area 9 identified AODA and health concerns, and building skills for healthy family relationships, stability and well-being as two of the top five priority needs. This was based on a broad representation of stakeholder/partner input and surveys, and is consistent with results of a 2010 formal Survey of Issues and Themes Impacting WI Families and Communities that I conducted with local partners, as part of a statewide Family Living Program effort. Responses from dozens of partners confirmed my programming focus on education and prevention for family relationships and financial security, especially for vulnerable populations. Local Community Health Improvement Plans, United Way Community Assessments and Youth Risk Behavior Survey data continue to validate these programming priorities.I hold a leadership role within the Institute for Human Development and Relationships by chairing two state efforts: Healthy Relationships, and Correctional Systems Audiences. In order to make the greatest impacts at the local, regional or state levels, it is important that I leverage resources and be clear about my facilitating, research, education, planning and evaluation roles. Where possible, a prevention approach that reached a wide audience has been the foundation of programming efforts and, when necessary or appropriate, intervention strategies have been used. I rely on research and specialist support, as well as multiple sources for assessing current and future community needs. I advance a collective impact with partners and coalitions.Provide educational resources and opportunities about healthy couple, co-parenting and other family relationships parenting, child development, either direct education or contacts, online or through key partners.

Many communities depend on a sustainable forest products industry. As harvesting from industry-owned land decreased, to ensure a continuous timber supply the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources (DNR) looks toward those who own nearly 70% of the 16 million acres of forested land   private woodland owners. Traditionally only a small percentage of woodland owners participate in learning events, and only about 25% have a management plan for their forests. Of these, 16% turned to extension for advice and Cooperative Extension is taking up the task of identifying and reaching those among the state's estimated 414,000 non-industrial private forest landowners who are seeking technical assistance to manage and transfer their woodlands to the next generation with active management on the 6,197,990 family-owned acres yet to be covered (DNR, 2013).

Traditionally only a small percentage of woodland owners participate in learning events, and only about 25% have a management plan for their forests. Of these, 16% turned to extension for advice and Cooperative Extension is taking up the task of identifying and reaching those among the state's estimated 414,000 non-industrial private forest landowners who are seeking technical assistance to manage and transfer their woodlands to the next generation with active management on the 6,197,990 family-owned acres yet to be covered (DNR, 2013). It can not be under estimated that the majority of private land owners are managing their lands without professional conservation assistance. Landowners are dealing with daily decisions on activities in the management of their lands on an as needed basis. Very little long term planning has been attempted to guide decision making. When manipulating vegetation in complex natural ecological systems land owners need more information in order to properly manage and not degrade the environment. In order to provide a trusted source of conservation information to landowners, governmental agencies and private non-profits organizations have created a strong service related organization to assist land owners. This organization is called the Driftless Forest Network (DFN) and does business under the name MY Wisconsin Woods (MWW).

Document_Name: Capacity-building for Polk United and a flourishing Polk County
Segment: Grounding of the work. The work planned in this document is grounded in theory at three levels: (1) at the comprehensive or "grand" theory level by ecological systems theory (Bronfenbrenner, 1979) and bioecological theory (Bronfenbrenner & Morris, 2006); (2) at the domain-specific, evidence-based human services level by Walsh's (2003, 2016) family resilience framework; and (3) at the level of practical application by way of implementation science, which is based in large part on diffusion of innovation theory (e.g., Rogers, 1996). In describing work planned for 2019, I will tie in these three levels where appropriate. For more information, including a position paper describing this grounding, please contact me directly. Importantly, this work is grounded in the needs of Polk County residents and the organizations that serve them, subjects that are addressed below.County needs overview. Moving on to the context of my work, Polk County is a largely rural county in northwest Wisconsin with approximately 44,000 residents. Racially and ethnically, Polk County is not unlike others in the region in that the population is highly homogenous, with more than 95% of the population being white. Its population density is about half that of the state overall (45 residents/sq. mile vs. 90/sq. mile), and the county's largest towns Osceola, Amery, and St. Croix Falls have fewer than 3000 inhabitants. Eight school districts serve residents, with the largest enrolling only about 1800 K-12 students, and the smallest having fewer than 500 across all grades (WI DPI, 2018). A major east-west corridor, US Highway 8, divides the southern third of the county from the northern two-thirds. This split is not merely geographical; demographically, the residents of the northern section tend to suffer greater economic hardship than those in the southern part of the county. Overall, about 10% of the county's population is below the poverty line, and more than a third of county residents belong to the group of "working poor," defined as being at or below ALICE levels (asset limited, income constrained, and employed; United Way, 2019). In several of the towns and rural areas north of Highway 8, the ALICE rate exceeds 50%. With respect to barriers to human flourishing, as in much of the region, Polk County residents suffer from high rates of mental health issues, obesity, and substance abuse. Mental health presents significant challenges for residents and the systems that support them; 23% of Polk residents report having experienced aspects of depression.Residents are more likely to be obese than the typical Wisconsinite (30% in Polk vs. 28% for the state)In 2017, Polk County had the singular distinction of topping the state's list of methamphetamine cases; substance abuse creates tremendous strain across criminal justice, healthcare, and human services systems. In other risk areas, nearly 15 % of teenagers report use of marijuana or non-prescribed drugs in the past 30 days. For alcohol, Polk County residents are more likely to report excessive drinking than the state average (24% vs. 23%).The county's three health systems, along with nonprofits such as United Way, the Mental Health Task Force of Polk County, and the Second Harvest Heartland, as well as the county's Community Service division (which houses the departments of Children & Families, Behavioral Health, and Public Health) are committed to increasing the well-being of Polk residents. They seek to achieve this through the workings of their individual organizations, but also through a county-wide coalition, Polk United. Organizational capacity is a critical issue for making progress against the three focus areas described above. In September of 2018, I was invited to participate in coalition, and then subsequently to join Polk United's executive committee. In October, working in consultation with Polk County's director of public health, I drafted a Statement of Work (SoW) that outlines Extension's planned capacity-building efforts related to Polk United. In November, the SoW was signed by representatives of Polk County administration and Extension. Key aspects of the SoW are included in this work plan; for a copy of the actual SoW, please ask me directly.

Document_Name: Connecting Horticulture Programming to Stakeholders with Extens
Segment: The Horticulture Outreach Program Manager position is a newly created position in the UW-Extension Next Generation model. As part of the process, the Horticulture Team along with Administration developed a RACI (Responsible, Accountable, Consulted Informed) document. The process elucidated the following programmatic initiatives within horticulture programming in Wisconsin.  Educational Programming: Consumer or Commercial based educational programming that focuses on teaching the science of horticulture or principles to the audience. Diagnostics: The process of identifying or diagnosing plants and insects and related yard and garden problems at the county office level. Master Gardener Volunteer Program: Activities related to advising, coordinating and delivering the Master Gardener Volunteer Program. Community Programming: Programming for consumer audiences that uses horticulture as a vehicle to accomplish another goal such as community building, food security and personal development.Furthermore, as part of the process, it was identified that the Horticulture Outreach Program Manager would likely be accountable for ensuring state-level diagnostic initiatives in support of county-colleagues and Master Gardeners (in collaboration and cooperation with the Diagnostic Labs, and State Specialists), provide and coordinate training of current and new colleagues (i.e. liaison role for Horticulture-focused Educators), maintain the horticulture website, coordinate and compile statewide reporting, work with campus- and county-based colleagues in developing outreach materials, and provide colleague support and programmatic advocacy within the organization.

Document_Name: Garden of Hope at the Vel R. Phillips Juvenile Justice Center
Segment: Situation StatementFrom the 1990s on, critical job skills identified by employers have included a mix of soft skills and technological acumen. Research shows that cognitive skills like reading, writing and arithmetic and non-cognitive skills such as responsibility, independence, and initiative are important in predicting academic and employment success. These non-cognitive skills are also called "enabling", "soft", "interpersonal", "applied", "workforce", "life", "knowledge economy", "career", or "21st Century" skills depending on which sector is defining them (Garcia 2014). They also need to be independent, learn things on their own, and manage themselves without relying on others. Many students leave high school with the skills to work in jobs that are no longer available in our country. Only one third of graduating students are ready for college, yet in order to earn a decent wage, most will need at least some post-secondary education (Wagner 2008).The American Management Association (AMA), the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) are both national and international in focus. The Definition and Selection of Competencies Project, created by OECD (an organization of 30 industrialized nations) and the Partnership for 21st Century Skills (a group that is comprised of representatives from the business community, education leaders and policy makers) say it is critical for young people to develop 21st Century skills in order to function effectively in today's knowledge-focused economy (AMA 2015) (P21 2015) (OECD 2005).In an article from the Journal of Instructional Psychology, 13 job critical job skills were rated by numerous Fortune 500 companies, with survey response from 1970 and 1997 reported. Topping off the list for 1997 were: 1) teamwork, 2) problem solving, 3) interpersonal skills, 4) oral communication, and 5) listening (Cassel and Kolstad 1998).The 2010 American Management Association Critical Skills Survey Executive Summary reports "employees need to think critically, solve problems, innovate, collaborate and communicate more effectively at every level within an organization." (AMA 2010).A survey conducted by Pennsylvania State University in 1992 to 1993 identified the following qualifications as rating of top importance among 700 employers: oral and written communication skills, interpersonal skills, proficiency in field of study/technical competence, demonstrated ability for teamwork, and demonstrated leadership (Davis & Miller, 1996). A trend noted by Davis and Miller in their research is that businesses are relying more and more on people working in teams.More recent research has also shown teambuilding and communication skills to be of utmost importance to employers, along with problem-solving, decisiveness, and workflow prioritization (Adams, 2014). Ku generalizes the most sought after skills as fitting into three broad categories: life skills, literacy skills, and learning skills, and identifies three popular career tracks as computer systems analysis, computer software development, and civil engineering (Ku 2014). An article in U.S. News & World Report identifies seven skills employers are looking for; these are: social media literacy, critical thinking, sales experience, project management, writing, problem solving, and fluency in computer languages (Graves 2013).A key difference in the expectations of employers going forward revolves around literacy. For today's (and tomorrow's) employers, literacy no longer refers to one's ability to read and write, but also their ability to navigate online communication platforms. Today's youth are born into a world where technology is part of how they learn, communicate, and experience life (Ku 2014). Wisconsin Data: In Wisconsin, the Governor's office has established workforce development goals that serves as the basis for local/regional responses to economic development and workforce needs, including a plan for youth (Department of Workforce Development 2013). The soft skills/life skills previously identified align with the Governor's goals for Wisconsin's "emerging workforce" - youth (Western Wisconsin Workforce Development Board, Inc. 2014).Milwaukee County Data:The challenges that many individuals and families in Milwaukee face are complex, with roots in historical segregation and racism, generational poverty, low-quality educational systems and more. Many young people in Milwaukee's most distressed neighborhoods grow up with trauma as a daily reality due to violence, emotional and physical abuse, addiction, lack of support from parent/role model. Additionally, the public school system often does not prepare young people with the skills and/or confidence they need to identify and pursue post-secondary goals. The segregation and lack of understanding of/empathy towards other communities and cultures, as well as what is portrayed by the media, perpetuate stereotypes and misunderstandings that contribute to an overall sense of apathy and hopelessness for too many young people in Milwaukee. It is estimated that 33% of children in Milwaukee County live in households where income in the past 12 months was below poverty level, and 63% of children qualify for free or reduced lunch (www.countyhealthrankings.org/app/wisconsin/2015/measure/factors/24/data). 83% of children in Milwaukee Public Schools meet the federal qualifying standard to receive free or reduced lunch (http://mps.milwaukee.k12.wi.us/MPS-English/CFO/Bud...). Extreme disparities exist when comparing data from Milwaukee Public Schools (MPS) to data for the state. Students attending MPS schools are five times as likely to be truant. 62% of MPS students graduate in four years, compared to 89% at the state level. Of those 62%, only 57% go on to a two or four-year college, compared to 74% at the state level. 13% of teachers in MPS do not hold a license for their assignment, compared to 1.6% for the state. Only 3.5% of FTE in MPS have five or more years of experience, compared to 75.2% at the state level. The suspension rate in MPS is 13.6%, compared to 3.9% for the state. And of those 13.6%, only 59.1% of those that are eligible to return actually come back to school (wisedash.dpi.wi.gov/Dashboard/portalHome.jsp).Furthermore, the statistics around youth incarceration in Milwaukee County are startling. While overall juvenile arrests and incarceration in Wisconsin are declining, over 60% of the total number of incarcerated youth in the state come from Milwaukee County. 61% of the youth who were released from incarceration committed a new criminal offense within three years of release (youthjustice.org). A Community Needs Assessment (21 stakeholder interview, 4 focus groups with teens) conducted in 2018 revealed the following data/information:There are significant gaps in programming for young people between the ages of 18 and 24; most programming ends at age 18 or high school graduation, though many young people are not prepared to pursue post-secondary goals at that point and would benefit from continued programming/support.Young people want (and need) programming that focuses on social and emotional development (skills including communication, teamwork, responsible decision making, goal setting, critical thinking, etc.) and job skills. Young people want and need connections to both their own communities and communities outside of their neighborhoods; programming needs to expose young people to diverse experiences, people and post-secondary options.Strong and trusting youth-adult partnerships are critical to effect and impactful programming.Youth voice needs to be infused into program development and implementation.Resources and support around mental health need to be available for both young people and youth-serving staff alike.Greater resources and opportunities need to be dedicated to professional development and training for direct-service staff, including how to develop social and emotional skills through programming, mental health, positive communication, and self-care (particularly for staff).

Document_Name: Employee training and management programming for diversified or
Segment: Diversified Organic vegetable farmers are having a hard time attracting and retaining farm labor. While the exact causes of this situation are not known, contributing factors include: the seasonal nature of many vegetable farm jobs, low wages, farmer focus on production over labor management, reduced farmer interest in worker education/training in the last 15 to 20 years, and (likely) fluctuations in the overall economy. As farmers are feeling the stress of inadequate labor on the farm, they are more and more interested in improving their labor management skills. This information is taken from the FairShare CSA Coalition Annual Survey (completed by over 50 farms per year), the FairShare Grower Education Committee (6 to 8 farmers tasked with proposing educational programming for their farmer peers), ongoing program evaluation surveys, conversations with farmers, and the Area 18 Situational Analysis.

While representing only ~7% of the surface area and ~1.4% of the volume of Lake Michigan, Green Bay receives approximately one-third of the total nutrient loading within the entire Lake Michigan basin. Hypereutrophic conditions have been a persistent feature of Green Bay throughout most of the last century and have been, along with PCB contamination of the lower Fox River, one of the principal criteria for the southern bay's designation by the International Joint Commission (IJC) as an Area of Concern. Although it has probably been a feature of the system for decades, the occurrence of hypoxia in Green Bay has only recently received attention with indications that it may be becoming more prolonged during summer monthsTo address hypoxia and other water quality concerns in Green Bay, land management practices in the contributing watersheds will need to change in order to reduce the amount of phosphorus and sediment entering the bay. Understanding how changes to land management practices, especially on agricultural lands, impact the delivery of phosphorus and sediment to the bay through the use of modeling is important to be able to demonstrate to land owners and conservation professionals how decisions on the land impact the water quality in the bay. On top of all that, climate changes will impact the effectiveness of management practices and the resulting water quality.

Document_Name: Resource Development for Extension Farm & Risk Management Progr
Segment: Due to ongoing economic conditions in agriculture, many farms are facing significant financial challenges, resulting in questions regarding the viability of the businesses. Based on the Economic Research Service's latest farm income forecast, farm income has now been in general decline for 4 years and seems to be headed for a fifth in 2019. The downturn has clearly started to take a toll, financially and mentally for many farms, farm families and rural communities which depend on agriculture. Farms are experiencing challenges in their ability to successfully transfer the business to the next generation, and others will need to consider an exit strategy, and off-farm employment. At the same time, UW-Extension currently faces the challenge of bringing a number of new educators on board with the organization. Many educators come to UW-Extension with a formal education and professional experience in their field (for example, production agriculture). However, working with farmers, farm families, and rural communities, given current challenges, can involve difficult and emotional conversations, which Extension educators may have little experience or training. The 2017 Agriculture Census report will be release in 2019. Ag Census data and information related to Agriculture's Economic Impact on Wisconsin's economy will be of interest by agriculture associations, farmers, rural communities, UW-Extension agriculture educators and agents. This information informs the agriculture industry and members of the public with regard to the importance of agriculture in the state. Extension has an important role in the development of the County Ag Economic Impact Reports.

Dane County is regarded as a hub of food system innovation, with many organizations and municipalities addressing the many aspects of the system (e.g., production, aggregation/distribution, transportation, processing, marketing, waste management). Dane County Extension has played an important role in networking food system players, initiating new programs, and providing educational programming for gardeners and farmers. The Extension office has several educators engaged in food systems work. For this educator (community development) the central aspect of my food system programming is around food business entrepreneur development and ecosystem network building. Why entrepreneurship? Conway and Deller (Dept. of Agricultural & Applied Economics) document the importance of entrepreneurship in the Wisconsin economy in their analysis of sources of job growth (https://cced.ces.uwex.edu/eda-university-center/the-wisconsin-economy/sources-of-job-growth/). They find that small businesses generate a significant portion of job growth. Sole proprietor startups are the majority of new businesses, and these grow to generate jobs as they add employees. Communities that invest in and support entrepreneurship (through financing, educational programming, networking, mentoring) will benefit from vibrant community centers, job creation, innovation, and community appeal. Additionally, Conroy & Deller document that new business startups generate about 27% of new jobs in Wisconsin; however, startups have a high rate of failure - thus leading to job loss. Conroy & Deller (Wisconsin Small Business Survival Rates, https://cced.ces.uwex.edu/files/2018/11/0307-WI-Econ-Job-Growth-Factsheet-05.pdf , recommend that resources be invested in early stage businesses that have survived start-up turmoil (over 3 years old, and turning a profit). Entrepreneurship, as an engine of economic growth and job creation, is an important aspect of community economic development. But in Dane County, a county with well documented disparities in racial equity and justice, the goal should be inclusive and equitable community economic development. The food entrepreneurial sector is one where opportunity for inclusion experiences fewer barriers than in other economic sectors. Southern Wisconsin boasts a 'foodie culture' where consumers are interested in locally grown and processed foods, and also interested in culinary adventures. Immigrants and populations that experience structural barriers to ownership and advancement within traditional firms often have experience and skills in food preparation, as well as entrepreneurial characteristics (risk-taking, hard working). For these reasons, work in expanding opportunities for entrepreneurship in the food sector makes good sense.

Document_Name: Connecting Forest County Youth to positive physical, social, an
Segment: Multiple layers of wellness choices make up a healthy life - healthy eating habits, physical fitness, positive social interactions and relationships, a healthy and balanced inner life, and the avoidance of risky behaviors. Each of these layers is connected to and impacts the others. For young people, the ability to maintain a healthy life is further influenced by internal beliefs and personal practices as well as their environment - the community, school and home in which they live.Social-Emotional HealthSuicide is the 2nd leading cause of death for young people ages 10-24 and the national suicide rate among all ages has been rising for more than a decade. For every suicide death in Wisconsin, there are 11 hospitalizations or emergency department visits for self-inflicted injuries. Wisconsin's teen and young adult population have the highest rates for self-inflicted injury. Statistics like these point to low social and emotional wellness among young people. A further concern is that many of the counties with the highest suicide rates coincide with those having the highest numbers of Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs). Many of those counties are rural as well, just one of many indicators of a growing rural health disparity.According to the 2017 Wisconsin Youth Risk Behavior Survey, reports of electronic bullying are increasing - 16.6% in 2011 to 18.4% in 2017. Likewise, 27% of high school students reported feeling sad or hopeless for more than 2 weeks in a row, up from a low of 20.4% in 2009. On a local level, Forest County's 2018 YRBS data5 reports a significant higher number of youth feeling sad or helpless than the Wisconsin average. According to the report, 31% of youth reporting sad or hopeless for more than 2 weeks in a row, so much that they stopped doing some usual activities. This figure represents a 10% increase over the 2016 report.Alcohol, Tobacco and Other DrugsChallenges with high ACE scores and poor mental health have a significant impact on the choices young people make around alcohol, tobacco, and other drugs. According to the Wisconsin Youth Risk Behavior Survey (YRBS), the smoking rate has decreased from 29% in 2005 to 11% in 2017. Similarly, the rate of marijuana use has also decreased from 7% in 2005 to 5% in 2017. However, a growing trend is the use of electronic vapor products, which was at 11% in 2017. Forest County's smoking rate has not decreased as significantly as the state of Wisconsin's average. In 2018, 18% of Forest County youth reported using tobacco within the past twelve months, a decrease from 20.2% in 2016. Additionally, our youth also report a higher rate of vaping with 26.1% of Forest County youth reporting that they have used a vaping product during the past 30 days. Youth rates of prescription drug misuse - an important precursor to use of street drugs like heroin also need to be addressed. According the 2018 YRBS 1 in 10 youth report having taken prescription pain medications differently than the doctor's recommendation. Marijuana use, also considered an important precursor to the use of street drugs and opioid abuse, is of concern in Forest County. In 2018, 31.3% of Forest County youth reported that they had tried marijuana, with 12.8 % of them trying it before the age of 15.

Document_Name: Pathways to the World of Work:  Emphasis on STEM
Segment: When considering the importance of science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) education, many reports speak of job opportunities and economic drivers in a global environment. Research strongly suggests that STEM educational initiatives are not just creating scientists and engineers, but producing STEM literate persons in all areas of the workforce. Eighty percent of the fastest growing occupations in the U.S. require STEM adequacy, and science and technology jobs are projected to grow by 20.6 percent through 2020, more than doubling the 10.1 percent overall U.S. labor force's projected growth . Amid the top ten fastest growing U.S. occupations are solar photovoltaic installers and wind turbine service technicians, five health care related roles, statisticians, software developers/applications, and mathematicians. The renewable energy positions top the list growing at an average of 100% in the 10 year period (U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics, 2019). Despite gains over the last twenty years, females remain underrepresented in STEM careers, with the greatest disparities occurring in engineering, computer science, and the physical sciences (NSF Science & Engineering Indicators, 2016). The U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics shows that while women make up about half of the total U.S. college-educated workforce, they comprise only 29% of the science and engineering workforce (National Girls Collaborative Project, 2018). They constitute 39 percent of chemists and material scientists, 28 percent of environmental scientists and geoscientists, 16 percent of chemical engineers and just 12 percent of civil engineers (Camera, 2015). The reasons for the gender gap are believed to begin as early as grade school and are caused by stereotyping and unconscious biases which impact girls as they mature. As described in Forbes, "Young girls are rarely encouraged to pursue math and science, which is problematic considering studies show a lack of belief in intellectual growth can actually inhibit it. In addition, there exists an unconscious bias that science and math are typically 'male' fields while humanities and arts are primarily 'female' fields, and these stereotypes further inhibit girls' likelihood of cultivating an interest in math and science." This can be combatted by involving girls in hands-on science workshops, allowing them to directly interact female science professionals (as guest speakers/presenters), and increasing the visibility of females in science roles (Hughman, 2012). Better preparing youth, both male and female, for career paths is a growing priority among policy makers and educators. Though much of their effort remains focused on preparing high schoolers, middle school students are beginning to get some attention. As noted in a New America Blog Post, "The middle grades are a crucial time to engage, or re-engage, students and put them on a path to college and career success. Research has demonstrated that grades, attendance, and engagement in middle school are strong predictors of high school graduation and postsecondary success (Garza & Swishe, 2017)." A bipartisan bill presented on Capitol Hill in September, 2017, introduced the Middle STEP Act which was intended to expand technical education and career exploration programming to middle schools. The Act called for exposing middle school students to broad career fields and experiential or project-based instruction which may help them refine their high school course selection and start them on a more direct path to postsecondary studies. Essentially, how we think about career preparedness is shifting. In the words of America's Promise Alliance, "How do we expect young people to dream if they don't know what they can dream about? Opportunities for career exploration give young people broader exposure to the working world they will one day enter. It helps them "connect the dots" between school and career in ways that keep them motivated to graduate with the skills they will need for the future" (2019). As a mission mandate, the impacts of STEM educational programming within 4-H have been investigated. Hershberg et al. found that youth in 4-H science programs were nearly two times more likely to participate in science, engineering and computer technology programs during OST (Grades 10 - 12). Additionally, girls who participate in 4-H are two times more likely (Grade 10) and nearly three times more likely (Grade 12) to take part in science programs compared to girls in other OST activities . Other researchers state that STEM education within 4-H can improve science literacy and build problem solving skills .For more than a century, 4-H has engaged the nation's youth in the building blocks of economic success. This has meant a solid focus on agriculture science, electricity, mechanics, entrepreneurship, and natural sciences. Today, 4-H also offers opportunities in subjects like rocketry, robotics, renewable energy, and computer science. 4-H science, engineering, and technology programming is part of the long-term solution for improving science literacy and aptitude of America's youth. As a public-private partnership, 4-H can focus a variety of resources and expertise to strengthen young people's discovery and exploration of science (Science, Engineering, & Technology, 2012). The plan that follows is part of a multi-year effort to foster enthusiasm for STEM and science-related careers through deliberate community club and outreach activities.References:America's Promise Alliance. Document_Name: Increase youth's capacity to be civically engaged (2019)
Segment: Understanding local government and being civically engaged is important for the functioning of a democratic society and contributes to personal development. Programs like Future Leaders Active in Government ( F.L.A.G.) provide an opportunity for students to participate in local government and civic engagement activities. F.L.A.G. members improve skills that enable civic engagement such as public speaking, leadership, teamwork and organizational skills. Research shows that civically engaged youth have improved social and school performance skills, greater self-confidence, reinforced ties with family and peers, reinforced moral values and integrity and compassion for others.

Society has made tremendous progress reducing surface and groundwater pollution since passage of the Clean Water Act. In recent decades nonpoint source pollution from agricultural, urban, forested and other land uses remains the single largest cause of ongoing water quality problems. These problems manifest most commonly in Wisconsin as surface water algal blooms and sedimentation and in groundwater as elevated nitrates and other contaminants. These impacts have significant effects on public health, local economies and natural communities.Reducing the impacts on nonpoint source pollution through regulation is, by definition, problematic given the dispersed nature of the pollutants. Therefore, outreach and education plays a prominent role in alternate approaches. The Regional Natural Resources Program employs a variety of responses to this challenge, primarily through a contractual relationship with the Wisconsin DNR Nonpoint Source Program.

Leading the nation in paper production and wood furniture manufacturing, Wisconsin's $24.7 billion forest products industry provides 64,000 jobs, and employee compensation adds another $6.4 billion to local economies. Many communities depend on a sustainable forest products industry. As harvesting from industry-owned land decreased, to ensure a continuous timber supply the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources (DNR) looks toward those who own nearly 70% of the 16 million acres of forested land   private woodland owners.Traditionally only a small percentage of woodland owners participate in learning events, and only about 25% have a management plan for their forests. Of these, 16% turned to extension for advice and Cooperative Extension is taking up the task of identifying and reaching those among the state's estimated 414,000 non-industrial private forest landowners who are seeking technical assistance to manage and transfer their woodlands to the next generation with active management on the 6,197,990 family-owned acres yet to be covered (DNR, 2013).

Research strongly suggests that STEM educational initiatives are not just creating scientists and engineers, but producing STEM literate persons in all areas of the workforce. Eighty percent of the fastest growing occupations in the U.S. require STEM adequacy, and science and technology jobs are projected to grow by 20.6 percent through 2020, more than doubling the 10.1 percent overall U.S. labor force's projected growth (Beatty, National Research Council Committee on Highly Successful Schools or Programs for K-12 STEM Education, National Research Council Board on Science Education, & National Research Council Center for Education, 2011). Additionally, in middle-skill jobs (jobs that require more than a high school diploma, but less than a four year degree), over 67% of openings require, at a minimum, proficiency in productivity software such as Microsoft Excel or Microsoft Word and typically other digital literacy skills (Burning Glass Technologies, Captial One, 2015). Overall, it seems clear that middle-skills work has shifted decisively and is now digitally intensive.As a mission mandate, the impacts of STEM educational programming within 4-H have been investigated. Hershberg et al. found that youth in 4-H science programs were nearly two times more likely to participate in science, engineering and computer technology programs during OST (Grades 10 - 12). Additionally, girls who participate in 4-H are two times more likely (Grade 10) and nearly three times more likely (Grade 12) to take part in science programs compared to girls in other OST activities (Hershberg, DeSouza, Warren, Lerner, & Lerner, 2014). Other researchers state that STEM education within 4-H can improve science literacy (Smith, Heck, & Worker, 2012) and build problem solving skills (Daniels et al., 2013).

Document_Name: Providing countywide rural drinking water testing and education
Segment: A clean and dependable supply of water is necessary to maintain a high quality of life and strong economy in Columbia County. Groundwater is particularly important since it serves as the primary source of water for the residents and many industries in Columbia County. Because we cannot see groundwater it is important that we pay extra attention to this resource if we are to ensure that the quantity and quality of groundwater is maintained for our future needs. The luxury of quality drinking water is something that many of us commonly take for granted. Municipal and other public water supplies are subject to strict guidelines and water quality testing to ensure that the water meets current drinking water standards and is safe to drink. However, there are also over 900,000 private wells which serve as the primary water supply for a large number of people throughout Wisconsin, which are not required to be tested or treated. Determining the safety of private water supplies is the responsibility of the individual homeowner. Groundwater is vulnerable and if it is not carefully monitored, managed, and protected has the potential to be depleted or degraded. While much has been done to protect our groundwater supply we increasingly face the question of how to improve groundwater quality. Wide-spread land-use activities have resulted in elevated concentrations of contaminants such as nitrate and pesticides throughout the state, including Columbia County. Cleaning up groundwater after it is contaminated has proven difficult and expensive; therefore it is beneficial to prevent groundwater from becoming contaminated in the first place. As a way to address the concerns of Columbia County residents regarding the quality of their drinking water supply, Columbia County UW-Extension, Land & Water Conservation and Health & Human Services in cooperation with the Center for Watershed Science and Education in Stevens Point conducted a number of drinking water testing programs with each town throughout the county. These programs offered community members an opportunity to learn about their individual water quality as well as groundwater basics and the overall groundwater quality in Columbia County.

Water is fundamental to our ability to grow and thrive. As the human population grows, water from drinking and fishing to farming and industry is under pressure. Water-related issues are interconnected and regional in nature, making strengthening networks and sharing expertise across states and sectors critical. Land-grant universities, with sound science and effective outreach and engagement, are uniquely positioned to help individuals, businesses, organizations, and communities adapt in the face of complexity and change. A substantial body of research demonstrates that strengthening networks and learning within networks can increase the ability of complex systems to adapt more quickly and in positive ways.By working together as a network of extension programs across the North Central Region was are able to pool our resources and coordinate our efforts to tackle complex water-related issues like water allocation, hypoxic zones and non-point source pollution. Moreover, by working together we can increase the capacity of extension educators and researchers in each state and across the region to address water issues by connecting them to professional networks that include expertise from multiple states, disciplines, and sectors, while diversifying our funding sources and building strong multidisciplinary teams who can work in side-by-side with leading federal, state and private partners.Rebecca Power, Anne Nardi, and Amber Mase provide primary support forthe North Central Region Water Network, with Rebecca Power coordinating andproviding overall programmatic leadership; Anne Nardi providing communicationand marketing strategy, coordination and and delivery; and Amber Mase providingevaluation services.

Document_Name: Equity Program Planning, Training, and Facilitation (2019)
Segment: The United Nations measures the Human Development Index which captures human progress combining information on people's health, education, and income. Yet, the simplicity of the HDI leaves much unsaid, and despite progress, large pockets of poverty, exclusion, and inequality exist. The United States HDI is a .924, however, when inequalities, like health, education, poverty, and having a voice are factored in, the score drops to .796 (Human Development Report, 2016). The State Wellbeing Score measures each states wellbeing, looking at purpose, social, financial, community, and physical wellbeing. Wisconsin has a score of 62.4 (National Score is 61.7) placing at thirteenth out of the 50 states. While, Wisconsin measures well in this assessment, it places at 31st in both purpose and social wellbeing (Gallup Healthways Wellbeing Index 2015). The COMPASS Now Report, a community health and wellbeing assessment facilitated by Great Rivers United Way for La Crosse County and five surrounding counties, indicated that the five top issues La Crosse County faces are: a need for more livable wage jobs, increased access to mental health, increased inclusion of socially diverse people, decrease of alcohol and drug misuse and abuse, and improved wellbeing of children and youth (Gromoske, 2018).Through community assessments and informal interviews of strategic stakeholders in La Crosse County, ACEs (adverse childhood experiences) are a factor in many issues affecting wellbeing including health, life expectancy, education, relationships, mental health, substance abuse, and financial wellbeing (Centers for Disease Control, 2016). Not only is trauma history an important issue that affects wellbeing in La Crosse County, but historical trauma, cultural differences, and socioeconomic differences are also issues that affect wellbeing of all community members as well as participation in services, programming, and having a voice. Research has indicated that being culturally, trauma, and socially/emotionally responsive improve wellbeing, participation, and social emotional learning for all community members. In 2014, La Crosse County Juvenile Justice Arrest and Disproportionate Minority Contact Task Force indicated that La Crosse County has a higher juvenile arrest rate than the statewide average as well as like-sized counties, disproportionate minority contact factors are present in the juvenile justice system, a large range of discretion in the intervention options occurred at public schools, a lack of programs that could serve as arrest alternatives, and an indication that some arrests occurred so the students could receive assistance or programming that was not otherwise available without an arrest. Since that time, a system of care has been developed and implemented to work on the system, policies, and with individuals. One recommendation was to conduct a shared system-wide cultural competency training which was done with the partners on the Task Force. Training exists in the county through a variety of agencies, yet has not been done strategically, at wider system levels, within businesses and organizations, or for the general community.Improving wellbeing has been researched at an individual level, looking at methods to improve resilience, decrease stress, and increase happiness (Lyubomirsky, 2013). Further, the United Nations promotes six pillars of human development: equity, sustainability, productivity, empowerment, cooperation, and security. Initiatives like the Full Frame Initiative, positive psychology like wholebeing, and cultural and trauma responsivity, combine the academic pillars with tools and skills to improve relationships, organizations, systems, and communities to shift their fundamental focus from fixing problems to fostering wellbeing and relationships and looking holistically at people, policy, and community. Document_Name: Expanding Access to Youth Programs in Shawano County
Segment: Demographically, the United States continues to grow more diverse and this demographic trend is even more apparent nationwide with the youth population (Chart 1).Chart 1 (Child Trends, 2016)Wisconsin's racial minority population increased 500 percent between 1970 and 2013 including significant increases in Latino/Hispanic, Black/African American and Asian populations (Gordon, 2016). Similarly, the growing number of foreign-born youth and families provide opportunities for 4-H youth development to grow its membership base and reach new audiences. In 1990, census figures showed the foreign-born population at about 121,500; in 2015, that number had increased to nearly 279,000. This represents an increase of 130% over the 25 year span (Long, Jones, & and Ewald, 2017). These audiences are historically underserved by 4-H Youth Development. Families and individuals may lack familiarity with 4-H (knowledge barrier) or unable to access 4-H programs by traditional means (organizational barrier). 4-H Youth Development can benefit by welcoming youth and volunteers from diverse backgrounds. As an organization, UW-Extension needs diversity in its staff, volunteers and learners to effectively participate in an intercultural and global world.The 4-H Community Club program had 29,912 youth (grades 5K-13) enrolled in 2017. Of those youth enrolled in 4-H Community Clubs, 94.7% identified as White (4-H Youth Development State Office, 2018). Given that Wisconsin's population is 86% White according to Census 2010, it is clear that the community club program does not reflect the state's demographic profile (United States Census Bureau, 2010).In 2017, 10,787 adults had been certified as 4-H Youth Development volunteers of those 97.1% of these adults self-identified as White (4-H Youth Development State Office, 2018).In addition to the 4-H Community Club, 4-H Youth Development in Wisconsin offers programs for youth that include 4-H Afterschool programs, in-school enrichment programs, and group educational experiences at camps, demonstrations, library programs and more. In 2017, 27,392 youth participated in these experiences across the state and 82.3% of these youth were identified as White (4-H Youth Development State Office, 2018). Although gains have been made in delivering educational programs to underserved youth through these types of modalities, more effort must be made to provide racially and ethnically diverse 4-H participants with all the opportunities available through 4-H club programs, including staff support, awards, educational trips and scholarships.In April of 2016, National 4-H launched a new campaign aimed at rebranding 4-H as a strategy to increase the number of ethnically and racially diverse youth participating in the program. National 4-H has set their goal high. By 2025, 4-H wants to add 4 million new members and in so doing double the number of African American and Hispanic youth engaged in the program. This goal is especially pertinent in Wisconsin where the state's youth of color face extreme racial disparity across all measures of well-being and could benefit greatly from quality youth development programs. According to the 2016 KIDS COUNT Data Book, Wisconsin ranked 12th among the 50 states in overall child well-being, but persistent challenges hinder children living in immigrant families and children of color, especially African-American, Latinx and American Indian children (The Annie E. Casey Foundation, 2018; Kids Forward, 2018). Black children and American Indian children in Wisconsin are more than four times as likely to live in poverty as White non-Hispanic children, and Hispanic children are nearly three times as likely as White children (Kids Forward, 2018). In 2015, a 24/7 Wall Street Special Report listed Wisconsin as the worst state in the nation for Black Americans. Authors citied home ownership, unemployment, and incarceration rates as key indicators of extreme racial inequality (Frohlich, Sauter, & Stebbins, 2015). According to a 2002 study conducted at the Institute for Applied Research in Youth Development, Tufts University, researchers discovered that compared to their peers, youth involved in 4-H programs excel in several areas. 4-H Youth are: Four times more likely to make contributions to their communities (Grades 7-12); Two times more likely to be civically active (Grades 8-12);  Two times more likely to make healthier choices (Grade 7); Two times more likely to participate in Science, Engineering and Computer Technology programs during out-of-school time (Grades 10 - 12); and 4-H girls are two times more likely (Grade 10) and nearly three times more likely (Grade 12) to take part in science programs compared to girls in other out-of-school time activities (Tufts University).Adapting what works in 4-H Youth Development programming to the needs of emerging and underserved audiences is a major goal of the Expanding Access Team. We know from recent focus groups conducted with diverse stakeholders that parents are interested in these programs and willing to assist with programming in their communities. In April 2017, 4-H Youth Development was reviewed for Civil Rights Compliance by a team from NIFA-USDA (Hicks, 2017). The review was conducted to determine whether UWEX was complying with the provisions of the U.S. Civil Rights law and USDA's Civil Rights rules and regulations. The team found significant areas of improvement. Serious civil rights concerns include:  the ability to collect participant data inequitable access to participate in activities and opportunities supporting a diverse and inclusive volunteer base the absence of a strategic plan for expanding access the lack of a diverse and demographically representative advisory groupAccording to the U.S. Census Bureau, Shawano County has a total area of 909 square miles, of which 893 square miles is land and 16 square miles is water. According to the U.S. Census Bureau American Community Survey 2016, a total of 41,146 people live in Shawano County. Population growth for the nation outpaced the rate of growth for both the state of Wisconsin and Shawano County. During 2017, Shawano County's population decreased by 194 residents, or 0.5% (Demographic Services Center: Department of Administration). Of this population, 89.5% identify as white, 7.4% as Native American, 2.4% two/more races, .4% Asian, and .3% African American. This is concerning, as you look at our Community Club Enrollment demographics. 98% of our youth population identify as White, non-Hispanic. In a county that has 7.4% Native American population, we have less than 1% of our 4-H Community Club represented. People identifying as two or more races in the county is 2.4%, versus 2% in 4-H. However, at this time we do not have anyone identifying themselves as African American, Asian, or Pacific Islander. Shawano County hosts three Native American tribes: Ho Chunk, Stockbridge-Munsee, and Menominee. About 18% of our population is aged 0 - 19. Both access to care and educational opportunities are greatly impacted by the geographic location of residents; the more rural an individual lives, the more difficult it is to receive services. There is a need for educationally appropriate programming in safe environments. 74% of Shawano County is considered rural (Shawano Menominee County Community Health Assessment, 2014.) As you map out where the rural areas are, poverty overlaps, as well as needed services being located farther away. There are issues with transportation as well; even if able to offer an educational program at a community base, it is difficult to discern if people (especially youth) are able to attend without having transportation to get them back home. Couple this with more and more single-parent households, or dual working parent households, we are seeing more youth take care of themselves upon getting home from school, or seeking care from a grandparent or neighbor. The need for educational programming in a safe environment is wide-spread across the county and needed as a Protective Factor to make these youth as resilient as possible.
