Document_Name: Living Healthy: Emphasis on ATOD and Social-Emotional Health fo
Segment: Situation Statement:Multiple layers of wellness choices make up a healthy life - healthy eating habits, physical fitness, positive social interactions and relationships, a healthy and balanced inner life, and the avoidance of risky behaviors. Each of these layers is connected to and impacts the others. For young people, the ability to maintain a healthy life is further influenced by internal beliefs and personal practices as well as their environment - the community, school and home in which they live. Acknowledging the interconnectedness of all layers of health to make up a healthy life, the Living Healthy Team operates in three primary areas:  Nutrition and physical activity - including fitness, nutrition, safety, sexual responsibility, general hygiene, and adequate sleep Social-emotional well-being - including youths' sense of confidence, self-efficacy, emotional regulation, self-reliance and optimism, empathy, connection, contribution, ability to lead a team, teamwork, appreciation of cultural diversity, and civic responsibility  Prevention of alcohol, tobacco and other drugs (ATOD) Furthermore, the nationwide mission mandate of 4-H Youth Development is to expand participation among youth and their families in the dynamic process of healthy living, so they are physically, socially, and emotionally prepared to meet the challenges of the 21st century.Social-Emotional HealthSuicide is the 2nd leading cause of death for young people ages 10-24[1] and the national suicide rate among all ages has been rising for more than a decade. For every suicide death in Wisconsin, there are 11 hospitalizations or emergency department visits for self-inflicted injuries. Wisconsin's teen and young adult population have the highest rates for self-inflicted injury.[2] Statistics like these point to low social and emotional wellness among young people. A further concern is that many of the counties with the highest suicide rates coincide with those having the highest numbers of Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs).[3] Many of those counties are rural as well, just one of many indicators of a growing rural health disparity.According to the 2017 Wisconsin Youth Risk Behavior Survey,[4] reports of electronic bullying are increasing - 16.6% in 2011 to 18.4% in 2017. Likewise, 27% of high school students reported feeling sad or hopeless for more than 2 weeks in a row, up from a low of 20.4% in 2009. Nearly 1 in 5 (17%) high school students reported having hurt themselves purposely without wanting to die, self-harm being a coping strategy for many young people who don't have other, healthier strategies available to them.Alcohol, Tobacco and Other DrugsChallenges with high ACE scores and poor mental health have a significant impact on the choices young people make around alcohol, tobacco, and other drugs. According to the Wisconsin Youth Risk Behavior Survey (YRBS), the smoking rate has decreased from 29% in 2005 to 11% in 2017. Similarly, the rate of marijuana use has also decreased from 7% in 2005 to 5% in 2017. However, a growing trend is the use of electronic vapor products, which was at 11% in 2017. Similarly, youth rates of alcohol use has decreased overall, but the early age of onset (having their first drink of alcohol other than a few sips before age 13) increased from 14.6% in 2013 to 15.5% in 2017, the first increase since 1999. Youth rates of prescription drug misuse - an important precursor to use of street drugs like heroin - have also decreased; yet 1 in 10 youth report having taken prescription pain medications differently than the doctor's recommendation. While the use of alcohol, tobacco and other drugs in Wisconsin is reportedly decreasing, trends within these statistics must be addressed. Vilas County DataVilas County covers 1,018 square miles, nearly 43% of which is public land[5] and therefore non-taxable. Residential areas tend to be widely spread out due to the prevalence of water, as it is home to one of the largest collections of freshwater lakes in the world - more than 1,300 lakes and 73 rivers and streams. The largest town is the county seat of Eagle River with a population of 1,498. The county has approximately 21,683 residents, 17% of whom are 18 years and younger. It is home to a large number of retirees, with approximately 30% of Vilas County residents aged 65 years and older. The Lac du Flambeau Band of Lake Superior Chippewa reservation sits within the county's borders, and Native Americans make up approximately 11% of the total population[6]. Prevention of alcohol, tobacco and other drug abuse is a top priority for Vilas County's departments of health, social services, and law enforcement. A county profile includes the following information[7]: The annual cost of excessive alcohol abuse in Vilas County was $18,100,000 in 2013. OWI arrests per 100,000 population was 818 in 2014. Wisconsin's state average was 431. Doses of prescription drugs dispensed per county population in 2016 was 33.14 vs. 26.38 statewide. Controlled substance prescriptions written per 1,000 population in 2013 was 736 vs. 572 statewide. Drug law arrests per 100,000 population was 860 in 2014. The state average was 439. Access to drugs and alcohol tends to be higher here than other areas. In terms of alcohol distribution, Vilas had 5.3 alcohol licenses issued per 500 population, vs 1.5 statewide (2014)[8]. And a strong contributing factor to the high number of prescriptions, including controlled substances, is the proportion of retirees. As this group ages and their medical needs increase, more drugs can be found in homes. The prevalence of drugs and alcohol in a rural area such as Vilas County is especially problematic when paired with the lack of mental health practitioners. The vast majority of patients, no matter the age, have to travel 1.5 - 2.0 hours to Marshfield or Wausau for appointments, and no child psychiatrist works in the county. Native AmericansVilas County Sheriff's Department staff members estimate 95% of inmates have addiction issues to drugs and/or alcohol. They also report the majority of inmates have family members with the same issues, and residents of Lac du Flambeau make up a disproportionately high number of cases. Native American families are particularly vulnerable to mental health issues and substance abuse because of high ACE scores due to historical trauma that was suffered on a multi-generational level. The average jail population in 2018 was 113 and on average 64 were Native American.[9] Kit Van Stelle, an evaluation specialist hired by the tribe, searched the records of the Lac du Flambeau police department for data on opioid overdoses and suicides because anecdotal evidence suggested both were underreported. For example, suicide is the leading cause of death among Wisconsin's Native American youth - more than double that of all other races combined - yet there were less than 5 suicides reported in a 5-year period in Vilas County for Native youth and adults combined[10]. Van Stelle probed for data involving threats and attempts as well as deaths, and found that in 2018[11]: Lac du Flambeau police responded to 52 calls for suicide threats. 80% were for natives and 50% for 13 - 25-year olds. There were 17 calls for suicide attempts. Of these, 94% were natives, 75% were female, and 66% were 13 - 25 years old. There were 17 calls for intentional injury. There were 15 calls regarding opioid overdoses, and 12 overlapped with suicide attempts. It is very likely the numbers of opioid overdoses and suicide attempts were underreported. A leading factor is the tribe's distribution of Narcan kits to community members as well as professionals. It is highly likely friends and family members are resuscitating loved ones without reporting the incidents.The Vilas County Board of Supervisors is concerned about the drug epidemic on tribal lands, both in terms of addiction and criminal activity related to the drug trade. Consequently, I have been tasked with focusing almost half of my time on the needs of the Lac du Flambeau tribe. Building working relationships with tribal members takes extra patience because of the following factors: Distrust because of the way Native Americans have been treated by the U.S. government and various educational/social service agencies, both historically and currently. Previous works of non-Natives have failed because of a lack of cultural sensitivity and/or lack of perseverance.  The tribe has its own government, law enforcement, 4K - 8th grade school, and youth center. When combined with the above-mentioned factors, access to tribal youth is more limited than other communities. In addition, the high school students attend Lakeland Union High School, which is in a different county.A recent development that may help connect my work to tribal efforts is a 2-year grant project spearheaded by the Medical College of Wisconsin: Building Capacity for Community-School-University Partnerships for Systemic Transformation - Toward a Culturally Responsive Indigenous Learning Lab. The first year of the project will entail a facilitated process of school-community conversations about school policies/procedures that result in over-representation of Native American students in special education. (Many of these students' issues are referred to special education based on behaviors rather than underlying mental health issues.) New strategies will be developed to address this disproportionality. The following year will be spent on building the capacity of the school-community partnership to sustainably implement this new plan and strategies. I will not discuss this venture at length in my narrative because whatever role I would play is undefined; however, I have included it in my Logic Model to show how it fits into my Plan of Work.As of January 2019, most of my efforts in Lac du Flambeau are based out of three coalitions:  Minobimaadiziiwin Coalition (Mino) Healthier Community Action Team (HCAT) A grassroots-level Community Engagement Team that generates 90-day work plansThese meetings often have the same core people in attendance because of overlapping goals, and this is helping me build relationships. Most of the coalition work will be described in detail in the next section. The Community Engagement Team will not because it doesn't fit under the two major program headings, so I will simply mention two partnership possibilities emerging from this assemblage: One group is starting to work on staging a youth-led conference for all high schoolers in the area, and another is working on establishing a Junior Tribal Council. The latter is especially interested in my background coordinating the youth delegation for Superior Days as I could train students how to lobby government leaders. They are also excited about the option of conducting Community Placemaking exercises. PYD colleague Michelle Gobert and I are getting trained in Placemaking and have discussed having our youth swap communities, both county-wide and between the Lac du Flambeau Chippewa and Forest County Potawatomi reservations. Current Structures: Vilas County Youth Coalition and PartnersShifting the perspective back to the county as a whole: Opportunities for all Vilas County youth are limited. Outside of schools and churches, there are few Third Space sites in the county. There is no Boys & Girls Club, YMCA, or similar programs, and the one existing 4-H club in the county dissolved due to a lack of interest and leaders. In addition, participation in extracurriculars can be difficult for students without driver licenses or vehicles, as many have to commute 45 - 60 minutes to reach their campus. In 2000, my predecessor Nancy Ann Miller founded the Vilas County Youth Coalition (VCYC). Members include school administrators and guidance counselors, AmeriCorps and Recovery Corps personnel, county staff from the health and social services departments, other non-profits, and members of the Lac du Flambeau tribe who work on prevention issues. It has three main guiding principles: Provide a forum for youth-serving agencies to exchange resources and information Foster activities that promote intergenerational partnerships Provide positive opportunities and activities for youth, families and communitiesThe Vilas County Youth Coalition is a 501c3 and the fiscal agent for two other groups: The Northland Pines Community Garden, which is located on the ground of the Northland Pines High School; and the Lac du Flambeau Minobimaadiziiwin Coalition, whose mission is to prevent and reduce substance abuse, especially among youth, by promoting healthy lifestyles with a heavy emphasis on native culture. VCYC's budget includes a $25,000 Partnership for Success grant and $2,000 in grants from the Northwoods Coalition. The Minobimaadiziiwin Coalition and Lac du Flambeau's Healthier Community Action Team also receive grants and we coordinate our efforts with theirs to avoid duplication and stretch our resources as far as possible. For example, VCYC orders lockboxes for all three groups to distribute to community members. Doing so enables us to get volume discounts and reduces the amount of paperwork. We also share a Hidden in Plain Sight Bedroom kit, an upcoming microsite, promotional efforts and ad campaigns for Dose of Reality and kNOwMeth.In addition to these formal partnerships, VCYC also works with: An area-wide Community Engagement Team based in Lac du Flambeau Northwoods Coalition Alliance for Wisconsin Youth A new tri-county version of Children's Coordinated Services Teams for Vilas, Oneida, and Forest counties.The number of area-wide partnerships is reflective of the fact that individual counties do not have enough resources to deal with the ongoing drug epidemic. As noted earlier, many residents must cross county lines for services because they are not offered in their communities. Another reason for the recent proliferation of coalitions is that our counties' populations are not large enough to receive funding from grant providers who are looking to make a large impact. As costs related to the opioid epidemic keep straining county budgets, service providers have gotten more creative finding revenues. One highlight of cross-county coalitions work: I was part of a small task force that successfully recruited all the schools in Forest, Oneida and Vilas counties to administer Wisconsin's Youth Risk Behavior Survey. All students in grades 7 - 12 will take it this spring, providing area health and social service departments important data they can use for needs assessments and grant writing.Leading the Vilas County Youth Coalition and attending various meetings of other coalitions has been very beneficial to my work. My network of contacts is spreading exponentially, including many in decision-making positions. One new development is a shared vision for afterschool programs that will offer middle and high school students opportunities to build their self-reliance as they head towards adulthood. Document_Name: Building Resilient and Financially Capable Families
Segment: In Oneida, Vilas and Forest Counties there is a large number of families and individuals accessing services assisting with financial need, including utility assistance and the food pantry. Poverty in the area remains high due to low-wage jobs, part time/seasonal jobs and low educational attainment. Oneida County has a poverty rate of 11.3%, Vilas County 14.4% and Forest County 17.9%. All three counties lack the resources to offer free or affordable financial education programs or coaching to teach those in need how to prioritize spending, maximize income and understand borrowing. In recent years, Northwoods Saves used to offer similar services, but the non-profit folded due to lack of funding. Currently, other than local banks or financial planners that usually charge fees, there is no service such as this available to the public.The Health & Well-being Educator will partner with local agencies to offer financial coaching to individuals that are returning monthly for assistance to help them develop a budget and provide them with the skills needed to support themselves. In addition to coaching services, the Health & Well-being Educator will also provide support for the Get Real financial simulation in Forest County, as well as facilitate pre-simulation financial programming to 11th graders to prepare them for the event. Financial Capability programming will also be done at Head Start. In addition to financial programming, the Health & Well-being Educator will provide support, resources and education for digital parenting programs and court mandated co-parenting education in Vilas and Forest Counties.

State of African Americans in Wisconsin "Based on measures of racial inequity, no state is worse for Black residents than Wisconsin," according to Frohlich and Sauter (2016). Using data on labor force, poverty, incarceration, infant mortality, and other social indicators, Stebbins & Comen (2018) determined that Milwaukee-Waukesha-West Allis and Racine are the third and fourth worst cities for African Americans in the U.S. Likewise, the Annie E. Casey Foundation's "Race for Results" index found Wisconsin to be the worst state for Black children to have "opportunity for success in adulthood" (p. 6). In spite of these devastating predictions for the life chances of Black residents, Wisconsin's African American population increased by 18% between the 2000 and 2010 US Census. The University of Wisconsin Applied Population Lab reports that Milwaukee County has 71% of the state's African American population with 253,764 people. Eight additional counties also have significant African American populations: Dane (25,347), Racine (21,767), Kenosha (11,052), Rock (7978), Brown (5491), Waukesha (4914), Winnebago (2975), and Dodge (2381). The median age of the African American population in Wisconsin is about 28 years, more than ten years younger than the entire WI population (Applied Population Lab). Further influencing the lives of Wisconsin's Black residents, Pawasarat and Quinn (2013) report "one in eight of African American working age men" are in prison or jail. This rate of mass incarceration is the highest for African American men in the country and nearly double the national average" (p. 2). They specify that in Milwaukee County, this means "over half of African American men in their 30s and half of men in their early 40s have been incarcerated in state correctional facilities (Pawasarat & Quinn, 2013, p. 2). Prison records prevent individuals from working in certain industries, and thus African Americans have additional barriers to wealth creation given that 43% of incarcerated men and 21% of incarcerated women in prison in Wisconsin are Black (Wisconsin Department of Corrections, 2018). This is reflected in state data showing that African Americans have the lowest labor force participation rate out of all racial or ethnic groups in the state. In 2017, only 58.5% of all African-Americans in Wisconsin were employed and in the labor force (American Community Survey, US Bureau of the Census). Incarcerated men are estimated to make 40 percent less than their potential annual earnings after release (The Pew Charitable Trusts, 2010), and even when working full- or part-time jobs, 72% of Black parents with children under age six have low incomes, according to the Black Child Development Institute (2014, p. 34). The need for a concentrated effort to expand employment and income generation opportunities for African American residents in Wisconsin is clear.Through the Community Development Institute, county-based Extension educators have been teaching and expanding opportunities for Wisconsin's entrepreneurs for many years, most notably in Bayfield, Fond du Lac, and Waukesha counties. This is a well-documented strategy for rural wealth creation (Deller & Conroy, 2016) since it engages local residents to create and work jobs where they are, rather than relying on newcomers or employers relocating to remote areas. Until now, none of these programs have focused specifically on African-American, incarcerated, or recently released entrepreneurs who could most value it. Nationally, minorities and immigrants start new businesses at higher rates than non-Hispanic white people (Fairlie & Robb, 2010; Obuko & Planting, 2015), despite facing a wide range of challenges such as barriers in accessing information, technical supports in terms of business planning, and financial resources necessary for business startup and expansion (Bonds, 2007; Erdmann, 2016; Freeland & Keister, 2016; Kopkin, 2017). Thus teaching entrepreneurship to soon-to-be-released incarcerated men and women in Wisconsin could have dramatic impacts on their individual life outcomes, their families, their communities, and our state.Why Extension? With its network of county-based educators, state specialists, and local organizational partners, Extension is particularly well-positioned to teach entrepreneurship in prisons. Extension staff are skilled at teaching vulnerable audiences and will easily learn DOC protocol for success in a prison environment. Defy offers training for those starting prison-based programs, includes the use of mentors who are partnered with participants, and engages local organizations in the program, all of which complement Extension's local approach and deep community connections. Because of Extension's statewide presence, mentors will be found in the participants' hometowns who can be a point of inspiration and connection for both them and parole agents in the transition from the institution to their community again.

Document_Name: Milwaukee County Community Cultural Development Program (2019)
Segment: In-depth analysis and utilization of personal commitments identified from both the stories told by individual residents speaking to how they situation themselves within their community as a collective narrative of civic engagement could break the perpetual cycle of generational poverty, transforming both the statewide Wisconsin and local Milwaukee community environments for necessary policy change, as well as quality of life. From the needs assessment lens, interdependent factors between the state of Wisconsin and the city of Milwaukee's 189 neighborhoods present a daunting demographic profile. Wisconsin has the highest incarceration rate for African American men in the nation, up to 62% in Milwaukee ZIP code 53206 alone. One in eight African-American men in Wisconsin (12.8%) are in state and local prisons; nearly double the national average of 6.7%. Half of African American men in their 30s in Milwaukee County have been in state prison[i]. Across the city of Milwaukee, neighborhood and community leaders are screening the recent 2017 locally produced documentary, Milwaukee 53206. The film illustrates the lived experiences of three 53206 residents, illuminating the story of the individuals and families within communities across the United States who live with the everyday impacts of excessive jail sentencing[ii]. In 2015, Milwaukee suffered with more than triple the violent crime rate in the next most dangerous Wisconsin city and the sixth-highest violent crime rate of U.S. cities. Due in part to the city's high crime rate, in 2016 Milwaukee was selected to receive federal assistance to reduce violence[iii]. As of 2017, Milwaukee is the sixth worst American city to live in[iv], where 26.8% of Milwaukee adult residents and 41% of children under 18 live in poverty. These are the highest poverty rates of any city in the state of Wisconsin, and also are well above the 14.7% national poverty rate. The unemployment rate for black males (ages 25-54) in Milwaukee is 52.7%[v]. Further, Milwaukee is the most segregated city in America, including the greatest segregation of the poor from everyone else than any other metro region.[vi] Wisconsin has been ranked the worst state in the country for racial disparities between black and white children[vii]. Milwaukee Public Schools' 2016 graduation rate was 59.7%, where at that time it has also been stated, "Over the last five years, the graduation rate at MPS has trended generally downwards and is still nearly 30 points below the statewide average." [viii]77.6% of children in Milwaukee Public Schools qualify for free or reduced lunches, which their 2016-2017 reports as an indicator of "economic disadvantage".[ix] As of 2018, thirteen of Milwaukee County's nineteen municipalities are at or above the 40% of median poverty level indicator for the former UW-Extension Expanding Access program (November 2017, Extension Milwaukee County-specific workshop) as also Asset-Limited, Income-Constrained, Employed (ALICE)[x]. This means that the majority of the residents across backgrounds in these thirteen municipalities of Milwaukee County are functioning just above the median federal poverty rate but are not able to meet the basic living expenses for their municipality and county cost of living, even when factoring in three core factors of economic viability (housing affordability, job opportunities and community resources). Viewed from an asset-building lens, the city of Milwaukee has current opportunities that can turn the tide at the community-wide and neighborhood levels, based on an intentional and developmental infrastructure of community conversations. Throughout calendar year 2017, United Way of Greater Milwaukee and Waukesha County conducted 21 Community Conversations with 215 participants from 55 different zip codes, across Milwaukee and Waukesha Counties. Participants ranged in age from 18-74. 59% of participants were female; 36% of participants were people of color; and 49% of participants reported a household income of $49,999 or less. In their public report of the 2017 Community Conversations, United Way stated they will use this information to inform current partner and community engagement, find new opportunities for collaboration, develop strategies, and mobilize resources.[xi] United Way reported an "overwhelming" Community Conversations participant response to the question, "who do you trust to take action on these issues?" across all conversations was "I trust myself." Additionally, United Way Community Conversations participants mentioned that they trust people they know, faith-based organizations, certain community organizations, and that it takes everyone coming together to truly make progress.Last, the following thematic priorities were revealed from the Community Conversations:1. Safety: address the root causes of crime and drug use, such as poverty and lack of access to family-sustaining jobs, healthcare, safe housing, and positive outlets for kids and teens.2. Diversity: Create opportunities for conversations to help people overcome bias and feel comfortable with one another. Interactions between Neighbors & Neighborhoods: More no- or low-cost, accessible opportunities for families and neighbors to interact, like block parties, clean, safe parks and outdoor events, support groups, etc. Encourage less dependence on, or breaks from, technology and social media Community Connectedness: Again, create no- or low-cost opportunities for neighbors and families to come together in a positive way. Start support groups or networks for community members of all ages to share stories and lean on one another during tough times. Address the root causes of violence and fear, such as systemic racism, trauma, and lack of equitable access to basic needs, like safe housing, family sustaining wages, and quality education and programming for youth.[xii] Wisconsin has built a nationally recognized database about the sustained health impacts of adverse childhood experiences, or, ACEs[xiii]. Statewide as well as in the city of Milwaukee, officials and advocates are just recently putting more resources into understanding community trauma; helping youth and communities recover and heal using a range of methods and practices. ACE surveys determine how many potentially traumatic experiences a child has had, including divorce, death or incarceration of a parent, experiencing or witnessing violence, and living with someone who has a serious mental illness or drug or alcohol problem. Data released January 2018 shows that about 40% of children in multiple Wisconsin counties have had at least four or more ACEs experiences - Milwaukee County included. Sharing their story and reframing their personal narrative through storytelling and narrative construction helps youth and their community support members (and thus the community at large) heal and thrive.[xiv] Moreover, building a community-engaged curriculum based on personal-to-community storytelling and narrative construction is a form of building social support and social cohesion, two social determinants of health that are improved when used alongside related strategies such as reducing social, socio-political and economic inequalities that affect the everyday lives of youth, adults and related community residents[xv]. UW-Extension's working definition of community capacity building integrates the Kretzmann and McKnight (1993) asset-based community development methodology of practice with the Hinds (2008) method of building community capacity. The Hinds (2008) model states that the triangulation of the community environment (analysis from the neighborhood-level out to the broader community boundary), community structures (the relationships and functions between individuals as residents, organizations, networks, and interim structures) and five specific purposed-based actions (planning, learning research, evaluation, and operating/supervising) determines the process of building the community's capacity. I have been working with two specific local Milwaukee-to-national grassroots resident-led/driven learning communities that are centered in aiming to apply John McKnight & Jody Kretzmann's 1993 asset-based community economic development and community capacity building methodology. The two networks are Performing our Future, and, the Population Change Learning Community. Performing our Future partners with several local and national knowledge building partners to support four local community networks, including "Rural/Urban FLOW", the Wisconsin community network between Milwaukee County and Sauk County of a specific group of artists and agricultural entrepreneurs that are centered in a core geographic area that they have defined as their central focus, and, they are connected to the city of Milwaukee's formal creative and community placemaking effort One of the lead Milwaukee County artist entrepreneurs involved in the Rural/Urban FLOW Network is Dasha Kelly Hamilton, with whom I am completing an Extension Data Jam February 20,2019 of five of the ten storytelling-centered community forums we held in August 2018 (data to be analyzed by Extension Program Support and Services staff, myself, Dasha and the local youth and adult community artists we engaged to conduct community surveys in seven neighborhoods pre-forum, reviewing the community research-based spoken word pieces that were utilized in each of the five forums as discussion prompts after personal stories were told by participants, and, some of the 250 forum participants we engaged in a total of ten forums between fall 2017 and summer 2018 The Population Change Learning Community (PCLC) is led by UCLA Center for Healthier Children, Families and Communities faculty Patricia Bowie and also partners with several local and national knowledge building partners to support nine local community support organizations in nine local communities, including the WI, which is adjacent to several of the neighborhoods involved in the "Rural/Urban FLOW" network above. I began working with PCLC in 2014. Both of these networks are aiming to include social impact analysis/social & community network analysis and "culturally responsive community development/evaluation" as desired tools to support each of their learning community practice goals of culturally inclusive and equitable "development". Document_Name: Enabling Citizens to Better Engage Government / Superior Days
Segment: Douglas County in a 2015 priorities setting session, determined that Superior Days is a continuing priority for Douglas County. It is the expectation of the Douglas County Community and Economic Development Educator that they coordinate this event.

Document_Name: Team Plan for Wehr Nature Center Adult Programming
Segment: Wehr Nature Center's programming has been primarily focused on families and school age children. Data collected from a master planning process indicated a need for more programs targeting adults. Topics requested were natural history, citizen science, wellness, stewardship, and "fun" things to do outdoors. In response to this request Wehr Nature Center (WNC) and the Friends of Wehr (FOW) have formed several teams to develop and implement a variety of adult programs. These teams are made up of staff, FOW members, and general public participants.

Document_Name: Social Emotional Well-being of Children and Families: Coalition
Segment: Families perform a number of functions that provide private benefits to their members and public benefits to society. For example, in the midst of a global economic transformation, every nation's competitiveness will depend more than ever on its human capital, specifically the education and social skills of its labor force (Reynolds & Temple, 2005). Human capital in today's knowledge-based economies requires cognitive and noncognitive skills, which are shaped, to a large extent, by socialization that occurs early in family life (Heckman, 2006). Families also contribute to the rearing of caring, committed member of society. When children have relationships with their parents that are sensitively responsive and reliably available, they develop many qualities that societies value in their citizenry. Things like, involvement, leadership self-confidence, and social competence in problem-solving situations (Englund, Levy, Hyson, & Sroufe, 2000).In 2017, community partners from Dodge and Jefferson Counties came together with shared concern for the children and families in our communities. Collective work began with a multi-agency Design Team comprised of 15 organizational representatives from these two counties. Out of that work came Every Child Thrives (ECT). ECT is a collective impact effort uniting community partners centered on the vision of ensuring all children thrive in health, learning and life. The two counties served by ECT share similar demographics and culture and have a long history of working together to advance health and education. In late 2015, our two county region was gifted with additional resources when the Greater Watertown Community Health Foundation (GWCHF) was created with an endowment to be utilized to measurably improve community health status. Through its needs assessment process in partnership with the Dodge Jefferson Healthy Community Partnership and through an extensive listening campaign, GWCHF learned of the many challenges and barriers that limit the potential of families and young children. The health providers, educators and human service providers serving the community noted that poverty, substance abuse, adverse childhood experiences and toxic stress were impacting the region at an alarmingly increased rate. Through these discussions, community partners not only identified a need to amplify efforts to support young children and families, they also identified a strong willingness to contribute to the efforts. Partners were energized by one another and by the possibilities the new resources and momentum presented. With this realization, ECT was born. Located midway between Wisconsin's two metropolitan centers of Madison and Milwaukee, Dodge and Jefferson Counties are primarily rural. The majority of residents live in small towns with limited resources including public transportation, affordable housing, access to mental health and dental care services for children. Manufacturing, agriculture and service are the primary industries.This work is initially focused on families and children, ages pre-natal through third grade, in the Dodgeland School District and the Watertown Unified School District. As success is demonstrated, the scope will expand to include all families and children in Jefferson and Dodge Counties.

Document_Name: Social Emotional Well-being of Children and Families: Outreach
Segment: Family Well-beingFamilies perform a variety of key functions that contribute to both the mental and physical health of individuals as well as the public health and functioning of society. Throughout all developmental stages, from the prenatal period to the last years of life, strong healthy relationships help families effectively and efficiently raise healthy children, care for vulnerable members, and sustain productive workers and contributing community members. Children who are born into and raised in an environment of positive relationships have a strong foundation that can help them develop into healthy adults and productive citizens. This environment of relationships involves not only parents and children but also extended family and social networks, schools and childcare providers, and others who engage with the family. Stable, nurturing relationships have a powerful protective impact on children. They help prevent exposure to multiple risks and stressors, including family violence and neglect, parental incarceration, and mental illness. Exposure to these stressors is associated with numerous poor outcomes, some of which are commonly seen across multiple generations within families and are very costly to society. In addition to contributing to prevention, safe, stable, nurturing relationships with parents and other caregivers serve as a buffer to help mitigate the damaging impacts of toxic stress. Healthy relationships help children thrive. Quality ChildcareSince many families depend on childcare providers during the first years of a child's life, providers can play a key role in strengthening families and building stronger communities. Childcare programs provide important preventive services, often taking on the role of family resource centers in communities that lack such services. Childcare providers are viewed as the "experts" in child development. They connect parents to community resources, model developmentally appropriate parenting practices and provide education related to stages of child development. Parents and providers working together in partnership create healthy environments and long-term benefits for children. Social, emotional and intellectual learning are inextricably linked. Supportive relationships and healthy interactions shape brain circuits and lay a foundation for academic and developmental successes. Most young children spend some time in non-parental care. Infants and toddlers with employed mothers spend an average of 25 hours per week in childcare, and 39% are in childcare for 35 hours or more each week. In Dodge County, there are more than 5,000 children, under the age of six, in regulated childcare settings (including certified or licensed home-based centers, group childcare centers, Head Start and preschool programs, and half-day 4K programs). It is estimated that more than 70% of Wisconsin's young children are in some type of child care or early education programs outside of their homes. The quality of childcare care is a key determinant of how well prepared children are for school. Technology and the Modern FamilyRecent trends in technology are changing the way that families interact, learn and build relationships. Infants, toddlers, and preschoolers are now growing up in environments saturated with a variety of traditional and new technologies, which they are adopting at increasing rates. Ninety-eight percent of homes with children under eight have mobile devices according to a study from Common Sense Media. Although there has been much hope for the educational potential of interactive media for young children, accompanied by fears about their overuse during this crucial period of rapid brain development, research in this area remains limited. The American Academy of Pediatrics has recently addressed the influence of media on the health and development of children from zero to 5 years of age, a time of critical brain development, building secure relationships, and establishing health behaviors. Through this research, the Digital Parenting Workgroup has been able to apply findings to current and future work around digital media. Research shows that digital media can be a useful means for providing education to parents and studies have found that online parenting education can be as effective as face-to-face settings in influencing positive parenting change. Today's average American spends almost nine hours per day using technology and owns four digital devices. Digital devices have proven to be a great equalizer, providing young adults, minorities, those with no college experience, and those with lower household income levels a connection to the Internet. Access to digital devices and the Internet is no longer limited to middle class families; the clear majority of parents, including those from low-income and vulnerable populations, are now connected. Available web-based knowledge and programs can both stand-alone and supplement face-to-face programs. Increasingly, the web has become the initial point of contact where parents seek out and access information. It also functions as the "front door" through which parents learn about and connect to local and county resources, including face-to-face education and assistance. Having a prominent online presence is critical to successfully reaching and educating parents in the 21st century.

Document_Name: Work Plan for FoodWIse Interim State Coordinator, FFY19 quarter
Segment: Situation statement (Why): The FoodWIse program is funded by two major grants (SNAP-Ed and EFNEP) which provide for a program that serves over 75,000 low income individuals and families each year. As Interim State Coordinator, my role in the next 6 months is to continue to implement the 3-year program plan and the daily management of partnerships, budgets and staff. During this period there will be an annual program planning/budget planning process that takes place at the county project level and state level. The total budget allocation for FoodWIse is approximately $8 million and an effort to "right size" project budgets in response to demographics and need has been ongoing for several years. This year, county projects will begin the process with a 3-year plan and action plan in place, and will make adjustments to budgets only as needed. A simplified process for gathering and reviewing this information will save time and effort for coordinators as well as state staff.There are several new state staff and new positions with statewide responsibility that require ongoing guidance as they develop into their roles. There may also be a permanent State Coordinator hired within the next 6 months. A major effort of this position will be to help these teams clarify roles in developing and implementing programming that meets local needs within the state plan.

Document_Name: Building community capacity through research, strategic plannin
Segment: Situational Analysis:To effectively address current and emerging community needs in Chippewa County, it is important to build community capacity using unbiased research-based knowledge and practices. This includes utilization of local data to understand phenomena and make informed decisions regarding priorities and allocation of resources. Faced with growing needs and limited resources, many government departments and nonprofit organizations have reached out to the Extension for assistance in the areas of research, strategic planning, and evaluation. While a lot have been achieved in this area, strategic planning and evaluation are need-based and ongoing programs area that will continue to be critical for prioritization and efficiency.

Document_Name: Community Engaged Leadership: Civic Engagement - Youth Governan
Segment: This area of emphasis focuses on youth cultivating the habits and skills necessary for political participation in a democratic society and taking individual and collective action to identify and address issues of public concern.4-H Youth Development prioritizes learning by doing to maximize positive youth development outcomes. Successful strategies include:building youth/adult partnership practices into community decision-making, whether within the 4-H organization or in other community settings, from community coalitions to organizational boards and committees. Resources to inform these practices can be found at https://fyi.uwex.edu/youthadultpartnership/ facilitating action planning processes, by which youth can address community issues, either in youth-led spaces with adult coaching or in partnerships with adults working on the same issues. Resources for action planning have been developed for the Tech Changemakers program (https://fyi.uwex.edu/wi4hcitizenship/research-resources/) and the FoodWIse/4-H Youth Development Youth Action for Community Health project)creating opportunities for youth input and decision-making including Teen Courts where youth enact restorative justice, opportunities for youth to serve as advisors on local government boards (Youth in Governance), etc. where they can build relationships with and inform adult decision-makers, youth input into community development through participation in planning process, etc. These opportunities help youth to build understanding of community issues and their civic roles.Youth who participate in these types of opportunities develop habits that make civic participation as adults much more likely. In Wisconsin, we have also seen evidence that youth develop an appreciation for the communities where they live and develop supportive relationships with community adults. Outcomes for communities of youth civic engagement include greater economic and social development that includes young people in all aspects of community life. Key practices developed by the Engaging Young People to Sustain Communities include empowering more diverse community leadership, increasing social capital, and strengthening sense of community and sense of place (see, for example, https://blogs.ces.uwex.edu/engaging-youth/files/2015/02/EYP-White-Paper-February-2015.pdf). These outcomes are particularly important for groups that are marginalized from community leadership due to race, class, or other characteristics.Dane County Situation StatementDane County is one of the most racially and ethnically diverse counties in Wisconsin. The county is also home to some of the fastest growing communities in the state[1]. Dane County is expected to experience the highest numeric growth in the state through 2040[2]. With this population growth comes a growing youth population, and those youth are more diverse than the generations who came before them. Multiple data analyses of educational, employment, and demographic data indicate that Dane County has pervasive and extreme disparities between its black and white citizens[3]. The Race to Equity Baseline Report released in 2013 compiled the data showcasing these disparities. Many of these had a disproportionate impact on Black youth, including the following:Black children in Dane County are over 13 times more likely to be growing up in poverty than white children.Black youth in the Madison Metropolitan School District, the largest school district in the county, have a 50% graduation rate. White children in the same school district have an 85% graduation rate.Suspensions in Dane County schools were 15 times more likely to involve a Black student than a white student. In 2010, the county's black youth arrest rate was 469 per 1,000, compared to 77 per 1,000 for whites, yielding a disparity ratio of 6.1 to 1. Black teens in Dane County in 2010 were six times more likely to be arrested than whites living here, while black youth in the rest of the state were just three times as likely to be arrested as whites.Race to Equity created an extensive list of suggested actions for Dane County agencies and organizations. The following suggested actions, excerpted from their document, could inform Dane County 4-H Youth Development's approach to programming and partnerships:  City and County agencies along with non-profit providers and public school districts should provide increased availability of quality afterschool care and summer/vacation child care and youth programming for school age  Public, private and non-profit sectors should invest in significantly enhancing the availability of core family strengthening resources and amenities in the county's low-income neighborhoods, including access to groceries, pharmacies, banks and safe places for positive supervised youth activities for children of currently underserved working or job-seeking families of color. Many grassroots, neighborhood-based nonprofits and agencies have been working for years to build a network of support for Black youth in Madison. These agencies are deeply connected with their communities, and Dane County 4-H Youth Development can honor these connections by taking the time to learn the history of each organization and build trust with organizational leaders as we form partnerships. The Latinx* population in Dane County is another large and growing portion of the county's overall demographic make-up. Between 2010 and 2014, Dane County's Latinx population was the County's second fastest growing population[4]. Over three-quarters of the Latinx population of Dane County is located in two municipalities: Madison and Fitchburg. Reflecting larger county population patterns, the Madison Metropolitan School District (MMSD) has the highest enrollment of Latinxs with 5,554 Latinxs in K through 12 institutions. These Latinx youth are the second largestracial group in the district after whites (11,724) and represent 20.5% of all MMSD enrolled students. Latinx youth in K through 12 schools are also a growing population. For example, between the 2005-2006 and 2015-2016 school years, Latinx enrollment in MMSD increased 96.3% from 2,830 to 5,554. Of all the major racial groups in Dane County, Latinxs have the lowest levels of educational attainment of adults ages 25 and above. Almost a third (31%) of Latinxs 25 years and above in Dane County do not have a high school diploma. The lowest rates of educational attainment are concentrated toward the near periphery of the County. For example, in Middleton, 41% of Latinxs lack a high school diploma, 38% in Sun Prairie, and 36% in Fitchburg. Recent University of Wisconsin-Extension research on Latinx families in Wisconsin identified specific programming recommendations for families[5]. Through focus groups and interviews, the researchers heard about cultural and language barriers within Latinx families. Parents can struggle to communicate with their own children because of the significant language differences and different cultural experiences between generations. The report recommends English and Spanish language programming for adults and youth; and programming that highlights educational pathways for parents and youth so that Latinx families can better navigate the school system. This is just a snapshot of the disparities existing within the county. As the United Way of Dane County states in their Academic Success Mobilization Plan, "disparities are not an issue of potential, but rather of students not in a position to receive the same opportunities."[6] It is the responsibility of UW-Extension 4-H Youth Development staff to analyze and identify where disparities in opportunity exist within our programming, and to work to change institutional and programmatic circumstances so that we can offer more equitable opportunities to the youth of Dane County. It's also our responsibility to apply an asset-based approach to youth development programming. Rather than focusing on disparities and deficits, we need to celebrate youths' strengths and use a culturally relevant approach. We can partner strategically with other youth-serving organizations to build community capacity. *The Dane County Latino Consortium for Action uses the term Latinx to reflect the community's diversity and inclusivity. The term refers to people of Hispanic/Latino origin, regardless of race, or gender identity. We use that term throughout this document to honor that preference. Document_Name: WI Tree Farm Committee Website Evaluation (2019)
Segment: The WI Tree Farm Committee has been reviewing the need to improve their website to meet the new needs of inspecting foresters and tree farmers. The committee agreed to survey potential users of the website to gain further insights as to future changes of their website.

The dairy industry in Wisconsin produces the equivalent of 12 billion gallons of liquid manure annually. (That's enough to cover a football field more than 5 miles high). Properly managed and applied, it is a valuable nutrient source and builds soil health. Improperly managed, and it has a high potential to contribute to ground and surface water contamination (nutrient and pathogen). State agencies (DNR, DATCP) and federal partners (USDA NRCS, EPA) recognize the issue and have implemented a variety of voluntary and mandatory programs/rules to reduce the risk. While implementation has reduced the problem, it has not successfully eliminated it. Extension's role is toa. Provide education to those who apply and manage manureb. Explore research and innovative technologies that producers can use to reduce the riskPrevious work with the for-hire manure applicators, impacted local citizen groups (such as Midwest Environmental Advocates, Kewaunee Cares), USDA-ARS DFRC, UWEX Groundwater experts and my own peer-reviewed journal article) documents the impact of manure-related runoff on the drinking water supplies of rural residents who do not have access to municipal water systems, but also shows that incremental changes in management do have an impactBoth educational outreach and technological solutions will need to be employed to reduce livestock agriculture's impact on ground and surface water quality. Annual surveys of the for-hire manure applicators (personally conducted) document changes in equipment used and technology adoption in the industry.A separate but unique situation is the recent increase in manure spill impacts. Discussions with DNR staff indicate that many larger manure spill impacts could have been prevented if farmers had access to private sector consultants who could advise them on the proper steps to take during a spill or runoff event.

Document_Name: Fostering Health and Wellness in Waushara County in 2019
Segment: Unhealthy individual behaviors in Wisconsin and Waushara CountyWaushara County is a rural, low-income county in central Wisconsin that is located 80 miles south of Madison, with 24,496 residents. The population is predominantly White and non-Hispanic; the largest minority group is Hispanic, at 6.1% of the population or approximately 1484 people and Black or African Americans at 2.1% of the population or 511 people. 19% of the population is under the age of 18. The Waushara County Average Annual Wage is $31,608 compared to Wisconsin's $46,031. Waushara County is ranked 48 in the County Health Rankings for overall health outcomes. In Waushara County 34% of adults are obese; 61% of residents have access to exercise compared to the state at 86% having access. 9% of residents are uninsured. According to the June 2018 Report of Annual Death from the Department of Health Services, in Wisconsin cancer is the leading cause of death for ages 25-64. In that age range in 2016, 3093 people died from cancer, 846 from drug overdose, and 1895 from heart disease. In Waushara County, 96 died from heart disease and 72 from cancer, and there's insufficient data for drug overdose mortality.Approximately two-thirds of all deaths in Wisconsin are attributed to chronic diseases such as heart disease, cancer, stroke and diabetes. In Waushara County, the top two killers are heart disease and cancer according to the 2015 DHS Annual Death Report, with 96 deaths from heart disease, and 72 reported from cancer. The leading age group for cancer deaths in Wisconsin is ages 45-64. According to the Wisconsin Behaviors Risk Factor Surveillance System over half of Wisconsin residents are living with at least one chronic disease. These chronic diseases can be disabling, can cause distress and require extensive medical treatment and care for individuals and families living with these conditions.Obesity and overweight contribute to these chronic diseases. The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reports that nearly 3 out of 10 Wisconsin residents are obese and another one-third are overweight. One of every 4 Wisconsin high school students is overweight or obese and 29 percent of 2-3 year old children participating in the WIC program are overweight or obese. The incidence of obesity is greater for Wisconsinites who are black, Hispanic, Native American or who have low incomes. A small set of modifiable risk factors are responsible for most of the leading chronic diseases: unhealthy diet; insufficient physical activity; tobacco use/smoke exposure; and alcohol abuse. Approximately 43% of Wisconsin adults fail to meet physical activity recommendations and nearly 1 of 5 engages in no leisure-time physical activity. About 75% of Wisconsin adults do not consume fruits or vegetables 5 or more times per day. Most food-borne illness is due to improper storage, handling, and preparation of food in the home. Therefore, in addition to improved diet and physical activity behaviors, Wisconsinites need to use safe food handling practices.Girls starting puberty (ages 9-12) are at an increased risk of low self-esteem and poor body image which is related to depression and lower academic grades. Factors contributing to low self-esteem include obesity and media influence. Girls with low self-esteem at the age of 12 are 2.5X more likely to engage in heavy alcohol use at the age of 15. Girls who have a low opinion of themselves are 4X more likely to engage in activities with boys that they will regret later. The 2018 Waushara County Youth Risk Behavior Assessment was completed by 302 sophomore and senior high school students. 75 students identified being bullied in the past year. 48 seriously considered attempting suicide in the 12 months before the survey. In the 30 days before the survey 33 students had five or more alcoholic drinks in a couple hours; the same number had used marijuana, and 18 students had used prescription medications that were not prescribed to them, or different than their doctor had prescribed[11] Wisconsin Department of Health Services. Document_Name: Nonpoint Source Pollution Outreach and Education
Segment: Society has made tremendous progress reducing surface and groundwater pollution since passage of the Clean Water Act. In recent decades nonpoint source pollution from agricultural, urban, forested and other land uses remains the single largest cause of ongoing water quality problems. These problems manifest most commonly in Wisconsin as surface water algal blooms and sedimentation and in groundwater as elevated nitrates and other contaminants. These impacts have significant effects on public health, local economies and natural communities.Reducing the impacts on nonpoint source pollution through regulation is, by definition, problematic given the dispersed nature of the pollutants. Therefore, outreach and education plays a prominent role in alternate approaches. The Regional Natural Resources Program employs a variety of responses to this challenge, primarily through a contractual relationship with the Wisconsin DNR Nonpoint Source Program.

A clean and dependable supply of water is critical to ensure a high quality of life and maintain a strong economy. Groundwater is of particular importance to Wisconsin with nearly 95% of communities and all rural residents rely wells that access it for their water supply. Groundwater also supplies the majority of water to Wisconsin's streams and rivers and is instrumental to lake levels and wetlands. Groundwater is often referred to as Wisconsin's "buried treasure". As valuable as this resource is to Wisconsin, it is often not well understood by the general public or elected officials who may be asked to make decisions about managing this resource. Thanks to scientists we now have a much better understanding of this resource than we once used to, but confusion and simple questions such as what groundwater is, how it moves, or what causes groundwater contamination still exist. Translating that scientific knowledge to the broader community however is an ongoing need. One of the best tools to educate people about groundwater is the sand-tank groundwater model. The sand-tank model is a highly visual teaching tool that represents a cross section of the earth and allows people to see how groundwater moves through the soil and rock layers below us. By adding colored dye to simulate pollutants, or pumping wells to simulate groundwater withdrawals; viewers are better able to visualize and understand complex groundwater principles. A previous survey of educators indicated that for participants in trainings where models have been used, over 90% of respondents said that the sand-tank model increased their confidence in teaching about groundwater. In addition, 88% indicated that incorporating the sand-tank groundwater model into their curriculum was more effective than traditional teaching methods for helping students understand groundwater; and that it resulted in students that were more actively engaged in groundwater lessons. This Extension research and programming is designed to enhance literacy of groundwater and ultimately help the next generation of Wisconsinites and future leaders make informed decisions related to waters of the state.

Document_Name: Developing more profitable and resilient community food systems
Segment: Introduction and backgroundCommunities in Chippewa County faces arrays of social and economic challenges. According to Chippewa Community Health Improvement Partnership 2018 needs assessment, mental health, substance abuse and alcohol abuse, and obesity emerged are among major concerns. Although the U.S census Bureau indicates poverty rate in Chippewa County to be 11%, there is a wide perception among community leaders and organizations that poverty is more widespread than reported on national data. According to the United Ways ALICE 2018 report, the overall percentage of households struggling to meet basic cost of living in Chippewa County was 26%, which is slightly higher than the state overage of 25.8 %. Cities with the highest ALICE poverty households include Stanley 55%, Chippewa Falls 51%, Cornel 51%, Edson 48%, Cadott Village 48%, and 42% in Bloomer. ALICE is an acronym for Asset Limited, Income Constrained, Employed - households that earn more than the Federal Poverty Level, but less than the basic cost of living for the county.Chippewa County is situated in the Chippewa River Valley of west central Wisconsin. The county is bordered by Rusk and Barron counties to the north, Taylor and Clark counties to the east, Eau Claire County to the south, and Dunn County to the west. In 2017, the county population was 63,813, with 46% being rural. The county comprises of 11 villages and cities: Bloomer, Boyd, Cadott, Chippewa Falls, Cornell, Holcombe, Jim Falls, Lake Hallie, New Auburn, and Stanley. Chippewa county seat is located in the city of Chippewa Falls that has the population of 13,965. Major economic sources in the county are agriculture, forestry, fishing, hunting, manufacturing, and healthcare and social services. Frac sand mining has been an important employment source but has slowed down probably due to decline in energy costs. My two major educational programing below were informed by results of community needs assessments I conducted in 2016 and 2017-2018, available existing data, county priorities, and three-year experience working in the community.Situational Analysis:Chippewa County continues to prioritize agriculture for community economic development. This project builds on three-year experience working with small family farms and other stakeholders to organize more profitable local food system that increases income for farmers, enhances local economy, and addresses food insecurity across. Regardless of great potential, infrastructure for local food is lacking and there is limited market for local food in the area. For example, there are no opportunities for farmers to connect and share knowledge and experiences. Similarly, there is no mechanisms to link farmers and potential customers seeking local food. Chippewa Community Health Improvement Partnership needs assessment has consistently indicates the need for improving food security among poor households and communities, particularly in rural setting lacking grocery stores. According to the assessment, about one quarter of Chippewa County residents lives in areas designated as food deserts - defined by the USDA as "urban neighborhoods and rural towns without ready access to fresh, healthy, and affordable food"[i]. Establishing strong profitable local food systems requires leadership and active participation of the community involved. In addition to providing fresh healthy food and education about food and nutrition, community gardens serve as platforms for social interaction, bringing people together to share experiences and information. Social interaction is particularly important in the increasingly socially isolated communities as it provides safe spaces for residents to inclusive build networks, with the potential for overall neighborhood improvement. A recent community needs assessment in the county indicate great interests in community garden. Research participants specifically cited the need for community gardens as an ideal space for socialization and peer-to-peer interaction to exchange resources and build skills. This program will address the issue of infrastructure for local foods in Chippewa County through research, education, and leadership development. [i] USDA https://apps.ams.usda.gov/fooddeserts/fooddeserts.aspx.

Document_Name: 2019 field research with western WI farmers and partners to enh
Segment: Situation StatementDiscovery Farms has conducted a nitrogen use efficiency (NUE) project with 50+ WI farmers, as guided by Dr. Matt Ruark and our staff (2015-2017). Through this time, we refined field methodology and results messaging while working with farmers and their corn production practices. This process offered participants 1:1 season-long, and between production year, insights into how corn nitrogen (N) management can be altered to achieve economically optimum yields while reducing N losses to the environment.Current Land and Water Resource Management Plans for Sauk, Pepin and Dunn Counties, WI, each define groundwater quality as a resource priority. USDA Soil Surveys and County Plans also show that they each have significant agricultural production areas of courser textured soil over somewhat shallow sedimentary bedrock aquifers, and similar production areas over unconfined sand and gravel aquifers. Each county defines approximately 15% of private drinking water wells to exceed the safe drinking standard of 10 mg/l nitrate-nitrogen.In 2018, Discovery Farms began a 3-year partnering process with local Extension and natural resource agencies to teach them NUE field trial methodology as we jointly delivered 1:1 NUE training to small groups of farmers in Sauk, Pepin, and Dunn Counties. Year number two of this process will be pursued in 2019. This process allows both the partners and farmers they work with to enhance local, practical, and feasible corn N management under the guidance of Discovery Farms. After 3 years, a framework will exist for farmers and their local education / conservation agencies to pursue ongoing field trials that teach best corn N management for production and water quality, allowing Discovery Farms to begin the process with other partners.

Document_Name: Environmental Education 2019 Statewide - DOTS and Data Literacy
Segment: Embracing Technology Rooted in Heritage of Upham WoodsWhen the University of Wisconsin received the donation of land that would become Upham Woods, Wakelin McNeel served as the Center's first superintendent. McNeel was also known as "Ranger Mac", a persona he created for a Wisconsin Public Radio show that he hosted. As part of his show, he invited youth and adults from all across Wisconsin to reflect on, observe, engage, and conserve the state's wonderful natural resources. On the program, he often noted that "If you didn't take a walk yesterday, you missed out on many things that may not come again" (Matkin-Rawn 2004). Today, we share these same sentiments with our students, encouraging them to observe their surroundings and ask questions that enable them to better understand the world they inhabit. While Ranger Mac worked at Upham Woods in the 1930s and 1940s, many parallels exist between his service to the state and the direction Upham is headed today. Ranger Mac used the technology of the era radio to connect a statewide audience to the environment. By using a resource that was both pervasive and accessible, he drew youth and adults to issues in our natural world and also enabled them to explore Upham Woods. Today, we accomplish these same objectives through the Digital Observation Technology Skills (DOTS) program and web-based resources. Ranger Mac's approach focused on observation and wonder in the outdoors. Today, we use terms such as informal science learning (ISL), inquiry-based instruction, project-based learning and place-based education to describe this same approach. Although there have been many changes in the last 76 years at Upham Woods, it continues to serve a crucial statewide presence in environmental education outreach by leveraging an effective blend of technology and youth development, within a context of vibrant natural resources and scenic beauty.Confidence in this Well-founded ApproachThe National Research Council's research shows that ISL is guided by student inquiry about the natural world, data collection related to their inquiry, and opportunities to present their findings to peers and community members (National Research Council, 2009). Further, the National Research Council states that informal learning environments are, in principle, accessible to all learners, and evidence suggests they have particular potential for supporting learners from non-dominant groups (National Research Council, 2009). In addition to providing experiential learning opportunities grounded in environmental concepts, ISL centers like Upham Woods expand the network of educators and facilitators engaged in environmental education and provide students with "direct access to compelling phenomena in the natural world" (National Science Foundation, 2011).While ISL centers, such as camps and nature centers, have historically had programming legacies rooted in the natural sciences, their educational practices can be in tension with the emphasis on the adoption of modern technology that often guides contemporary STEM education (Cuthbertson, Socha, & Potter, 2004). Yet using technology in outdoor education settings holds great promise in deepening scientific connections to local places through data collection. As an example, data collection within a context of location, community, and inquiry provides a place-based approach to education that contributes to active and engaged citizens (Hougham & Kerlin, 2016; Sobel, 2004). In modern science classrooms and careers, most scientific tools are digital. Consequently, adopting digital tools requires ISL centers to strike a careful balance between retaining the connection to place that outdoor, experiential learning promotes and serving youth and educators with modern STEM curricula. Connecting this further, place-based education like that promoted at Upham Woods has been shown to connect learners' STEM engagement to their experiences in informal settings, develop their acute observation skills, and increase their capacity to care about the environment around them (Land & Zimmerman, 2015; Greenwood & Hougham, 2015).

Kewaunee County is rural with a population of 20,545 and 8,125 households. Ninety-six percent of the residents are White with a growing Hispanic population of 4.5%. In 2016, 19% of residents were 65 or older and 18% are caregivers of elderly or disabled family member or friend. The median household income is $53,023 which is slightly higher than the state average but 39% of households are struggling to afford basic needs (ALICE report, 2014). Employment opportunities are limited in the county and 35% of workers have longer commutes (30 minutes or more) to work compared to 17% of workers in neighboring counties (Kewaunee County Quality of Life Report, 2012). Research has linked long work commutes to stress and poor health. Occupational stress related to agriculture work is also a concern in Kewaunee County. The stress of workers is not isolated, it impacts their families and communities. Adults report 3.4 mentally unhealthy days per month (County Health Rankings, 2018) and 24% of youth reported feeling sad or hopeless almost daily (Kewaunee County YRBS 2018). In 2015, Kewaunee County had 108 marriages and in 2016 there were 52 divorces; nearly a 50% divorce rate. Through survey feedback and during community coalition work, families have expressed to me the challenges they experience as a result of divorce, separation, incarceration, foster care placement, caregiving responsibilities, or work-related stress. Educational programs and collaborative community supports can promote resiliency to strengthen families and the community as they address challenges affecting their physical, mental and emotional wellbeing across the lifespan. Research is clear that strong family and other interpersonal relationships significantly contribute to the health and wellbeing of individuals across the lifespan. Family strengthening programs and policies help build strong relationships within supportive communities, improving outcomes for children, families and society.Families perform a variety of key functions that contribute to both the mental and physical health of individuals as well as the public health and functioning of society. Throughout all developmental stages, from the prenatal period to the last years of life, strong healthy relationships help families effectively and efficiently raise healthy children, care for vulnerable members, and sustain productive workers and contributing community members.Children who are born into and raised in an environment of positive relationships have a strong foundation that can help them develop into healthy adults and productive citizens. This environment of relationships involves not only parents and children but also extended family and social networks, schools and childcare providers, and others who engage with the family. Stable, nurturing relationships have a powerful protective impact on children. They help prevent exposure to multiple risks and stressors, including family violence and neglect, parental incarceration, and mental illness. Exposure to these stressors is associated with numerous poor outcomes, some of which are commonly seen across multiple generations within families and are very costly to society. In addition to contributing to prevention, safe, stable, nurturing relationships with parents and other caregivers serve as a buffer to help mitigate the damaging impacts of toxic stress. Healthy relationships help children thrive.Adult health and well-being also depend in great part on the quality and success of relationships. Adults in stable relationships have better health outcomes, greater financially stability, a greater sense of well-being and improved capacity to provide care for vulnerable family members, including children and older adults. It has long been understood that a strong parent/child relationship is a key factor in preventing negative outcomes for children. More recent research suggests that strong relationships between parents and other adults, including romantic partners, friends and extended family, can help prevent child maltreatment and improve the capacity of adults to parent effectively. Healthy relationships help adults nurture.For seniors, social connections and strong family relationships are critical to continued wellbeing and engagement. As the nation and Wisconsin experience a demographic shift toward a greater proportion of older adults, it is critical to invest in programs that keep seniors connected and contributing in their roles as active citizens, caregivers for children and older adults, and as part of the social support system of partners, friends and others. Healthy relationships support seniors' wellbeing.In this plan, I will work to strengthen the family and enhance relationships in order to promote lifelong mental, physical and emotional health. Recognizing that families do not exist in isolation and that they are influenced by many settings, institutions, norms, policies, and transitions, I will offer programming which acts on research to:? support caregiver skills across developmental stages,? target periods of significant stress for families and caregivers,? reach learners through traditional and digital methods, and? connect individuals and communities through systems level work.
