Document_Name: Addressing Accessibility, Availability and Acceptability in Rur
Segment: The topic of improving mental health is at the forefront of conversations in both Green and Lafayette Counties. In 2016 and 2019 Green County's Community Health Needs Assessment ranked mental health in the top four issues to be addressed. Lafayette County last performed a Community Health Needs Assessment in 2015 and ranked mental health seventh behind drug and alcohol issues, aging problems, healthy lifestyle choices/behaviors and access to care. Green and Lafayette Counties have a ratio of community members to mental health providers of 1120:1 and 560:1 respectively. The statewide suicide death rate for 2009-2013 was 13.5 per 100,000 individuals. In Green County the suicide death rate was 15.8 and Lafayette's was 17.9. Beyond the rankings around mental health lay the factors of everyday life. Both communities' economies rely heavily on the agricultural sector. Much stress exists due to the current agriculture climate. The Hispanic community expresses anxiety both with the agricultural economy and the state of immigration in the United States. Stigma in Lafayette County is especially strong due to the occurrence of a triple homicide in April of 2013 that was committed by a stranger to the community with a mental health history. Transportation to and from appointments and support groups outside the county is difficult due to the lack of public transportation. There is also a distinct lack of community supports geographically located in Lafayette County. An investigation reveals there is no community based care groups for miscarriage, divorce, AODA issues, death, or anger management. The nearest group I could locate is Alcoholics Anonymous coming in at almost 54 miles away. The scientific data and the daily living data both suggest a strong need to increase accessibility, availability and acceptability concerning rural mental health in both Green and Lafayette County.

Document_Name: Maintaining and Improving the Water Action Volunteers Program (
Segment: The Water Action Volunteers (WAV) program engages Wisconsin citizens in monitoring water quality in their local streams and rivers. The goals of the program are to educate and empower citizens to collect high quality data, and to share their data and knowledge. There are currently over 1,000 citizen science projects worldwide with over 1 million volunteers (Source: CitizenScience.org.) The WAV program expands Extension's presence in the booming area of citizen science, broadens Extension's stakeholder base, and brings fiscal resources to Extension (funding from the DNR to support WAV.)

Document_Name: Creating healthy young leaders through exposure to new outdoor
Segment: The following Rusk County statistics, as recorded by the 2017 United States Census Bureau, state that 22% of youth ages 5-17 live below the poverty level, and 90% of those youth are enrolled in public school. Rusk County has three public schools and one private school for grades K-8. Approximately 6% of youth, ages 10-19, make up the total population in Rusk County where the median age is 48.6 years old. Each public school in the county provides breakfast for their students, as well as has a free or reduced lunch program. Bruce Public Schools is a Community Eligibility Provision (CEP) participant. According to the Rusk County Community Health Improvement Process: Intervention Proposal, conducted by the UW-Madison School of Nursing, data collected proves that there is lack of physical activity in adults in Rusk County as well as a problem with obesity. Roughly 29% of adults ages 20 and up report having no leisure time with physical activity. That number is 8% higher than the Wisconsin state average. Approximately 31% of adults reported a BMI of 30 or higher, which is the same as the Wisconsin state average. When asked if lack of physical activity and obesity is a problem, 31.3% said yes it is a major problem and 53.4% said it is a moderate problem.Data shows that 82.7% of people in Rusk County reported that being physically active is not an easy or desirable choice, i.e. lack of motivation or time. Of those surveyed, 44.4% said they suffer from health problems that prevent physical activity, and 41.1% said that they cannot easily access, or are unaware of where to go to be physically active. Approximately 37.4% of people surveyed stated that they are unaware of the health risks of obesity. The 2017 Wisconsin High School Youth Risk Behavior Survey reports that 13.7% of youth were obese and 15% were overweight. Of those surveyed, an eye opening number of youth, 44%, were trying to lose weight. According to the National Association of Sport and Physical Education and the American Heart Association, Wisconsin mandates physical education classes for grades K-6 and requires daily recess throughout elementary school. The state also mandates physical education classes in grades 7-12 and requires high schools to provide their students with physical education. The state requires 1.5 physical education credits to graduate high school. Wisconsin Department of Instruction states that quality physical education programs are needed to increase the physical competence, health-related fitness, self-responsibility, and enjoyment of physical activity for all students so that they can be physically active for a lifetime. As you can see from the data above, youth and adults in Rusk County have expressed a want, need, and an unfamiliarity with recreation areas in our community to be active in. Because 44% of the youth population surveyed has expressed that they are trying to lose weight, conversations were had with stakeholders in regards to possibilities of creating new outdoor recreation activities to promote healthy, active lifestyles for youth.

Document_Name: Nonpoint Source Pollution Outreach and Education (2019)
Segment: Society has made tremendous progress reducing surface and groundwater pollution since passage of the Clean Water Act. In recent decades nonpoint source pollution from agricultural, urban, forested and other land uses remains the single largest cause of ongoing water quality problems. These problems manifest most commonly in Wisconsin as surface water algal blooms and sedimentation and in groundwater as elevated nitrates and other contaminants. These impacts have significant effects on public health, local economies and natural communities.Reducing the impacts on nonpoint source pollution through regulation is, by definition, problematic given the dispersed nature of the pollutants. Therefore, outreach and education plays a prominent role in alternate approaches. The Regional Natural Resources Program employs a variety of responses to this challenge, primarily through a contractual relationship with the Wisconsin DNR Nonpoint Source Program.

Document_Name: Kids Paddle Forest to Lake-Investigating Land, Water and Cultur
Segment: This initiative builds upon an existing program partnership between the Northern Great Lakes Visitor Center (NGLVC) and University of Wisconsin-Extension to deliver a place-based habitat stewardship programs for youth at the NGLVC and the adjacent Fish Creek Estuary and Lake Superior. The non-profit Superior Rivers Watershed Association (SRWA) will contribute expertise in involving students in experiential assessments of watershed health and integrity to reinforce the "Kids Paddle Forest to Lake" connections.This initiative creates a new youth habitat stewardship program featuring half-day on-the-water field investigations that I teach using safe, 2-seater kayaks, supported by on-land water habitat investigations taught by Chequamegon-Nicolet Forest Service-NGLVC interpretive services specialist and SRWA water quality specialists.Many students have never had meaningful hands on learning experience within an aquatic ecosystem. Through demonstrations and guided discussions delivered in this aquatic "classroom", students will explore how historic-to-the-present interactions of economic development, natural resource use, and changing societal needs impact upland forests and the sustainability of the Lake Superior ecosystem. They will engage in hands-on water quality experiments and habitat assessments to evaluate the impacts of forest management on downstream aquatic habitats.Students will gain confidence in being in an on-the-water learning environment and interacting with aquatic resources. They will explore the importance of forests in supporting water quality, wildlife habitat, and recreation within a watershed and learn how they strengthen their stewardship of these resources.This initiative is supported by a $10,000 US Forest Service grant through 2019.

Document_Name: Nonpoint Source Pollution Outreach and Education
Segment: Society has made tremendous progress reducing surface and groundwater pollution since passage of the Clean Water Act. In recent decades nonpoint source pollution from agricultural, urban, forested and other land uses remains the single largest cause of ongoing water quality problems. These problems manifest most commonly in Wisconsin as surface water algal blooms and sedimentation and in groundwater as elevated nitrates and other contaminants. These impacts have significant effects on public health, local economies and natural communities.Reducing the impacts on nonpoint source pollution through regulation is, by definition, problematic given the dispersed nature of the pollutants. Therefore, outreach and education plays a prominent role in alternate approaches. The Regional Natural Resources Program employs a variety of responses to this challenge, primarily through a contractual relationship with the Wisconsin DNR Nonpoint Source Program (DNR NPS).Specifically, my contractual work with the DNR NPS program includes education and outreach to farmers in the Rock River basin. Of this basin, 60% of the land use is for agriculture, and agriculture accounts for 64% of total phosphorus and 89% of total suspended solids on an average annual basis. To address this, the concept of soil health has been widely promoted as it can lead to increased infiltration that would reduce runoff and improve water quality. To promote soil health and water quality, farmer-led groups have formed in the Rock River basin. These groups host successful educational programs, but the groups have challenges in building organizational capacity. Additionally, I met with a stakeholder group from Jefferson county, and they are interested in having more educational programs in the county that are focused on soil health. To address these needs, I will be planning various soil health outreach events in Jefferson county, and work with farmer-led groups to help them build organizational capacity.

In Wisconsin, approximately 12% of the state workforce is employed in nonprofit organizations. The revenue generated by these organizations (and secondary impact of wage earners) place the sector as an important contributor to the economy. We know nonprofits at their best are foundational pillars of vibrant communities. Increasingly, nonprofits are asking how they can go beyond meeting basic needs and providing services, and instead work toward addressing core causes in order to alleviate societal problems.In Dane County, nonprofits have a significant presence in the community: there are over 2,800 organizations (501c3 public charities) together drawing over $5 billion in annual revenue. (Davey, Sifting Through Abundance, 2018). The range of issues these organizations address is broad, including: improving education, reducing poverty and providing affordable housing, strengthening the health care support system, protecting and enhancing natural resources, and sustaining the arts. The ability of nonprofits to make substantial and lasting impacts on these issues, however, depends on their organizational capacity and the skills and training of staff. Many employees and volunteers -- including board members -- have not received training in non-profit governance nor organizational or program management. Oftentimes professionals starting in nonprofit management learn the skills necessary for running an organization from sporadic experimentation or harried individual research and networking. Extension Dane County provides assistance to non-profit organizations in the form of strategic planning, facilitation, program planning, and evaluation. Consulting efforts with individual non-profit organizations are high touch and time extensive. In particular, strategic planning work can take from 6-12 months. These high-touch efforts are valuable, but their reach is limited.In order to address the needs of non-profit organizations in the county, my programming in this area will touch on three different aspects for 2019. (1) Direct work with organizations along a consulting for capacity development model; (2) Research to more fully understand the environment/extent of non-profit serving organizations and to determine training and resource needs; (3) Revision of strategic planning methodologies, based on current research and informed by practice, and documented in a usable strategic planning manual.

Document_Name: Environmental and science education programs for PreK-12 (2019)
Segment: Though a contract for service Wehr Nature Center and its Outreach staff are contracted through the Milwaukee County Parks Department to provide outdoor field experiences, indoor science enrichment, and community enhancement programs focused on environmental, life and geologic sciences for a Pre-K-12 audience. These programs are aligned with local, state and national standards and incorporate literacy and STEAM. Programs are available year round and are small fee for service. Program sites include Wehr Nature Center, Milwaukee County Parks, local schools and Libraries.Many Milwaukee Public School teachers and those in the surrounding suburbs do not have the science content knowledge and management training to take students on outdoor field experiences. Wehr/Outreach provides those opportunities by working with the teachers and tailoring experiences to meet their classroom needs. Providing these environmental education experiences enhances knowledge, creates a sense of place, and builds awareness of the rich natural resources available in SE Wisconsin and how to care for them. All of this helps create the base for an environmentally literate adult.This is a group plan of work for the 3 Milwaukee County and 5 UWEX staff that provide these experiences.

Document_Name: Leadership Training - Community Leadership Alliance of Southwes
Segment: Ideas are easy but implementation of ideas requires effective, dedicated, and skilled leaders. Finding people willing and prepared to accept leadership positions, whether formal or informal, is a challenge everywhere but it is often more acute in rural areas. A rural area like ours has a stable but somewhat stagnant base of citizens. Plus our population is aging which puts more of a leadership burden on an ever smaller number of younger and often inexperienced individuals. Extension leaders in Grant, Iowa, and Lafayette Counties along with the Platteville Area Chamber of Commerce and the University of Wisconsin - Platteville recognized this challenge and combined their resources to create a program to address this issue. 20 years ago they formed the Community Leadership Alliance with the intent of providing locally based and locally focused training for existing and emerging government, business, and volunteer leaders in our tri-county area. Today that program plays a significant and ongoing role in the development of individuals who will serve the future of our area. Extension continues to play a lead role in both the ongoing development and delivery of the CLA program.

Segment: FoodWIse federally funded by the Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program-Education (SNAP-Ed) and the Expanded Food and Nutrition Education Program (EFNEP) and serves Wisconsin residents with limited incomes. Document_Name: Promoting the social-emotional well-being of children and famil
Segment: According to the Census Population Estimates, Florence County has 4,456 permanent residents. With a racial and ethnic makeup as follows: 99.7% white, 0.3% two or more races, 0.3% black or African American, 0.9% Hispanic or Latino and 0.3% American Indian and Alaska Native. The median age of Florence County is 52.1. Research is clear that strong family and other interpersonal relationships significantly contribute to the health and well-being of individuals across the lifespan. Programs for individuals across the lifespan help build strong relationships within supportive communities, which directly improve outcomes for children, parents, and society. Healthy relationships help children and families thrive.Children who are born into and raised in an environment of positive relationships have a strong foundation that helps them develop into healthy adults and productive citizens. Programs that focus on humans across the spectrum help prevent children having a high ACEs score and decreases exposure to stressors. Divorce/parental separation has become an increasingly common experience for children. Research shows parental conflict is the primary cause of child problems related to separation, divorce, or family transition. Wisconsin statue gives family courts the authority to mandate Co-Parenting programs for couples who are separating. These programs are built upon the belief that a family is an ongoing system of interconnected members. Family members are not identical to each other, and you cannot interact with one without thinking of the others.In 2015, Florence County had 34 divorces (dhs.wisconsin.gov). Divorce/parental separation has become an increasingly common experience for children. Due to a high divorce rate, the opioid epidemic, and other life transitions, we are also seeing an influx of Grandparents raising Grandchildren in Florence County. Through stakeholder and participant conversations, kinship care is reaching out for further support and resources. Families perform a variety of key functions that contribute to both the mental and physical health of individuals as well as the public health and functioning of society. Strong healthy relationships are a contributing factor to health in all ages and stages of development. Individuals and families in communities who strive within these connections and relationships have strong foundations that can help them grow into productive citizens. Stakeholder and partnership conversations in Florence County expressed the need for co-parenting workshops.

Document_Name: Lake Superior National Estuarine Research Reserve Research and
Segment: The Lake Superior Reserve is situated on the freshwater estuary at the confluence of the St. Louis River and Lake Superior, the largest and most pristine of the Great Lakes. An expansive system, it forms the river mouth of the largest US tributary to Lake Superior. The St. Louis River Estuary contains diverse estuarine habitats and interfaces with urban areas and a busy industrial port, allowing for extensive research opportunities. The Reserve encompasses 16,697 acres of land and water that are significant to supporting the Reserve's goals and protects the integrity of core areas for long-term research and monitoring. Although there are multiple universities, federal, state and local agencies, and tribal governments conducting research and monitoring in the St. Louis River, there are several scientific barriers that prevent informed management and decision making. The Research Advisory Board has identified the Research and Monitory Program as filling a unique niche within the Superior - Duluth research community. The program is designed to foster collaboration among all the various research, monitoring, and management entities and identify further research needs. By working collectively within the research community, the Program is posed to identify data gaps and work to fill them.

Document_Name: Dairy Management and Nutritional Strategies to Lower Farming's
Segment: Brown County is uniquely characterized by its strong urban population and rural agricultural community. The demographics of Brown County are also changing to include a greater population of Hispanic residents and also an increase in Hispanic workers on farms. Home to both Green Bay and 20 concentrated animal feeding operations (CAFOs), there is a great need for limiting the environmental impact caused by farms through improved farm management practices but not at the economic expense of the farm. Brown County agriculture provides 17,045 jobs to its residents and accounts for $4.6 billion in economic activity. Agriculture pays $80.8 million in taxes and contributes $1.28 billion to county income. Especially at a time of depressed commodity prices across all farming enterprises, it is important to support the agricultural industry through these trying times. In order to maintain a strong agricultural industry, greater workforce development and training resources are needed, especially with a bilingual component to support the growing Hispanic workforce population on farms. In addition, growing suicide rates among farmers has created a need for mental health awareness education and strategies for coping with stress.It is also important to create more positive relationships and better understanding between city residents and the agricultural community through agricultural literacy education. In recent years, news headlines featuring manure spills, resident and community complaints against farms, and general discontentment between city/non-agricultural residents and farmers/agricultural community have become more and more prevalent. This region of the state in particular is under great scrutiny and so are its farming practices. Residents are demanding to know what is being done to improve farming practices, especially as it relates to the environment.In January 2015, this educator conducted a needs assessment survey regarding agricultural and agricultural literacy educational topics in Brown County. A total of 39 agriculture surveys were completed by Brown county residents and regional agribusiness owners/employees. The survey identified five top general areas of importance by those surveyed. They are forages, nutrient management, soil health, dairy, and water quality. One of the top educational needs for farm business management was employee management education. A separate survey was conducted to identify the educational needs regarding agricultural literacy education. Fifty-four people completed the survey, and results showed that people want to learn more about where their food comes from and how farms affect the environment.Based on this information, this agent will focus on dairy and farm management; dairy conservation nutrition; and agricultural employee workforce development to support a struggling agricultural and farming industry for the 2019-program planning year.

Document_Name: Building Collaboration among Tribal and State Land-grant Univer
Segment: There are 20 tribal land-grant institutions in the North Central Region. While there are great examples of collaboration between state and tribal land-grants on water-related issues, there is room for growth. Strengthening collaboration and learning from local successes can achieve greater benefits for land-grant faculty, staff, and students, communities and tribal nations in the North Central Region and the water resources upon which we depend.A recent First Americans Land-Grant Consortium (FALCON) member survey showed there is a strong interest among TCUs nationwide to work on water quality-related projects. While there are examples of collaborative water quality programs supported by other agencies, there is a need to expand extension collaborative programming and partnership among state and tribal land-grants.The tribal collaboration team is working to fill the gap in collaborative programming between state and tribal land-grant institutions. The North Central Region Water Network provides funding support, strategic guidance, communication support, and evaluation support for the tribal collaboration team, with Rebecca Power, Anne Nardi, and Amber Mase providing primary support.

Document_Name: Using New Media to Expand the Reach of Parenting Education and
Segment: Today 90% of Americans are online and 69% of US adults use social media. The average American spends more than 10 hours per day on screen. In fact, smartphones are the great equalizer, providing young adults, racial and ethnic minorities, and those with lower household income levels a connection to the Internet. Parents use mobile devices and social media to seek out parenting tips, interact with other parents, and connect with their children. Research shows that digital media can be an effective educational tool for influencing positive parenting change. Results from our digital parenting educational programs show that parenting programs delivered via new media like text messages, blogs, video, and social media can increase parents' knowledge about child development and parent-child relationships and boost social and informational connections for parents. New media holds strong promise for embodying the Wisconsin idea and bringing applicable knowledge and skills to all parents and caregivers of children. However, our digital programs do not adequately reach historically underserved populations such as Spanish-speaking parents, low-income parents, and families separated due to divorce or other life circumstances. Our online programs reach primarily English-speaking, middle income families. Yet that demographic is an incomplete picture of Wisconsin's population. Hispanics compose 18% of the US population and are the 2nd largest and fastest growing minority racial and ethnic population in Wisconsin. The poverty rate is increasing statewide and most children live with one of their biological parents. By expanding the reach and impact of our outreach to underserved populations, Wisconsin parents and caregivers will more fully benefit from our online educational offerings.

Document_Name: Enabling community development through community organizations'
Segment: Community development in Waushara County is primarily accomplished by community organizations made up of volunteers who have either joined or been elected the organization. Very few of these organizations have staff, so their work must be carried out by the volunteer board/commission and members of the organization. There are about 500 IRS recognized nonprofits, 25 lake organizations, and 25 municipalities. These organizations provide services in Waushara County to improve and maintain the local quality of life and enhance the local economy.

Document_Name: Addressing Leadership and Organizational Development Challenges
Segment: This program plan was prioritized based on the continued need to raise the majority of my salary and benefits from sources outside of the UW-Madison Division of Extension's budget with grants, contracts and fees for educational services. This is my 15th year operating within this type of budgeting plan. In 1999, the Wisconsin Legislature expanded comprehensive planning with the "Smart Growth" law, providing a framework for communities to develop, adapt, implement and amend plans. Nine elements to be addressed include: Issues and Opportunities, Housing, Transportation, Utilities and Community Facilities, Agricultural/Natural/Cultural Resources, Economic Development, Intergovernmental Cooperation, Land Use and Implementation. According to the State of Wisconsin's comprehensive planning law, adopted comprehensive plans are to be reviewed and updated at least once every 10 years (Section 66.1001(2)(i)). Upon review of the City of New Berlin's 2020 Plan, previous work done with consulting group left staff with many questions about data sources and analysis. Through numerous conversation with their Planning Department, a decision was made to work with Extension staff to provide an educational service and support through updating the 2030 plan. This process also seeks to increase staff capacity for data analysis in future efforts for updating their plan. UW-Extension will assist the city by coordinating with staff to update the plans demographics and statistics, to make the document more user friendly. This effort will be done in cooperation with the Plan Commission to also prepare for community conversations amongst key challenges identified.

Document_Name: Interpreting Climate, Ecology and Culture for the Apostle Islan
Segment: Apostle Islands is the only Lakeshore in the National Park Service that exists primarily on islands (94% of the land base) in Lake Superior, the world's largest freshwater body (by surface area). However, this unique location and marine context puts the park at greater risk from climate change; Lake Superior is one of the fastest warming lakes in the world due to the combination of increasing summer air temperatures and decreasing winter lake ice. This has strong potential to alter natural disturbance regimes and subsequently the parks rare ecosystems and species. Furthermore, unlike mainland parks, Apostle Islands could face decline of forest ecosystems coupled with poorly understood potential for immigration of southerly species due to the barrier of Lake Superior.The impacts of climate change on the vulnerability of Apostle Islands National Lakeshore (APIS) ecosystems and resources is being conducted by the Northern Institute of Applied Climate Science combined with information from literature reviews, climate change projections, ecosystem modeling, and an expert panel to identify climate associated vulnerabilities. This project is a $22,000 grant funded partnership with APIS to review results of the APIS Ecosystem Vulnerability Assessment and develop effective interpretive messaging and education outreach to target audiences including visitors, teachers for outreach to youth, and the general public. The project will increase their awareness of climate impacts and vulnerabilities on the Park's terrestrial resources, how the National Park Service (NPS) is addressing these impacts through adaptation practices, and how these audiences can make choices to reduce climate change and promote Park stewardship. Deliverable include design of exhibits and web-based outreach to outreach interpretive themes and messages, and a 1-day teacher workshop will train educators to teach about climate impacts and adaptation strategies using place-based examples from APIS climate vulnerability research. The integration of Traditional Ecological Knowledge (TEK) and partnerships with tribal educators will be fostered to assure culturally relevant content, programming, and outreach.

Document_Name: Leadership Waupaca County: Addressing Engagement and Inclusion
Segment: Communities are most effective for the citizens when the citizens engage - with local politics, with associations and charities, with volunteerism, with personal interests, and with each other (social connectedness). With the exception of volunteerism, which Wisconsin currently holds the #3 spot nationwide, civic engagement is low across the state. According to the US Census Current Population Survey's Voting, Volunteering, and Civic Engagment, only 11.4% of Wisconsinites work with neighbors to fix or improve (the) community, only 13.4% attend a public meeting, only 14.1% do favors for neighbors, and only 16.5% have contacted or visited a public official. According to the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, "residents of socially connected communities are more likely to thrive."Exacerbating the situation is a change in demographics - the population in Waupaca County is aging and diversity and poverty are increasing, creating challenges for future engagement and inclusion ((get exact data and insert)). In the past three years, this issue has come up twice as a Leadership Waupaca County self-selected team project, and has shown up as Veterans organizations struggle to maintain or gain membership as their existing membership ages and experiences declining numbers, with new members choosing to start their own organizations. Further, with an aging populations, employers are scrambling to attract new people to the area. This issue is also an important part of the solution to several issues discussed in the 2018 Situation Statement for Area 10: social isolation of elders, access to jobs, resilience related to mental health/substance abuse, and stress related to changes in family structures.Individuals need to cultivate their own connection and belonging within their communities through the ways in which they engage, and collectively the citizens as "the community" need to send signals of inclusion and openness to residents, visitors, and prospective newcomers in order to be truly connected communities.

Document_Name: Promoting the Social-Emotional Well-being of Children and Famil
Segment: According to the 2010 Census, Pierce County has a total population of 41,019 (est. 41,901 in 2017) with a racial and ethnic makeup as follows: 97% white, 1.3% two or more races, .7% Asian, .6% black, .4% American Indian and 1.5% Hispanic or Latino. Because of its geographic location on the west-central border of the state, it is considered part of the Minneapolis-St. Paul MN-WI Metropolitan Statistical Area.A variety of factors contribute to the health of Pierce County residents. As shown in the County Health Rankings Model from the University of Wisconsin Population Health Institute, there are four major health factors that shape health. Those factors and relative percent weight on shaping health are health behaviors, 30%; clinical care, 20%; social and economic factors, 40%; and physical environment, 10%. In the current rankings (2018), Pierce County ranks 39 of 72 for health behaviors with a higher than state average for excessive drinking and alcohol-impaired driving deaths; and 67th for physical environment with 43% of individuals driving alone with long commutes to work compared to 27% for the state. We have a very low ratio of population to mental health providers with a ratio of 2,430:1 opposed to the state at 560:1. (http://www.countyhealthrankings.org/) According to the local Sherriff's office and Department of Human Services there has been a marked increase in drug use cases resulting in out of home placement for children.Individuals and families need knowledge and skills to make healthy decisions in all of these health factors. They also need community supports and environments, as well as systems and policies to assure that the healthy choice is the easiest choice for them and their families. Health initiatives often focus on downstream symptoms like obesity, depression and addiction as the cause of poor health, rather than upstream exposures that precede the emergence of these symptoms. Adverse childhood experiences (ACEs) have been identified as some of the most significant precursors to poor long-term health. Paired with the systemic inequities caused by adverse community environments (Ellis, W., & Dietz, W., 2017) such as poverty, violence, poor quality housing, discrimination, limited economic mobility, etc., individuals lose hope and community vitality plummets leading to pressing health crises like the current opioid epidemic. "Improving community health takes partnerships, time, and commitment. It takes sustainable changes to policies, systems and environments. It takes problem-solving and innovation. It takes all of us working together toward a shared goal." (http://www.countyhealthrankings.org/what-is-health) UW-Extension has the ability and will to build organizational capacity to strengthen 1) community resilience and vitality and 2) individual protective factors to reduce toxic stress and adverse childhood experiences. Protective factors are positive conditions in families and communities that strengthen all families and increase their health and well-being. The Center for the Study of Social Policy Strengthening Families (https://www.cssp.org/young-children-their-families/strengtheningfamilies) identifies the following five protective factors: Parental resilience, social connections, concrete support in times of need, knowledge of parenting and child development, and social and emotional competence of children. Research studies support the idea that when these protective factors are strong in a family, the likelihood of child abuse and neglect decreases. Due to ongoing economic conditions including low commodity prices, high production costs and rising debt levels, many Wisconsin farmers are facing increased financial and emotional stress. This chronic stress affects individual health and wellbeing as well the relationships they have with family, friends and even service providers (e.g. lenders, crop consultants, sales representatives, etc.). Extension has the capacity to address this issue with a, multi-level, cross-disciplinary response.  Pierce County Health Rankings Data (2018): http://www.countyhealthrankings.org/app/wisconsin/2018/rankings/pierce/county/outcomes/overall/snapshot Pierce County KIDS County Indicators: http://datacenter.kidscount.org/data/customreports/7088/any Highlights From the November 2018 Farm Income Forecast https://www.ers.usda.gov/topics/farm-economy/farm-sector-income-finances/highlights-from-the-farm-income-forecast/

Document_Name: (2019) FoodWIse:  Special projects - Video development for stak
Segment: FoodWIse federally funded by the Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program-Education (SNAP-Ed) and the Expanded Food and Nutrition Education Program (EFNEP) and serves Wisconsin residents with limited incomes. FoodWIse operates in almost all counties in Wisconsin. There are several printed reports available of the program's success; however, video stories can make a lasting impact on the viewer.

Document_Name: Building Resilience by Supporting Safe, Stable, & Nurturing Rel
Segment: Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs) are a serious health and economic issue nationwide and in Bayfield County. Exposure to extreme or prolonged stress in childhood is associated with changes in brain development that impact behavior and health. These changes can contribute to a lifetime of challenges, such as poor adaptation to stress, poor social functioning, physical and behavioral health problems, financial problems and even early death. Many of these challenges result in increased demand on community resources such as assistance programs and the criminal justice system. They also contribute to health, education and criminal justice inequities related to race, location and poverty. Yet many individuals and families remain resilient in the face of these stressors. Research supports the importance of safe, stable, nurturing relationships (SSNR's) and several other key protective factors in building resilience, improving health and reducing harm from exposure to adversity. Examples of childhood stressors that are especially impactful in Bayfield County include poverty, high levels of family conflict, exposure to domestic violence, substance abuse, child abuse/neglect. This information is drawn from statewide data, nterviews and data gathered through the county Criminal Justice dept, Red Cliff Tribal Court, the Bayfield, Ashland Iron Counties Community Health Needs Assessment and other county and tribal family serving agencies. Poverty is a key source of toxic stress in Bayfield County. The percent of children in poverty is 22% compared with a statewide rate of 16%. (County Health Rankings and Roadmaps). The county faces the challenges of a rural economy with few high paying jobs. According to the Dec 2018 WI Dept of Workforce Development report, Bayfield County had the highest unemployment rate among counties in the state. Median household income in the county is $50,110, compared to the state median of $56,759. According to the MIT Living Wage Calculator a family of two children and two working adults must earn $64,788 annually to meet basic living expenses without assistance programs in Bayfield County. A single parent must earn over $59,056. These wages are well above median earnings and the wages offered in the typical service industry, hospitality, farming and support positions most commonly available in the county. Substance use disorders take a major toll on residents of Bayfield County. Substance addictions, particularly to meth, are resulting with a dramatic increase in out-of-home placements for children. This contributes to additional exposure to stress for children and their caregivers, many of whom are grandparents and other older adults. It is also putting a major strain on county funds. Substance abuse is a multi-faceted problem, but research is clear that healthy family relationships and social connections are protective factors. Another source of toxic stress for children in Bayfield County revolves around high conflict family relationships. It has been repeatedly demonstrated that high levels of parental conflict are related to negative outcomes for children. In a recent survey by the Bayfield County Criminal Justice Department, 99 percent of Bayfield County Jail inmates reported a history of family violence in childhood. While family conflict and family violence are complex issues, an environment of healthy relationships and strong social emotional skills,have an important role in prevention.The importance of healthy relationships includes not only adult/child relationships but also those between adults and other adults. Social connections for adults play a key role in interrupting the cycle of child maltreatment. (Children Benefit When Parents Have Safe Stable Nurturing Relationships, CDC, 2013). Relationships with romantic partners, friends, extended family and other social supports contribute to positive outcomes for parents and their children. Safe, Stable, Nurturing Relationships protect from negative outcomes in two ways: 1. They help prevent many sources of toxic stress in the first place and, 2. In the face of adversity, they have been shown to serve as a buffer that mitigates damage to children from a prolonged stress response. (Defining Toxic Stress from a Community Perspective, Center for the Study of Social Policy). To build awareness around and address sources of toxic stress, Bayfield County Human Development & Relationships programming is framed around the Center for Study of Social Policy's Strengthening Families Protective Factors: hese five factors: Parental Resilience, Social Connections, Social Emotional Skills, Parenting Knowledge and Concrete Support in Times of need are shown to enhance child development and reduce the likelihood of child maltreatment. They are also important to the well-being of all families, not just those at risk.

Document_Name: Increase Social and Emotional Wellbeing for Youth and Families
Segment: Dunn County Situation StatementThis situation statement will provide an overview of an ongoing assessment of Dunn County, a primarily rural county with a pocket of urbanization, located in northwestern Wisconsin. The following will include, (1) a brief review of Dunn County demographics and social statistics, (2) discussion on protective factors and how improving social emotional skills enhances long-term community wellbeing and economic outcomes, (3) four research informed strategies to increase social and emotional wellbeing in youth and families based on local needs, and (4) how these strategies align with the vision of both Dunn County and UW-Extension.Demographics and Social StatisticsThe following is a brief review of general demographics and social statistics of Dunn County. This is not an exhaustive detail of the county, however, four main points including (1) population, (2) race and ethnicity, (3) poverty and ALICE (Asset Limited, Income Constrained, Employed) rates, and (4) ACEs (Adverse Childhood Experiences) statistics will be addressed to discuss local needs.Population and Geographic ConcentrationDunn County is home to 44,603 Wisconsin residents and the population is steadily growing, increasing by 10% from U.S. Census data in 2000. This county is geographically rural with a concentrated urban population in the city of Menomonie. The most recent U.S. Census data (2010), with urban to rural populations, indicated a ratio of 40.0% of residents living in urbanized areas to 59.3% in rural. The largest municipality in the county, the City of Menomonie, which is also the county seat and the only incorporated municipality with an urban population, represents just over 88% of the total urban population in the county. The urban population is further concentrated in the center of the county as all towns with an urban population border the City of Menomonie, including the towns of Menomonie, Tainter, and Red Cedar which make up the other 12% of the urban population.Race and Ethnicity According to the Applied Population Lab, Dunn County's population by race and ethnicity is estimated as the following 93.3% White alone (not Hispanic or Latino), 2.2% Two or more races (not Hispanic or Latino), 2.1% Asian alone (not Hispanic or Latino), 1.7% Hispanic or Latino (of any race), 0.4% Black or African American alone (not Hispanic or Latino), and 0.2% American Indian and Alaska Native alone (not Hispanic or Latino). Just over 4% of the population speaks a language other than English at home.Income, Poverty, and ALICE The median household income for Dunn County is $49,788 and the per capita income is $24,098; both lower than the state averages. The poverty rate for the county is higher than the state at 13.5% to 12.1%, respectively. A more holistic picture of finical demographics includes, ALICE an acronym for Asset Limited, Income Constrained, Employed, are households that earn more than the Federal Poverty Level, but less than the basic cost of living for the county. Combined, the number of poverty and ALICE households equals the total population struggling to afford basic needs. In 2014 Dunn county's average below the ALICE Threshold was 43%, this number increases in specific towns experiencing economic and social distress, for example the town of Wheeler had 70% of the population below the ALICE Threshold. Similarly, the town of Knapp had 58%, Menomonie had 57%, and the town of Boyceville 53% below the ALICE Threshold. Dunn County experiences a slightly higher amount of households below the ALICE Threshold at 43% while across Wisconsin, 42% of households struggled to afford basic household necessities.ACEs and Socioeconomic Status The Wisconsin Ace Brief (2012) defines an ACE or Adverse Childhood Experience as "a traumatic experience, which occurs prior to the age of 18, such as child physical or sexual abuse, having an incarcerated household member, exposure to domestic violence or parental divorce." Approximately 58% of Wisconsin residents have experienced at least one ACE, with14% experiencing 4 or more. There is significant comprehensive research that concludes the higher the number of ACEs the greater the risk for long term social, emotional, and cognitive impairment, as well as higher adoptions of healthy-risk behaviors (e.g. smoking, alcohol and drug abuse), and which leads to an increased risk in disease, disability, and social problems. Overall these risks and ripple effects may lead to early death. Dunn County's ACEs or Adverse Childhood Experiences ranking is relatively high. The Wisconsin ACE Brief identifies Dunn County as having 15-20% of the county's adult residents have four or more ACEs. ACES have been strongly linked to a wide range of negative outcomes (mentioned above) in adulthood that impacts the community as a whole. Furthermore, ACEs are also strongly associated with poverty and ALICE rates. The Wisconsin Ace Brief (2012) indicated adults with $25,000 or less in yearly income are 27 percent less likely to report zero ACEs, and almost twice as likely to report 4 or more. In addition, there is also a disparity for high level ACEs and race. According to the study on Racial Disparities in Child Adversity in the U.S.: Interactions With Family Immigration History and Income "across all groups, black and Hispanic children were exposed to more adversities compared with white children". However, there is hopeful news, high levels of ACEs in our community is not an end all be all. There is a concept of "protective factors" that lead to increased resiliency that can outweigh the negative long term impacts of Adverse Childhood Experiences.

Document_Name: Empowering Individuals to Perform Better at Work / Workforce De
Segment: The unemployment rate in the Twin Ports is currently just over 3%. A workforce study recently completed by CREC and IDM for APEX has identified workforce challenges for area companies that includes: retention of current talent, attraction of talent, and skills gaps (in technical and soft skills). Douglas County is also not immune to these market conditions. In 2019, I will offer a Leadership Development Course for Douglas County and the City of Superior with approximately 20 in the cohort. In addition, work of the Douglas County Workforce Roundtable will continue, and will adopt at least one strategy from the APEX Talent Forecast report.

Oneida, Vilas and Forest Counties includes a large number of vulnerable populations, including a high and increasing aging population, children from low-income homes, economically challenged, those with chronic health conditions, as well as three tribal communities. According to data collected for the Forest, Oneida, and Vilas Counties Community Health Improvement Plan (CHIP) the averaged cancer Incidence rate in Oneida, Vilas and Forest Counties is 191 per 100,000 people, with Vilas and Oneida's incidence and mortality rates being the highest in the state. The Obesity rate is also quite high with an average of 31% in the three county area. One of the three county CHIP priority areas is Chronic Disease Prevention and Management. The Health & Well-being Extension Educator will intentionally align work to meet the goals and objectives Northwoods CAN!, the chronic disease prevention coalition. This alignment of programming will also include recent community needs in building resiliency among vulnerable populations by supporting and educating on stress management and mindfulness techniques to build resilience.

The Microsoft and 4-H Digital Ambassadors partnership empowers youth to help close the broadband internet gap. Currently in the U.S. there are 23.4 Million people who lack broadband internet access. Access is only half of the problem, feeling secure and knowledgeable enough to adopt and use the technology is the other half. This partnership will elevate teens as teachers to provide training and communication to assist adults in their community with increasing their comfort level in utilizing new technology. This will empower the adults to truly adopt and use technology to improve their opportunities and outcomes. 4-Her's serve as a trusted voice and have many long-standing relationships within their communities, which create an effective training environment and build a compelling movement throughout the community. This work will have profound effects in education, workforce development and community sustainability.In addition to the programmatic training, the youth leaders (Digital Ambassadors) will be trained as spokespeople to lift up and expand youth voice in this critical conversation. This will ensure their experiences as well as hopes and dream for their communities are heard. The youth leaders will host a minimum of six to ten (6-10) learning sessions in their community by June of 2020.

Document_Name: Building Community Capacity to Strengthen Families and Increase
Segment: Empowering citizens to identify and address community problems through networking, coordination, prevention and collaboration across county lines and in urban and rural settings, was the theme of the 2013 visioning session that took place in Eau Claire County. "The future of any society depends on its ability to foster the health and well-being of the next generation. Stated simply, today's children will become tomorrow's citizens, workers, and parents. When we invest wisely in children and families, the next generation will pay that back through a lifetime of productivity and responsible citizenship. When we fail to provide children with what they need to build a strong foundation for healthy and productive lives, we put our future prosperity and security at risk." (Center on the Developing Child, Harvard) With this in mind, building our community with the goal of improving family life and childhood experiences creates a coordinated effort to strengthen families and build futures for our community. Science tells us that meeting the developmental needs of children is just as much about building a strong foundation for lifelong physical and mental health as it is about enhancing readiness to succeed in school. By leading and participating in coalitions and action teams focused on prevention and early intervention, we can grow the knowledge base and develop new strategies across multiple domains to strengthen families and increase the health and well-being of families. Results from the 2014 health survey, as well as results from health surveys from the past three years have shown that mental health continues to be a top priority of community members in the Eau Claire area. The Chippewa Valley is 90% done with the 2018 community health assessment, and that too is showing that mental health is still our community's number one health priority. About 75% of people in Eau Claire County with mental health conditions receive no treatment at all for their mental illness. Community members have identified the complexity of navigating the mental health system as a major barrier to receiving treatment. Nationally, as many as one in five children has a diagnosable mental health issue and the Substance Abuse and Mental Health Service Administration (SAMHSA) estimates the US prevalence of childhood Serious Emotional Disturbance (SED) as one in eight children. In Wisconsin, approximately one in 10 children qualifies as having a SED. The general population is beginning to understand children's mental health as less an absence of pathology but instead a state of social, emotional and mental well-being which includes the ability to develop friendships and connections with others; participate with confidence in school, the family, and the community; regulate emotions; and maintain high self-esteem with knowledge that one matters in the world. In 2016, Eau Claire City-County Health Department and the Chippewa County Health Department received a grant titled, "Mental Health Matters" to improve behavioral health of children in the Chippewa Valley. Through my role serving on the Mental Health Action Team, I was asked to participate in the Mental Health Matters Steering Committee. Our group is assessing community needs, resources and feasibility of implementing programs and policy changes to impact children's mental wellness. My role on this grant and other mental health initiatives is to promote the health and well-being of individuals, families, and communities of Eau Claire County through collaborative and focused action on education, prevention, building upon the community strengths of diversity and resources, leading community assessment, planning, implementation and evaluation. Also, in 2015 I was able to conduct the Family Needs Assessment to better understand the needs and strengths of families and individuals in our community. The survey was distributed to individuals in Eau Claire and Chippewa counties. Based on the results of that survey, my work will continue to grow with the needs of families, serving in a role that will support this research. The survey resulted in 672 respondents. Key findings indicated that chronic stress was the number one area in which families could use additional support, and that mental health ranked as the highest area of need for families. Co-chairing the Mental Health Action Team, serving on the steering committee for the Mental Health Matters grant, co-chairing the Education/Awareness subcommittee and providing leadership and education around mental wellness is an important part of my current and future programming. The work in building community capacity has a direct relationship with the Human Development and Family Relationships Team. Locally and statewide, we work to strengthen the family and enhance the relationships within it in order to raise healthy children, care for vulnerable members, and sustain productive workers and residents who contribute to community life and a civil society. The work of the team recognizes that families do not exist in isolation and that they are influenced by the many settings, institutions, norms, and policies that surround them. The team's work strives to understand these influences so that it can provide educational programs, professional development, community initiatives, and local leadership that strengthen the family's ability to perform its critical functions.

Document_Name: Adopting Profitable Agricultural Practices which Enhance Enviro
Segment: Iowa County was founded in 1829 and has 23,000 residents (2012 Census). While still a rural county it is becoming a commuter community to a metro area (Dane County) and sits within a circle of some 75 million consumers within a 5 hour drive. The county is located in the un-glaciated, southwestern corner of the state, dominated by a gently rolling to steep, rugged terrain, recognized for its' scenic beauty along with productive farmland. The majority of the county is underlain by highly fractured limestone and sandstone formations, soil depths range from several inches to several feet. Ground water resources are excellent and many valleys are bisected by small streams and rivers, feeding into the Upper Mississippi River basin. The highly erodible topography, soil, and sub soil make this landscape fragile to degradation of soil and water quality. The 2012 Census of Agriculture, indicates that farm numbers are decreasing(1588), reversing a recent trend observed in the 1990 and 2000 Census of Ag, where more (1813), but smaller farm sizes were reported. There are 1183 farm operations and Census of Ag also demonstrates that less than 50% of farm operators (n=749) derive their income exclusively from farming. The census data infers that 400 farm owners (25%), are not operating their farm.Agent needs assessment of county and township elected officials (n=30), and interviews with ag lenders identified 12 key issues. The highest priorities were - value of farm products, impact of agriculture on the environment in terms of water quality and soil erosion, and farm income for small family farms.A UWEX office needs assessment in 2011 (n=145) identified concerns from farmers and rural landowners about the impact of runoff and manure on water quality and increased soil erosion and sedimentation from more tillage. Regional organization surveys reinforce these concerns. Southwest Badger Resource, Conservation and Development needs assessment survey (2012) (n=98) - soil erosion, surface and ground water quality were identified as the most pressing conservation issue in the region. Southwest Regional Planning Commission implemented a visioning needs assessment (2013) "Grow Southwest Wisconsin" and established regional objectives to preserve, sustain, and manage Southwestern Wisconsin's agricultural and natural resources, support education and research related to agriculture, and to conserve water and soil. The consistent concern from farmers and rural landowners over time and about the impact of agriculture on soil and water quality has led to educational programming efforts focused upon the sustainability of agriculture. Recent (2018) rural ground water assessment in Iowa, Grant and Lafayette County has resulted in 42% of rural wells with some form of contamination. Society, rising incomes and growing populations are placing more demands upon agricultural lands to provide safe, affordable food and to reduce US dependence upon imported oil by producing alternative bio-energy products. Unfortunately this contributes to a negative feedback loop, more people equals more food and energy consumed resulting in more intensity of agriculture. More mined fertilizer (limited resource) used at faster rate, more acres cropped more intently (more fuel - limited resource) resulting in more soil (limited resource) erosion. An outcome is lowered capacity of soil to produce food and fuel and collapse. As agriculture increases its' intensity, some production practices will rank higher or worse than others in the degree of effect on soil quality and erosion and impacts on surface and ground water. Iowa County has had the highest level of Conservation Reserve Program acres in Wisconsin, as gross acres and as percent of total crop acres. High commodity prices triggered rapidly increasing lands rental values and have attracted many of these acres back into row crop production. In 2009, the Geological Natural History Survey completed mapping the underground water geography of Iowa County, with depth to bedrock data, creating a 3-D map and potential areas of high concern for groundwater contamination. The shallow upper aquifer is in the most intensive ag area of the county and is highly susceptible to contamination. The deep aquifer is located on the more rugged and rugged landscape. The US Environmental Protection Agency and USGS have identified the Upper Mississippi Basin as a large contributor of nitrogen and phosphorous to the waterway resulting in a growing hypoxia zone in the Gulf of Mexico. Blue Mounds State park is the highest point in southern Wisconsin at 1719', US Highway 18 roughly follows the old Military Ridge with an average elevation of 1200'. Runoff to the south drains into the Pecatonica River system, as this water leaves Iowa County at Blanchardville, it has lost 400' of elevation over a distance of 17 miles. High commodity prices resulting from government incentives, lack of effective enforcement and freedom to farm have encouraged sod busting, the conversion of pasture and transition of CRP acres into row crop production. Current low commodity prices are encouraging producers to work even more land to pay bills, while the best strategy may be to not row crop these marginal acres at all. Forages whether as hay or grazed pasture are ideally suited to address multiple concerns - profit, soil regeneration, improved water infiltration and higher soil health compared with row cropping. Reduced and No-till also further the goal of reducing soil loss and improving water infiltration rates, further adoption of cover crops can push soil building, water infiltration closer to the levels of managed pasture. Nutrient management planning is essential to producers for managing production input costs on fertilizer purchases and understanding soil loss rates on their farm under current and potential improved management. Educating both producers and land owners who control access to a significant portion of ag lands on the value of conservation is imperative lest we repeat the folly of the poor ag practices of the past. By deploying best ag practices, runoff can be reduced, water infiltration can be increased soil maintained and improved. The judicious use of dairy and livestock manure with a carbon source can build soil organic matter and make Iowa County more resilient. Good and improving soil and water quality will maintain and enhance our environment, agricultural productivity and quality of life.

Document_Name: Sustainable Agriculture for Douglas County: Nutrient Manageme
Segment: Douglas County has experienced a loss in productive agricultural land over the past 30 years, particularly as most of the dairy farms have discontinued. Presently there are 5 active dairy farms. The majority of the agricultural land is in grassland hay and beef production. The transition out of more intensive agriculture has resulted in the vast number of farming operations relying on "off farm" employment to fulfill income needs. At the same time, it has been observed through on farm visits, yearly Dairy Roundtables, facilitating Local Food Coalition gatherings, serving as an advisor on the Douglas County Farmland Preservation Planning Committee, participating in grazing and nutrient management field days and on farm research plots: farmers expend energy and resources on agricultural methods that do not allow the potential economic, environmental or societal return of sustainable agronomic management.A particular need continues to be management of the nutrients for a productive system, both economically and environmentally. Locally, UW- Extension has been able to address these questions by engaging individual landowners, businesses, elected officials with University Wisconsin- Madison Agriculture Specialists in the College of Agriculture and Life Sciences to offer education, research and outreach in Farm Management, Dairy Profitability, Agronomy, Soil Science and Community Food Systems.As indicated in the Douglas County Farmland Preservation Plan (2018-2028) and the Douglas County Comprehensive Plan (2010-2030), the County and its citizens consider agricultural land an important land use in its county for economic strength, conservation of their natural resources and a desirable way of life. Sustainability for agriculture is important to maintaining and growing these outcomes. There is a growing awareness that farmers often purchase or rent more grassland acres to meet their forage needs rather than sustainably manage what they own currently. This strategy results in increase infrastructure costs (rent, time, machinery) and results in lower yields, loss of quality forage, decrease in soil health, and valuable time away from family and community.The diversity of population is relatively low in Douglas County, particularly for those that influence the rural land use. This will need to be addressed when gathering data, providing outreach, and gathering input. This should be achieved by engaging the new and young farmer demographic and encouraging non farmers in offering ideas, participating in programing and making decisions for sustainable agriculture outcomes in Douglas County.

Document_Name: Reality Check Financial and Life Choices Program (2019)
Segment: Buffalo and Pepin are adjacent, rural counties and share a combined total of a little more than 20,500 individuals living in 8,759 households (U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts estimates, July 1, 2016), spread across 1,004 square miles. In both counties, agricultural-related activity is the primary economic base. Statistics show that family composition is mixed, with a greater percentage of single-parent households, unmarried parents and stepfamilies, in comparison to two-parent households. (American Community Survey Profile Report: 2011-2015 5-year estimates). Racial/ethnic composition in Buffalo County is 97.7% white alone; Pepin 98.2%. Although a relatively small percentage, Latino is the predominant minority, and I have utilized partnerships for outreach to connect with Latina-led young families for parenting and relationship education. Alcohol abuse, illegal drug use and mental health are top concerns for residents across both counties. (Great Rivers United Way COMPASS NOW 2015 Survey; Buffalo County Community Needs Assessment, 2015; Pepin County Community Health Improvement Plan 2016-2020; Buffalo County Community Health Improvement Plan 2016-2020). According to the National Provider Identification Registry, there were no mental health care providers available in Buffalo County prior to 2015. There are now two part-time mental health providers available in Buffalo and Pepin counties, with a patient to provider ratio of 6,679:1, compared with the WI state average ideal patient to provider ratio of 623:1. The lack of access to mental health services is a problem for families and individuals.Both Buffalo and Pepin counties face a dramatic doubling (from 15% to 30%) of residents age 65 and older by the year 2035. A need to prepare aging-friendly communities has been expressed among local government and agency partners, and will be a part of future programming planning. (This may become a secondary programming priority).Median household income is $50,196 and $49,516 for Buffalo and Pepin counties respectively. However, there are wide disparities between age groups, ranging from $16,917 for younger adults to $63,182 for seniors (U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts estimates, July 1, 2016). And, while unemployment rates are low, so are high-paying "living wage" jobs (livingwage.mit.edu, living wage calculator, 2017). Only 4% of Buffalo County respondents rated the availability of jobs with wages that offer a good standard of living; 74% responded poor or fair (2015 United Way: Buffalo County Random Household Survey). The percentage of high-paying jobs is low and a high household income is not enjoyed by most residents. The UW-Extension 2018 Developmental Situational Analysis process for Area 9 identified AODA and health concerns, and building skills for healthy family relationships, stability and well-being as two of the top five priority needs. This was based on a broad representation of stakeholder/partner input and surveys, and is consistent with results of a 2010 formal Survey of Issues and Themes Impacting WI Families and Communities that I conducted with local partners, as part of a statewide Family Living Program effort. Responses from dozens of partners confirmed my programming focus on education and prevention for family relationships and financial security, especially for vulnerable populations. Local Community Health Improvement Plans, United Way Community Assessments and Youth Risk Behavior Survey data continue to validate these programming priorities.I hold a leadership role within the Institute for Human Development and Relationships by chairing two state efforts: Healthy Relationships, and Correctional Systems Audiences. In order to make the greatest impacts at the local, regional or state levels, it is important that I leverage resources and be clear about my facilitating, research, education, planning and evaluation roles. Where possible, a prevention approach that reached a wide audience has been the foundation of programming efforts and, when necessary or appropriate, intervention strategies have been used. I rely on research and specialist support, as well as multiple sources for assessing current and future community needs. I advance a collective impact with partners and coalitions.Provide educational resources and opportunities about healthy couple, co-parenting and other family relationships parenting, child development, either direct education or contacts, online or through key partners. Specific to the Reality Check program, many of the local schools do not offer life-skills or personal finance courses for students. This program ensures that all students receive essential education and authentic learning experiences toward decision-making, education and career, and personal finance as a successful young adult.

Document_Name: Addressing Leadership and Organizational Development Challenges
Segment: This program plan was prioritized based on the continued need to raise the majority of my salary and benefits from sources outside of the UW-Madison Division of Extension's budget (with grants, contracts and fees for educational services). This is my 15th year operating within this type of budgeting plan. Jefferson and Waukesha Counties are geographically located between Madison and Milwaukee along the I-94 interstate corridor. Both counties have experienced substantial population growth over the past 35 years. Since 1980, Waukesha County has grown by over 116,000 people and Jefferson County has grown by over 18,000 people. Collectively, in 2016, Waukesha County (396,449) and Jefferson County (84,262) had a combined population of over 480,000 people.Since the spring of 2017, Waukesha County UW-Extension has worked with the Village of Palmyra on understanding demographic trends, understanding their trade area, and connecting small businesses to resources. UW-Extension has connected small businesses in Palmyra to the resources offered by the Small Business Development Center at UW-Whitewater. UW-Extension also conducted small business retention and expansion visits with 22 companies with under 50 employees. Based on what we heard on these visits from business owners, UW-Extension developed three workshops for small businesses in collaboration with a steering committee of the Chamber of Commerce. The majority of this effort was funded by a USDA Rural Development Grant that Waukesha County UW-Extension wrote to provide educational and technical assistance to Palmyra. Palmyra has requested additional assistance from UW-Extension in 2019 to assist them with formulating a plan for a Wisconsin Department of Tourism Joint Effort Marketing (JEM): Destination Marketing grant to better capture visitors from the Kettle Moraine State Forest, Southern Unit. Annually, over 1 million people visit the southern unit of the Kettle Moraine State Forest. Farmers Markets, Parks, Trails, and Pedestrian uses are topics of high interest in attracting and retaining millennials in communities. This remains a continued need with non-profit groups in Jefferson County and an area that UW-Extension has the skill sets to deliver with data analysis, strategic planning, and organization development. Currently, Jefferson County has over 400 registered non-profit organizations.

Document_Name: Traditional Ecological Knowledge, Culture and Ecology Field Cou
Segment: The success of the G-WOW Changing Climate, Changing Culture professional development model which integrates place-based investigation, traditional Ojibwe ecological knowledge (TEK), and "western" science has evolved from a 4-day climate institute (offered annually from 2011-2016) into a series of multi-day natural resource and climate change field courses based on this model for youth, undergraduate students, and professionals, These are multi-day field courses featuring a curriculum that I customize to meet each group's learning objectives. I partner with the Great Lakes Indian Fish and Wildlife Commission, and Bad River and Red Cliff Tribes to offer place-based learning, culturally relevant experiences and with state and federal agencies, such as the Northern Institute of Applied Climate Science, to provide additional "western" science research. Demand for climate change educational programs based on the G-WOW climate literacy model continues. I continue to offer single and multi-day G-WOW Climate Camps" for school and youth groups; and present the model to adult audiences on request. In addition, I maintain the G-WOW website (www.g-wow.org) as a online climate training curriculum and repository of climate resources.
