Document_Name: Network Literacy Team, Military Families Learning Network: Addr
Segment: Network Literacy (NetLit) helps people become more resilient and adaptive within complex social systems through relationship building, personal growth, and shared work. We do this by creating space for practice, reflection, connection, inquiry, co-learning and collaboration.The term network literacy describes competence in using online networks to learn, teach, create, share, and build both personal and professional communities.Network literacy is an important part of the work of the Military Families Learning Network and specifically the NetLit team because it:Involves how people find information, connect with others, communicate, work, learn, share knowledge, and teach through networks.Investigates and creates understanding of the social, economic, and political implications of knowledge distribution via networks.Focuses on how technology and social networks are influencing and reshaping society.However, the work of the NetLit team extends beyond competence in using online networks.The complex and interrelated issues facing military families, call for emergent and adaptive solutions. NetLit will help MFLN better contribute to these solutions by:Producing and sharing knowledge about complex systems and the role social networks play in building resilience within those systemsCreating learning experiences and spaces for the practice of network building.Facilitating network-wide discussions on creating conditions for engagement and program innovationCollaborating with MFLN concentration areas to support more collaborative, learner-centered, and issue-driven programmingMeasuring and monitoring the health of the MFLN network

Document_Name: Climate Strong! Building Tribal Youth Leadership for Climate Re
Segment: Tribal governments are facing harsh realities as extreme weather, development, and economics threaten not only the sustainability of natural resources but also their culture. Because their culture is intertwined with the land and the plants and animals that living there, tribes face unique challenges in maintaining their cultural practices as a changing climate affects those resources. This initiative is based on the 2019-2021 Climate Strong! $500,000 NOAA grant to the Fond du Lac Tribal and Community College (FDLTTC) to develop a training curricula and outreach for educators and tribal youth to build their leadership in helping their communities build climate resiliency within the 3-state Ojibwe Ceded Territory of Wisconsin, Minnesota, and Michigan. I assisted in developing this grant and initiative and am serving as a Co-Principal Investigator. Other partners include the Great Lakes Indian Fish and Wildlife Commission (GLIFWC), the 1854 Treaty Authority, and the Lake Superior National Estuarine Research Reserve as a NOAA asset. The project integrates the G-WOW climate literacy model to build awareness of how climate impacts community and cultural systems and build leadership skills to contribute to resiliency strategies through integration of place-based culturally relevant traditional ecological knowledge (TEK) and NOAA earth science assets.

Document_Name: Through deliberate leadership opportunities early adolescent yo
Segment: National Data: Since the 1990's employers require a mix of soft skills and technical expertise from future employees. Soft skills include interpersonal communication like team work, problem solving and critical thinking. In addition, listening in being able to reflect, summarize, and para phrase what another person is saying. Furthermore, prioritization of work flow, written communication and innovation highlights essential areas. Cognitive skills like reading, writing, and arithmetic is crucial in predicting academic and employment success. In 2008, the Association of American Colleges and Universities (AACU) reported on a multi-year dialogue between employers and institutions of higher learning. In which, each institution must foster a high level of intellectual and practical skills. Garcia, in 2014 confirms the AACU report with employment sectors requiring various skill sets from interpersonal to applied skills. Only one third of graduating students are ready for college or engaging in the workforce (Wagner 2008). Positive youth development programs provide life skill development and the opportunity to apply learned leadership skills. Deliberate leadership activities create opportunities for youth to lead and work with peers and adults. The University of Illinois Extension (Diaz et al, 2015) identified six action areas where youth leaders develop competency in 4-H Youth Development: 1) planning, 2) promoting, 3) teaching, 4) mentoring, 5) advocating, and 6) advising. The 2010 Wisconsin 4-H Youth Leadership study found older 4-H youth demonstrated the following: Individual growth in life skills Youth participation in intentional leadership practices (club officers, committee members, camp counselors, leadership training workshop participants, etc.)  Increased opportunities for in group and teamwork development. A key difference in the expectations of employers going forward revolves around literacy. For today's (and tomorrow's) employers, literacy no longer refers to one's ability to read and write, but their ability to navigate communication platforms, specifically in-person relationships, while navigating the online platforms. Today's youth are born into a world where technology is part of how they learn, communicate, and experience life (Ku 2014). Conversely, soft skills; teamwork, problem solving, critical thinking, listening, and communication skills will keep the workforce moving in a united and upward direction. Wisconsin Data: In Wisconsin, the Governor's office has established workforce development goals that serves as the basis for local/regional responses to economic development and workforce needs, including a plan for youth (Department of Workforce Development 2013). The soft skills, life skills, and leadership skills previously identified align with the Governor's goals for Wisconsin's "emerging workforce" - youth (Western Wisconsin Workforce Development Board, Inc. 2014). These skills align with the 4-H youth developments essential elements of Belonging, Independence, Generosity, and Mastery. In addition, the 6 C's of positive youth development: connection, competence, confidence, character, caring, and contribution.4-H Data: 4-H Youth Development has been preparing youth for a successful future outside of school since 1904. Youth leadership and life skills are synonymous with positive youth development. Youth leadership programs provide life skill development and the opportunity to apply learned skills. The 2010 Wisconsin 4-H Youth Leadership study found that older 4-H youth demonstrated individual growth in life skills. Intentional leadership practices found active participation as a club officer, a committee member, a camp counselor, a facilitator of a project area, and more develops independence, and mastery. Purposeful opportunities to work in groups contribute to life skill development. The strongest outcomes in the 2010 Wisconsin 4-H study were in community connectedness and self-efficacy (beliefs about one's capabilities to produce effects). The strongest skill results related to communication, decision-making, and problem-solving skills. Exactly the skills employers are looking for. Local Data:A 4-H youth and adult assessments were conducted in the fall of 2017. The premise for conducting the survey was to identify why Clark County 4-H has difficulty retaining youth over the age of 12. Questions revolved around the priorities youth and parents participate in and outside of 4-H. The respondents identified parallels with 4-H, FFA, Sports, other extracurricular school activities, religious obligations, and work. Challenges experienced in 4-H yielded a range of responses from the risk of failing (not doing well), availability (time), new people, reporting (record books), and uncomfortable with the unknown. The University of Illinois Extension (Diaz et al, 2015) identified six action areas where youth leaders develop competency in 4-H: 1) planning, 2) promoting, 3) teaching, 4) mentoring, 5) advocating, and 6) advising. Clark County 4-H's primary focus has been on teaching and mentoring with older youth and their parents.

Document_Name: Building Community Capacity Strengthening Families and  Increas
Segment: The 2017 estimated population of Grant County is 51,999 people, with 96.5% being white, 1.4% Hispanic, and 1.4% black. It has a slightly higher percentage of people aged 65 and older (15.6%) than Wisconsin as a whole and a lower percentage under 18 (21.3%) as compared to Wisconsin as a whole (23.6%). It is a rural county with a population density of 43 people per square mile and experienced a minimal (0.42%) growth rate in the last decade. Grant County has a poverty rate of 15.4%, higher than the 12.5% state average. The medium household income is $49,067, which is well below the national average of $56,516. The child poverty rate is 17%, also higher than the Wisconsin rate of 16%. In Grant County, the proportion of the population receiving FoodShare increased from 2.8% in 2000 to 14.7% in 2015. In Grant County during the same period, the share of school-age children certified for free or reduced price meals grew from 27% to 45%. These economic statistics along with priority issues determined by Grant County UW-Extension needs assessment completed in 2015/16 has assisted in setting a framework for the Grant County Family Living Program. In 2015-2016 Grant County UW Extension partnered with the Survey Research Center (SRC) at the University of Wisconsin at River Falls to conduct a county wide needs assessment. Programming priorities on topics related to the family are more evenly distributed than for any of the other Extension programming areas. There are no clear top priorities for family-focused programming, but the overall average level of importance attached to these topics was higher than all other Extension programming areas. There several topics that about half or more of the respondents felt were very important: personal finances (saving/investing for the future, budgets, debt, credit reports, etc.), child development, identity theft, caring for aging family members, healthy lifestyles (nutrition, physical activity, social and emotional health), coping with family transitions, communication and relationship building. In a comparison with the 2015/16 needs assessment over previous efforts ranked a higher awareness or concern in regards to health & well-being over parenting practices gathered from open ended questioning as noted in the following bullet points.  Discuss and plan how to deal with incursion of drugs, gangs, and crime in Grant County.   Expand substance abuse programs possibly through the court system.  Mental illness treatment for Grant County residents.   Programming for healthy living, lifestyle behavior change, and healthy decision making.  Promotion of health of all aspects i.e. food, physical, mental, relationship, etc.  Find out why cancer is so prevalent in this county.  Healthy lifestyles.After careful consideration of priorities and needs of Grant County, the determined priority program efforts will focus on building community capacity supporting and building family financial security and economic well-being, building family strengths, improving parenting supports and practices, and promoting healthy lifestyles while strengthening the collaborative efforts of all agencies serving families improving outcomes for children, families and society.The profound influence of families on society makes evident the importance of supporting and strengthening families. Issues' relating to parenting or the strengthening of families is nothing new for Grant County UW Extension, but often takes on new forms as parenting issues change with the times. Whether looking at families seeking basic parenting skills, support and prevention of AODA issues or child abuse, families struggling with divorce, couple relationships, connecting to community, or spending quality time together; citizens of Grant County are concerned about families enduring ongoing challenges that remain a fact of life. It is also apparent within Grant County that even though families remain the primary place where children are raised there is increasing evidence that the task is shared by others, and that "care giving is everyone's business."Families perform a variety of key functions that contribute to both the mental and physical health of individuals as well as the public health and functioning of society. Throughout all developmental stages, from the prenatal period to the last years of life, strong healthy relationships help families effectively and efficiently raise healthy children, care for vulnerable members, and sustain productive workers and contributing community members. Children who are born into and raised in an environment of positive relationships have a strong foundation that can help them develop into healthy adults and productive citizens. This environment of relationships involves not only parents and children but also extended family and social networks, schools and childcare providers, and others who engage with the family. Stable, nurturing relationships have a powerful protective impact on children. They help prevent exposure to multiple risks and stressors, including family violence and neglect, parental incarceration, and mental illness. Exposure to these stressors is associated with numerous poor outcomes, some of which are commonly seen across multiple generations within families and are very costly to society. In addition to contributing to prevention, safe, stable, nurturing relationships with parents and other caregivers serve as a buffer to help mitigate the damaging impacts of toxic stress. Healthy relationships help children thrive. Adult health and well-being also depend in great part on the quality and success of relationships. Adults in stable relationships have better health outcomes, greater financially stability, a greater sense of well-being and improved capacity to provide care for vulnerable family members, including children and older adults. It has long been understood that a strong parent/child relationship is a key factor in preventing negative outcomes for children. More recent research suggests that strong relationships between parents and other adults, including romantic partners, friends and extended family, can help prevent child maltreatment and improve the capacity of adults to parent effectively. Healthy relationships help adults nurture.For seniors, social connections and strong family relationships are critical to continued well-being and engagement. As the nation and Wisconsin experience a demographic shift toward a greater proportion of older adults, it is critical to invest in programs that keep seniors connected and contributing in their roles as active citizens, caregivers for children and older adults, and as part of the social support system of partners, friends and others. In a recent Community health needs assessment social isolation was identified as an area of concern. Healthy relationships support seniors' well-being.Connecting to the Human Development and Family Relationships Team will assist Family Living in Grant County to strengthen the family and enhance relationships in order to promote lifelong mental, physical and emotional health. Recognizing that families do not exist in isolation and that they are influenced by many settings, institutions, norms, policies, and transitions Grant County Family Living will provide programming which acts on research to ? support caregiver skills across developmental stages,? target periods of significant stress for families and caregivers,? reach learners through traditional and digital methods, and? connect individuals and communities through systems level work.

Document_Name: Learn About Your Land natural resource education program (2019)
Segment: Leading the nation in paper production and wood furniture manufacturing, Wisconsin's $24.7 billion forest products industry provides 64,000 jobs, and employee compensation adds another $6.4 billion to local economies. Many communities depend on a sustainable forest products industry. As harvesting from industry-owned land decreased, to ensure a continuous timber supply the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources (DNR) looks toward those who own nearly 70% of the 16 million acres of forested land   private woodland owners.Over ninety percent of the woodland in SW Wisconsin are owned by private woodland owners. The majority of these woodland owners are managing their lands without the help of a conservation professional. The Learn About Your Land program was created as an outreach tool to provide instruction to these woodland owners. Woodland owners who participate in this education program gain insights as to how to enhance sustainable management of their lands.

Document_Name: Addressing Leadership and Organizational Development Challenges
Segment: UW-Madison Division of Extension is part of the land grant system and federal extension system, in partnership with the National Institute of Food and Agriculture (NIFA) of USDA. As a recipient of NIFA and other federal funding, the organization must comply with federal civil rights, equal opportunity and nondiscrimination laws. The USDA prohibits any discrimination in all programs/activities based on race, ethnicity, age, ability, gender, family status, and sexual orientation. Compliance with Civil Rights laws assures that all participants and colleagues are treated with respect, equality and fairness, we are operating in an inclusive manner and have adequate diversity. The value crating through research-based educational outreach must also surpass USDA Civil Rights compliance. To ensure compliance and nondiscrimination, the Civil Rights Leadership Team, provides coaching, assessment and professional development to strengthen our organizational pillars of community and inclusiveness by identifying gaps and opportunities to develop and improve strategies for engaging nontraditional and historically underserved audiences.

Document_Name: Tribes Lead!  Tribal Leadership Development in the Great Lakes
Segment: This plan of work element includes two tribal leadership initiatives :Tribal Nations Lead! Tribal Leadership Development in the Great Lakes Region: The Great Lakes North Central Region is home to 56 federally recognized Tribes, 23 of those reside in Michigan and Wisconsin, each with a unique system of governance. Based on federal trust responsibilities the Cooperative Extension services in Michigan and Wisconsin have a responsibility to build relationships and partnerships with the tribal communities that we serve. Community development has been the responsibility of local governments, planners and politicians. But in many communities there is a deep desire for more grass roots involvement in the development of current and future leaders. It is essential for Tribes to develop successional leadership plans within their communities in order to address emerging cultural, economic, and social issues. While there are Cooperative Extension leadership development programs, there is a lack of training that integrates indigenous teachings with western leadership concepts to promote culturally relevant leadership in tribal communities. Likewise, there are important leadership lessons to be learned from Tribal cultures that can be shared to strengthen non-tribal leadership development programs across the region. This initiative is a $20,000 North Central Regional Center for Rural Development (NCRCRD) grant initiative and partnership between UW-Extension and Michigan State University Extension.This project will develop a cross-state collaboration to create a culturally relevant leadership training model for emerging Native American leaders. It will be replicable across the diversity of tribal nations within the North Central region and its outcomes will help enrich leadership training programs for non-native audiences. This project will increase the capacity of land grant institutions by demonstrating how integration of indigenous knowledge with University-based research can strengthen programming and build relationships with tribal communities based on a reciprocity and respect. This project builds on the tribal leadership curriculum and activities developed for the Great Lakes Indian Fish and Wildlife Commission's leadership development program listed below.Great Lakes Indian Fish and Wildlife Commission (GLIFWC) Leadership Development Program is an on-going relationship to develop the curriculum and training for provide professional leadership development for GLIFWC's Biological Services Division. Training builds on a building capacity for shared leadership management model and integrating traditional ecological knowledge in their western science-based natural resource research and management. As a result of this initiative, additional requests for leadership training from other tribal departments is expected in 2019.

UW Extension programs have a unique and valuable role in assisting individuals and families to improve the nutritional quality of their dietary choices, increase their physical activity levels, and maximize the safety of the food they eat. UW Extension FoodWIse is a federally funded by the Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program-Education (SNAP-Ed) and the Expanded Food and Nutrition Education Program (EFNEP) and serves Wisconsin residents with limited incomes. FoodWIse employs a combination of evidence-based educational strategies, accompanied by environmental supports, designed to facilitate voluntary adoption of healthy food choices and active lifestyles. FoodWIse works out of county Cooperative Extension offices and in collaboration with state and local partners. FoodWIse is engaged in 66 of 72 Wisconsin counties. SNAP-Ed funds programming in 66 counties.Prior to the creation of the Regional Program Manager position, there was a missing connection between the state and county staff. Connecting counties with state FoodWIse staff helps to create a strong relationship and fulfills the purpose of teamwork. The FoodWIse Regional Program Manager actively supports and works with County Coordinators within their assigned areas to ensure county project educational programs and partnership efforts are within SNAP-Ed Federal Guidance and supported with resources they need to be successful, such as providing coaching, plan development, implementation, evaluation, and reporting. The Regional Program Manager also works collaboratively with the FoodWIse State Coordinator in supporting administrative functions related to human resources and grant program management.

Wisconsin has a long history of specialty crop production and processing, including potatoes and vegetables. This production represents significant economic contribution across Wisconsin's rural and suburban communities. Potato and vegetable, alone, accounts for over $750 million annually. In total, specialty crop production and processing account for more than $5.8 billion of annual economic impact and about 24,500 jobs (Mitchell et al., 2017, Economic impact of specialty crops and irrigated agriculture in Wisconsin). The spectrum of growers producing these specialty crops include both small scale as well as large scale, and organic and conventional. In addition, in my role in disease management extension, I also address vegetable disease concerns of home gardeners. My research program is driven by questions stemming from my extension interactions - and logically - my extension program is fueled by results of my research program which specifically addresses disease management concerns of the numerous grower groups served by my UW-Madison-based integrated research and extension program. Overarching research objectives include: 1) exploration of pathogen ecological factors for improved understanding of disease and its persistence in the environment, 2) development of integrated disease management approaches suitable to specific growing systems of Wisconsin and the region, and 3) advancement of detection and management tools ro reduce reliance upon chemical control inputs to enhance sustainability of healthy food production in our environment.

Document_Name: Building the Capacity [footnote] of Oneida County (2019)  [Capa
Segment: Community and organization capacity building and leadership development is also a result of the April 2015 visioning and survey work. It will continue to be a priority. My reputation for this work is growing. The need is endless.
